<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a1000 05-26 1131</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a1000,1,100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Lashes ``Liberal Elite,'' Dukakis and Jackson Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 20 grafs to UPDATE with more debate material;
picks up 14th graf pvs, bgng, The Massachusetts</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush lashed out Wednesday at political
liberals, accusing them of destroying a bipartisan consensus toward
the Soviet Union, while Democratic presidential front-runner
Michael Dukakis said Bush's advocacy of the death penalty for drug
dealers was ``the height of hypocrisy.''
   During a one-hour debate in San Francisco, Jesse Jackson pressed
his Democratic rival for specific budget details as well as on his
policy toward South Africa. But the two Democrats saved their
strongest comments for criticism of the Reagan administration for
its dealings with Panamanian military leader Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   After the debate, Jackson and Dukakis met privately.
   With President Reagan en route to a Moscow summit, the two
Democrats said they hoped the superpowers would move toward less
reliance on military solutions to world problems.
   Dukakis said the superpowers were ``wandering around the world
like lonesome cowboys'' intervening militarily.
   Jackson said he wished Reagan ``godspeed and a good astrologist,
as he believes in both'' and added he hoped the superpowers would
``look beyond the arms race.''
   The debate _ their first in more than a month _ took place only
hours after Secretary of State George P. Shultz announced the
failure of negotiations aimed at getting Noriega to relinquish
power in Panama. Shultz said no new talks were scheduled.
   Bush said the fact the negotiations had broken down ``doesn't
depress me.''
   ``I'm convinced Noriega will be out of power,'' Bush told
reporters in Lakehurst, N.J. ``We'll have to go back and figure it
out.''
   Bush has advocated the death penalty for drug kingpins.
   When Jackson was asked if he supported that position, he
replied, ``I do not. I do not think we have the moral authority to
execute in that sense. We have the obligation to take them off the
streets and above all, do not deal with them and give them
sanctuary and put them on the CIA payroll.''
   Dukakis then interjected, ``It's the height of hypocrisy for
people in the administration to be advocating the death penalty for
drug pushers while they are doing business with Noriega and
funneling aid to the Contras through convicted drug dealers.
   ``I don't know of anything phonier than that kind of policy.''
   Questioned about his opposition to the death penalty, Dukakis
said, ``You don't have to be for the death penalty to be tough on
crime.''
   He said views on the death penalty would not be a standard for
judges he would appoint as president.
   ``I don't apply ideological litmus tests,'' he said.
   Dukakis said trying to forumlate a detailed budget plan so far
in advance would be ``a serious mistake.''
   Jackson kept pressing him, however, saying that ``the governor
is laying out a budget of prommises but not a budget of numbers.''
   When Jackson asked Dukakis if he would use military force
against South Africa, the Massachusetts governor replied that he
would press for more effective sanctions.
   When Jackson kept pressing him, Dukakis said, ``Yes, one aspect
of a tough anti-terrorist policy is the use of military force
against terrorist base camps. But there are many ways to attack
terrorism.''
   The Massachusetts governor expects to lock up the Democratic
presidential nomination on June 7, when California, New Jersey,
Montana and New Mexico hold primaries, the last major contests of
the long pre-convention campaign.
   During a stop at the U.S. Capitol before he flew west, Dukakis
picked up endorsements from 18 members of Congress who will be
``super delegates'' to the Democratic National Convention in July.
   Bush, at West Point, N.Y., told cadets at the U.S. Military
Academy commencement ceremony that the ``liberal elite'' had
abandoned what he called the bipartisan consensus for maintaining a
strong national defense. Aides billed the Bush speech as
non-political.
   Standing under a small canopy in the pouring rain, Bush never
mentioned Dukakis or Jackson, but left no doubt of his targets.
   ``I'm sure they'd claim it isn't so and they're all in favor of
a strong defense,'' Bush said. ``They look the part, sober and
measured in their gray suits, moving their hands on the Sunday talk
shows with just the right amount of gravity and earnestness.''
   ``But what are we to think, when they say they're for a strong
defense but they oppose every new weapons system that would
preserve that strength?'' Bush asked.
   Bush spoke only hours after President Reagan departed for Europe
and a superpower summit in Moscow.
   He cautioned against allowing summit meetings to lead toward
complacency toward the Soviets.
   ``We must be confident that those who will lead our country
understand what it means to stand up to a challenge and meet our
commitments,'' Bush said. ``We must be confident that they will
pursue negotiations with the Soviets realistically.''
   He said that under Democratic presidents Harry Truman and John
F. Kennedy and then under Republican President Dwight D. Eisenhower
there was bipartisan agreement on the need to deal with the Soviets
from a position of strength.
   ``There are some today who have abandoned those principles,'' he
said. ``The liberal elite do not understand _ they never understood
_ the common sense behind the consensus.''
   Later, the vice president called for the naming of an
independent counsel to study recent alleged financial irregularties
surrounding House Speaker Jim Wright.
   ``If they want to talk about (Attorney General Edwin) Ed Meese,
how about talking about the speaker?'' he said. Meese's legal
problems have been frequently raised by the Democrats.
   While in Washington, Dukakis met with a former rival, Democratic
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, a private meeting he later
described as ``very cordial.''
   They met in Dukakis' hotel room and Gore still withheld any
endorsement of the apparent nominee. The senator wrote to his
delegates last week and urged them to stay loyal for the time
being. Gore has nearly 400 delegates.
   The 18 congressional delegates Dukakis picked up moved his total
to nearly 1,700. He needs 2,081 for a convention majority.
   Jackson has less than 1,000 in the latest Associated Press
survey.
   During meetings at the Capitol, Dukakis said, ``We are not going
to concede one single state to the Republicans in the fall.''
   One of his sessions was with Western members of Congress and he
said, ``The strategy is to win the West.'' He said it was ``one of
the great political paradoxes'' that while Democrats run well in
the region in contests for Congress, governor and other offices,
the party's candidates have been virtually shut out there in recent
presidential elections. The last Democratic presidential candidate
to carry the West was Lyndon B. Johnson in 1964.
</TEXT>
