<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Taxation-Representation     05-26 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taxation-Representation,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Republicans Lock Themselves In Room During Tax Hikes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Senate Republicans locked themselves
in a room in protest Wednesday night as Democratic senators adopted
two tax increase measures totaling more than $100 million.
   The Senate quickly approved a $70 million income tax loophole
closing measure and a 5 percent sales tax on cigarettes designed to
raise nearly $40 million and sent the measures to the House. As the
vote took place, six Senate Republicans sat in a locked room with
the telephones either in use or off the hook.
   The Republicans said they were caucusing and were hoping to
delay action on the tax increase proposals while at the same time
drawing media attention to the tax bills. The Senate, with many
Democrats also absent from the chamber, approved the bills on a
voice vote.
   ``For a $100 million bill to go through the Massachusetts Senate
without a roll call is outrageous,'' said Sen. David Locke, who led
the Republican caucus.
   Locke and fellow Sen. Paul Cellucci are top officials in Vice
President George Bush's Massachusetts presidential campaign.
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, the likely Democratic presidential
nominee, has called for additional revenue and spending cuts to
balance the $11.8 billion state budget, but has maintained it can
be done without raising cigarette taxes.
   He has campaigned for president, in part, on his ability to
balance the state's budget and on his success in reducing taxes
over the past six years.
   Senate President William Bulger derided the Republicans' move as
a publicity stunt.
   ``The minority party was well aware of what's been going on,''
Bulger said. He said that after several attempts to call the
Republicans failed, a court officer knocked on the door and
informed the Republicans that a vote was taking place.
   Two of the eight Republicans in the 40-member Massachusetts
Senate were absent.
</TEXT>
