<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Marcos     05-26 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos Leaves Hospital, Asks To Return to Philippines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
ended two-day's hospital treatment for chest pains Thursday, saying
he will ask U.S. officials to let him return to his homeland for
the funeral of his mother.
   ``I'd like to go home and preside over the funeral rites of my
mother,'' Marcos said from a wheelchair during a news conference
before he was discharged from St. Francis Medical Center.
   Marcos said his application for permission for him and his
family go to the Philippines and return to the Unites States at
will would be submitted Thursday or Friday at the U.S. Immigration
and Naturalization office in Honolulu.
   When asked whether the application would be a request to return
permanently to the Philippines, Marcos replied, ``Well, what else?
I would like the ordinary rights of a citizen.''
   President Corazon Aquino, saying Marcos poses a threat to
national security, has repeatedly rejected his pleas to return for
the funeral of his mother, Josefa Edralin-Marcos, who died May 4 at
age 95.
   Marcos said Mrs. Aquino should reconsider because, ``I've told
them I will not bother them ... but will hold back the people from
starting violence. She alone will not be able to hold them back.''
   Marcos is under ``a prevent departure notice,'' which means he
needs permission to leave the United States, said INS district
director William Craig.
   Marcos said he did not know how long it would take for the INS
and Philippine government to respond to his latest request. He said
no date has been set for the funeral.
   Marcos was accompanied by his wife, Imelda, several aides, a
nurse and his physician, Dr. Azucena Ignacio, who said Marcos would
be able to travel.
   Ignacio said Marcos' chest pains were caused by arthritis or
inflammation in the area of the left sixth rib. She said Marcos
improved dramatically by resting and was being treated with
painkillers.
</TEXT>
