<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     05-26 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ``Plimouth'' in first item cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been more than 300 years since this
town saw so much struggle over restraint, but Plimoth Plantation
visitors could soon be drinking beer and wine after a brief spell
of temperance at the tourist spot.
   For a while, it looked like the prudish reputation of those
early settlers had come back to haunt the village, which offers a
glimpse of 17th century life after Plymouth Rock. But Tuesday
night, after several go-rounds, the Board of Selectmen approved a
limited liquor license for the plantation.
   The board twice rejected requests for a license to serve all
types of liquor year-round or for one-day licenses.
   The license approved Tuesday applies only from April to
November, when the plantation visitor center is open. It still
requires state approval.
   The 41-year-old private, non-profit tourist spot first served
alcohol four years ago at a snack bar. But that license was
discontinued when the snack bar was torn down.
   With the opening of a new visitors center and 200-seat
restaurant, the plantation management hoped to draw more business
by opening in the off-hours for business conferences, during which
guests would expect alcohol on the menu.
   In the past, some residents objected that alcohol was not in
keeping with the Pilgrim spirit.
   But in fact, the Pilgrims cooked with wine and regarded beer as
more healthful than water, plantation officials said.
   However, plantation spokeswoman Sarah Mann said most of the
arguments against a comprehensive liquor license came from nearby
restaurants and bars.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Senate agreed with the saying,
``you can't take it with you,'' and approved a bill that would
allow elderly lottery winners to receive their jackpots sooner than
younger winners.
   The bill approved Wednesday and sent to the Assembly would allow
jackpot winners older than age 65 to take their earnings in one
lump sum or in periodic payments during their expected lifetime.
   ``The usual 20-year payoff on a lottery prize will not always
result in a total benefit to the winner who is over 65, as he may
not live to receive the full benefit,'' said a memo on the bill.
   ``The fact that the unpaid balance would be paid to his estate
is of little consolation to many elderly winners who may wish to
fully enjoy the fruits of their good fortune,'' it said.
   But John Quinn, director of the state Lottery Division, said he
opposes the bill because it would substantially reduce jackpots.
   For example, he said, the jackpot up for grabs Wednesday was $3
million, but ``I don't have $3 million to give them, I have $1.4
million. The difference is interest money.''
   A winner currently would receive 21 annual payments of $114,000
after taxes, said Quinn. If someone opted to take the prize in a
$1.4 million lump sum, they would owe about $580,000 in taxes, he
said.
   Quinn said he didn't believe any state lotteries offer the
lump-sum option.
   The average million-dollar lottery winner in New York is 49
years old, said Quinn.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEAVERVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are no traffic lights in all of
peaceful Trinity County _ and it's going to stay that way, despite
a state suggestion one is needed near a proposed shopping center.
   When an environmental impact report was prepared for a
140,000-square-foot mall east of Weaverville, the state Department
of Transportation said it ``would have some definite traffic
impacts,'' and suggested that ``the future need for a traffic
signal should be considered at this time.''
   But that's not how the Northern California county sees it.
   In fact, says Tom Miller, county director of planning and public
works, the lack of traffic lights ``is a source of local pride.''
   The county adopted a regional study in 1986 that makes the
feelings of its 12,500 residents clear: No traffic signals and no
widening of Highway 299, the main drag through Weaverville, the
county seat.
</TEXT>
