<DOCNO> AP880526-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0821EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SummitSpruce-Up     05-26 0867</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit Spruce-Up,0887</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moscow Dresses Itself Up For Superpower Summit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the white satellite dishes pointing west from
the Rossiya Hotel past the Kremlin's ancient church domes didn't
indicate something unusual was going on, the new paint and pavement
along Vorovsky Street might.
   Moscow is being inundated with American officials and Western
correspondents bringing the latest technology to cover President
Reagan's five-day visit, beginning Sunday.
   And in age-old tradition, officials are painting, paving and
otherwise sprucing up to ensure that Reagan and those accompanying
him get the best possible view of the Soviet capital.
   Reagan left Washington on Wednesday for a three-night stopover
in Helsinki, Finland, before flying to the Soviet Union for his
summit with Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   He comes to Moscow at a time when the city traditionally is
trying to right itself after another long, cold winter. The truck
traffic that roars along the Garden Ring Road slows to a crawl as
workers fill another spring crop of potholes, and scaffolding goes
up on buildings everywhere.
   Red tulips planted in squares and along boulevards are in bloom,
as are the lilacs bordering sidewalks and apartment buildings
around the city. Stately chestnut trees are in bloom on the Kremlin
lawns. The sun rises about 5 a.m. and doesn't set until almost 10
p.m., leaving a purple glow in the sky until almost midnight.
   But this year the spring cleaning has taken on a particularly
urgent air around several of the places Reagan will visit.
   The short street leading from the Garden Ring Road to Spaso
House, the U.S. ambassador's residence where Reagan will stay, has
been repaired for the first time in years. Pavement torn out months
ago has been replaced, and almost all the barricades that narrowed
traffic for two blocks have been removed.
   Vorovsky Street also is undergoing a major facelift. Nearly
every building along the street from the Writers Union, which
Reagan is scheduled to visit, to the Soviet Supreme Court building
several blocks away appears to have been given a new coat of paint.
   The Foreign Ministry press center, where Moscow's most important
press conferences are held, has been undergoing repairs for weeks
to improve the seats and the acoustics.
   Officials promised last week that it would be finished in time
for the summit, and a pre-summit news conference was held there
this week. When a reporter asked one of the speakers for a specific
example of changes wrought by Gorbachev's reforms, however, the
microphones and armchair earphones installed for simultaneous
translation suddenly failed, forcing a premature end to the session.
   The Tass news agency said newspapers and magazines from around
the world will be available at the press center next week, not just
the usual selection of papers from the Soviet bloc.
   At the U.S. Embassy, some last-minute painting was going on, and
workers cleared out the courtyard in front of the empty chancery in
the new red-brick compound. The building has been the source of
dispute between the United States and Soviet Union since U.S.
officials discovered that it was honeycombed with Soviet listening
devices. It never has been put into use.
   At stores, Soviet citizens said they had noticed no increases in
supplies to cut down on the lines that gather in the streets. One
young woman joked that closer to Reagan's arrival, ``maybe they'll
even bring out sugar'' which has been in short supply in the
capital and rationed elsewhere in the country because of
moonshining, hoarding and price increase.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said in an
interview with the newspaper Vechernaya Moskva that about 3,000
foreign journalists are expected for the summit, half from print
media and half from radio and television.
   Gerasimov said the Ministry of Communications could not handle
the demands of the Western television companies, so they wre
permitted to bring in satellite dishes and other sophisticated
equipment normally under strict government control.
   The American television networks have crammed room after room of
the mammoth Rossiya Hotel with shiny silver equipment cases,
preparing to broadcast their evening news programs from the Soviet
capital.
   With some 5,000 Soviet and foreign journalists accredited to
cover the event, the summit press corps is the largest to gather
here since the 1980 Olympics, Soviet officials say.
   Moscow dissidents say they have noticed another similarity
between the two events: Many deemed ``undesirable'' by the
authorities were forced to leave town. Eight years ago, they
included prostitutes, speculators and other criminals, as well as
dissidents.
   Father Valery Lapkovsky, a Russian Orthodox priest from the
Crimean city of Kerch, arrived in Moscow last Friday and was told
by authorities the next day to leave, said Russian Orthodox
activist Alexander Ogorodnikov.
   Lapkovsky was put into a mental hospital and diagnosed as
schizophrenic in 1966 after approaching the U.S. Embassy with an
appeal to then-President Lyndon B. Johnson to help him leave the
Soviet Union.
   Soviet officials also have set up roadblocks at the edge of the
city to inspect automobiles. The aim is to keep down the number of
broken-down cars on the streets of Moscow during the Reagan visit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
