<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NearCollision Bjt   05-26 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Near Collision, Bjt,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passenger Jets Came Within 300 Feet Of Each Other</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators are trying to determine why two
jetliners flying in opposite directions with 286 people on board
were assigned the same altitude, bringing them within 300 feet of
colliding head-on over the ocean north of Puerto Rico.
   The Federal Aviation Administration confirmed the Monday evening
incident, which involved a Pan American World Airways Airbus-300
and an American Airlines Boeing 727.
   Both pilots said in near-collision reports that they had no time
to take evasive action as the two aircraft passed wing tip to wing
tip in clear weather about 550 miles north of Puerto Rico in the
so-called Bermuda Triangle.
   The triangle is a region in the Atlantic Ocean where ships and
aircraft are reputed to have disappeared since the 1940s.
   The jets both were believed to be cruising at better than 500
miles an hour with a closing speed of more than 1,000 miles an
hour. Neither pilot reported seeing the aircraft until they were
about to pass each other.
   ``It is being investigated as a possible operational error'' by
air traffic controllers, FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said Wednesday,
when the incident was revealed. He said he did not know whether the
controllers involved have been removed from directing aircraft,
normally the case in such an incident.
   In addition to the FAA investigation, the National
Transportation Safety Board has sent a team of investigators to
Puerto Rico to talk to the controllers involved.
   Farrar confirmed that both of the jetliners were assigned to
29,000 feet and were under the control of the San Juan air traffic
control center at the time of the incident.
   That section of airspace is beyond FAA radar, so separation is
maintained by assigning specific altitudes. Normal separation would
be at least 1,000 feet vertically between aircraft and possibly
more in some areas, according to Farrar.
   He said that in oceanic airspace where there is no radar
tracking planes there also is supposed to be ``substantial''
horizontal separation well beyond the five-mile minimum in
radar-controlled airspace.
   ``These planes should not both have been at 29,000 feet,''
Farrar said.
   He said the two jetliners had about 300 feet horizontal
separation and that ``both aircraft observed each other as they
passed.''
   The incident involved Pan Am Flight 217, which was southbound
from New York to Caracas, Venezuela, with a later stop at Trinidad.
The plane carried 131 passengers and 10 crew members, according to
Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon.
   The other plane was American Flight 902 which was northbound
from San Juan on a flight to Philadelphia. The Boeing 727 carried
138 passengers and seven crewmembers, said John Hotard, a spokesman
for American Airlines.
   ``We understand it's an operational error by air traffic
control. It's our understanding that (both airplanes) were assigned
to 29,000 feet,'' said Hotard in a telephone interview.
   Farrar said the FAA is investigating who gave the planes their
altitude. Both planes were under San Juan air traffic control's
direction, he said.
   Another source, who asked not to be identified by name, said
that the incident occurred near where control of planes switches
from the FAA center in New York to the San Juan center and the
handoff may have resulted in an altitude mixup.
   The FAA's Farrar said he could not confirm that.
   Investigators for the NTSB flew to San Juan on Wednesday to
interview the controllers and may also speak later to the pilots
involved, said spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz.
   ``We are investigating the incident. We're looking into it,''
Lopatkiewicz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0825EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Noriega-Talks Bjt   05-26 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega-Talks, Bjt,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In the End, Nobody Liked The Deal Anyway</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the end, it seemed almost everybody,
ranging from Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega to his severest U.S.
critics, was saying the same thing about the administration's
proposed deal for Panama: ``Just Say No.''
   Vice President George Bush opposed it along with 86 members of
the Senate. Ambassador Juan B. Sosa, a leader of the anti-Noriega
forces here, said the plan would enable the ``criminal empire''
Noriega created to survive the temporary exile planned for him.
   A disgruntled administration official was embittered by the
terms the administration was offering for Noriega's departure:
``His mother could have written it,'' he said.
   Noriega disagreed. Just when an agreement appeared to be within
reach Wednesday, he could not bring himself to approve it.
   Critics of the plan are delighted but Wednesday's drama,
bringing an end to almost a month of intense negotiations, puts the
United States and Panama back to square one.
   Justice Department officials, who all along opposed the lifting
of drug smuggling indictments against Noriega, are pleased with the
outcome. But there is virtually no prospect that Noriega will ever
be prosecuted.
   The administration has withdrawn all its proposals from the
bargaining table and is left with few ideas on what to do next
beyond sounding out Latin American democracies on their thoughts.
   The negotiations ended almost three months to the hour after
Panama's crisis began with the failed attempt by President Eric
Arturo Delvalle to fire Noriega.
   Delvalle, who was fired himself the next day, remains in hiding,
portraying himself as Panama's legitimate president but without the
means to exercise power and with little hope of being able to do so.
   In 1903, when U.S. power in the hemisphere was unquestioned,
President Theodore Roosevelt arranged for the secession of Panama
from Colombia and for perpetual U.S. control over 10-mile wide
``canal zone.'' Those feats took all of two weeks.
   While the United States was once able to get Panama to leave
Colombia, it now is unable to perform a task seemingly much
simpler: getting Noriega to leave Panama.
   Privately, U.S. officials describe the administration's Central
America policy as in a shambles. Coupled with the collapse of the
Panama negotiations is the prospect of disintegration of the
Nicaraguan Contras and the consolidation of Sandinista rule.
   Initially, Delvalle's attempt to fire Noriega seemed to offer
the administration a rare opportunity. Panama's public opinion had
galvanized against Noriega, a general strike against his rule was
surprisingly successful and it seemed logical that a judicious
display of U.S. pressure would be enough to topple him.
   To many, the administration was in a position to strike a blow
for democracy in Panama and against an indicted drug dealer and to
achieve a badly needed victory in Central America after
congressional rejection of more Contra aid.
   Noriega's base of support seemed limited to a small coterie of
allies in Panama's Defense Forces and isolated segments of Panama's
peasantry.
   But Noriega proved to be extraordinarily resilient, sensing
correctly that as long as the Defense Forces remained loyal, he
stayed.
   He was not about to give up, nor about to repeat the humiliating
surrender of his countryman, Roberto Duran, who scandalized
Panamanians in the seventh round of a 1980 fight with Sugar Ray
Leonard when he walked, head down, to his corner and said ``No
mas.''
   Shultz echoed the spirit of Duran's famous remark on Wednesday
although in a far different context when he discussed the collapse
of the talks with Noriega.
   ``No further negotiations are contemplated,'' Shultz said. ``All
proposals addressed during these negotiations have been withdrawn.
No offers remain on the table.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
  _ George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for
the Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
