<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WritersStrike 1stLd-Writethru a0868 05-26 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0868,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Late Night Shows Reach Independent Agreements with Guild</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4 with four grafs to UPDATE with number of
independents signing, details of bargaining between writers and
producers' alliance. Picks up 5th graf pvs ``Earlier Wednesday...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Letterman could get back on the air and
Johnny Carson would have his writers back under agreements both
have reached with the striking Writers Guild of America, the
union's president said Wednesday as talks resumed in the
12-week-old strike.
   Carson, whose ``Tonight Show'' resumed production this month
when he began writing his own monologue, has signed an independent
contract and Letterman, whose ``Late Night'' is still in reruns,
has agreed to sign, said Guild President George Kirgo.
   Kirgo said he was confident that the union membership would
approve the three-year pacts with the producers of the two shows.
Guild members were scheduled to vote Thursday night on the
independent contracts, which executive director Brian Walton said
involved 39 companies as of Wednesday afternoon.
   The start of the fall television season could hang in the
balance as the striking scriptwriters and producers conduct
last-chance talks. The strike began March 7.
   Walton and the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television
Producers said the producers presented several proposals Wednesday,
and while the union left some open for discussion, it immediately
rejected a new payment structure for one-hour prime-time television
shows sold into syndication.
   The formula would drop a fixed payment schedule and reward
writers based on a show's success in syndication.
   Earlier Wednesday, Letterman issued a tongue-in-cheek statement
through NBC saying his manager and lawyer _ and U.S. Attorney
General Ed Meese _ were negotiating with the Guild. Apparently
seriously, though, he said he hoped to be back on the air, with his
writers back at their jobs, as early as June 8. ``In the meantime,
I am keeping busy with my gardening and phoning my favorite
talk-radio programs,'' he joked in the statement. ``Last month, I
splurged and treated myself to much-needed liposuction surgery on
my hips and thighs.''
   ``I talked to David last week,'' said Kirgo. ``He's waiting. He
will not go back to work without his writers. We had a long and
terrific talk.''
   Nearly 100 negotiators, attorneys and onlookers for the striking
Writers Guild of America and the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers were on hand at the alliance's Sherman Oaks
headquarters for the second mediated session in three days.
   Alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg said there had been some ``new
thinking'' as a result of Monday's meeting with a mediator. Asked
what areas the new thinking included, Steinberg replied, ``the key
issues.''
   Kirgo did not share Steinberg's enthusiasm over a possible break
in the deadlock. ``We were here eight hours Monday and nothing
happened,'' he said.
   Producers are preparing to begin important talks June 15 with
the Hollywood craft unions and Teamsters, whose contracts expire
July 31.
   If writers are still negotiating by then, talks would have to be
scheduled around the other unions' talks.
   Both sides have suffered from the walkout over creative control
on the set and residual payments for both one-hour syndicated
television show reruns and works distributed in foreign countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
