<DOCNO> AP880526-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Britain-AIDS     05-26 0113</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Britain-AIDS,0116</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Medical Association Issues Advisory On Aids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British doctors should in some cases inform the
sexual partners of AIDS patients that they are in danger, even if
the patient does not consent to the disclosure, the body
controlling British doctors said.
   In guidance which will be given to all doctors, the General
Medical Council also said on Wednesday that doctors may test
children for AIDS without their parents' consent in some cases.
   The 130-year-old council controls the education, registration
and disciplining of members of the medical profession in Britain.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome cripples the body's natural
immunity to infections and certain cancers and is invariably fatal.
</TEXT>
