<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     05-26 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Would Ban Nuclear Weapons In Philippines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Philippines-Marcos, Bjt
^By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate is one step away from
passing a bill that would ban nuclear weapons on Philippine
territory but allow port calls by nuclear-powered ships.
   The bill, tentatively approved on Wednesday, is aimed at U.S.
bases in the Philippines and some officials view it as a slap in
the face of the Americans.
   In another development, the military charged that six New
Zealanders have been linked to communist rebels who staged an
ambush in February in which a general's son and 10 other soldiers
were killed.
   The announcement followed military claims that foreign
journalists may have paid communist New People's Army guerrillas to
stage the ambush in Albay province in which Lt. Felix Brawner III
and 10 of his men were killed.
   Brawner was the only son of Brig. Gen. Felix Brawner Jr., who
retired last month as the military commander for northern Luzon.
   Regarding the Senate, Orlando Mercado, majority floor leader,
said the body is expected to pass the nuclear weapons bill next
week on its third reading, a formality where legislators officialy
register their votes.
   The bill prohibits manufacture or storage of nuclear weapons in
the country, but was amended to allow nuclear-powered vessels to
make port calls after they are inspected by Philippine authorities.
   The chief sponsor of the measure, Sen. Wigberto Tanada, is an
anti-nuclear activist who opposes U.S. bases in the Philippines.
   Most senators backed the bill and said it would give President
Corazon Aquino's administration a stronger hand in negotiating with
U.S. officials on the future of Clark Air Base, Subic Naval Base
and four smaller U.S. military facilities in the Philippines.
   Government sources, however, said Mrs. Aquino expressed
misgivings about the bill because of the negative affect it could
have on U.S.-Philippine ties.
   Sen. Mamintal Tamano, who earlier expressed concern about the
bill's implications, said:
   ``This is a backdoor way of repudiating the existing treaty
between the U.S. and the Philippines and the termination of the
bases agreement. The Americans will be very uncomfortable with such
a law, which will render the bases ineffective.''
   U.S. military policy forbids the military from disclosing which
vessels are carrying nuclear weapons.
   Similar legislation in Denmark led to a parliamentary election
and raised questions about that country's committment to the NATO
alliance.
   American aircraft carriers and other warships believed to carry
nuclear weapons call frequently at Subic. Many of them are either
in transit to the Persian Gulf or are returning from duty there.
   The claim linking foreign journalists to communist guerrillas
was made by an alleged former rebel, who said she was a member of a
guerrilla unit which staged the ambush in February, the military
said.
   She reportedly said the foreigners were journalists and that
they provided money and weapons to the guerrillas to stage the
attack.
   Military officials said captured rebel documents indicated the
six New Zealanders included five women and one man.
   In Wellington, the New Zealand Journalists Union and the Public
Service Association, which represents journalists employed by
state-owned media, said they had no records indicating the six are
journalists.
   In the documents, all six were identified as members of various
left-wing and women's organizations in New Zealand.
   One of the women identified herself as a member of the ``New
Zealand Conference for Filipino Concerns.'' She also reportedly
said she was a member of the Workers Communist League.
</TEXT>
