<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0412EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-HumanRights     05-26 0853</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Human Rights,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Human Rights: Progress But Basic System of Repression
Unchanged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During a speech several months ago, the
U.S. ambassador to the Soviet Union used a water glass to describe
Soviet progress on human rights.
   Holding the glass aloft, Ambassador Jack Matlock said that it
would be inaccurate to view such a glass as half empty or half full.
   ``It's more like a glass that was dry and now has a little bit
of moisture in it,'' he said.
   The issue of human rights is one of the touchiest subjects on
the U.S.-Soviet agenda, evidenced by a sternly worded defense of
Soviet policies by Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev during the
December summit in Washington.
   ``What moral right does America have to assume the pose of the
teacher?'' the general secretary asked. He said that he told
President Reagan, ``You are not the prosecutor and I am not the
accused. ... I am not on trial.''
   In an apparent attempt to soothe such touchiness, Reagan used
one of his pre-summit speeches earlier this month to laud Gorbachev
for taking steps to loosen the stringent restrictions on the
practice of religion, freedom of speech, press and emigration.
   In fact, the National Conference on Soviet Jewry reported last
week that 1,086 Jews departed the Soviet Union in April, the
highest monthly total in nearly seven years. Even though the figure
has been rising for about a year, it falls far short of the 1979
levels, when the monthly average was about 4,000 departures.
   As U.S. officials prepare to face their Soviet counterparts at
the Moscow summit _ the 10th session on human rights in 15 months _
they point to such signs of progress, even as they warn that the
basic system of repression has not changed.
   ``A few years ago, the entire process would have been simply
unthinkable,'' Richard Schifter, the assistant secretary of state
for human rights and humanitarian affairs, said recently.
   He called such discussions ``a good first step,'' but only the
beginning of an effort to see that the Soviet Union abides by the
human rights provisions of the Helsinki Final Act, which it signed
along with the United States in 1975.
   Besides pressing for movement in the traditional cases of
divided families, divided spouses and blocked marriages, the
administration also has on its human rights agenda the problems of
political prisoners, emigration and religious freedom.
   ``You cannot speak of freedom of speech, freedom of assembly,
freedom of association, freedom of the press being recognized in
the Soviet Union, that is not the case. ... But sledgehammer
tactics are no longer being used,'' Schifter said.
   Freedoms are still severely limited but people are not being
punished as harshly for alleged transgressions. While
demonstrations are still broken up, he said, the demonstrators
might be arrested for a while and released, rather than being sent
to Siberia for several years.
   Shifter said it also appears that the Soviet leadership ``has
basically given up on the deep commitment ... to conducting
atheistic propaganda. That doesn't mean they have more respect for
religion than they had previously, but they simply have decided
that this just isn't working ... and they might as well tackle the
situation differently.''
   He described the human rights situation as ``coming up to a
better level from very, very far below, but nevertheless, there's a
trend there and all we can say is we wish it would continue and
perhaps accelerate.''
   Other experts have suggested that whatever change is taking
place is partially due to the Soviet leadership's domestic concerns
rather than reaction to outside presssures.
   One administration expert, speaking on condition he not be
identified, pointed to Gorbachev's overtures to the religious
communities, in particular his meeting with a group of Russian
Orthodox archbishops. The session apparently was held to show that
his ``glasnost'' policy of increased openness included religion.
   ``That could very well be seen as an effort of the Soviet
authorities to mobilize a very large portion of the population,
which has been practically excluded from civil life for decades, ''
the official said.
   He said that Gorbachev was impressive ``in recognizing that
believers are Soviet patriots and Soviet citizens who can
contribute.''
   Seen in this light, Reagan's planned visit to the Danilov
monastery and his discussions with Soviet dissidents and refuseniks
are not expected to overly concern Soviet officialdom, said another
administration expert on the Soviet Union.
   ``They'll act like it won't bother them, they know it's going to
occur and they know the president won't do anything gratuitously
embarrassing,'' he said.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz has met with dissident
Andrei Sakharov and Gorbachev had sessions with American citizens
during the Washington summit last December so it is fully
anticipated that Reagan will hold such sessions, the expert said.
   ``They clearly know they have to do something on human rights to
improve relations with the United States, but they won't admit
it,'' he said. ``They want it to appear to be their initiative, and
if that's the case, that's just fine.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
