<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Marcos 1stLd-Writethru a0415 05-26 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Marcos, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0415,0722</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos Hospitalization Adds New Twist To Bizarre Funeral Drama</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 8-9 pvs, ``They have...'' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with comments from mortician. Pickup 10th graf pvs, ``The use...''
^By ROBERT H. REID</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hospitalization of Ferdinand
Marcos in Hawaii has added a new twist to the bizarre drama in
which Marcos supporters are trying to use his mother's unburied
body to help their hero return home.
   Marcos was admitted on Wednesday to St. Francis Medical Center
in Honolulu suffering from chest pains.
   The Philippine consul in Honolulu, Tomas Gomez, accused the
70-year-old Marcos of faking his illness to win sympathy in the
Philippines.
   Marcos' wife, Imelda, said in a radio interview today that her
husband was suffering because President Corazon Aquino has refused
to allow him to return to bury his 95-year-old mother, Josefa
Edralin-Marcos, who died May 4.
   Presidential spokesman Teodoro Benigno reiterated on Wednesday
that Mrs. Aquino would never waver from the ban, imposed in 1986
after Marcos was forced into exile following a civilian-military
uprising.
   Meanwhile, the remains of Marcos' mother, a former
schoolteacher, continue to lie in state in a suburban church, where
dozens of Marcos followers have maintained a round-the-clock vigil
since her death three weeks ago.
   Indeed, the body of ``Dona Josefa'' has become the focus of
renewed protests by Marcos' dwindling followers to demand their
leader be allowed to come home.
   They have pledged that the body will stay in the church until
Marcos returns to bury it. Mortician Frank Malabed said he embalmed
the body twice and it could remain unburied for up to three months.
   To press their point, Marcos loyalists have organized street
marches, some drawing up to 10,000 people, where speakers rail
against the government for denying Marcos the ``human right'' to
bid farewell to his mother.
   The use of corpses as political instruments is not without
precedence in Philippine politics. The 1983 assassination of Mrs.
Aquino's husband, Benigno, was exploited by Marcos opponents to
mount street protests against the government.
   More than 1 million Filipinos turned out for Aquino's funeral 10
days after his assassination. Benigno Aquino's mother, Aurora,
refused to have the body, which lay in state in an open casket,
cleaned by morticians, saying she wanted the ``whole world to see
what they have done to my son.''
   Marcos' sister, Elizabeth Keon, was buried two weeks after her
death in December 1986 as the family lobbied unsuccessfully with
the Aquino government to allow the former president to return for
the funeral.
   But even by Philippine standards, the saga of ``Dona Josefa''
has dragged on to bizarre lengths.
   Mrs. Edralin-Marcos is expected to be buried in the family plot
in Batac in the northern Philippine province of Ilocos Norte. But
an employee of the suburban church, who refused to give her name,
said the family has still not informed the parish staff when the
body will be moved.
   ``The family has not yet set any particular date for the
funeral,'' Marcos' sister, Fortuna Barba, told reporters on
Wednesday. ``When we do decide, it will be properly announced and
disseminated by us and nobody else.''
   Uncertainty about the funeral date appears to reflect divisions
within the pro-Marcos camp among various groups seeking to
demonstrate that they speak for the ``Apo,'' or ``Grand Old Man,''
as Marcos is known to his followers.
   One group has called for a huge caravan to accompany the body
from Manila north to Batac, a distance of 240 miles. They have
suggested stopping at cities along the way for public viewings in a
bid to stir up support in Marcos' northern strongholds.
   On Tuesday, rumors spread that Marcos supporters would hold a
pre-dawn mass Wednesday morning and then spirit the body secretly
to Batac. Reporters rushed to the church, Sanctuario de San Jose,
only to find the coffin still there.
   The unseemly performance prompted Mrs. Barba to issue a
statement warning against ``conjectures, speculations, canards or
disinformation to mislead and confuse the people.''
   Meanwhile, residents of the swank Greenhills neighborhood, where
the church is located, have threatened to launch a petition drive
to demand that Archbishop Cardinal Jaime Sin intervene and order
the body removed.
</TEXT>
