<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0400EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-GayProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0440 05-26 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Gay Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0440,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gay Protests May Help Rather Than Hurt Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to correct spelling of protesters</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the gay and lesbian protesters who
picket campaign appearances by Democratic front-runner Michael
Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor is virtually certain to get
their votes in the fall.
   ``The choice is pretty obvious. Lesbians and gay men will vote
for Mike Dukakis in the fall'' when presented with a choice between
Dukakis and Republican George Bush, said Sue Hyde, who was sharply
critical of Dukakis over his position on foster care by homosexuals
for children.
   Vin McCarthy, a Boston lawyer in charge of the Dukakis
campaign's efforts to reach out to the gay community, said, ``There
is no question in my mind that he will receive the lion's share of
the gay and lesbian vote in November.''
   It is Dukakis' support for giving heterosexual couples
preference in placement of children in foster homes that draws gay
protestors to his appearances, but many political strategists say
the Massachusetts governor comes out ahead politically on that
confrontation.
   ``The vast majority of the American people agree with Dukakis,''
said Robert Beckel, who managed Walter F. Mondale's 1984
presidential campaign. ``From a political standpoint, that's a
no-win issue for the gay community.''
   In fact, many Republicans working to elect Bush chafe at the
fact that Dukakis is being perceived as a moderate because of his
primary battles with Jesse Jackson and because he is being picketed
by homosexual groups.
   A Democratic Party strategist, speaking only with assurance of
anonymity, said that a candidate such as Dukakis, on the verge of
winning the party's presidential nomination, is not looking to
create fights.
   ``But to the degree that you have to have somebody picket you,
you certainly would not mind the gays picketing you over the issue,
not of civil rights or civil liberties, but over foster care for
children, saying your law is too pro-family or too
pro-heterosexual,'' the Democrat said.
   Still, foster care is a highly charged issue in the gay
community.
   ``For Dukakis to have gone out of his way to limit or restrict
the parenting options for lesbians and gay men was a kick in the
gut,'' said Hyde, director of the privacy project for the National
Gay and Lesbian Task Force.
   Hyde said she believes Dukakis considers lesbians and gay men
``sexual criminals.''
   While campaigning in California prior to that state's June 7
presidential primary, Dukakis repeatedly has encountered gay
demonstrators.
   ``Bush + Dukakis ... More AIDS Deaths,'' read signs carried by
demonstrators at a recent Dukakis appearance in Los Angeles.
   ``We need a president who's not afraid to talk about AIDS,''
shouted a demonstrator.
   A disproportionate number of victims of AIDS _ acquired immune
deficiency syndrome _ are homosexuals.
   Dukakis responded that Massachusetts ``spends more per case for
AIDS than any state in America.'' He repeatedly referred to AIDS as
``the most serious public health problem we've had in our
lifetime.''
   Hyde said that in 1985 there was no funding for AIDS in the
state budget and money was later included only after pressure from
Dukakis' state health director.
   ``People were pretty upset about it,'' she said. ``Since that
time I think that Dukakis' administration has been fairly
responsive. It was only after this pretty major outcry in the
Boston area around the zero-funding that they responded.''
   When the Massachusetts governor appeared before a group of
homosexual activists in Los Angeles, he was asked repeatedly about
the foster care policy.
   ``Because I think it's best, all things being equal, for a child
to grow up in a household with a mother and father and other
children,'' he said.
   ``Bigot,'' shouted one man. ``You're anti-gay, why don't you
admit it,'' yelled another.
   The Massachusetts policy on placing of foster children gives
preference to heterosexual couples with child-raising experience
and to relatives of the child in need of care.
   Dukakis vetoed legislation that would have prohibited homosexual
couples from providing foster care.
   McCarthy said, ``There's a perception in the gay community that
the governor did damage to the gay and lesbian community when he
adopted the foster care policy. Attitudinal issues are always the
toughest things to work through.''
   But, he said, ``Notwithstanding the anger, much of which was
legitimate _ I certainly felt it as a gay supporter of Mike Dukakis
_ he has stayed stable in terms of his commitment to gay and
lesbian civil rights and in terms of a sound and balanced AIDS
policy.''
</TEXT>
