<DOCNO> AP880526-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     05-26 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Plays Up His State's Similarities To California</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Should stand for PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner
Michael Dukakis, trying to establish a bond with voters 3,000 miles
from home, says California has ``great similiarities'' to his home
state of Massachusetts.
   Dukakis was in California today, campaigning in advance of the
June 7 primary. But California's 47 electoral votes make it the
biggest prize in the general election, and Dukakis tentatively has
made plans to return shortly after the primary for additional
campaigning.
   Both Massachusetts and California have a ``very strong
commitment to education,'' he said Wednesday night during a debate
with rival Jesse Jackson, brushing aside a comment from a panelist
that there also were notable differences.
   ``We are both high-tech states,'' he went on. ``We're both
states that value our environment ... we're both states and regions
that are coastal, states and regions that understand how important
these ocean resources and coastline happen to be, and how important
it is to preserve them.''
   Dukakis, a methodical man campaigning in a state known for
flamboyance, made his pitch to the California voters as he set out
on a quick campaign swing through the state on Wednesday.
   And as befits the almost-certain Democratic nominee, he made it
clear that he is looking beyond the primary to the November
election.
   In his five-minute closing statement during the debate, he not
only appealed for support in the primary _ less than two weeks away
_ but also pointed out that voters will face a choice between two
very different candidates in the fall.
   Public opinion polls show him leading Jackson in California, and
ahead of Vice President George Bush, the certain Republican
nominee, in a fall matchup.
   Dukakis took care not to offend his Democratic rival during
their hour-long debate, but he also held his ground when Jackson
tried to pressure him into proposing a detailed budget plan and
into declaring South Africa a terrorist state for its support of
rebels fighting neighboring black governments.
   Dukakis says it is too early to make a detailed spending plan,
and wants to pursue other measures against South Africa, including
stronger economic sanctions, before considering tougher measures.
   The two men met privately after the debate, although the
governor declined to say what they discussed beyond ``a lot of
things, family, campaign debates, issues.''
   Dukakis used his time during the debate to repeat criticisms of
President Reagan's policies, but he also issued a statement wishing
the president a ``successful summit'' with Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   ``Today we have the best opportunity in our lifetimes to reduce
the risk of nuclear war,'' he said.
   During the debate, he said the superpowers should stop
``wandering around the world like lonesome cowboys'' intervening
militarily.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
