<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0358EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NoriegaProfile     05-26 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega Profile,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Is A Shrewd Man Toughened By Poverty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pamana-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To his followers, Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega is a symbol of Panamanian nationalism _ a brave David
standing firm against the imperialist Goliath of Washington.
   Detractors see Panama's military leader as an unscrupulous
despot who threatens to drag the country down with him.
   The general is a shrewd, tough child of poverty, schooled in
intrigue.
   As far as the White House is concerned, Noriega is criminal, a
man who enriched himself by selling his country to Colombian drug
traffickers.
   On Wednesday, Secretary of State George P. Shultz announced that
talks with Noriega's people on the general's exit from power had
broken down.
   Noriega managed to become head of the Defense Forces _ chief of
Panama's military and police _ through his loyalty to his
predecessor and mentor, Gen. Omar Torrijos.
   Noriega, whose official biography says he is 50, has little
faith in the ability of civilians to rule.
   ``Our young officers are much better prepared to govern when
Panama takes over the (Panama) Canal operations in the year 2000,''
he once said in an interview.
   The handsome, charismatic Torrijos changed the Defense Forces
from an organization led by the social elite into a tightly
disciplined force of 15,000 with absolute police, military and
political power.
   He opened the upper ranks to the lower economic classes and
created a base of power from a new generation of officers. Noriega,
a poor boy who went to military school in Peru on a scholarship,
was among them.
   Less than a year after taking power in a coup in 1968, Torrijos
made Noriega, an obscure provincial lieutenant with only four years
of military service, his chief of intelligence.
   Noriega quickly began collecting dossiers on everyone who
counted in Panama, friends and enemies alike. He developed close
ties with U.S. intelligence agencies interested in any potential
threat to the security of the Panama Canal, a vital shipping link
between the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
   Torrijos also gave Noriega jurisdiction over customs and
immigration, long a source of funds for the military.
   After Torrijos died in an unexplained plane crash in 1981, it
took Noriega about two years to shoulder his way to the top
command. Once there, Noriega boldly exercised his power and
tolerated little opposition.
   He closed the private news media for months at a time for
alleged offenses ranging from personal insults to incitment to
disobedience. Unhappy with the outcome of the first popular
election in 16 years, Noriega installed his own president in 1984.
   Noriega, a short, jowly, pockmarked man his detractors call
``pineapple face,'' never possessed the charisma of his populist
mentor, but he was backed by the Democratic Republican Party, which
Torrijos founded.
   As demands for Noriega's ouster have grown during the past year,
the party vowed to stick by him ``to the end'' and portrayed him as
the defender of Panamanian ``sovereignty and dignity'' in the face
of U.S. aggression.
   Noriega has worked hard to develop the image of a man of the
people. His private life is that of a rich man, but publicly he has
stressed his humble origins and spent weekends courting the
residents of rural towns and villages.
   With the deepening of his political crisis, Noriega has tried to
use his popular image to build support in this nation of 2.2
million people, many of them black and mulatto.
   ``The humble, the poor, the blacks, they are the utmost
authority of this people,'' he said in one speech.
   His official salary is $60,000 a year but he is said to have his
finger in a wide range of enterprises, among them duty-free liquor
stores, maritime services, banks, gambling casinos, newspapers, a
television station and 12 radio stations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ForeignAid     05-26 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Foreign Aid,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Aid Bill Denies Money To Drug-Trafficking Nations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has sent to the Senate a $14.3
billion foreign aid bill that includes a ban on aid to any foreign
government or military force involved in drug trafficking, bribery,
tax evasion, graft or price fixing.
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., offered the amendment banning aid to
those nations involved in drugs or other crimes after Rep. Robert
Walker, R-Pa., offered one limited to drugs.
   ``If we're against the baddies of this world, we might as well
be against them all,'' Obey said.
   Obey's amendment was approved on a voice vote.
   The foreign aid bill, passed by the House on a 328-90 vote, was
the first separate foreign aid package the the House has approved
since 1981. Lawmakers generally are reluctant to support spending
overseas when domestic needs go unfulfilled, and in recent years,
the legislation has been buried in large, catchall spending bills.
   But last fall's deficit reduction agreement set the overall
foreign aid spending level for fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1. A
bipartisan compromise, with administration support, was reached in
the House Appropriations Committee on how to divide up that pie.
   About $5.8 billion of the total would be earmarked for military
aid, $3.3 billion in economic grants, and most of the remainder for
the United Nations and international organizations and financial
institutions.
   Overall, the bill would continue current programs and authorize
about 2 percent more spending than last year, reversing the trend
of the past few years to cut foreign aid.
   Israel and Egypt would receive about a third of the money in the
bill. Israel again would receive more than any other country, $1.8
billion in military aid and $1.2 billion in economic assistance.
Egypt would get $1.3 billion in military assistance and $815
million in economic aid.
   Pakistan would receive $220 million in economic aid and $240
million dollars in forgiven loans for purchase of military goods.
   The Philippines would receive about $250 million, half in
military assistance. About $700 million in economic assistance
would go to African countries.
   In Central America, Honduras would get $85 million in economic
aid, Costa Rica $90 million, El Salvador $185 million and Guatemala
$80 million. Military aid for those and other countries was not
earmarked, but would come out of separate military aid and credit
accounts. Aid to the Contra rebels in Nicaragua was not part of the
legislation.
   About 100 countries receive U.S. aid directly.
   Besides Obey's amendment, another voice vote removed the
earmarking of money for specific countries cooperating with U.S.
drug eradication efforts, allowing the individual totals to be set
later based on the performance of the countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
