<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-Chronology     05-26 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Chronology,0772</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chronology of Major Events In Panamanian Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of events in the Panamanian crisis:
   FEB. 25 _ Panama's president, Eric Arturo Delvalle, announces he
is dismissing Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, who faces U.S. drug
charges, as defense chief and replacing him with Col. Marcos
Justines, chief of staff. Justines refuses the job.
   FEB. 26 _ Noriega-dominated National Assembly votes to oust
Delvalle. Education Minister Manuel Solis Palma is named new head
of state. Noriega opponents call for general strike in protest.
   MARCH 1 _ General strike gains support. Locally owned banks
close. International banks limit withdrawals.
   MARCH 3 _ Organizers end general strike as support fades. U.S.
federal courts block withdrawal of Panama funds from U.S. banks.
   MARCH 4 _ National Bank of Panama says it cannot meet banks'
cash demands. International banks fearing a run on deposits close
their doors. Local banks remain closed.
   MARCH 11 _ President Reagan imposes economic sanctions,
including eliminating trade preferences for Panama and withholding
Panama Canal fees from the Noriega government by placing them in
escrow. Noriega government meets army payroll.
   MARCH 14 _ Public employees stage work stoppages and riot when
government is unable to pay wages. Riot police use tear gas and
truncheons to disperse hundreds blocking traffic. United States
sends 100 additional military personnel to beef up security around
canal.
   MARCH 16 _ Noriega survives abortive coup attempt by dissident
officers of Defense Forces. Violent demonstrations occur and
workers strike at state-run electric, water and telephone
companies, ports in Panama City and Colon and government ministries.
   MARCH 17 _ Government declares a ``state of urgency'' and
soldiers patrol capital.
   MARCH 18 _ Noriega meets with U.S. State Department officials
who offer freedom from extradition on drug charges if he seeks
asylum in third country. Noriega reportedly says he wants to remain
in Panama and take part in formation of transitional government.
   MARCH 20 _ Secretary of State George P. Shultz says indictments
against Noriega will not be dropped and Noriega cannot have say
about government after his departure.
   MARCH 21 _ Armed soldiers patrol Panama City as general strike
paralyzes nation.
   MARCH 30 _ Nation's three biggest supermarket chains open,
signaling a major rupture in strike.
   APRIL 8 _ President Reagan bans payments, direct or indirect,
from American citizens or companies to Panama's government,
including bills, fees or fines.
   APRIL 16 _ Hundreds of protesters clash with riot police in
anti-Noriega demonstration.
   APRIL 18 _ Some banks open to accept deposits only.
   APRIL 20 _ Government lifts state of emergency. U.S. officials
report for second time in a week unidentified intruders at American
military installations, including one instance of a gunfight.
   APRIL 25 _ Power cut off at U.S. Embassy annex and homes of 45
embassy workers for non-payment of bills.
   APRIL 30 _ Washington relaxes its order prohibiting payments by
Americans to Panama's government.
   MAY 4 _ Noriega attends graduation ceremony of hundreds of
civilian volunteers who have received military training against
what the government says is an imminent U.S. invasion.
   MAY 9 _ Banks open to let customers make limited cash
withdrawals.
   MAY 11 _ Reagan administration sources say Washington has
offered to drop drug charges against Noriega if he steps down and
leaves country.
   MAY 12 _ Noriega says no deal with U.S. authorities as long as
American ``aggression'' against Panama continues.
   MAY 13 _ Attorney General Edwin Meese III meets President
Reagan, argues against dismissing drug indictments. Noriega says
talks have collapsed.
   MAY 20 _ U.S. and Panamanian negotiators tentatively agree on a
deal that calls for Noriega to leave Panama for nine months
starting in August and for the United States to drop drug smuggling
indictments against him. But Noriega says he wants recognition of
his president and a reduction of U.S. forces in Panama before he
agrees to end his standoff with Washington.
   MAY 21 _ President Reagan meets with top advisers to discuss
policy on Panama.
   MAY 22 _ The United States has put a deal ``on the table,'' but
Reagan has not yet approved the plan, national security adviser
Colin Powell says.
   MAY 23 _ President Reagan's chief emissary to Panama returns
there seeking a deal, and the administration says it hopes to break
the long stalemate before the Moscow summit begins.
   MAY 25 _ Shultz announces negotiations to remove Noriega from
power have failed and no further talks are planned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
