<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NoLifeguards     05-26 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-No Lifeguards,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town With Traditional Claims on Lifeguards Can't Afford Them This
Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HULL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Budget problems will force beachgoers to swim
at their own risk this summer in this town, which has its own
lifesaving museum.
   ``It's not funded,'' Selectman Claudette Fitzsimmons said of the
lifeguard allotment. ``It's not going to be funded.''
   The town 10 miles southeast of Boston has allocated less than
$24,000 to pay eight full-time and four part-time summer police
officers, about equal to the payroll for 10 lifeguards and a
supervisor.
   When the budget was being considered, ``it came down to a
judgment call whether it was seasonal lifeguards or seasonal police
officers,'' said Exeuctive Administrator Christopher J. McCabe.
   So, four beaches normally supervised by Hull lifeguards will not
be staffed this year.
   Police Chief Donald F. Brooker contended that summer police are
badly needed to deal with overflows on hot days. Hull's population
of 10,000 swells to 100,000 on the hottest days.
   Hull is in the middle of a prolonged fiscal crisis. A referendum
is scheduled for June 27 to seek approval for an additional $1.5
million in taxes on top of the already approved $15 million
operating budget. None of the additional money is slated for
lifeguards.
   Local hero Joshua James's rescue of shipwreck victims more than
100 years ago gave rise to Hull's claim to lifesaving fame.
   Judith Wiers, director of the Hull Lifesaving Museum, said it's
ironic that a town with Hull's history would have to cut its
lifeguards.
   ``We have a really strong fire department that wears a badge of
Joshua James on their sleeves; some are descendants of the original
lifesavers,'' she said. ``There's a commitment to lives here.''
</TEXT>
