<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Conservatives     05-26 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Conservatives,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney General Makes His Case With Conservatives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III is waging an
aggressive campaign to offset the political damage his legal
troubles have caused the Republican Party, says a congressman.
   In two meetings Wednesday which he initiated, Meese made clear
he has no intention of resigning and intends to advance the
conservative agenda in the waning months of the Reagan
administration, said participants in the discussions.
   He said the Justice Department will aggressively prosecute child
pornography cases, work to break a logjam on judicial nominations
and help lead the administration's attack on drugs.
   Meese offered an 18-page rebuttal to criticism of his assistance
to scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. and told another group of
conservatives, the Free Congress Research and Education Foundation,
his conduct has been entirely proper.
   At a meeting with 16 conservative congressmen, ``a couple of
members'' said the year-old criminal investigation of Meese is
resulting in ``political damage being done,'' said Robert Walker,
R-Pa., head of a group of conservative House members called the
Conservative Opportunity Society. Walker said the context of
``political damage'' was to the Republican Party and the
presidential campaign of Vice President George Bush, the likely GOP
nominee.
   Walker said Meese was told that if he is going to take an
aggressive stance in response to criticism, it ``is going to have
to be a very good offense.''
   Meese ``acknowledged he would have to take that kind of
(aggressive) position to stem the political damage,'' said Walker.
``He felt he had a duty in terms of himself and the law and
politics to clear the air.
   ``He made it quite clear that he has no intention of
resigning,'' said Walker.
   Meese also met at his own urging with senior editors of The
Washington Times, a conservative newspaper that recently called on
the attorney general to resign.
   In a report on the interview today, Meese said he ``recently''
discussed his legal problems with Bush.
   ``I'm not going to do anything to hurt the vice president,'' he
said, adding that the only negative impact on Bush's presidential
campaign is that ``a lot of people ask him questions about this,
which takes up time to answer which ought to be reserved for
answers on the issues.''
   Meese said he stays ``in pretty close touch'' with the people
who advise President Reagan on public opinion polls and would
``take into account'' poll data ``on whether I am damaging the
president.''
   Meese told the congressmen a report in the next few weeks by an
independent counsel who has been investigating Meese since May 11,
1987, ``will clear him completely,'' said Rep. Cass Ballenger,
R-N.C., who attended the meeting. The report is expected to raise
questions about Meese's ethical behavior, but participants said
that issue didn't come up in the discussion.
</TEXT>
