<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0444EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     05-26 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Criticizes U.S. Policy In Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson took Michael Dukakis to task
over budget matters and South Africa, but he emerged from a meeting
with his Democratic presidential rival saying that the two are
``keenly aware of our joint responsibility to our party.''
   The two aired a few disagreements during a debate Wednesday
night, but spent far more time talking about matters they agreed on.
   Jackson was campaigning in California today. In recent days, he
has been stumping hard in the state, which holds its primary June 7.
   Jackson also had stops planned later today in New Mexico, which
holds its primary the same day as California's.
   During the one-hour debate in San Francisco, Jackson pressed
Dukakis for details about his budget plan. In response, Dukakis
said trying to formulate a detailed budget plan so far in advance
would be ``a serious mistake.''
   Jackson kept pressing him, however, saying that ``the governor
is laying out a budget of promises but not a budget of numbers.''
   When Jackson asked Dukakis if he would use military force
against South Africa, the Massachusetts governor replied that he
would press for more effective sanctions.
   Dukakis later added, ``Yes, one aspect of a tough anti-terrorist
policy is the use of military force against terrorist base camps.
But there are many ways to attack terrorism.''
   But Jackson reserved his toughest comments for criticism of the
Reagan administration's dealings with Panamanian leader Manuel
Antonio Noriega. The debate came hours after Secretary of State
George P. Shultz announced that talks aimed at getting Noriega to
step down had collapsed.
   Jackson mocked the administration's efforts to negotiate with
the military leader.
   ``All we really know is, there was this courtship of Noriega by
the administration. ... There was marriage to Noriega, putting him
on the payroll ... There was a divorce. And then there was the
bargain to patch up the marriage,'' Jackson said. ``Now we're being
discredited in a failed policy.''
   Earlier Wednesday, he made a speech criticizing administration
policy in Central America.
   ``The $10 billion spent chasing 3 million Sandinistas ... that
money should have been spent chasing poverty, illiteracy and
disease and building houses ... in Central America,'' Jackson said.
``It was immoral and illegal and a misappropriation of funds.''
   The Democratic contender helped load food and medical supplies
onto a truck bound for Central America.
   After the debate, Jackson met privately with Dukakis, and spoke
of the need to ``keep expanding our coalition.'' He also joked they
had talked about ``trying to balance my ticket with a
conservative.''
   Jackson said the two also discussed party unity.
   ``We are keenly aware of our joint responsibility to keep
expanding our party ... (and build) a strong coalition.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
