<DOCNO> AP880526-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0450EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Security     05-26 0929</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Security,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police State Ensures Tight Security During Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan-Summit Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few years ago, an oft-told story goes, a city
traffic cop had somehow obtained a hand-held radar gun and decided
to test it by clocking the speeding motorcade of then-Soviet leader
Leonid I. Brezhnev.
   As the Communist Party chief's shiny black ZIL limousine, two
others bearing bodyguards and a pair of Volga sedans flashed onto
the horizon of Kutuzovsky Prospekt, the officer aimed the detector
at the fast-approaching motorcade.
   The radar gun broke as it crashed to the ground, dropped by the
policeman who had been shot between the eyes by sharp-shooting
secret police agents who guard the Soviet leader.
   The story cannot be verified and may well be apochryphal, as
radar traps are still rare in the Soviet capital. But the armed
guards who ride in the leader's motorcade, with their gun barrels
poised low in the open car windows, are reputed to be expert
riflemen.
   And the tale of the hapless policeman surfaces whenever talk
turns to security around the Kremlin leader.
   Protection of the current ruler or visiting dignitaries is more
effectively ensured in a police state, where the untold legions of
secret agents keep a close eye on known troublemakers and are less
encumbered than their Western counterparts by rules protecting
citizens' civil rights.
   The risk of a terrorist strike against Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev or President Reagan during their May 29-June 2 meetings
here is probably lower than in just about any other country of the
world. But the measures taken to protect them will be no less
visible than in the most dangerous spots on the globe.
   Soviet founder Vladimir I. Lenin was wounded in a 1918
assassination attempt, inspiring development of a security force
around the leader that strengthened during the nearly three decades
that dictator Jos ef V. Stalin was in power.
   No other attempts on the life of the leader have been
documented, although there have been rumors about several,
including against Gorbachev.
   Gun ownership has been forbidden here since the 1917 Bolshevik
Revolution that brought the Soviets to power, and illegal
possession of firearms carries a five-year prison term. Soviets are
even prohibited from carrying hunting knives without special
permits attesting that the potential weapons are part of a national
costume or for actual use while hunting.
   Secrecy surrounds most of the movements of the Soviet leader and
his guests, with exact departure and arrival times for trips
outside the capital kept secret from all but the uppermost echelon
of power. When the official Tass news agency announces that
Gorbachev will visit a Western nation, it usually specifies only in
which half of the month the trip will take place.
   The first indication that the Soviet leader has left the capital
for his summer vacation is often the arrival of paving crews on
Kutuzovsky Prospekt, the route regularly traveled by the leader to
and from the Kremlin.
   Traffic in both directions of Kutuzovsky is forced to the outer
lanes when top officials or state guests travel the broad
thoroughfare, while the privileged center lane is left clear for
the VIPs. As the leader approaches, traffic lights along the route
are switched to green by policemen who man the controls in
miniature, glass-enclosed control towers overlooking the central
streets.
   Most of the meetings between Reagan and Gorbachev will take
place within the heavily fortified Kremlin. Vehicles can enter only
through two archways, with dozens of armed KGB guards in sight and
others likely at the ready behind the historic fortress' crenelated
russet walls.
   If Reagan chooses to make an impromptu stop among the crowds of
Soviets lined up along the streets to greet him, as Gorbachev did
during his Washington stay, the president's own Secret Service
agents will keep a wary eye on the flock of flag-waving welcomers.
   One of Reagan's Secret Service agents was asked during the
Washington summit whether the superpowers' two squads of bodyguards
are able to work well together.
   He replied that their work styles were so similar, ``It's like
they're working out of our manual.''
   Gorbachev's bodyguards often resemble Reagan's in appearance as
well as demeanor. The tall, well-dressed men, with their trim
haircuts and tiny earphones connected to two-way radios, are
quickly identifiable during the leader's televised talks with
Soviet citizens. They encircle Gorbachev and face away from him,
silently scanning the crowd for suspicious movement.
   Security has always been tight around the Soviet leader, but the
net has pulled in even closer over the past two years.
   Rumors of an assassination attempt spread through the capital
after Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, visited the southern Russian
city of Krasnodar in September 1986. Both appeared on television a
few days after their return looking tan and fit, but the number of
bodyguards more than doubled at that time, and screenings of
reporters and onlookers at public events intensified.
   Metal detectors are rarely used in the Soviet Union but have
been appearing recently as security for Gorbachev appearances. And
uniformed police at the entrances to virtually all public buildings
closely check visitors' credentials and search purses and camera
bags before permitting entry.
   When reporters are allowed into the Kremlin for photo sessions
or political meetings, they must clear a dozen security checkpoints
before entering the room in which the session is to take place.
   During Reagan's visit to Moscow, the routine will likely
intensify as the Soviet hosts seek to preserve their image as a
country rarely touched by terrorism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AirplaneStolen Bjt   05-26 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airplane Stolen, Bjt,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unlicensed Pilot Takes Stolen Jet On Joyride, Kills Self</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDY SHORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flight mechanic who stole a private jet and
killed himself after a 1,600-mile joyride was ``upbeat'' until the
moment his radio went silent, says the pilot who talked him through
a safe landing.
   ``I was shocked,'' said Bob Cunningham, who helped his former
co-worker, Mike Christiansen, 24, land the plane at Stapleton
International Airport on Wednesday. ``The thing that stays in my
mind is that he did take his life after all that.''
   Within minutes of the relatively routine landing, police, FBI
agents and emergency crew members who approached the twin-engine
Learjet 36a found Christiansen dead at the controls of a gunshot
wound.
   ``As the crash crew and law enforcement personnel approached, he
was ordered to lock his brakes,'' said Stapleton spokesman Richard
Boulware. ``They heard a noise and when they looked in the cockpit,
they found him dead. Things happened really fast.''
   The FBI and the Federal Aviation Administration have begun
investigations to find out why Christiansen stole the 10-seat jet
from Patrick Henry International Airport in Newport News, Va., why
he killed himself, and where he obtained the gun.
   ``The indication was that he just wanted to fly around for
awhile,'' Boulware said.
   Christiansen, who did not have pilot's license, worked as a
flight mechanic at the Virginia airport for the Atlanta-based
Flight International, which owned the plane he stole, officials
said. The company operates the world's largest fleet of Learjets.
   Pete Daikos, spokesman for Patrick Henry airport, said
Christiansen took off early Wednesday, clipping a security guard's
van on a runway and shearing off part of a wingtip fuel tank. The
guard escaped injury.
   Cunningham, 42, who worked with Christiansen at International
Jet Aviation Services in Denver last year, said he was preparing
for a flight from Denver to his hometown of Albuquerque, N.M., when
air traffic control officials asked for his help in landing the jet.
   ``He was upbeat on the radio, and responded readily. I asked him
several times how he was doing, and he came back and said he was
doing fine,'' said Cunningham. At one point, he asked Christiansen
how he was and Christiansen replied, ``Feeling great.''
   After Christiansen landed, Cunningham asked, ``Are you OK, Mike?
Mike, are you OK? Have you got that thing shut down yet?'' There
was no reply, and, Boulware said, Christiansen was found dead
moments later.
   Christiansen apparently grew up in Colorado and attended
Colorado Aerotech in Broomfield last year. He was certified by the
FAA to work on aircraft in June.
   International Jet officials said he worked as ``aircraft cleaner
and helper'' for about 10 months, resigning in August to take a job
with Continental Airlines. In March, he moved to Virginia.
   Cunningham recalled Christiansen as a ``very personable'' man,
who sometimes acted as his chauffeur during his stops at Stapleton.
   ``I believe he was in school at the time, training to be a
flight mechanic and that was on his mind, of course,'' Cunningham
said. ``He did the job well, to my knowledge.''
   Cunningham said he did not know why Christiansen stole the
plane. ``We didn't have time to go into too much background,'' he
said. ``We wanted to get the plane down safely.''
   Attempts to reach Christiansen's family members by telephone at
the Lakewood address Christiansen gave the FAA were unsuccessful.
The Associated Press made 30 calls to the apartment complex where
he lived in Virginia and found only one resident at home. She said
she never had heard of him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
