<DOCNO> AP880526-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0500EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-BeautyPageant     05-26 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Beauty Pageant,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canton Bucks Trend, Says Show Will Go On</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The freewheeling Chinese city of Canton is
bucking a national trend of canceling beauty pageants by going
ahead this week with a contest to select top models, a pro-Beijing
newspaper reported today.
   About 5,000 people braved the rain and packed a city sports
stadium Wednesday night to watch judges whittle a field of 30 men
and women to a final 15 who will compete for the titles of ``Miss
Canton'' and ``Mr. Canton'' on Saturday, the Chinese-language Wen
Wei Po said.
   Shanghai and Beijing are among the Chinese cities to cancel
planned beauty contests. Typically, local leaders have said
``conditions are not ripe'' for pageants in a country with a low
standard of living.
   Authorities in Canton, the capital of Guangdong province just 90
miles from the British colony of Hong Kong, decided to allow the
completion of the ``Canton Television Model Competition'' because
it already is in its final phase.
   But the report said local media were instructed to play down the
event and the organizing television station scrapped plans to
televise the contest live. Provincial and city officials invited to
the competition on Wednesday night also did not show up, the
newspaper said.
   The report quoted members of the audience telling reporters that
Cantonese people are able to accept beauty pageants because their
area opened up to the outside world earlier than the rest of China.
   The region is one of the country's most prosperous and has been
relatively successful in attracting foreign investment.
</TEXT>
