<DOCNO> AP880526-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0348EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-DandelionCanner Bjt   05-26 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dandelion Canner, Bjt,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dandelions, Fiddleheads Mean Business For Maine Canner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in last graf.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AU1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GLENN ADAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILTON, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Let the rest of the country attack the
stubborn weed with trowels and poisons. Adrian R. Wells prefers to
grow his dandelions by the acre, then put them in cans so people
can eat them.
   Wells, who owns a canning company that has been in the family
for four generations, plans to ship 1,000 cases of dandelion greens
this year from his little cannery in the western Maine foothills.
   Wells, who hates to see a thriving dandelion go to waste, talks
about the plant with fondness, respect and knowledge. The roots, he
explains, can be made into herbal tea; the bright, yellow blossoms
can be pickled or made into wine and jelly; the leaves are
excellent cooked or served fresh in salads.
   ``And the stem, you use that to siphon gas out of someone's
car,'' Wells deadpans. He admits he has grown weary of offers of
dandelions from homeowners plagued by the hearty, prolific weeds.
   Wells sees dandelions' tendency to grow back after being
snipped, a trait that frustrates gardeners, as another plus. Five
days after the last batch of foot-high dandelions was harvested,
new shoots appeared.
   Wells' W.S. Wells and Son cannery was founded 102 years ago by
his grandfather, Walter Scott Wells. The barn-size factory also
packages beans and cans beet greens and a vegetative delicacy known
as fiddleheads.
   Fiddleheads, named for their deep-green stems that are
gracefully curled a couple of inches from the ground before they
sprout into ostrich ferns in swampy, northern woodlands in late
spring, make up the bulk of the products bearing Wells' Belle of
Maine label. His only competition comes from canners in Canada,
where fiddleheads also are popular.
   While fiddleheads are best known to New Englanders, who gather
them with ritualistic zeal in late spring, they have a few
scattered devotees as far away as California. Wells, 52, also ships
fiddleheads to fashionable restaurants in New York and
Philadelphia, ``and I do a whale of a business in Boston.''
   The Four Seasons restaurant in New York serves 300 pounds of
fresh fiddleheads a week in the spring, and features a soft shell
crab and fiddlehead combination as one of its ``signature dishes,''
said purchaser Bob Menge.
   ``It's a unique type of vegetable _ I don't even know if you
call it a vegetable,'' said Menge. ``It's got a wonderful flavor to
me, sort of between a string bean and asparagus.''
   Wells loves to eat fiddleheads, even though he can't quite pin
down what gives them appeal.
   ``There isn't that much flavor to a fiddlehead,'' said Wells,
who likes them salted and slathered with butter or served in one of
his wife's fiddlehead quiches. ``To me, it tastes like a
fiddlehead.''
   Wells' company also pickles fiddleheads and dandelions.
   The harvest is now in full swing. While Wells cultivates and
harvests the monstrous dandelions that grow in neat rows on his
land, he hires up to 200 pickers, from children to a woman in her
70s, to gather the young ferns from secret patches all over Maine,
and in parts of Vermont and New York.
   Wells compared fiddlehead pickers to sport fishermen. ``When
they find a good spot, they keep it a secret.''
   This season, Wells expects to can at least 1,200 cases plus ship
15 tons of fresh fiddleheads to market. As the canning season
peaked in late May, some cannery workers had been on the job for
nearly 20 straight days.
   Pat Stanley, who trims the stems and cleans a brown, flaky skin
from fiddleheads before they are washed, blanched and canned, said
she has been working ``pretty near seven days a week.''
   Adrian R. Wells Jr., the 22-year-old manager of the plant and
the fourth generation of the family of canners, said he had just
finished working 22 straight 14-hour days when his wife gave birth
to their first son.
   ``I'm tired as hell,'' he said as he loaded armfuls of
fiddleheads into a bin for cleaning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
