<1ST_LINE>r i PM-OAU     05-26 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OAU,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>African States Declare Determination To Rule Their Destinies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Organization of African Unity
marked its silver jubilee with a declaration promising more help
for the military overthrow of South Africa and the independence
struggle in Namibia.
   The declaration, released Wednesday, said the OAU would achieve
such goals through a renewed commitment to ``unity, solidarity,
liberation and development'' although it offered no new plans of
action.
   Earlier Wednesday, President Kenneth Kaunda of Zambia, the
outgoing OAU chairman, celebrated the organization's 25th
anniversary with a chorus of ``Happy Birthday, OAU,'' as he cut a
cake.
   African leaders planted trees and unveiled a marble plaque with
gold engraving of the organization's anniversay theme: Unity,
Solidarity, Liberation, Development.
   Groups from Sudan, Zambia, Guinea and Algeria danced and sang.
   Security was light for the more than 30 heads of government and
state gathered at the 50-member body's headquarters in the capital
of Addis Ababa. The celebration will be followed by a three-day
summit beginning today.
   Many of the 40 points in the 11-page declaration repeated the
original objectives of the OAU's founding fathers, voiced in Addis
Ababa 25 years ago.
   The declaration highlighted a renewed commitment to bring about
the early independence of Namibia, also known as South-West Africa,
and to eradicate South Africa's policy of race segregation, called
apartheid.
   Namibia is under South Africa's control.
   The declaration reaffirmed ``the primacy of the armed struggle
and resolve to increase financial, material and military assistance
to the national liberation movemments.''
   However, money might be a problem. Thirty-four of the
organization's members owe the OAU's liberation fund a total of $12
million.
   The declaration repeated a commitment to the imposition of
comprehensive, mandatory sanctions against South Africa's white-led
government and urged international support for such sanctions.
   It did not say, however, how it would impose the sanctions on
many of its members who do about $1 billion of trade each year with
the apartheid state.
   The declaration noted with grave concern continued acts of
aggression by South Africa against its neighbors and reaffirmed the
OAU's commitment to provide financial and material help to
strengthen their defenses.
   The declaration also expressed support for recent Angolan peace
talks involving top officials of Cuba, South Africa and Angola.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
