<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0485 05-26 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economic Distress And Strikes Improve Chances For Dialogue In
Poland</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to RESTORE dropped word `pact.' Picks up 6th
graf pvs, `The idea ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Midway through the 15-day strike wave that
ended this month, tentative agreement was at hand for the communist
leadership's architect of economic reform to meet with Solidarity
chief Lech Walesa.
   But the promise of the first direct contact in six years between
prominent opposition leaders and authorities went unfulfilled when
Walesa joined a strike at the Lenin shipyard in Gdansk.
   Now, there are signs such talks may actually be in the offing.
   The ``thread of dialogue'' may actually have a better chance
because of the strikes, Ryszard Wojna, a leading communist deputy
in Parliament, was quoted as saying in this week's issue of the
official newspaper Odrodzenie (Rebirth).
   Senior communist leaders are encouraging talk of an
``anti-crisis pact'' by which the opposing camps would agree on and
unite behind a program to breathe life into a lethargic economy.
   The idea was raised by historian Bronislaw Geremek, a close
adviser to Walesa, in an interview published in February by the
official press. Publication of an interview with such a prominent
opposition figure was in itself an unusual event.
   Spurring the renewed search for dialogue is the sense that the
impasse that has prevailed since a 1981 military crackdown on the
Solidarity independent labor federation cannot continue forever.
   Poland's economic crisis is especially acute and the
government's attempt to institute reforms has won scant public
support.
   Authorities have raised prices 45 percent this year and say they
plan to reduce central management of the economy and encourage more
free enterprise. But, according to one recent public opinion poll,
just 7 percent of the public believes the program will succeed.
   A pact on reform with the opposition, which demands a voice in
shaping it, could improve its chances and encourage the assistance
of Western lenders.
   Although it is not clear who would speak to whom, the idea for
an ``anti-crisis pact'' appears to be gaining advocates within
official circles. And Walesa said on Tuesday that the idea is being
considered by Solidarity.
   Earlier this month, Politburo member Alfred Miodowicz, leader of
the official unions created after Solidarity was outlawed in 1982,
said he would not rule out meeting Walesa if it would improve the
public mood.
   Walesa last met with a senior government official during his
post-martial law internment in March 1982.
   Wojna said in the Odrodzenie interview that he envisioned that
Deputy Prime Minister Zdzislaw Sadowski, the government's architect
of reform, and a team of party economic experts would meet with a
dozen or so opposition representatives.
   Wojna said such a meeting could be successful if ``all
propaganda, demagogy and mutual prejudices'' were left in the
cloakroom.
   He said the canceled meeting of Sadowski and Walesa had
represented a ``thin thread (of dialogue), but still it indicated
the direction of thinking.''
   Sadowski's spokesman, Jerzy Malkowski, said on Wednesday that
Sadowski's attitude toward such a meeting is ``still the same _
open.''
   And chief government spokesman Jerzy Urban told his weekly news
conference on Tuesday that ``one certainly can expect further
active striving for talks and cooperation'' with the opposition.
   Asked specifically about a meeting between Sadowski and Walesa,
he said it was not possible at present but, ``The future will show
how it will go.''
   From his home in Gdansk, Walesa responded: ``I have said that
they would come to us on their knees. And they will, sooner or
later. My problem now is whether I should wait until they do or
not.''
   Reinstatement of independent Solidarity locals was a key demand
by participants in most of the five major strikes that began April
25 and ended May 10. It was championed with the greatest vigor by
strikers at the Gdansk shipyard, who ended their stoppage
peacefully but without resolution, and the Lenin steelworks outside
Krakow, whose strike security forces crushed.
   Poland is afflicted with a $39 billion foreign debt, climbing
inflation, low wages and lack of capital to overhaul its outmoded
industrial plant.
   The government's economic reform progam aims to decrease
bureaucracy, encourage private and managerial enterprise, reduce
central planning and make the economy more market-oriented. But
implementation has been slow.
   Solidarity supports the program's direction, but says it is
doomed to fail unless the government enters a dialogue with
opposition groups.
   Three times in postwar Poland, price increases have led to labor
unrest that has toppled governments.
</TEXT>
