<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Hamilton     05-26 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Hamilton,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hamish Hamilton, A Leading British Publisher, Dies At Age 87</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American-born Hamish Hamilton, a leading British
publisher for 50 years, died in London after a long illness, his
family announced today. He was 87.
   Hamilton, who died Tuesday, founded the London publishing house
Hamish Hamilton Ltd. in 1931.
   He enjoyed the company of writers, ran his company on autocratic
lines, distrusted computers and sales directors, and always had to
see for himself.
   Hamilton was an intrepid flyer of small planes and, when he
published Jacques Cousteau's ``The Silent World'' in 1953, he
characteristically went diving with the undersea explorer.
   He once worked two weeks selling books in Harrods, the London
department store, and only admitted defeat when he failed to sell a
Hamilton book to a store detective.
   In 1926, after serving an apprenticeship at the London
publishers Jonathan Cape, Hamilton became London manager for the
American publishers Harper and Brothers.
   His first bestseller after founding Hamish Hamilton Ltd. with
his entire capital of $40,000 was John Gunther's ``Inside Europe.''
   Over the years, Hamilton published authors including Dean
Acheson, Luigi Barzini, Albert Camus, Truman Capote, Raymond
Chandler, John Kenneth Galbraith, John Hersey, Walter Lippmann, Ed
McBain, J.D. Salinger, Jean-Paul Sartre, A.J.P. Taylor, James
Thurber and Alexander Werth.
   He sold Hamish Hamilton Ltd. to Thomson Publications Ltd. in
1965, though continuing on as chairman until 1981. Four years
later, Thomson sold Hamish Hamilton Ltd. to the giant publishing
company Viking-Penguin.
   Hamilton was born in Indianapolis, Ind., of a Scottish father,
James Hamilton, and an American mother, Alice van Valkenburg, but
was brought up mainly by relations in Scotland.
   He was educated at Rugby, one of Britain's top private schools,
and at Cambridge University, where he studied modern languages and
became one of Britain's top oarsmen.
   Hamilton qualified as a lawyer and later became an honorary
attache at the British Embassy in Washington, which gave him a
lifelong interest in Anglo-American relations.
   When World War II broke out, he joined the Army and served in
France and the Netherlands before being transferred to the U.S.
division of the Ministry of Information.
   Hamilton is survived by his second wife, Countess Yvonne
Pallavicino of Rome, and their son Alastair, an author and
translator.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
