<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief 730   05-26 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief, 730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Safety Commission to Ban Most Lawn Darts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission has
voted to ban most lawn darts, saying the pointed metal toys present
a danger of death or serious injury.
   Lawn darts, which have long metal tips, have become popular as a
yard game. They are tossed through the air, with the player trying
to sticking the points into the ground in or near a target.
   Three children, aged 4, 7 and 13, have been killed in accidents
involving the darts in recent years, according to commission
records. In addition, an estimated 670 lawn-dart injuries are
treated annually at hospital emergency rooms.
   The ban, voted Wednesday, now goes back to the commission staff
to develop a formal rulemaking to enforce the ban and to solicit
comment from the public before being returned to the commissioners
for a vote on a final ban, likely in late summer or fall.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Federal Pollution-Fighters Find Bad Air in Their Own Offices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the nation's pollution-fighters at the
headquarters of the Environmental Protection Agency have been
gasping and wheezing from an air pollution problem apparently
caused by new carpeting.
   Sixty-five employees have sought medical attention and seven
can't enter the building at all because of their reactions when
they do, William Hirzy, president-elect of Local 2050 of the
National Federation of Federal Employees, said Wednesday.
   Hirzy said he was ``90 percent certain'' the reactions came from
exposure to phenylcyclohexene, a gas given off by the backing of
new rugs the agency has been installing in the building used by
5,100 employees.
   The agency has stopped putting in new carpets, but Charles
Grizzle, assistant administrator for administration, said
phenylcyclohexene had not been fixed definitely as the cause of the
problem and ``I don't see any reason to rip up the carpets until we
are sure.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Votes to Lift Curb on Interstate Ads for Gambling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill approved by the House would would allow
advertising across state lines of gambling activities, such as
casino gambling, church raffles and bingo games.
   The House voted Wednesday to remove a federal prohibition on
interstate advertising of gambling.
   Under current law, states can advertise state-conducted
lotteries only in adjacent states that also have lotteries. All
other advertising of games of chance is prohibited.
   The bill, approved by voice vote and sent to the Senate, would
still allow individual states to restrict such advertising.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Virginia Congressmen Join Fight Against Development at Civil War
Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While members of Congress signed on as
co-sponsors of a bill to protect the Manassas National Battlefield
in northern Virginia from commercial development, the Virginia
delegation had been quiet.
   On Wednesday, Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., changed that by
introducing a bill he says is better than anything else that has
been offered in the effort to stop developers from putting a
shopping mall next to the park.
   Rep. Stan Parris, another northern Virginia congressman,
immediately said he would be a co-sponsor.
   ``I think everyone should be pleased that a Virginian has
finally said no to the shopping mall,'' said Rep. Michael Andrews,
D-Texas.
   Andrews and Rep. Robert Mrazek, D-N.Y., and 166 co-sponsors have
a bill pending that calls for acquisition by the Interior
Department of about 600 acres next to the battlefield where the
Hazel-Peterson Co. wants to build the shopping center, homes and
offices.
   Wolf said his bill is better because it calls for ``legislative
taking'' of the land, a faster process than going through the
Interior Department.
