<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Government Opens Another Front in Oranges Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is trying on another front to
boost sales American oranges and orange juice in Japan.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter announced Wednesday
that he has accepted a Florida citrus industry petition for a
formal investigation of Japanese restrictions on orange and juice
imports as unfair trade practices.
   The restrictions include import quotas and a requirement that
imported juice be blended with home-grown juice.
   Yeutter's office already is pursuing the orange dispute at other
levels. After months of unsuccessful negotiations with the Japanese
government, it moved earlier this month to have the Japanese orange
import quotas _ along with those on beef imports _ declared illegal
under international trading rules by GATT, the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade.
