<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpaceBudget     05-26 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Budget,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Budget Cuts Could Kill Space Station, Says NASA Head</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0510 to fix category, priority codes.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proposed deep cuts in NASA's budget
could kill America's space station, reducing the nation to a
second- or third-rate space power, the space agency's head warns.
   ``Without the space station, the U.S. manned space flight
program would be dead-ended, and America's leadership in space
would be put on hold indefinitely,'' James C. Fletcher said
Wednesday as he spoke to a group of reporters attending briefings
on U.S. space goals.
   The Reagan administration has asked Congress to give NASA $11.5
billion in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, an increase of 27
percent over the current budget.
   However, key lawmakers have said the agency can expect no more
than $10.7 billion. A House budget resolution would slash that to
$10.2 billion.
   The administration has asked for $967 million to continue space
station development. Earlier cuts already have delayed the program
three years. Current plans call for putting people in the orbiting
laboratory in late 1995.
   Fletcher, speaking from Washington, said that if the budget were
reduced to $10.2 billion, ``NASA would have to recommend killing
the space station.''
   The result, he said, could be reduction of the United States
``to a second-rate or even a third-rate power in space.''
   Fletcher said the station is needed to support space research
and to prepare humans for deeper excursions into space, perhaps to
build a moon base or to mount an expedition to Mars.
   Asked how much money it would take to continue the space station
next year, the administrator replied, ``The House has reported out
$900 million. Unless we get close to that figure, I wonder if it
would be worth going ahead with the space station.''
   Fletcher said most members of Congress favor a strong space
program, ``but when it comes to balancing the space station with
their favorite programs in the present budget climate, it is a hard
choice to make.''
   He said cancellation of the space station would have a
``devastating'' effect on the space programs of the Europeans and
the Canadians, who have invested $1 billion, and are planning to
double that, to develop modules and other equipment for the U.S.
facility.
   Fletcher said a steep budget reduction would also lead to a drop
in the number of space shuttle flights after launches resume, now
scheduled for late August. NASA plans seven launches next year,
building up to 14 a year by 1994.
   He said the Soviets have been gathering valuable flight
experience over several years with their Salyut space station and
with the new Mir station.
   ``There is no doubt the Russians are far ahead of us in moving
out into space,'' Fletcher said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0603EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FallenWunderkind     05-26 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fallen Wunderkind,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Whiz Kid Hospitalized With Mother After Assets Seized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-year-old computer whiz and his
mother apparently tried to commit suicide after authorities closed
the budding millionaire's company and seized its assets, police say.
   Tex Zachary Hildreth and his 50-year-old mother, Rose, were in
serious condition today at Elliot Hospital, said nursing supervisor
Laurie King.
   Hildreth left the Braintree, Mass., area just before his
5-year-old computer services company, Massdata Corp., was closed by
authorities and its assets were seized Tuesday. He left behind
about 30 angry employees and irked investors.
   Hildreth was arrested as a fugitive here Tuesday after a Holiday
Inn employee called police to report a bloodied man wandering in
the lobby. Police found Hildreth's mother lying injured in the room
the two shared.
   Police Lt. William Bovaird said it appeared Hildreth may have
slashed his wrists. A bottle of non-prescription pills was found in
the hotel room, along with what appeared to be suicide notes,
Bovaird said.
   Both Hildreths were incoherent, the lieutenant said.
   Massdata was closed Monday when the Rockland Trust Co., which
was owed more than $400,000, tried to seize its assets, said Senior
Vice President John O'Connor.
   Norfolk County, Mass., authorities and state police secured
Massdata's offices Tuesday night.
   The county district attorney's office began investigating
Hildreth on Tuesday after receiving complaints from several people
who said they did business with him, said spokesman Mike McGorty.
   Police in the Boston suburb of Weymouth charged Hildreth with
larceny of more than $250 on the same day after receiving another
complaint, McGorty said. Hildreth collapsed in his office on his
24th birthday May 18, suffering what was described as an aneurysm,
a dangerous weakening of a blood vessel. His father died of an
aneurysm when Hildreth was 7.
   Employees became suspicious last Friday when Massdata's
president told them their paychecks were being withheld because
Hildreth had not signed them. McGorty said the investigation into
Hildreth's business dealings was expected to be lengthy.
   But there were signs of unusual behavior before this week. The
Boston Herald reported Wednesday that Hildreth often tried to trick
employees into believing that New York real estate tycoon Donald
Trump called to chat.
   Employees said Hildreth would disguise his voice and call
himself, pretending to be Trump, then would leave the office door
open as he conducted an imaginary conversation.
   Hildreth transformed himself from an overweight, unhappy
teen-ager into a budding millionaire just a few years out of high
school, according to a profile last month in The Boston Globe.
   After buying his first computer at age 16, he began writing
computer programs. The confidence he gained prompted him to lose
115 pounds in less than two years.
   With the help of a mentor in the Braintree area, Hildreth rented
office space at the age of 20 and went into business as a computer
consultant. He gradually built up his business, hiring young
computer experts from other companies.
   Hildreth rapidly acquired symbols of success: a $220,000
Weymouth condominium, a $32,000 BMW and a 50-inch, $4,000 color TV.
   His mother, who once lived with him in subsidized housing and
worked as a lunch matron at his school, was made clerk of the
company.
   The company had more than 300 clients, an employee told the
Herald.
   Massdata turned profitable in 1987 and predicted sales of about
$4 million this year, the Globe said.
   Last November, Hildreth, accompanied by a beautiful woman,
arrived in a limousine for the fifth reunion of his Braintree High
School class.
   ``This was my revenge for four years of hell,'' he said at the
time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
