<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Punjab     05-26 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two More Bodies Unearthed At Golden Temple</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more bodies were recovered from the
Golden Temple complex today and police said the victims had been
tortured to death by Sikh radicals, United News of India reported.
   Authorities said more than 20 other corpses could be buried
around the temple, Sikhism's holiest shrine.
   On Wednesday, two human skeletons, one a male and the other
female, were recovered by municipal workers from the complex.
   Amritsar Police Superintendent Baldev Singh said today's remains
were ``people tortured and then killed by Sikh terrorists'' and
said a search was under way for more.
   Sikh extremists waging a guerrilla war for an independent
homeland turned the Golden Temple into an armed camp earlier this
month. The radicals were forced out during a police siege of the
shrine.
   The siege, from May 9 to 18, resulted in the surrender of more
than 200 extremists and sympathizers. More than 46 people died in
the ordeal.
   There had been frequent reports that people were being detained
and tortured by militants inside the shrine. Several people were
reported missing by families after they went to the temple to pray.
   The bodies found today were buried near the dining hall that
stands to the east of the temple. On Wednesday, the bodies were
found to the west of the temple.
   Sikhs, whose religion was formed 500 years ago as an alternative
to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated against by
India's majority Hindus.
   More than 1,150 people have been killed by Sikh extremists in
Punjab state since the start of the year. In 1987, 1,030 people
were killed.
   Indian security forces raided the Golden Temple in 1984, killing
1,200 people, mostly Sikhs. Prime Minister Indira Gandhi ordered
the raid. Two of Mrs. Gandhi's Sikh guards assassinated her five
months later.
</TEXT>
