<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brite--WarofWorlds     05-26 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite--War of Worlds,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Examines Orson Welles' ``War of the Worlds'' Broadcast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America, which panicked nearly 50 years ago
when it heard Orson Welles' radio play describing a Martian
invasion, could go gaga again, says the Court of Historical Review.
   The mock court _ featuring a real judge, real attorneys and
bogus witnesses _ convened Wednesday to celebrate the 50th
anniversary year of Welles' ``War of the Worlds'' broadcast on
Halloween 1938.
   Municipal Judge George T. Choppelas said he was convinced by the
testimony of a man playing the late Welles, who sat in the witness
chair with his vest stuffed with a pillow.
   ``The broadcast was real and everything else is fiction,''
boomed the ersatz Welles, played by retired drama teacher E. Wyman
Spalding.
   ``Based on what we know, it could happen again,'' said Choppelas.
   The 1938 CBS radio version of H.G. Wells' science fiction
classic was heard by an estimated 6 million Americans, becoming a
landmark of sorts in broadcasting when it provoked mass panic among
listeners who mistook it for a news show.
   Published accounts of the broadcast estimated that nearly 2
million people believed that Martians had actually landed.
   Wednesday's session began with a reconstructed repeat of the
program on tape.
   ``Good heavens,'' gasped a fictitious newsman. ``Something's
wriggling out of the shadows! Ladies and gentlemen, it's
indescribable ...''
   The San Francisco mock court convenes periodically to explore
such weighty topics as whether chicken soup is really Jewish
penicillin.
</TEXT>
