<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Jane's     05-26 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Jane's,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jane's Says Soviet Navy, Scared Of Defections, Operates Close At
Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nato, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet navy operates close to home in part
because the Kremlin does not trust its sailors and fears defections
by naval personnel, according to the editor of the new ``Jane's
Fighting Ships.''
   Richard Sharpe also said the U.S. Navy is so much stronger than
Western Europe's forces that Washington is finding it harder and
harder to work with its allies at sea.
   The new edition of the prestigious reference book was released
Wednesday.
   Sharpe, a recently retired Royal Navy captain, recalled passing
a Soviet cruiser in the English Channel. He said that while almost
the entire crew of the British warship lined its decks, on the
Soviet vessel just one young sailor was visible above deck.
   ``I don't think the Politburo trusts its navy and that is one of
the reasons why we see so few ships of the Soviet fleet ranging the
waters of the world,'' Sharpe said.
   He also said the Soviet Union keeps its navy bottled up because
Moscow sees its fleet as fulfilling an essentially defensive role.
   Indeed, this hypothesis is now so widely accepted that the
latest U.S. naval policy envisages entering Soviet home waters
during a war, said Sharpe.
   But despite such a ``visibly wimpish Soviet policy at sea,'' the
Soviet fleet is capable of a ``swift breakout into the vulnerable
sea lanes of the Western world,'' he said.
   Pointing to the recent buildup of U.S. naval forces, Sharpe
called the U.S. Navy ``rejuvenated and formidable.''
   But he said such improvements have made coordination with
America's weaker allies more difficult.
   ``The United States is more and more operating on its own and is
going to find it harder and harder to ally with the NATO forces on
this side of the Atlantic,'' Sharpe told a news conference on
Tuesday.
   In times of trouble, Sharpe said, the U.S. Navy would probably
not wait to consult with NATO and ``subordinate itself to a
polyglot talking shop of the Brussels variety.'' Brussels is the
headquarters of the 16-nation North American Treaty Organization.
   Sharpe noted U.S. Navy commanders publicly deny a go-it-alone
policy. But he maintained this policy is what has developed because
of U.S. naval superiority and slow decision-making by NATO.
   Every navy now operates ``in the shadow'' of the huge fleets of
the superpowers, he said.
   But despite Soviet naval advances, including development of
quieter submarines, Sharpe said the U.S. Navy still has the edge
because of its better-trained personnel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
