<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Korea     05-26 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Attack U.S. Bank; Anti-American Protests Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students threw firebombs and rocks at
an American bank today, farmers opposing U.S. imports battled riot
police, and Prime Minister Lee Hyun-jai ordered a crackdown on
anti-American protests.
   Police said four people were arrested when 30 students dashed
out of sidestreets and hurled rocks and about 10 firebombs at a
branch in southern Seoul of the Koram Bank.
   The bank, a joint venture between the Bank of America and Korean
business groups, had not yet opened for business and had shutters
over its windows and entrance. It was not damaged.
   Shouting ``Go home Yankees'' and other slogans, the students
scattered leaflets calling for ``independent, democratic''
reunification with North Korea. It was the first attack on an
American business in a wave of violent anti-U.S. protests in Seoul
and other cities during the past week.
   Radical students blame the United States for the partition of
the Korean peninsula and accuse Washington of supporting military
rule in the south. They demand the withdrawal of the 42,000 U.S.
troops stationed in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   Last week protesters hurled rocks and firebombs at American
cultural centers in Seoul and the southern city of Kwangju and
threw homemade bombs at the U.S. Embassy in Seoul. Up to a dozen
police and students were hurt in the attacks, but no U.S. personnel
was injured.
   U.S. and Soviet troops split the Korean peninsula when the
Japanese occupation ended in 1945 at the end of World War II. The
two Koreas _ the pro-Western south and the communist north _ are
bitter opponents.
   Riot police fired tear gas to disperse 500 farmers trying to
march into the National Assembly building in Seoul today. The
farmers were protesting plans to increase imports of U.S.
agricultural products.
   In some rural areas police scuffled with groups of farmers
staging similar protests. At least five people, including an
opposition lawmaker, were injured. The farmers, accompanied by two
calves, hurled cow dung, burned an effigy of the United States and
used clubs to fight police. Police in green combat fatigues and
black helmets kicked and punched farmers.
   The protest in Seoul lasted two hours, with farmers shouting
``Oppose American beef and its pressure to open the Korean market''
and other anti-U.S. slogans. At one point, a calf ran amok through
the 1,000 riot police surrounding the assembly compound before
being grabbed by police.
   The United States is pushing South Korea to widen its domestic
markets to American imports to redress Seoul's $10 billion trade
surplus with Washington.
   The trade issue has fanned anti-U.S. sentiment and dissidents
charge the United States disregards the wishes of the Korean people
with ``coercive'' demands.
   Prime Minister Lee, in a Cabinet meeting today, called for tight
security to guard foreign legations and public facilites from
violence by radicals.
   Lee said the recent wave of violent protests posed a threat to
the people and ``inflicted undesirable influence on the nation's
security and diplomacy before staging the Olympics.'' The Olympic
Games open in Seoul in September.
</TEXT>
