<HEAD>Conservative Talk Show Host Introduces His Brother With AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative talk-show host Morton Downey Jr.'s
recently taped program on AIDS included one surprise guest: the
host's own brother, who has AIDS.
   The outspoken Downey surprised the studio audience at the taping
of his TV show on Friday by introducing his 52-year-old homosexual
brother, Tony, the New York Post reported today.
   Downey, 55, said his younger brother would move to New Jersey
from California to stay with him and his family.
   ``He's my family and I'm going to take care of him,'' said
Downey, known for his anti-gay tirades on his soon-to-be nationally
syndicated program. ``I still object to what I call perverted love,
but nonetheless, he's my brother.''
   The program, to be broadcast June 15 locally on WWOR-TV, also
deals with the high cost of AIDS drugs like AZT. Tony Downey pays
$1,200 a week for the medication, the Post said.
   ``He (Tony) had told me a long time ago that if the time came
when there was no reversal, he would like to come on my show and
talk about his lifestyle to help people,'' Downey said. ``I had to
give him his moment.''
   ``The Morton Downey Jr. Show'' will begin national syndication
Monday.
