<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Afghanistan     05-26 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Says 100,300 Soldiers In Afghanistan Before Withdrawal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Soviet general today provided for the
first time a count of Soviet troop strength in Afghanistan, saying
100,300 soldiers were deployed there before the contingent began to
withdraw on May 15.
   The number provided by Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev, chief of
the Soviet military general staff and a first deputy defense
minister, was nearly 15,000 less than claimed by Western
intelligence sources.
   Akhromeyev provided the figure the day after Gen. Alexei D.
Lizichev, another leading ministry official, provided a casualty
count for the first time _ 13,310 Soviet soldiers killed in
Afghanistan, 35,478 wounded and 311 missing.
   Lizichev had refused to provide a figure for the size of the
Soviet force.
   Akhromeyev, asked at a news conference on U.S.-Soviet relations
about the size of the Soviet force in Afghanistan, said: ``The
contingent in Afghanistan as of May 15 numbered 100,300.''
   He said 9,500 soldiers had left the country since the withdrawal
began.
   The size of the Soviet force in Afghanistan has been estimated
for years by Western intelligence sources at about 115,000
soldiers. But earlier this spring, Italian officials who met with
First Deputy Foreign Minister Yuli Vorontsov quoted him as putting
troop strength there at 100,000.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979, replaced one
Communist government with another and remained to help fight
anti-Marxist guerrillas.
   Under an agreement signed in Geneva on April 14, all Soviet
troops are to be out of Afghanistan within nine months.
</TEXT>
