<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MayorForAWeek     05-26 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mayor For A Week,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor For A Week Now Ousted As Chicago's Deputy Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MENSING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ``accident of history'' made him mayor for a
week. But now David Orr is facing the reality of politics.
   Just a day after his photograph was unveiled on City Hall's
``Wall of Mayors,'' Orr was dumped Wednesday as vice mayor by the
City Council on a 31-15 vote.
   The action was apparently a retaliation for his demands for
better accounting among Council members.
   Orr, 43, a Democrat known as a strong proponent of ethics
legislation, was thrust into the spotlight as acting mayor when
Harold Washington died of a heart attack Nov. 25. Orr held the
mayor's job just seven days before the council, in a raucous,
all-night session, elected Eugene Sawyer to succeed Washington. Orr
had not sought the post.
   But in presiding over that council meeting, Orr angered some
Sawyer supporters who thought he delayed calling for a vote. His
support in the council continued to erode as council members
objected to his persistent call for more controls over the way they
spend their money.
   In Monday's Chicago Tribune, Orr repeated his view that council
members should be more accountable for their $18,000 continency
funds and for their travel and office expenses. Currently, they are
not required to disclose how that money is spent.
   ``Everything he has done ... has been done to demean us, to make
us out to be thieves, ignoramuses and low-lifes,'' fumed Alderwoman
Anna Langford. ``He has to tell us how to run the council.''
   Orr, however, said he will continue to push for accountability
despite his ouster.
   ``This is only going to invigorate me,'' he said. ``I'm
absolutely convinced that the majority of the people of Chicago
support me. ... In some ways, I'm honored to be dumped by some of
these folks.''
   Orr said he didn't know whether Sawyer, also a Democrat,
actively supported his ouster but added that he believes the
current administration is weak.
   Alderman Terry Gabinski was named to succeed Orr as vice mayor,
a post considered mainly ceremonial.
   Orr taught history and urban affairs at Mundelein College before
he defeated three challengers to win election to the City Council
in 1979. His support for ethics legislation matched the agenda of
Washington, who made him vice mayor in 1986 as Washington began
building his council base.
   Being mayor, Orr said, was ``kind of an accident of history, and
I'm really proud of what I did.''
   ``I fought for religious and racial tolerance and City Council
accountability,'' he said.
   Orr's ouster came a day after his photograph was unveiled on the
``Wall of Mayors'' outside Sawyer's fifth-floor office.
   ``He still was mayor,'' Sawyer told reporters when asked why
Orr's picture should join the honored group. ``It is extremely
well-deserved. ... What's fair is fair.''
</TEXT>
