<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brite-MissingDecatur     05-26 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite-Missing Decatur,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Decatur' Contest Organizers Overlook Tiny New York Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A promotional firm in Decatur, Ill.,
thought it had finished its research when it asked 11 other
Decaturs around the country to compete in a contest to raise food
for the needy.
   But it missed Decatur, N.Y.
   However, the 312 citizens of the central New York village say
they aren't insulted since they're used to being overlooked.
   ``I'm not surprised,'' said town supervisor Gary Hughes. ``We
don't show in the Rand McNally atlas.''
   A group called Decatur Advantage came up with the idea of
challenging the country's Decaturs to see which one could collect
the most cans of food for the poor based on percentage of
population.
   After poring through atlases, the Illinois group found Decaturs
in Alabama, Arkansas, Georgia, Indiana, Michigan, Mississippi,
Nebraska, Tennessee and Texas. They also found Decatur counties in
Iowa and Kansas, said Jan Cook, a spokeswoman for Decatur Advantage.
   But they didn't spot Decatur, N.Y.
   ``It's nice to know there's another one out there,'' Cook said.
``We didn't mean to forget you.''
   The Nebraska Decatur, with 723 people, was thought to be the
smallest of the communities, but the central New York village's
population is less than half that. The largest, Decatur, Ill., has
more than 94,000 people.
   Hughes said he's not surprised his town was overlooked. After
all, he said, it doesn't even have a zip code, its ``downtown''
consists of 10 houses and the only way to find it is look at a
town-by-town map of the state.
   The official competition between Decaturs starts Friday and runs
through Aug. 3, Cook said. Hughes said he'd like to see more
information before committing the Otsego County village to the
contest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
