<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSOrder     05-26 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Order,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Test Ordered for Convicted Sex Offender</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ordered a convicted sex offender to
submit to a test for the AIDS virus over the objections of the
man's attorney, who called it an invasion of privacy.
   Attorney Robert Gombiner said he would advise client Steven G.
Farmer not to comply with the order by King County Superior Court
Judge Charles Johnson, and said he would appeal.
   Johnson ruled Tuesday that Farmer, 34, should receive the test
before sentencing June 7.
   The former flight attendant was convicted last month of two
counts of patronizing a teen-age male prostitute and two counts of
sexual exploitation of a minor.
   Deputy prosecutor Rebecca Roe said that if the test is positive,
she would seek a 10-year sentence for Farmer. The normal maximum
sentence for the crime is three years and seven months.
   Ms. Roe contended Farmer knew he had tested positive for the
virus that can cause AIDS when he had contact with young male
prostitutes.
   She said that if Farmer resists the order, she will seek a
warrant to take the blood by force in the county jail.
   Johnson said the test results would be supplied only to the
court and to lawyers.
   ``It is a patently illegal order,'' said Gombiner. ``If your
honor wants to hold us in contempt, you can, but I am telling Mr.
Farmer he is not to comply with this order.''
   He said the ruling violated Farmer's right to privacy,
especially in light of a state law enacted this year that restricts
such examinations.
   ``There is no God-given right for the state to go around
sticking needles in people and taking out little vials of blood,''
Gombiner said.
   He said he would ask the state Court of Appeals to stay
Johnson's order and review the ruling.
   AIDS, which damages the body's immune system and leaves victims
susceptible to infections and cancer, is spread through sexual
contact. It is also spread through needles or syringes shared by
drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant
women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
