<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-SovietArt     05-26 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Soviet Art,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Artists Match West In Lively Paintings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An exhibition of works by 34 Soviet artists that
is touring Europe shows Russian painters are doing work as lively,
innovative _ and often as strange _ as anything done in the West.
   The 35 paintings, which will be sold in July at the first
international art auction in Moscow since the 1917 Russian
revolution, are being shown in Europe to attract bidders.
   ``The tour and the sale introduce the excellence of modern
Soviet painting to Western collectors, as well as offering more
familiar works of the avant-garde period that followed the
revolution,'' said Simon de Pury, managing director of the 23
European offices of Sotheby's auction house.
   The works were shown in New York earlier this month and have
just been displayed at Sotheby's in London for three days. They
will be seen in Paris today and Friday, in Cologne May 31-June 3
and in Zurich June 9-15, before returning to Moscow.
   In one painting, by Ilya Glazunov, a glowing scene depicts an
old Russian city with monks and onion-shaped church domes
surmounted by modern buildings and a red-flag procession.
   Another, by Svetlana Kopystianskaya, is comprised of a blue
crumpled cloth in a box, mysteriously titled ``Dialogue: N.2.''
   Ilya Kabakov paints words on his canvases. One of his works
titled ``Where Are You?'' consists of 36 sheets of paper with words
on them, each page signed and dated and contained in a box.
   From 1928, when dictator Josef Stalin achieved supreme power,
there were two kinds of Soviet art: the official one that glorified
the state and the unofficial one which didn't and was practised
behind the scenes.
   ``Under the new policy ... the distinction between `official'
and `unofficial' art is no longer being made by the Ministry of
Culture,'' de Pury said.
   He helped select the works for auction after getting to know the
artists during Moscow visits to arrange loans of pictures when he
was curator of Baron Heinrich Thyssen-Bornemisza's famous picture
collection in Lugano, Switzerland.
   The auction was negotiated with the Soviet culture ministry by
Lord Gowrie, Sotheby's chairman in Britain and a former arts
minister and art dealer. Most of the sale works are in the $3,700
to $9,300 price range. A few run up to $22,000 to $28,000.
   There is a strong emphasis on abstraction and fractured images
in the pictures, but there are also portraits and dreamy views of
the land and cities.
   The London showing drew a large number of viewers.
   ``Some of our visitors asked if we had been taken over by the
Russians,'' said a Sotheby's receptionist as a banner with the
firm's name in Cyrillic letters was taken down from the building.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
