<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-26 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against most major currencies
in European trading today ahead of the release of key U.S.
econonmic data. Gold prices fell.
   Traders said market sentiment for the dollar was generally
bullish, but said little movement was expected before the scheduled
1:30 p.m. (8:30 a.m. EDT) release of revised figures on
first-quarter growth of the U.S. gross national product.
   One dealer at a West German bank said there was a growing
perception that the dollar had support at its current levels.
   Midmorning dollar rates, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.7085 West German marks, up from 1.7045
   _1.4260 Swiss francs, up from 1.4245
   _5.7675 French francs, up from 5.7550
   _1.9133 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9090
   _1,268.65 Italian lire, up from 1,264.50
   _1.2380 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2434
   The dollar rose against the British pound, which was quoted at
$1.8615, compared with $1.8650 on Wednesday.
   The U.S. currency closed at 124.50 Japanese yen in Tokyo, up
from 124.30 yen. In London trading later today, the dollar was
quoted at 124.63 yen.
   London's major bullion dealers fixed a recommended gold price of
$453 a troy ounce, down from $454 late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, gold was bid at $452.70, down from $454.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell sharply, closing at a bid of
$452.42, against $460.27 Wednesday.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a bid of $6.56 a troy
ounce, down from $6.67.
</TEXT>
