<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrincetonDrinking     05-26 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Princeton Drinking,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Student Given Jail Time For Drinking Party At Princeton</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jail terms given two Princeton
University students for their role in initiation parties that
prompted 46 students to seek medical attention for overdrinking
were ``excessive,'' the school's president says.
   Kenneth Simpler, 20, of Rehoboth Beach, Del., and Lisa
Napolitano, 21, of Geneva, N.Y., were each sentenced to 30 days in
jail and a $500 fine Wednesday.
   Simpler, a junior who is president of the Charter Club, and Ms.
Napolitano, a junior who is the university eating club's former
social chairman, were convicted May 18 of serving alcoholic
beverages to minors in February.
   Municipal Court Judge Russell Annich said Wednesday he did not
consider the incident a college prank that got out of hand.
   ``I'm not aware of a similar event that has produced as many
casualties,'' said Annich. ``It is a violation of the law.''
   He delayed the start of the sentences so attorneys could appeal.
   Princeton President Harold Shapiro said he was shocked to hear
the students will have to serve jail sentences.
   ``While the incidents in question are certainly serious in
nature, the penalty seems to me clearly disproportionate and
excessive,'' Shapiro said.
   The initiation parties Feb. 6 by the Charter Club and the
Cloister Inn _ two of 13 fraternity-like eating clubs on campus _
resulted in 39 students going to the university's McCosh Infirmary
and seven requiring treatment at the Medical Center at Princeton.
   Many of the students were underage. New Jersey's legal drinking
age is 21.
   Simpler and Ms. Napolitano were convicted after a one-day trial
in which witnesses testified that students seeking to join the club
were blindfolded and led from room to room as club members poured
drinks down their throats.
   James Martin, 20, the social chairman of the Cloister Inn,
previously agreed to plead guilty to a disorderly persons offense.
Charges against two other Cloister Inn officers were dismissed for
lack of evidence.
   Defense attorney Kim Otis called the jail penalty ``totally
inappropriate.''
   ``We argued that there was selective prosecution and this is
selective sentencing _ this is scapegoating,'' Otis said.
   But prosecutor Michael Barrett said ``if we had information that
pointed a finger at other people we would have pursued it.''
   The case was one of two major drinking incidents at New Jersey
universities.
   Aggravated hazing charges stemming from the drinking-related
death of an 18-year-old fraternity pledge have been filed against
15 Rutgers University students, including seven officers of the
now-closed Lambda Chi Alpha fraternity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
