<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolShootings     05-26 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Shootings,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspicious Juice Package Addressed to Dann's Ex-husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINNETKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An envelope leaking fruit juice was found
in a postal box addressed to the ex-husband of Laurie Dann, and
authorities were trying to determine if it was part of the woman's
shooting and poisoning spree.
   The package addressed to Russell Dann was found Wednesday at a
suburban post office, police said.
   It had no return address and was turned over to a laboratory to
determine if the juice had been tainted and Dann sent it, said
police Sgt. Gene Kalvaitis.
   Dann, 30, fired on students Friday at Hubbard Woods Elementary
School in this affluent Chicago suburb, killing an 8-year-old boy
and wounding five other children. She then wounded a young man at a
home nearby and killed herself.
   Before her death, Dann mailed or delivered up to 24 packages of
snacks or juice _ most tainted with arsenic _ to acquaintances,
including several families for whom she had worked as a babysitter,
Kalvaitis said.
   The FBI and police are investigating.
   Investigators said they would seek a court order today forcing
Dr. John H. Greist, a psychiatrist affiliated with the University
of Wisconsin-Madison, to release his records on Dann, whom he
treated when she was a student there in 1977.
   Greist also received a drink container in the mail this week
that is being tested for poison, the FBI said.
   Meanwhile, the principal of Hubbard Woods Elementary School,
Richard Streedain, said the psychological impact of the shootings
lingers in the school's classrooms and hallways.
   ``One child is now in extreme stress because she (Dann) stuck a
gun to his head and pulled the trigger, but it clicked,'' he said
in a interview in today's Peoria Journal Star.
   Three of the shooting victims were reported in good condition at
hospitals today, two were in fair condition and one was in serious
condition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
