<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos Examined by Transplant Doctor, Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A transplant specialist examined Ferdinand
Marcos two days before the former Philippine president entered a
hospital complaining of chest pains, a TV station reported.
   Dr. Livingston Wong, chief of St. Francis Medical Center's
transplant team, and two unidentified doctors _ a cardiologist and
a kidney specialist from the Philippines _ saw Marcos on Sunday at
his home here, KHON said Wednesday.
   The station gave no sources for the report.
   Wong refused to comment on the report. Marcos spokesman Gemmo
Trinidad said he knew nothing about the reported visit.
   Marcos, 70, remained in guarded condition Wednesday night in the
intensive care unit at the medical center, Trinidad said. Earlier
in the day, Marcos' physician, Dr. Derek Pang, ruled out the
possibility of a heart attack, Trindidad said.
   More tests were ordered for today to determine if a lung ailment
caused the chest pains that led Marcos to enter the hospital
Tuesday night, he said.
   Marcos' staff stationed guards in the intensive care unit and at
every entrance to the hospital.
   Marcos wife, Imelda, said in a radio interview aired in Manila
that the former president is suffering because he has not been
allowed to return home.
   Tomas Gomez, Philippine consul general to Hawaii, dismissed the
pains as an attempt on the part of Marcos to return to his homeland
for the funeral of his mother, Josefa Edralin-Marcos, who died May
4 at the age of 95.
   ``I think these are charades. These chest pains are not
substantiated medically,'' Gomez said. ``The problem I have with
Mr. Marcos is you never know when he's telling the truth.''
   President Corazon Aquino, saying Marcos continues to pose a
threat the national security of the Philippines, has refused to
lift the ban on his return, which she imposed in 1986 after he fled
into exile here.
   Marcos' quest to return home drew support from several
Philippine politicians.
   ``This is going to create another problem if (Marcos) comes home
in a box,'' said Sen. Ernesto Maceda. ``Now is the time for the
government to act to allow him to return.''
</TEXT>
