<2ND_LINE>PM-Record Deal,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Men Convicted In Federal Extortion-Conspiracy Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury convicted two record company
executives and a reputed mob figure of conspiring to extort $1.25
million from a record wholesaler.
   Morris Levy, 60-year-old president of Roulette Records in New
York, Roulette comptroller Howard Fisher, 60, and reputed Genovese
crime family member Dominick Canterino, 57, were convicted
Wednesday.
   Each could receive up to 40 years in prison at sentencing July 8
for conspiracy to commit extortion.
   Defense attorneys said they would appeal.
   U.S. District Judge Stanley S. Brotman raised bail for Canterino
and Levy from $500,000 to $1 million after Assistant U.S. Attorney
Bruce Repetto said Levy might flee to Australia. Repetto had asked
for $5 million bail each.
   Prosecutors contended the three defendants sought to move in on
the wholesaling business of John LaMonte of Darby, Pa. Authorities
said the case is an example of how the mob is trying to infiltrate
the recording industry.
   Defense attorneys said the three merely wanted LaMonte to make
good on a 1985 deal to pay for $1.25 million worth of records and
tapes bought from MCA Records Inc. of Los Angeles. MCA was not
charged in the case.
