<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Vietnam-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru a0549 05-26 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Cambodia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0549,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Announces Pullout Of 50,000 Troops</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Cambodia news agency, Tass
reporting pullout announcement, details; picks up 3rd graf, `The
diplomat ...' EDITS thereafter to trim.
^By PETER ENG</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam will withdraw 50,000 troops
from Cambodia by the end of the year and will pull out all its
forces by 1990, the official Cambodian SPK news agency said today.
   The Soviet news agency Tass, reporting from Hanoi, also reported
the pullout announcement.
   SPK quoted a communique from the Ministry of National Defense as
saying the soldiers would be returning home from June to December.
   Remaining troops will be placed under the command of the
pro-Vietnamese Cambodian government, SPK said.
   A 50,000-troop pullout would be by far the largest of six
partial withdrawals Vietnam claims to have made since 1982.
   About 20,000 troops returned home in the most recent and largest
withdrawal last November. The United States says that was the only
genuine withdrawal, and it estimates that 120,000-125,000
Vietnamese troops remain in the country battling about 50,000
guerrillas.
   SPK, monitored in Bangkok, said that over the past nine years,
the Cambodian government ``has gradually undertaken the defense
work by itself, thus creating the conditions for six annual
withdrawals of Vietnamese volunteer troops from Kampuchea
(Cambodia).''
   ``This time, the command of the Vietnamese volunteer army in
Kampuchea will also be pulled out from Kampuchea and the remaining
Vietnamese troops in Kampuchea are to be placed under the command
of the People's Republic of Kampuchea until their complete
withdrawal in 1990.''
   The announcement followed word on the Vietnamese pullout by a
senior Vietnamese Foreign Ministry official Wednesday to a group of
foreign diplomats in Hanoi, a Western diplomat in Bangkok said
today.
   The diplomat, quoting a cable from his country's embassy in
Hanoi, said he had no other details. He gave the information on
condition of anonymity.
   The development came before Sunday's start of the Moscow summit,
at which President Reagan has said he will ask Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev to encourage the Vietnamese to resolve the
Cambodian conflict.
   The Soviet-armed Vietnamese invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and
are fighting guerrillas backed militarily or diplomatically by
China, non-communist Southeast Asian countries and the United
States.
   Hanoi had warned it will take unspecified action if the
guerrillas take advantage of the pullout to try to return to power.
   The strategy of the Khmer Rouge, the largest of the guerrilla
groups, has been to gain control of villages and wait for the
Vietnamese to withdraw in 1990.
   The Western diplomat said the Vietnamese were moving into the
interior of the country, leaving the Phnom Penh forces to guard the
Thai border area, the traditional area of fighting.
   Earlier this week, Reagan said in response to written questions
from reporters from Southeast Asian countries that he would raise
the Cambodian issue in Moscow.
   Foreign Minister Siddhi Savetsila of Thailand quoted Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze as telling him last week in
Moscow that the Kremlin would talk to the Vietnamese about ending
their occupation of Cambodia.
   That could represent a significant change of position _ the
Soviets previously stated they have no direct role to play in the
conflict and that Vietnam is a sovereign country whose policies the
Kremlin cannot influence.
   In exchange for rights at Vietnam's numerous military bases, the
Soviet Union gives Vietnam several billion dollars a year in aid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0851EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SavannahRiver     05-26 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Savannah River,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DOE, Environmentalists, State Health Agency Settle Waste Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative agreement that would
immediately close two dumps has been reached in a legal battle over
the regulation and disposal of hazardous waste from the Savannah
River nuclear weapons plant.
   Under the agreement, the federal Energy Department must close
two major hazardous waste dumps at the government plant and begin
developing detailed plans for closing and monitoring three others.
   The department also agreed the South Carolina Department of
Health and Environmental Control should have an active role in
regulating hazardous waste facilities at the Savannah River Plant,
a concession the state had sought for years.
   The agreement, submitted for approval this week to U.S. District
Judge Charles E. Simons Jr., was signed by the federal and state
agency and a coalition of environmental groups that had sued in
1985 over the handling of hazardous waste at the plant.
   James Chandler, a lawyer for the environmental groups, said the
agreement will lead to a cleaner environment at the facility and
make the Savannah River Plant more accountable to state and federal
laws.
   The Savannah River Plant produces plutonium and tritium for
nuclear weapons.
</TEXT>
