<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0904EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     05-26 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writers Reject Payment Proposal But Agree to Meet Again Saturday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking scriptwriters again failed to come
to terms with producers on residual payments from reruns but agreed
to another bargaining session this weekend in the 12-week-old
walkout.
   Negotiators for the Writers Guild of America also rejected a
proposal by the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers
to extend the proposed contract from three years to four, said WGA
Executive Director Brian Walton.
   However, Wednesday's five-hour bargaining session, conducted by
a federal mediator, ended with agreement to meet again Saturday.
   The 9,000 TV and film writers went on strike March 7 over
creative control and residuals.
   The walkout cut the TV season short for many shows and is
expected to delay the start of the fall season. It has also delayed
countless movie projects.
   The guild also announced it would take a membership vote tonight
to approve several independent contracts with TV production
companies.
   As of Wednesday afternoon, Walton said, 39 companies had signed
contracts with the union.
   Among the companies, he said, were those producing ``It's Garry
Shandling's Show,'' ``The Tonight Show,'' starring Johnny Carson,
Alien Productions, which makes ``Alf,'' Kenny Rogers Productions,
Henson & Associations, which makes the ``Muppets,'' and the
production company for ``Days and Nights of Molly Dodd.''
   ``Late Night With David Letterman'' agreed to an as-yet-unsigned
contract this week, union President George Kirgo said.
   Producers spokesman Herb Steinberg said the contracts represent
less than 10 percent of all film production and less than 15
percent of TV production.
   ``We'd rather put 4,000 writers back to work than 400,'' he said.
   During Wednesday's negotiations, producers proposed a formula
for one-hour prime-time shows sold into syndication, based on the
premise that such shows are selling poorly.
   ``They rejected the numbers but not the concept,'' Steinberg
said.
   Under the formula, which the producers have offered twice and
the writers have rejected twice, the producers proposed to drop a
fixed residual schedule and pay writers based on a show's success
in syndication.
   Producers said writers could earn as much as 150 percent more
than under their present pay schedule.
   The producers alliance said in a statement that the offer would
``meet the fixed residual requirement of the WGA, while satisfying
AMPTP objectives of having a market price sensitive formula.'' The
release didn't detail the offer.
</TEXT>
