<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru   05-26 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0568,0790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Student Stabbed in Arab Market, Army Lifts Curfews</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Police said...' to UPDATE with police saying
stabbing probably not political.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab assailant sneaked up behind a Jewish
seminary student in a perfume market today and stabbed him in the
back, police said.
   The victim was hospitalized and identified as the son of an
Israeli government lawyer who handled land confiscation cases in
the occupied territories. But authorities said they believed the
attack was random.
   Police said another Jewish man was stabbed to death later today
in the predominantly Jewish neighborhood of Katamon, which borders
an Arab village. Israel radio quoted police as saying they believed
it was a criminal act not motivated by ethnic politics. The
neighborhood is a poor area with a high crime rate.
   The army lifted curfews imposed in parts of the occupied
territories after Palestinians defied the restrictions and called a
general strike to commemorate slain PLO leader Khalil Wazir.
   Curfews remained in effect in a village and a refugee camp in
the occupied West Bank.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, meanwhile, said the 24-week-old
Arab uprising has made peace more elusive, but reiterated that
Israel must vigorously pursue negotiations with its Arab neighbors.
   Since the Dec. 8 start of the uprising, 195 Palestinians have
been killed and hundreds wounded. Two Israelis have died.
   Witnesses identified the first stabbing victim as Chanoch
Albeck. Justice Ministry officials said he was the son of Plea
Albeck, who has handled land confiscation cases in the occupied
territories for the government.
   Jerusalem police spokesmen said the 16-year-old victim was
attacked from behind by a single Arab assailant as he walked
through the perfume market, a narrow lane in the Moslem Quarter,
apparently on his way to a seminary in the adjacent Jewish Quarter
of the city.
   Several Arabs were immediately detained for questioning and
police launched wide searches in the area, said spokesman Alex
Lapidot.
   A police source said it appeared unlikely that Albeck was
targeted and that investigators believed the attack was random.
   In a statement, Jerusalem Mayor Teddy Kollek said he was
``shocked and disgusted. The Arab public in Jerusalem must
understand that such actions in the end will only hurt the Arabs.''
   Albeck, who wore a black yarmulka, was rushed by ambulance to
nearby Hadassah hospital with the knife sticking out of his back
after two other seminary students helped him to the Jewish quarter,
police and witnesses said.
   ``He had a knife in the upper part of his back. The entire knife
was inside,'' merchant Alex Yosipo told Israel radio. ``He said he
was alone when it happened, that he was stabbed and didn't know by
whom. There was apparently no scuffle. He was simply stabbed.''
   The radio said a witness to the attack, identified as Rami
Shebach, said he tried in vain to chase down the Arab assailant.
   A hospital official, reached by telephone, said the youth was
being treated in the intensive care unit and declined to give
further details.
   The last attack on an Israeli in the old city was last October,
when a 24-year old man was fatally shot in the head.
   On Wednesday, a PLO-mandated general strike shut down
transportation and commerce in the West Bank, Gaza and Arab east
Jerusalem. An army curfew confined 200,000 Arabs to their homes in
the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
   The strike was called to mark the end of mourning for Wazir, the
PLO military commander, assassinated April 16 at his home outside
Tunis, Tunisia.
   Wazir, whose code name was Abu Jihad, spent his boyhood in Gaza
City. Israeli sources said Israel security forces were responsible
for his death. The Israeli government has not commented on the case.
   By early today, all curfews were lifted in Gaza, but two
remained in effect in the West Bank's Dheishe refugee camp and the
village of Shuweika, army officials said.
   On Wednesday, despite the curfews, scattered anti-Israeli
protests occurred, leaving at least six Arabs hurt.
   Peres' remarks were aimed at his political rival, Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir, who has said Israel should not enter peace talks
until calm has returned to the occupied territories.
   ``I think it's more difficult today,'' Peres, leader of the
leftist Labor Party, told Israel Television Wednesday night. ``The
road to peace is full of obstacles, full of disappointments. But
what is the alternative? To let the situation deteriorate?''
   Peres, responding to a question, told Israel Television he was
concerned about possible human rights violations in the occupied
territories, but did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
