<HEAD>Hammer Celebrates 90th Birthday Waving Baton For Orchestra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits a0492 to add People to keyword line</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrialist Armand Hammer celebrated his
90th birthday at a gala Kennedy Center concert which ended with
Hammer conducting the National Symphony Orchestra in John Phillip
Sousa's ``Stars and Stripes Forever.''
   Music Director Mstislav Rostropovich handed over his baton
Wednesday night moments after Hammer announced he was giving
$250,000 to the orchestra. More than 3,000 well-wishers filled the
center's Concert Hall to celebrate the birthday of the
philanthropist, art collector and chairman of Occidental Petroleum
Corp.
   During the concert, Hammer sat in the President's Box with his
wife, Frances, and Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin.
   The audience included high-ranking government officials, members
of Congress, diplomats and leaders of the business and arts
communities, as well as Lady Bird Johnson, widow of former
President Lyndon Baines Johnson.
   Mounting the stage after the concert, Hammer said his dream of
creating ``a meaningful peace in the world is closer to reality
than ever before.'' He predicted that the Moscow summit talks
between President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev
will be a ``tremendous success.''
   ``I believe the die has been cast for realistic negotiations
that will lead to a new period of understanding and respect between
the United States and the Soviet Union,'' Hammer said.
   Hammer has been close to a long succession of Soviet leaders and
has struck trade deals with the Soviets for many years. He also is
chairman of the president's Cancer Board and has spent millions of
dollars on medical research aimed at finding a cancer cure.
   He proposed that a ``March of Dollars'' similar to the March of
Dimes against polio begun 50 years ago be held to accelerate cancer
research. He said he is lobbying congressional leaders to back
matching government funds for $500 million in private money to be
given to the National Cancer Institute over four years.
   Hammer shared the stage with members of the National Symphony
and Wednesday night's guest artists: violinists Yehudi Menuhin and
Isaac Stern, soprano Kiri Te Kanawa and Chinese pianist Yuhui Hong,
who made her U.S. debut at the concert.
</TEXT>
