<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SmokingBan     05-26 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Smoking Ban,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago City Council Approves Smoking Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MENSING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ordinance restricting smoking in public places
in the nation's third-largest city was overwhelmingly approved by
City Council.
   ``Chicago has to line up with the rest of the major cities. We
have been lagging,'' said Alderman Raymond Figueroa, whose proposal
was approved 33-8 with little debate Wednesday.
   New York and Los Angeles, the first- and second-largest cities,
already have smoking restrictions.
   The ordinance, which takes effect in 60 days, requires
restaurants with 40 or more seats to set aside smoking and
non-smoking areas, although they can be in the same room.
   In addition, Figueroa said, the ordinance requires employers to
designate smoking and no-smoking areas if workers request them.
   The ordinance forbids smoking in enclosed public places like
taxicabs, public restrooms, polling places and public meeting
halls. Bars, hotels and private meeting rooms are exempt.
   Figueroa said the ordinance carries fines ranging from $25 to
$100, with enforcement details still to be worked out.
   The quick passage of the ban surprised even some supporters.
Mayor Eugene Sawyer was prepared to break a tie vote in favor of
the measure, said aide Monroe Anderson.
   About 150 cities have enacted some kind of legislation
restricting smoking, health officials have said.
</TEXT>
