<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon     05-26 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syrian Official: Agreement Reached To End South Beirut Fighting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Syrian official said Syria and a
pro-Iranian militia reached an agreement to stop fighting today in
the southern suburbs of Beirut.
   But gunners from the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, and
the Syrian-aided Amal continued fighting sporadically with mortars,
howitzers and tank cannons on the 21st day of struggle for the
slums, where 18 foreign hostages are believed held.
   Another report, in the leftist Beirut daily As-Safir, said a
solution to the conflict ``has been delayed because secret
negotiations on the fate of the American hostages in particular
have not reached a definite result.''
   Nine of the foreign hostages are Americans.
   The Syrian official, speaking on condition of anonymity in
Damuscus, said, ``Ending the fighting will create new hope for the
hostages, and Syria will spare no effort to secure their release,
regardless of their nationality.''
   The official did not give details of the agreement but said it
had been agreed to by all parties, including Iran and Amal, after a
meeting between President Hafez Assad of Syria and Hezbollah
leaders late Wednesday.
   Hezbollah is a group of Moslem Shiite fundamentalists in Lebanon
believed to be an umbrella for smaller organizations holding the
foreign hostages.
   Syria has been threatening to intervene to stop the fighting. It
has about 7,500 troops, 100 tanks and 400 armored units ringing the
16-square-mile warren of narrow alleyways and cement shanties,
where nearly 300 persons have been killed in the fighting.
   Syrian officials also have been negotiating with Hezbollah and
Iranian officials, including two deputy foreign ministers, to work
out a plan for Syrian troop deployment to bring security to the
southern suburbs.
   Syrian sources have said that they were willing to use force if
necessary but it was only a last option.
   Threats to kill hostages if the Syrians used force have been
reported. The Syrians have said any action against the hostages
would be considered an act against Syria.
   The battle between Amal and Hezbollah over control of the
southern suburbs has created tension between Iran and Syria, which
is Iran's only major Arab ally in its 7{-year-old war with Iraq.
   Israeli planes today attacked Amal and Hezbollah positions in
south Lebanon today. It followed ground attacks by Israeli-allied
militiamen on two villages Wednesday.
   The As-Safir report, which could not be verified, quoted
unidentified diplomatic sources as saying ``serious negotiations''
are being held between Washington and Tehran and some
``Iranian-allied groups'' on the nine American hostages.
   The short report did not disclose further details.
   The hostage held longest is American Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press. He was abducted
March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
