<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-USRelations     05-26 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-US Relations,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kremlin Advisers Paint Hopeful Backdrop for Reagan Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leading Soviet officials today called for burying
the ``corpse of the Cold War'' and lauded President Reagan for his
pledge to come to next week's summit in search of peace.
   They said the meetings could produce important advances in
negotiations toward a treaty to cut U.S. and Soviet long-range
nuclear arsenals by 50 percent.
   One official asserted U.S.-Soviet relations had warmed because
Reagan had adopted the Kremlin's way of thinking on disarmament and
international relations.
   Some of the nation's top advisers on foreign policy met with
reporters to discuss the summit and its significance for relations
between the superpowers. They generally forecast improving
relations.
   The state-run press also said superpower ties were improving.
The labor newspaper Trud pressed for a successful summit and said
that the vast majority of Americans want a better relationship with
Soviets. The newspaper Socialist Industry declared that the two
nations have entered a ``political thaw.''
   Reagan was to arrive Sunday for five days of meetings with
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the fourth summit between the
two leaders in less than three years.
   ``Previously, our goals were more limited,'' said U.S. affairs
expert Georgy A. Arbatov, observing that Reagan and Gorbachev in
the past focused on easing tensions built up since World War II.
   ``Now, we have the possibility to move toward demilitarization
of Soviet-American relations,'' said Arbatov, head of the
USA-Canada Institute in Moscow.
   He compared the Cold War to a dying patient kept alive by
artificial means. The task at hand for Reagan and Gorbachev is to
bury ``this corpse of the Cold War, which with the help of
artificial means _ political adrenalin and the political machinery
of an artificial heart _ has been maintained in a semi-living
state.''
   Asked about Reagan's comment Wednesday that he viewed his
journey to the Soviet capital as a mission of peace, Arbatov smiled
and replied: ``I think there is something symbolic in this, that
Reagan is now coming with an olive branch to Moscow.''
   He said he was happy to concede that his view of Reagan had
changed from that of a cold warrior to a statesman with whom the
Kremlin can work. But Arbatov said the president himself brought
about the improvement by coming around to the Soviets' way of
thinking on disarmament and international relations.
   Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev, military chief of staff and first
deputy defense minister, restated Kremlin positions that there is
no Soviet superiority in conventional weapons in Europe or
excessive military spending. But asked for details, Akhromeyev made
the rare acknowledgement that the reported defense budget does not
reflect spending on research, development and production of weapons.
   Akhromeyev declined to say how much of the Soviet Union's gross
national product is invested in defense, saying he was privy only
to the budget approved by the Supreme Soviet, the nominal
parliament, which amounts to about 5 percent of government spending.
   Western estimates have put Soviet defense spending as high as 19
percent of the gross national product, which represents the total
value of all goods and services producted.
   Arbatov dismissed foreign assessments as ``speculation,'' but
conceded that Soviet military spending is proportionately higher
than in the United States because the Soviet gross national product
is lower while the demands of security are equal.
   Poking fun at the United States, Arbatov said the Soviet
military ``cannot do as the United States does and sell toilet
seats for $700 or a hammer for $150.'' He was apparently referring
to reports of excessive costs charged the U.S. government under
some private contracts with the Defense Department.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Vladimir F. Petrovsky told reporters
that the Soviets view the upcoming summit as an important step in
continuing improvement of relations rather than as a farewell to
Reagan, whose term ends in January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
