<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0469 05-26 0959</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0469,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede NEWARK, N.J.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Calls for Drug-Destroying Strike Force</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 9 grafs with Bush drug comments, picking up in
2nd graf pvs, Bush said; deletes 7th graf pvs, Bush who; subs 2
grafs for next-to-last graf, adding detail on Wright</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SECAUCUS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush today called
for creation of an international drug strike force that would
destroy drug crops wherever they are grown.
   ``Our military forces have already made a substantial
contribution to our interdiction effort and today they're being
called upon to do more. Their primary target should be the
production of drugs abroad,'' he said.
   Bush, in a campaign speech to a Chamber of Commerce audience,
also said he opposes any effort to weaken the Justice Department's
``zero tolerance'' policy for seizing vehicles on which drugs are
found.
   ``Some call this policy controversial, especially among those
big yacht owners out there,'' the vice president said. ``I think it
makes great sense. If people can lose their cars for parking
violations, surely they should lose them for carrying drugs. Zero
tolerance should be the policy of every state in the union.''
   The Republican presidential nominee-to-be planned to stress drug
themes all day in campaign appearances, including a visit in Newark
to a drug rehabilitation center.
   Bush said that, if elected, he would urge other nations to join
in establishing ``an international strike force to hit back, quick
and hard and often, at foreign drug operations.''
   He said it would be far simpler and less expensive to eradicate
drugs at their source than to try to find and get rid of them
later. ``We need to wipe out crops wherever they are grown and take
out labs wherever they exist,'' Bush said.
   The vice president also said he would make adoption of drug-free
programs a condition for companies to receive federal contracts
``and I will ask the states to do the same.''
   In Jersey City on Wednesday night, Bush said that even though he
and President Reagan may have some differences on dealing with Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, both want the Panamanian leader out of
power.
   Bush said that he isn't discouraged that the administration's
efforts to negotiate an agreement with Noriega collapsed on
Wednesday.
   The vice president, who aides have described as opposed to the
talks, said ``public opinion may be more on the side of the United
States'' as a result of the impasse.
   Although Bush said that he and Reagan ``have had some
differences'' on the subject, the vice president said they share a
common goal.
   ``We have a policy objective of still getting Noriega out of
power,'' he told reporters on Wednesday.
   ``The fact that we haven't solved the problem at this instance
doesn't depress me, because I don't want a bad deal, I want a good
deal,'' he said.
   Addressing a Republican rally in Jersey City on Wednesday night,
the presumed GOP presidential candidate said that, if elected, he
would put his vice president in charge of anti-drug programs ``in a
drug czar-like posture.''
   Bush has called for the death penalty for ``drug kingpins,'' but
has dodged questions on whether this should also apply to Noriega,
who is under indictment in the United States on drug-trafficking
charges.
   Earlier in the day, Bush told reporters in Lakehurst, N.J., that
he was spending two days campaigning in New Jersey, even though he
has the GOP nomination clinched, because he was concerned about
polls showing him trailing the front-runner in the Democratic
presidential race, Michael Dukakis.
   ``We're behind. I'm the underdog. You've seen that in the
polls,'' Bush said.
   However, he later voiced confidence that he would close the gap,
asking: ``Why should I worry about polls in May when the election
is held in November?''
   He suggested that the race on the Democratic side between
Dukakis and Jesse Jackson was giving Dukakis a false image as a
conservative because he comes across as less liberal than Jackson.
   ``It's a blur out there,'' Bush said.
   Meanwhile, Bush campaign officials said that Peter Teeley, a
longtime Bush adviser, was stepping down from his job as campaign
communications director.
   Campaign Manager Lee Atwater said Teeley would remain with the
campaign but be ``a more creative type guy and work specifically on
the surrogate teams.''
   No further reason was given for the switch, but Teeley was known
to have been at odds recently with Bush chief of staff Craig Fuller.
   Teeley will ``continue on as a senior political adviser,'' said
Bush spokesman Stephen Hart.
   ``As we head into the fall campaign, roles and responsibilities
are going to shift and change. It's the right time for such shifts
to occur,'' Hart said.
   ``I wouldn't characterize it as a shakeup,'' Hart said.
   After a full day of campaigning in the Newark area today, Bush
planned to fly to his vacation retreat in Kennebunkport, Maine,
where he will spend a week in strategy sessions and in meetings on
issues with Republican governors and other GOP leaders.
   In other developments on Wednesday, Bush:
   _Called for naming of an independent counsel to study recent
allegations of financial irregularities surrounding House Speaker
Jim Wright, D-Texas. ``We're going to go after Congress hard and
talk about ethics. If they want to talk about (Attorney General) Ed
Meese, how about talking about the speaker?''
   The allegations concern royalties on a Wright book and his
intervention with federal regulators on behalf of troubled Texas
savings and loan associations.
   _Told a West Point commencement ceremony that a ``liberal
elite'' was jeopardizing the nation's security by failing to
support weapons programs he said were needed. Although he didn't
mention them by name, Bush's comments were apparently aimed at both
Dukakis and Jackson.
</TEXT>
