<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a051emergencylocatorradiothatbeepedthroughouttheday.
05-26 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0516,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegation Of South African Whites Talks With ANC</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with groups meeting and church
delegation meeting with Kohl. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of white South Africans
met today with four members of the outlawed African National
Congress to seek common ground in the struggle against apartheid.
   In Bonn, meanwhile, South African church leaders demanded in
talks with Chancellor Helmut Kohl that the Common Market adopt
tough measures to pressure the Pretoria government to dismantle its
race laws.
   Delegation leader Wynand Malan said the eight white delegates
were meeting confidentially with the ANC guerrilla movement to seek
``common ground and strategies.'' Malan is a member of Parliament
and head of the National Democratic Movement.
   The ANC is waging a bombing and sabotage campaign against the
white minority government of South Africa. It is based in Lusaka,
Zambia.
   ANC members at the Frankfurt meeting were Thabo Mbeki, head of
information and publicity; Tony Seedat, the ANC's chief
representative in West Germany; and Aziz Pahad and Jacob Zuma. All
four belong to the ANC's national executive committee.
   Malan told The Associated Press in an interview at a Frankfurt
hotel that the two groups would meet throughout the day.
   ``This is a normal further discussion with the ANC, seeking a
common ground and strategies out of the impasse,'' in South Africa,
Malan said. ``It's the National Democratic Movement's policy to
meet with all political groupings.''
   West Germany was chosen as a meeting site, Malan said, because
it was easy for both sides to get to quickly. Malan said he would
return to South Africa this evening.
   ``The ANC belongs to the essential political forces in South
Africa and is therefore an important dialogue partner,'' Malan told
reporters.
   Among those meeting with Kohl were the Rev. Allan Boesak,
president of the World Alliance of Reformed Churches; Dr. Christian
Beyers-Naude, former head of the South African Council of Churches;
and Denis Hurley, the Roman Catholic archbishop of Durban.
   The church leaders complained of ``a lack of engagement in
Europe'' toward real attempts to pressure the Pretoria government
for change, according to a statement issued by the group.
   They demanded that European Economic Community nations reduce
the number of their diplomatic personnel in South Africa, place
increased economic pressure on Pretoria, institute stricter visa
requirements for South Africans wishing to visit Western Europe,
and take other measures.
   The group made its demands in Bonn because West Germany holds
the rotating Common Market presidency. The church group was
visiting West Germany separately from the apartheid opponents.
   Tha talks with the ANC were expected to focus on a political
program for anti-apartheid groups that do not participate in South
Africa's tri-cameral Parliament. It has separate chambers for
whites, Asians and people of mixed race, but there is no
representation for the nation's 26 million black majority.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the blacks have no vote in South African national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
