<HEAD>NATO Adviser Says Conventional Forces Must Be Improved</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with adviser's comments on
conventional forces. Pick up 2nd graf pvs: `On Wednesday...' Edits
thereafter to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO's chief military adviser said
today the U.S.-Soviet treaty to remove ground-launched,
intermediate-range nuclear missiles means NATO's conventional
forces must be improved.
   West German Gen. Wolfgang Altenburg, chairman of NATO's panel of
chiefs of staff, said he has found no evidence the Soviet Union
will cut back its military.
   ``They (the Soviets) are not able to define in which way their
strategy has changed from an admittedly offensive to a presently
defensive strategy,'' he said.
   Altenburg spoke after giving NATO defense ministers, at their
regular spring conference, a routine briefing on Soviet military
capabilities.
   He also predicted the NATO allies will formally ask Italy to
accept the transfer of 72 U.S. F-16 jetfighters that are to be
removed from Spain within three years.
   Sources said the ministers discussed how the transfer, estimated
to cost $500 million, should be funded. Altenburg said this would
likely be done through NATO's joint infrastructure program.
   ``I am quite sure that all members of the alliance agree that we
do this economically.''
   The 72 jetfighters, comprising the U.S. Air Force's 401st
Tactical Fighter Wing, are to be removed from the Torrejon Air Base
near Madrid under a January agreement between Spain and the United
States.
   Altenburg said the Soviet Union still views NATO as an offensive
alliance and that it shows no signs of reducing its military
outlays. ``There is no evidence whatsoever in that respect that
things have really changed.''
   He added that unabated growth in Soviet military outlays were
linked to the treaty under which hundreds of intermediate-range
nuclear missiles will be removed from Europe.
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev signed the
treaty Dec. 8 in Washington.
   ``We think that after the INF treaty, the need to maintain our
conventional posture ... is more important than ever,'' he said.
   U.S Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and his NATO colleagues
were meeting to review how the allies must share their common
defense costs and ways they can make better use of available funds.
   On Wednesday, the alliance's European defense chiefs complained
that some of the recent U.S. criticism about their contributions to
the alliance was unjustified.
   In a report, the ministers detailed their contributions to NATO,
countering U.S. congressional criticism that Europe fails to pull
its weight in the alliance.
   ``Europe is taking a fair share of the burdens in the
alliance,'' Dutch Defense Minister Wim van Eekelen, chairman of the
meeting of the European ministers, said later.
   The debate over who pays what in NATO stems from congressional
efforts to curb U.S. defense spending.
   The Europeans' report said that of NATO's standing forces,
Europe provides 90 percent of the troops and artillery, 80 percent
of the tanks and combat planes and 65 percent of NATO warships.
   It said 3.5 million European men and women are on active duty
and 3.5 million are in reserve. By comparison, the United States
has 2.3 million active duty troops and 1.5 million reservists, the
report said.
   In their report, NATO's European members agreed all allies must
do more for NATO, in part by better managing their budgets.
   The United States spent 6.7 percent of its gross national
product on defense in 1987 against an average of 3.3 percent for
the European allies.
   The Europeans argue the spending comparisons ignore
unquantifiable burdens for them, such as environmental damage from
allied maneuvers and loss of income from real estate dedicated to
military bases and other defense facilities.
</TEXT>
