<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoneProbe     05-26 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bone Probe,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Investigating Medical Examiner's Office Over Sale of
Bones</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The county's chief medical examiner is
the target of an investigation into allegations he improperly
earned more than $100,000 selling bones from the dead, the San
Antonio Light reported today.
   The Light said an unidentified source provided documents
detailing the sale of hundreds of bones since 1983 by Bexar County
Chief Medical Examiner Dr. Vincent DiMaio's.
   The bones, obtained from bodies taken to the county morgue, went
to the non-profit Bone Bank Foundation of San Antonio, where they
were cleaned, chopped into pieces and freeze-dried for
transplantation, mostly for back, dental or reconstructive surgery,
the newspaper reported.
   Survivors of the dead gave their consent, thinking the bones
were ``gifts of life'' to the foundation, but DiMaio charged up to
$200 for each bone removed, the Light reported.
   A secretary in DiMaio's office today said he would be out of the
office until next week.
   The alleged sideline business is under investigation by the
district attorney's office, the newspaper said.
   The investigation focuses on whether DiMaio legally could charge
the fees if he was extracting the bones on county time and using
county facilities and employees, a source outside the district
attorney's office told the Light.
   The newspaper said invoices it obtained indicate the foundation
paid DiMaio up to $10,000 per month for bones, but none of those
payments went to the county.
   The county has a formal agreement with the Bone Bank Foundation
to be paid $25 for every donor to cover basic organ-harvesting
costs.
</TEXT>
