<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Cuba-Bombing     05-26 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-Bombing,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Home of Cuba Conference Organizer Bombed, Hotel Cancels Event</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded today outside the home of a woman
organizing a controversial conference on the future of U.S.-Cuba
relations. No one was hurt.
   The hotel hosting the forum immediately canceled it.
   No one claimed responsibility for the blast at the home of Maria
Christina Herrera.
   Ms. Herrera, who has favored dialogue with the Cuban government,
said it appeared to be the work of anti-Castro militants.
   The 3 a.m. bombing mangled a garage door, damaged the corner of
the house and blew out the windows of a rental car parked in her
driveway.
   The bombing came 2{ hours after a meeting at Ms. Herrera's house
ended early today with the conference organizers deciding to
exclude a representative of the unofficial Cuban Human Rights
Commission, Elizardo Sanchez Santacruz. He is a former political
prisoner who was given permission by the Castro government to set
up his organization, making him suspect among anti-communists here.
   Bill Ripple, general manager of the Sheraton-Brickell Point
Hotel, said the hotel canceled today's conference ``based on the
best interests of our employees and guests because of the recent
incidents, including the bombing.''
   A demonstration against the conference had been scheduled across
the street.
   Ms. Herrera, 53, is a professor at Miami-Dade Community College
and a founder of the Institute of Cuban Studies, an organization
dedicated to the free exchange of ideas with Cuba. She said she
wanted the conference to go on as planned.
   ``This was only to intimidate,'' she said. ``If they had wanted
to hurt me, they would have thrown it through my bedroom window.''
   The bomb was a ``relatively small explosive device,'' said Coral
Gables police Sgt. Dennis Koronkiewicz.
   FBI spokesman Dennis Erich said the agency is investigating.
</TEXT>
