<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CatholicEducation 1stLd-Writethru a0491 05-26 0847</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Catholic Education, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0491,0862</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic School Educators Try To Stem Declining Enrollment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `Instead, they ...,' with three grafs to
UPDATE with consensus statements. Picks up in 6th graf, `Only a
...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catholic educators, still facing a retreat
in parochial school enrollment, are looking toward a future in
which religious education programs outside school loom even larger.
   Indeed, at a week-long symposium on the future of Catholic
education that ends today, most of the discussion centered on
programs that reach out to children and adults outside the
traditional school structure.
   There was virtually no debate at the Catholic Education Futures
Project sessions about how to stem the erosion of parochial
schools, which lost 110 more schools and 103,000 students last year
alone. There are now 2.6 million students in 8,992 Catholic
schools, down from a peak of 5.6 million in more than 13,000
schools in 1964.
   Even before adjourning, the nearly 300 educators at the
conference had decided against trying to finish writing a ``vision
statement'' on their church's educational mission for the next
century.
   But asked to identify the most important elements of Catholic
education, they gave strongest support to the declaration,
``Catholic education exists to proclaim the gospel, to promote
lifelong personal growth and faith formation of all peoples, and to
support the mission of the church.''
   Other priority items included promoting ``respect for all
cultures which make up our pluralistic society,'' eliminating
sexism and racism, paying particular concern to education of the
poor, and making better use of ``our changing resources.''
   The actual writing of the final document was to done later by
representatives of the 22 church groups at the meeting held at the
University of Dayton.
   Only a quarter of the educators at the symposium are involved in
parochial schools. Others work with young adults, converts, college
students and Catholic children from public school.
   Historically, the public school child who attended weekly
religion classes ``was considered a second class citizen,'' said
Bishop James Malone of Youngstown.
   But now, archdioceses around the country are installing paid,
full-time directors of religious education, like Janet Kayser, a
laywoman who runs the programs for St. Thomas Parish in Crystal
Lake, Ill.
   ``When the topic of Catholic education comes up, there's too
much emphasis in thinking it means only schools,'' said Kayser, who
has 650 students in her programs.
   In some places, she said, ``there has been a real injustice in
balancing'' between the needs of the school and the religious
education program.
   The Rev. Thomas Lynch, pastor of St. James Church in Bridgeport,
Conn., said only 280 of the 2,900 families in his parish send
children to the parochial school, but the school, with a $530,000
budget, consumes half the parish revenues.
   Lynch is trying to rename the school the St. James Center for
Religious Formation to stress some of his parish's prayer classes,
scripture study and other educational activities, but he admits his
parishioners ``get nervous'' about such a change.
   Lynch said Catholic schools must emphasize the teaching of faith
``just as much as geography, math or anything else.'' There is no
reason to operate a parochial school that ``smells like and looks
like the public school except for maybe a course in religion and an
amorphous Catholic environment,'' he said.
   Bishop Francis Schulte of West Virginia, who heads the bishops'
committee on education, said in an interview, ``I believe there's
no adequate substitute for the full curriculum Catholic school.''
But he acknowledged that there are ``very substantial areas'' where
Catholic parents simply don't have a parochial school available.
   To those who would like to see the church shift more resources
into other religion education efforts, Schulte said, ``There's a
fallacy ... that if the Catholic school was not present in a
parish, then all or most of that money would then go into other
educational programs.'' Most of the money is in the form of tuition
that would disappear with the school, he said.
   Parochial schools flourished in big cities with immigrants from
Catholic lands like Ireland, Italy and Poland. When Catholics
became more affluent and moved to the suburbs, churches followed,
but schools did not.
   ``We have buildings in places where we don't have Catholic
children, and we have Catholic children in places where we don't
have schools,'' said Sister Lourdes Sheehan, of the National
Catholic Educational Association, a sponsor of the symposium.
   Malone said, ``The genius of the meeting has to be to affirm the
continued importance and place of the Catholic school ... but then
acknowledge generously and fully that these other activities and
ministries are a part of Catholic education.''
   ``Ideally, the Catholic school is the best vehicle we've had for
helping parents teach values in the Catholic tradition,'' said
Malone.
   But ``we've never had more than 50 percent of our kids in
Catholic schools,'' he added. ``What happens if you can't have a
Cadillac, you certainly find out you can fix up the Volkswagen
pretty well and get along with that.''
</TEXT>
