<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SAfrica-Blast 7thLd-Writethru   05-26 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Blast, 7th Ld-Writethru,a0614,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Bombs Explode in Downtown Pretoria, Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS grafs 6-10, `There was...white-led government.' to
UPDATE with Cabinet minister condemning white delegation meeting
with ANC. Pick up 11th pvs, `The ANC...'
^By GREG MYRE</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs exploded in downtown
Pretoria today and injured four whites as the National Party marked
40 years in power. A Cabinet minster blamed the outlawed African
National Congress guerrilla movement.
   The attacks in the South African capital coincided with
anniversary celebrations by President P.W. Botha's party,
responsible for the country's apartheid legislation. The National
Party has led the government since the whites-only election of May
26, 1948.
   Four white women, all librarians in their 30s, were returning
from lunch when a bomb exploded in a flowerpot at a busy street
corner.
   One woman lost an arm, a second suffered back injuries and the
other two had extensive facial burns, according to a statement from
H.F. Verwoerd Hospital.
   About five minutes earlier, a bomb placed under a parked car
exploded several blocks away. The car was completely destroyed, but
there were no injuries.
   Witnesses said earlier that at least five people were injured in
one blast and that one or two may have been killed, but there was
no confirmation of fatalities.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility. Law and Order
Minister Adriaan Vlok blamed the African National Congress, which
wages a bombing and sabotage campaign in a bid to overthrow the
white-led government.
   The ANC, based in Lusaka, Zambia, generally does not confirm or
deny any role in the attacks.
   Vlok also condemned a trip by white South African anti-apartheid
politicians who are meeting today and Friday with ANC leaders in
Frankfurt, West Germany. The group is led by Wynand Malan, a member
of Parliament and leader of the National Democratic Movement.
   Vlok said it was ``ironic'' that bombings were taking place at
the same time ``people such as Wynand Malan ... are busy holding
talks with this unscrupulous terror organization.''
   The government opposes all contact with the ANC and says it will
not negotiate with the organization until it disavows violence.
   There have been more than 70 bomb blasts in South Africa since a
nationwide state of emergency was declared in June 1986, although
the number of explosions has fallen sharply in the past year.
   The police have blamed virtually all the blasts on the ANC.
   The ANC did claim responsibility for deadliest bombing in South
African history. The May 20, 1983, blast in Pretoria killed 19 and
injured about 200.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
