<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UntechnicallyDead     05-26 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Untechnically Dead,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Body Exhumed Because of Technicality</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities don't suspect foul play in the death
of a 79-year-old woman but will exhume her remains more than a
month after the funeral on a technicality _ she was buried without
a signed death certificate.
   Cook County Circuit Judge Kenneth Gillis ordered the exhumation
and an autopsy because the burial of Marie R. Drake was illegal and
her estate can't be closed without a death certificate, officials
said Wednesday.
   ``Imagine putting yourself in the children's position _ having
buried their mother a month ago and then suddenly finding out the
death certificate was never signed,'' said Elliott Robbins, an
attorney for Mrs. Drake's children, Ronald Drake and Marion Sottile.
   ``They thought they had laid their mother to rest and now she
has to be dragged up again,'' he said Wednesday. ``It's a very,
very gut-wrenching experience. I don't know how this could have
happened.''
   Mrs. Drake was found dead, apparently of natural causes, in her
home in suburban Elmwood Park on April 14, a Thursday, said Sean
Fitzgerald, an assistant Cook County state's attorney.
   The county medical examiner's office was not called because
police didn't suspect foul play, and the family doctor was expected
to sign the death certificate, said Roy Dames, administrator in the
examiner's office.
   But the funeral home couldn't get in touch with the doctor over
the weekend and a funeral was planned for Monday morning, said
funeral director Steven Lewis.
   Lewis said that he knew that burying a body without a death
certificate is a violation of the law but that the funeral home
decided to proceed with the funeral anyway, believing the doctor
would sign the document after the fact.
   However, Dr. Charles Shallat refused to sign, apparently because
he hadn't seen Mrs. Drake as a patient in four years, said
Fitzgerald. Shallat did not return a message left with his
answering service Wednesday.
   The family didn't discover the problem until they began trying
to settle her estate in county Probate Court, said Robbins.
   Like the doctor, the medical examiner's office refused to sign
the certificate without inspecting the body.
   ``We can't tell what the cause of death is without looking at
the body. She might have a gunshot wound to the head for all I
know,'' said Dames.
   Fitzgerald said he didn't know whether charges would be filed
against the funeral home.
</TEXT>
