<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Seat Belts,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airliner's Safety Belts May Have Snapped in Turbulence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal inspectors are testing seat belts
on a Braniff airliner that reportedly snapped or loosened, injuring
four passengers, when the aircraft was buffeted by stormy weather
near Orlando.
   The belts will be tested to determine whether they were faulty
or improperly installed, said Jeff Kennedy, air safety investigator
with the National Transportation Safety Board.
   Three adults and a baby carried by one of them were treated at
an Orlando hospital Tuesday for minor injuries after the landing of
the twin-engine BAC-111, Braniff Flight 723 from Indianapolis to
Orlando.
   ``Seat belts coming loose _ that's not common,'' Kennedy said
Wednesday.
   Braniff said the aircraft was inspected and returned to service
Wednesday.
   Jack Barker, spokesman for the FAA in Atlanta, said the company
was responsible for replacing the three seat belts and inspecting
remaining safety belts before allowing the plane to fly again.
