<DOCNO> AP880526-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Summit-Bush     05-26 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Bush,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Summit Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Superpower Summit Seen as Having Little Value for Bush Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush is likely to
benefit only indirectly from President Reagan's summit next week
with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, scholars and political
observers say.
   Whereas Bush had a role in the Washington summit last December,
the vice president will be far from the Moscow drama, meeting
privately with Republican Party leaders at his home in
Kennebunkport, Maine.
   Bush, as many may remember, stood at Gorbachev's side during an
improptu stop the Soviet leader made at a Washington street corner.
   The Moscow summit may present for Bush another in the series of
Catch-22-type problems that have followed his quest for the White
House. The thinking is that if something goes wrong in Moscow, Bush
will be held as accountable as Reagan. But if there is some
surprising positive development, the American people will give
Reagan credit.
   ``The truth is, he probably should gain something from the
summit and he probably won't,'' said Larry Sabato, a presidential
scholar at the University of Virginia.
   ``I just don't think it's going to make any difference for him
because he's not going there,'' Sabato said. ``Besides, he seems to
be having all the good things (in the Reagan record) roll off, and
all the bad things stick, these days.''
   But Bush's campaign aides hope the vice presient gets some
advantage from the Reagan-Gorbachev summit.
   Communications director Peter Teeley said that ``whatever you
get out of the thing is going to depend on the accomplishments, the
mood and the tone.''
   Sabato, Teeley and others said Bush will almost surely benefit,
to a certain degree, if the summit proceeds without incident or
problems. They said that he would be credited with being a part of
an administration that is advancing the prospects of peace and
easing tensions with the Soviets.
   ``Much of the American public believes that relations between
these two countries are getting better, so the (Bush) experience
factor is important,'' Teeley said.
   Bush, in fact, met with Gorbachev before Gorbachev ascended to
the top Kremlin position, and the vice president attended the
funerals of fallen Kremlin leaders Leonid Brezhnev, Yuri Andropov
and Konstantin Chernenko.
   On the campaign trail, he's fond of telling how he observed
Brezhnev's wife doing the sign of the cross as she hovered over his
dead body.
   During the December summit, Bush made a big play over his
one-on-one meeting with Gorbachev at the Soviet Embassy. Pictures
were taken as the pair sat smiling on a sofa, and the Bush campaign
depicted the vice president as a person who would provide
continuity in U.S. dealings with the Soviets.
   Stephen Wayne, a presidential scholar at George Washington
University, said the chief advantage the summit presents to Bush is
that ``it basically takes a critical issue from the Democrats _ the
fear of war with the Soviet Union. It takes a scary world and makes
it less scary.''
   But Wayne said Bush would gain a much greater advantage if he
were to attend the summit, and said modern communications and other
precautions could remove the obstacles to both the president and
vice president being together on foreign soil.
   But he said ``I don't see the people around the president being
willing to share the glory'' with Bush if there is some stunning
accomplishment there.
   ``We know that the vice president is in the worst of all
possible situations,'' Wayne said., ``He cannot take credit for the
administration's successes and he has to share the blame for its
failures.''
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, a former aide when Bush was U.S.
ambassador to the United Nations, claimed it was Bush who talked
the West German government into accepting Pershing II missiles,
even though there was a burgeoning anti-nuclear movement in that
country and Chancellor Helmut Kohl was under tremendous political
pressure.
   U.S. officials have said they believe the Soviets would never
have come to the table to negotiate an intermediate-range missile
treaty had it not been for the willingness of West Germany and
other North Atlantic allies to have U.S. missiles placed on their
soil.
   Leach said that because ``the personal dimensions of summits are
almost always presidential,'' it would be difficult for Bush to get
close enough to center stage to get a big political bounce at home.
   Sabato said, ``If politics were fair, I think he ought to get
some credit, just because the summit is happening. But he won't.''
</TEXT>
