<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-USRelations     05-26 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-US Relations,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kremlin Advisers Paint Hopeful Backdrop for Reagan Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior Kremlin advisers urged superpower leaders
Thursday to bury remaining Cold War differences and praised
President Reagan's comment that he heads to Moscow on a mission of
peace.
   The task at next week's summit is to bury ``this corpse of the
Cold War, which with the help of artificial means ... has been
maintained in a semi-living state,'' said U.S. affairs expert
Georgy A. Arbatov, one of several foreign affairs advisers who
predicted improved U.S.-Soviet relations in a meeting with
reporters.
   The state-run press also painted a rosy picture of superpower
ties. The labor newspaper Trud invoked U.S. public opinion in
pressing for a successful summit, claiming most Americans want
better relations with the Soviets. And Socialist Industry declared
that the two nations have entered a ``political thaw.''
   Reagan arrives Sunday for five days of meetings with Mikhail S.
Gorbachev. It will be the fourth summit between the two leaders.
   ``Previously, our goals were more limited,'' said Arbatov,
observing that Reagan and Gorbachev in the past focused on easing
tensions built up since World War II.
   ``Now we have the possibility to move toward demilitarization of
Soviet-American relations,'' he said.
   Asked about Reagan's comment Wednesday that he viewed his
journey to the Soviet capital as a mission of peace, Arbatov smiled
and replied: ``I think there is something symbolic in this, that
Reagan is now coming with an olive branch to Moscow.''
   He said his view of Reagan had changed from that of a Cold
Warrior to a statesman. But Arbatov said Reagan had brought about
the improvement by coming around to the Soviet way of thinking on
disarmament and international relations.
   Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev, military chief of staff and first
deputy defense minister, joined in the spirit of ``new thinking,''
as the Kremlin refers to the force behind its foreign policy shifts
over the three years since Gorbachev came to power.
   Akhromeyev declared himself a ``completely different person'' as
a result of Gorbachev's reforms and said many other officials are
experiencing the same feeling.
   But he clung to standard Kremlin positions alleging that there
is no Soviet superiority in conventional weapons in Europe or
excessive spending on arms. But asked for details on Soviet defense
spending, Akhromeyev made the rare acknowledgement that the
reported defense budget does not reflect spending on research,
development and production of weapons.
   Akhromeyev declined to say how much of the Soviet Union's gross
national product is invested in defense, claiming he was privy only
to the budget approved by the Supreme Soviet, which amounts to
about 5 percent of government spending. That would put it at about
$33.9 billion.
   Western estimates have put Soviet defense spending as high as 19
percent of the gross national product, which measures the value of
all goods and services produced in a nation.
   Arbatov dismissed foreign assessments as ``speculation'' but
said Soviet spending on the military is proportionally higher than
in the United States because the Soviet gross national product is
lower, while the demands of security are equal.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Vladimir F. Petrovsky told reporters
that the talks would help in ``overcoming the heritage of the Cold
War.''
   All of the advisers contended that the Reagan-Gorbachev meetings
could produce important advances in negotiations toward a treaty
that would halve U.S. and Soviet strategic nuclear arsenals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
