<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RossAppeal     05-26 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ross Appeal,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Throws Out Murder Conviction Over Exclusion of Blacks From
Jury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has thrown out the 1974
murder conviction of a black death-row inmate in the slaying of a
white policeman, ruling that blacks and women were improperly
excluded from the jury.
   Willie X. Ross, now 48, was convicted by a Colquitt County jury
of 12 white men in the shooting death of Moultrie police Lt. Tommie
Meredith.
   U.S. District Judge Dudley H. Bowen, in a ruling made public
Wednesday, said blacks and women were intentionally excluded from
the pools used in selecting the grand jury that indicted him and
the trial jury that convicted him.
   The judge said there is no evidence that the lack of blacks and
women was due to ``neutral selection criteria and procedures.''
   Lamar Cole, district attorney in the state's Southern Judicial
Circuit, said he will seek to re-indict Ross.
   Ross, a native of Jacksonville, Fla., was scheduled for
execution after Georgia's new capital punishment law was upheld by
the U.S. Supreme Court in 1976, but the condemned man's appeals
delayed the execution.
   Ross' younger brother, Theodore Ross, testified at his trial
that Ross was the trigger man in the slaying. Theodore Ross served
a prison term for kidnapping and robbery and was released in 1987.
   Two other men convicted in the slaying, Freddie Lee King and
Rudolph Alonzo Turner, are serving life sentences.
</TEXT>
