<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MistakenIdentity     05-26 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mistaken Identity,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Shoots Woman By Mistake, Kills Himself</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUNTERSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man shot a woman he apparently
mistook for his wife, offered to take her to a hospital, then
killed himself with a shot to the head, authorities said.
   ``We're going on the assumption that it was a case of mistaken
identity,'' Marshall County sheriff's Capt. Randy Amos said after
the shootings Wednesday.
   Officials said Ernest Michael Bowman, 32, shot Marsha Lynn
Atchley, 26, at Lake Guntersville. She was in fair condition
Thursday at Carraway Methodist Medical Center.
   ``I think he realized just what a mistake he had made, and he
couldn't handle that,'' police Lt. Carl Fulmer said.
   Ms. Atchley, of Arab, told witnesses she had never before seen
the man who shot her once in the chest with a .32-caliber pistol.
   Witnesses said the woman was in a bathing suit and lying on a
chaise lounge at a lake when Bowman drove up, walked over to her
and knelt beside her.
   ``One witness said he heard the woman scream and then heard a
gunshot,'' Amos said. ``She begged Bowman not to shoot her again,
and he told her it was all a mistake and then asked her if he could
take her to the hospital.''
   Ms. Atchley refused and walked to her car and got in, Amos said,
while Bowman walked back to his truck.
   Fulmer said Bowman traveled about one-third of a mile, then
``pulled out a gun and shot himself in the head while the truck was
moving.'' He said the truck traveled about 300 more yards before
stopping in a ditch.
   Bowman apparently was upset that a warrant charging him with
parole violation was issued Wednesday. If convicted, he would have
faced serving the remaining three years of a 10-year sentence for
the Aug. 23, 1980, robbery of a package store.
   He was paroled about a year ago and had fulfilled all the
requirements of his parole until this month, parole Officer Bobby
Roberts said. On May 3, Roberts said, he was arrested and charged
with public intoxication, assault and harassment of his wife.
   He was found guilty on May 9. Roberts said that was sufficient
cause to revoke his parole and issue a warrant for his arrest.
</TEXT>
