<DOCNO> AP880526-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArmsTreaty 2ndLd-Writethru a0606 05-26 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Treaty, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0606,760</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf pvs, The Senate, to show amendment approved</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate negotiators worked today to clear away
the remaining obstacles to a U.S.-Soviet treaty banning
medium-range nuclear missiles and headed toward almost certain
approval of the first arms-control treaty to be ratified in 16
years.
   Meetings on the remaining issues resumed today between the
Senate's leaders and senior members of the Foreign Relations, Armed
Services and Intelligence committees.
   ``I'm very optimistic about finishing this matter,'' said Senate
Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., who noted that the areas of
disagreement had been whittled down to two or three. ``I'm
confident that everybody is going in the same direction,'' he said.
   The Senate, on a vote of 96-0, today approved an amendment
incorporating into the treaty agreements reached two weeks ago in
Geneva by Secretary of State George Shultz and Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze, dealing with warheads using
``futuristic'' technology and clarifying on-site verification rules.
   Leaders had conferred late into Wednesday night in an effort to
settle what appeared to be the thorniest dispute, one between the
administration and the Senate over possible future reinterpretation
of the treaty.
   ``We're not there yet, but we've made a good deal of progress,''
said Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.
   A key to progress on the treaty was the decision on Wednesday by
the leading opponent of the pact, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., to drop
his delaying tactics. Helms said he did so in the face of a
probable vote by the Senate to shut off debate.
   ``That was the end of it,'' Helms conceded in a floor speech.
``I've had no illusions about defeating this treaty. The American
people are beginning to understand that this is a dangerous
treaty.''
   Helms' concession ended more than a week of delay and raised
hopes that the accord could be approved in time to be shipped to
Moscow so that President Reagan could formally exchange
ratification documents with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev at
the summit meeting that begins Sunday.
   The primary remaining issue did not affect the treaty itself,
but the modified conditions under which the Senate would grant its
consent.
   Democrats sought to attach a condition stipulating that any
attempt by a future president to reinterpret the treaty would have
to be approved by the Senate in order to become effective.
   Backers of the change have said it is an attempt to preserve the
Senate's constitutional power of advise and consent on treaties.
The debate stems from a dispute with the Reagan administration over
its attempt to reinterpret the 1972 Antiballistic Missile Treaty to
permit more latitude in developing Reagan's Star Wars missile
defense.
   That treaty with the Soviet Union was the last arms-control pact
to win Senate approval.
   The treaty on intermediate-range nuclear forces, which Reagan
and Gorbachev signed in Washington on Dec. 8, requires elimination
within three years of U.S. and Soviet nuclear missiles with a range
of 300 miles to 3,400 miles. It would result in the elimination of
867 U.S. missiles in Europe and elimination of 1,752 Soviet
missiles.
   While the treaty is regarded as militarily insignificant because
it leaves most of both sides' nuclear arsenals intact, it holds
potentially great political significance as a model for a follow-up
treaty to provide for deep cuts in long-range nuclear missiles.
   As leaders wrangled throughout the day Wednesday in an effort to
clear remaining procedural hurdles, the Senate approved a pair of
relatively mild amendments to the accord and overwhelmingly
defeated two others.
   On a voice vote, the lawmakers approved a non-binding provision
urging negotiators in future talks on reductions in long-range
missile arsenals not to give up the U.S. right to maintain stocks
of conventionally armed air- and sea-launched cruise missiles.
   And the Senate urged the president to keep human rights in the
forefront of U.S.-Soviet relations and ``insist on sustained and
demonstrable human rights progress.'' That language was added on a
voice vote.
   Helms was rebuffed in an attempt to add a provision stipulating
that if either side provided ``materially misleading or false
data,'' the other side would be free to withdraw from the treaty.
The amendment failed on a vote of 89-9.
   And Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., failed on a 69-28 vote to win
an exemption from the ban for conventionally armed cruise missiles.
Hollings argued that keeping such missiles in the allied arsenal
would help offset Warsaw Pact superiority in conventional forces,
but opponents pointed out it would be impossible to verify that the
missiles were not nuclear-tipped.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-TestBan Bjt   05-26 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Test Ban, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Technology Sensitive Enough To Monitor All But Smallest Nuclear
Blasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seismic technology is sensitive enough to
confidently monitor all but the smallest Soviet underground nuclear
tests, a congressional scientific study said Thursday.
   The conclusions could help to reach a ban on all underground
testing, one of the unresolved issues between the two superpowers,
said Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla., chairman of the House Foreign
Affairs Committee.
   Fascell called the study ``an important contribution'' to the
effort to develop a test ban.
   The study, carried out by the Office of Technology Assessment,
an arm of Congress, was released as President Reagan rested in
Helsinki, Finland, while en route to the Soviet Union.
   Reagan will travel to Moscow this weekend for his fourth summit
with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, and one of the issues on
the agenda is underground nuclear testing.
   The two leaders are expected to sign a pair of protocols
designed to improve monitoring procedures.
   Open-air tests are banned by a 1963 treaty, while two separate
treaties, signed in 1974 and 1976, limit underground tests to 150
kilotons. Both sides claim to adhere to the 1970s accords, although
neither treaty has been formally ratified by the U.S. Senate.
   Reagan has promised to submit the pacts to the Senate if
adequate verification procedures can be worked out. The two
protocols will set the ground rules for joint experiments this
summer in Nevada and Semipalatinsk to measure the force of
detonations.
   The Soviets want to use seismic monitoring systems, similar to
the kind used to watch for earthquakes. The United States prefers a
system known as CORRTEX, which involves inserting a cable in a
shaft about 30 feet from the test hole and taking measuresment from
it.
   The OTA study said ``seismology now provides a means to monitor
underground nuclear explosions down to low yields, even when
strenuous attempts are made to evade the monitoring systems. By
doing so, seismology plays a central role in verifying arms control
agreements that limit the testing of nuclear weapons.''
   Seismic monitoring systems, even if none of the stations are in
the Soviet Union, can readily monitor tests down to the 10-kiloton
level ``with high confidence,'' the study said.
   In fact, ``expert opinion about the lowest yields that could
reliably be monitored ranges from 1 kiloton to 10 kilotons,'' the
study said.
   One kiloton has the explosive force of 1,000 tons of TNT. The
U.S. atomic bomb dropped Aug. 6, 1945 on Hiroshima, Japan, had an
explosive force of about 20 kilotons.
   Once a seismic signal is detected by the underground monitoring
stations, OTA said, its source could be reliably tracked down.
   ``Over 90 percent of all seismic events in the U.S.S.R can be
classified as earthquakes simply becuase they are either toop dee
or not in a plausible location for a nuclear explosion,'' the study
said. ``The combination of all methods, when applied in a
comprehensive approach, can differentiate between with explosions,
down to low yields, and earthquakes.''
   The report also looked at a comprehensive test ban, saying it
``could be considered adequately verifiable if it were determined
that the advantage of such a treaty would outweigh the significance
of any undetected clandestine testing belo the monitoring
threshold.''
   A total test ban has long been a goal of U.S. arms control
advocates and the Soviets have recently backed such a restriction.
For 18 months ending in February 1987 the Soviets unilaterally
suspended all testing, but the Reagan administration declined to
join the moratorium.
   In each of the past two years, the House has voted to ban atomic
tests above the one-kilton level, but the Senate rejected such a
ban and the White House has strongly opposed the limitation.
   OTA suggested that a phased approach could be adopted setting
the first step at 10 kilotons.
   ``This is a level that can currently be well monitored
seismically,'' the study said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
