<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru   05-26 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0454,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas and Contra Rebels Begin New Round of Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with nine grafs to UPDATE with talks starting. Pick up
4th pvs, `The rebels...' Edits to trim and conform thereafter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebel and Sandinista government
leaders started a new round of talks today aimed at ending their
6{-year war, and the rebels said they were proposing a peace plan
focusing on democratic reforms.
   The rebels, who have been supported by the U.S. government, said
they would lay down their arms and rejoin the political life of the
country if the Sandinistas guarantee democratization.
   At the center of the proposal is the demand that the Sandinistas
ease their control over the army and government. The rebels, also
known as Contras, also ask for constitional reforms, freedom of
expression and freedom of the press.
   ``We are not optimistic,'' however, said Alfredo Cesar, leader
of the Nicaraguan Resistance rebel delegation.
   Gen. Humberto Ortega, the nation's defense minister, led the
government delegation to the third round of top-level peace talks
held in Managua.
   Tight security was in effect at the Camino Real Hotel, where the
negotiators met. The witnesses are Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel
Obando y Bravo and Joao Baena Soares, secretary general of the
Organization of American States.
   The rebel plan sets a flexible timetable that eventually would
have Contra fighters lay down their arms before Christmas.
   The government said it was ready to offer political reforms to
guarantee clean elections. It offered to give congressional
representation to parties not in the National Assembly, to set a
timetable for municipal and other elections, and to change the
makeup of the electoral council to assure ``pluralistic
representation.''
   Cesar told reporters late Wednesday, ``We have come here to
present a comprehensive proposal to the government for a global
solution to the war.''
   The rebels, he said, were prepared to make a ``special effort to
achieve a definitive cease-fire.''
   But he said he was not optimistic because the government has not
complied with a preliminary peace plan worked out March 23 in
Sapoa, a small village on the Costa Rican border.
   The rebel delegation arrived Wednesday evening, ending a dispute
over where the talks would be held.
   The rebels had refused to return to Managua, the site of two
previous sessions. They complained the government restricted their
access to opposition political leaders.
   The government insisted the talks be held in the capital and
agreed to let the rebels meet with the opposition Nicaraguan
Democratic Coordinate and visit the Roman Catholic bishops'
conference, the opposition newspaper La Prensa and relatives.
   Col. Enrique Bermudez, the rebel military leader, arrived from
Tegucigalpa, Honduras, to take part in the negotiations, marking
his first trip to Managua since the war started in late 1981.
   ``My presence here is due to the fact that I'm a Nicaraguan and
that I'm opposed to the state of affairs in Nicaragua,'' he told a
news conference.
   ``I have come here to try to see Sapoa fulfilled, to discuss a
cease-fire and an end to the war because this is my country,'' he
said.
   In Washington, Wilson Morris, an aide to House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas, said on Tuesday the rebels planned to offer to
disarm themselves by Sept. 1.
   The two sides earlier agreed to a 60-day cease-fire to give them
time to arrange a permanent truce. The cease-fire was to expire on
May 30, but President Daniel Ortega announced earlier in the week
that he would extend it for an additional 30 days.
   Cesar told reporters the rebels do not want repeated extensions
of the cease-fire, but rather a permanent halt to the fighting.
   If the cease-fire ends on May 30, he said, the rebels will take
up ``defensive positions'' but will not break the truce.
   Ortega says the war has killed 26,500 people and caused $3
billion in damage to the economy.
   A major obstacle to agreement has been the question of how
non-lethal aid will be delivered to rebels gathered in cease-fire
zones inside Nicaragua.
   Under the Sapoa agreement, the aid was to come through a neutral
international organization. Contras insisted in the talks that they
had the right to choose the organization.
   Contra leaders were quoted as saying they would accept a
proposal for delivery of humanitarian aid to their forces inside
Nicaragua by an agency with ties to the Organization of American
States.
</TEXT>
