<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BishopCollege     05-26 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishop College,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Allows Bishop College Time to Reorganize Fund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN FAHLGREN-TORRES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small, Southern Baptist college has won a
reprieve from liquidation, but will have to come up with a plan by
June 3 to repay its $20 million debt, a federal judge has ordered.
   Bankruptcy Judge Robert McGuire acted in response to a motion
from Bishop College's attorneys to quash his March order that would
have changed the college's status from Chapter 11 reorganization to
Chapter 7 liquidation as of Wednesday. That would have closed the
107-year-old, predominantly black school.
   McGuire said Wednesday he would set a hearing on the
reorganization plan for creditors for the week of June 27, with a
confirmation hearing the week of July 25.
   The plan would take effect Aug. 15 and school officials promised
they would raise enough money to pay for the entire 1988-89 school
year. Officials said without that money in hand, Bishop would not
open in the fall.
   ``In order for the community to regain confidence, we need to
show we are fiscally responsible,'' said Trip Finley, a Bishop
attorney. ``But we not only have to convince our creditors, but
also the Southern Baptist Association.'' He said Bishop will be
re-evaluated by the association this fall for its accreditation.
   In March, McGuire ruled the 300-student college could remain
open on the condition officials raised at least $50,000 every two
weeks. The ruling further stipulated that without a substantial
change in the college's finances, Bishop would be ordered to
liquidate its assets to repay $20 million owed 400 creditors.
   School officials say Bishop has raised more than $617,000 in two
months and has pledges for $158,000 more.
   Finley said it will take seven to 10 years to repay all the
school's debts.
   The college has failed to meet Chapter 11 obligations to keep
all bills current, said George McElreath, the U.S trustee
overseeing the case. But he conceded the school had complied with
the $50,000 bi-monthly payments since March and officials seemed
willing to work out the remaining debt.
   Judith Swift, who represents the Faculty and Staff Committee,
said she was concerned that faculty members had not been paid about
$500,000 in back salary and wages.
   But Finley said a $125,000 payment to the salaries was made
Wednesday and that school officials hoped to pay $122,000 more _
the usual payroll _ from the next funds received.
</TEXT>
