<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hastings-Impeach 1stLd-Writethru a0475 05-26 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hastings-Impeach, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0475,780</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with testimony; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
Borders refused.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An FEB agent told a congressional hearing
today the government did not entrap U.S. District Judge Alcee L.
Hastings when it was investigating allegations of bribery involving
him and a Washington lawyer.
   William J. Murphy Jr., who headed the FBI's investigation in the
case, said the federal government attempted to determine the truth
of the allegations made by an informant who said Washington lawyer
William A. Borders had bragged that he could bribe several judges,
including Hastings.
   ``We were only trying to prove or disprove what (the informant)
said,'' Murphy told a House judiciary subcommittee holding
impeachment hearings on Hastings.
   Rep. Patrick L. Swindall, R-Ga., said the FBI had no evidence
against Hastings, only the informant's statement about Borders.
``Isn't this a classic textbook entrapment?'' he asked.
   Borders was arrested after an undercover agent allegedly gave
him $120,000 in $100 bills in Washington to bribe Hastings into
giving a lenient sentence to two men on trial before him in Miami.
   ``Would there have been a crime had the federal government not
given Borders the money?'' Swindall asked.
   Murphy said Borders approached the informant ``and he laid out
to (him) what he would be able to do.''
   Murphy said the undercover meeting with Borders, when the money
was exchanged, ``was a tool to respond to (the informant's)
allegations. If Borders didn't show up at the meeting and didn't
say the things he did, the case would have stopped.
   ``The information we were trying to prove or disprove was that
Borders and Judge Hastings were going to do a crime,'' he said.
``We didn't decide one day in the office to get Judge Hastings.''
   Borders refused to testify Wednesday at a House Judiciary
subcommittee's televised impeachment proceedings against Hastings,
citing his Fifth Amendment guarantee against self-incrimination.
   After serving 33 months of a five-year sentence in federal
prison, paying a $35,000 fine and being disbarred by the District
of Columbia Court of Appeals, Borders said, ``I believe that my
legal debt to society expired on May 22, 1988, after my release
from parole.''
   Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., the chairman of the inquiry,
said the subcommittee will decide later whether to grant Borders
immunity from prosecution and compel his testimony.
   Hastings was acquitted five years ago of conspiring with Borders
to solicit a bribe from two convicted racketeers, Frank and Tom
Romano, in exchange for the promise of a lenient sentence.
   But a special five-judge investigative panel of the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals concluded in September 1986 there was
``clear and convincing evidence'' that Hastings committed the crime
and tried to conceal his role by lying under oath and manufacturing
evidence at his trial.
   Hastings insists that he knew nothing of the bribery plot and
accuses Borders of using his name in an attempt to shake down the
Romano brothers.
   Hastings was allowed Wednesday to cross-examine the two fellow
judges who filed misconduct charges against him six weeks after his
acquittal.
   One of them, U.S. District Judge William Terrell Hodges of
Tampa, Fla., said it was a ``gut-wrenching decision'' to file the
complaint, and U.S. District Judge Anthony A. Alaimo of Brunswick,
Ga., said Hodges was ``on the verge of tears.''
   Retorted Hastings: ``I've cried a lot, Tony.''
   Hastings, who is Florida's first black federal judge, has
charged repeatedly that his prosecution was racially and
politically motivated. But Hodges told the subcommittee that
Hastings' race had ``absolutely not'' any bearing on his decision
to file a complaint.
   Conyers, laying the groundwork for Murphy's testimony, said it
was ``amazing'' that FBI agents arrested Borders and seized
$125,000 in bribe money before Borders had a chance to pass it
along to anyone else.
   Hastings was staying at a hotel a couple of miles away when
Borders was arrested Oct. 9, 1981, inside a car with the payoff
money supplied by an FBI undercover agent posing as Frank Romano.
   The judicial panel said that when Hastings learned of Borders'
arrest, he hurriedly flew back to Miami from a Baltimore airport
because he wanted to avoid questioning by FBI agents.
   John Doar, chief counsel to the judicial panel, said there was
sufficient circumstantial evidence to implicate Hastings in a
conspiracy. But he agreed with Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., that the
case against Hastings would have been ``almost impregnable'' if he
had actually received bribe money from Borders.
   A few hours after Borders' arrest, Hastings was to have appeared
at a boating party given by lawyer friends in Borders' honor.
</TEXT>
