<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     05-26 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Seminary Student Stabbed in Jerusalem's Old City</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Plea cq as first name of Mrs. Albeck</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old Jewish seminary student walking
through Jerusalem's walled old city Thursday was stabbed in the
back by an Arab, police said. Authorities said they rounded up 27
suspects.
   The victim's mother said her son told her the assailant shouted
``Allahu Akhbar!'' (God is Great) as he plunged in the knife.
   In the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, where a Palestinian
rebellion began Dec. 8, the army lifted curfews on eight villages
and refugee camps. Curfews remained in effect on Idna village and
the Dheishe refugee camp in the West Bank.
   Chanoch Albeck was wearing a black skullcap and was in the old
city's Moslem sector when the attack occurred. Two other students
helped him to the nearby Jewish quarter, where he was given first
aid and taken to a hospital with the knife still in his back.
   Justice Ministry officials said his mother, Plea Albeck, is a
government lawyer who has handled cases of land confiscation in the
occupied territories, but they said they believed it was a random
attack.
   Mayor Teddy Kollek of Jerusalem issued a statement saying he was
``shocked and disgusted.''
   ``The Arab public in Jerusalem must understand that such actions
in the end will only hurt Arabs,'' Kollek said.
   Arab attacks on Jewish civilians have been rare in Jerusalem,
where Jews and Arabs often live side by side,
   Israel captured Arab east Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967 war,
along with the West Bank, and has formally annexed it. Gaza was
taken from Egypt in 1967.
   At least 195 Palestinians have been killed in the Arab rebellion
in the occupied territories. An Israeli soldier and a Jewish
settler also have been slain.
   According to figures compiled by Law in the Service of Man, a
human rights group founded by Palestinian lawyers, 17,000 Arabs
have been detained since Dec. 8., and 7,300 remain in jail, 1,800
of them without being tried or charged. Most are said to be men
aged 15 to 35.
   The organization, an affiliate of the Geneva-based International
Commission of Jurists, said Israeli soldiers had blown up 36 houses
of Arabs suspected of security offenses.
   Rafi Levy, spokesman for the Jerusalem police, said Albeck was
attacked from behind by a single Arab. He said the student was
walking along a narrow lane in the Moslem Quarter, apparently on
his way to a seminary in the adjacent Jewish quarter.
   Dr. Oded Zamir of Hadassah Hospital said the knife passed very
near the heart but Albeck was was in stable condition. ``Only his
lung was injured,'' the doctor said on Israel radio.
   Mrs. Albeck said on the radio her son was conscious and feeling
``relatively good.''
   ``He said he heard somebody saying `Allahu Akbar' and then he
felt a push,'' she said. ``Afterwards he ... felt a knife sticking
in his back. He called for help and walked but nobody would help
him until he reached the Jewish area.''
   Alex Yosipo, a merchant in the Jewish quarter, told the radio:
``He said he was alone when it happened. ... There apparently was
no scuffle.''
   Mrs. Albeck said she hoped the stabbing would not increase
tensions in the old city.
   ``During the years we have all lived here and there was
progress,'' she said. ``With hope, with God's help, there will be
improvement in the future, more understanding.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
