<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrugBill     05-26 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Bill,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Propose Radio-TV Ad Campaign to Combat Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Senate Commerce Committee on
Thursday introduced a bill to provide $75 million annually for a
three-year radio and television advertising campaign aimed at
reducing demand for illegal drugs.
   The broadcasting industry branded some provisions of the
legislation unconstitutional.
   The media blitz would have the ``intensity of a presidential
advertising campaign,'' said Sen. John Danforth of Missouri,
ranking Republican on the panel, who introduced the bill with Sen.
Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., committee chairman.
   ``When people turn on their TV in the evening, we want them to
see at least once during the evening a commercial that is very
hard-hitting about the drug issue,'' Danforth said at a news
conference.
   Under the measure, the National Telecommunications and
Information Administration in the Commerce Department would oversee
production of the ads and buy time to air them on commercial radio
and TV stations nationwide.
   The bill would authorize $75 million a year over three years for
the program. Broadcasters would be required to provide the
government reasonable access to all time periods to air the spots
and to charge their lowest rates.
   The National Association of Broadcasters said the bill is
unconstitutional because it mandates government access to broadcast
facilities.
   Broadcasters support anti-drug efforts and already contribute
more than $1 billion a year in air time and facilities to the
anti-drug campaign, said NAB President Edward O. Fritts.
   Hollings cited precedents for the federal government advertising
on radio and TV, including the armed forces' recruiting ads and
promotions for Amtrak. But the NAB said that in none of those cases
is a broadcast station required by law to accept an ad.
   Danforth said an anti-drug ad campaign should be at least as
successful as anti-smoking campaigns, which have had to compete
against counter-advertising by the tobacco industry and relied
mostly on public service announcements.
   Despite the obstacles, anti-smoking campaigns produced a 25
percent decline in cigarette smoking among Americans over the past
two decades, he said.
</TEXT>
