<1ST_LINE>u a PM-TruckFire 1stLd-Writethru a0560 05-26 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Truck Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0560,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Propane Truck Burns Itself Out; Families Allowed Back</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with rail service resuming,
road to be reopened later; ADDS quote from county executive. PICKS
UP 10th graf pvs, `The closing ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEAFORD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An overturned propane tanker burned itself
out after two days this morning, enabling hundreds of families to
return home and promising some relief from the monumental traffic
jams caused by the accident.
   Fear of an explosion had prompted evacuation of about 500
families within a half-mile of the wreck and the closing of roads
and rail lines connecting New York City to its eastern suburbs.
   ``As of 6:28 a.m., the flames extinguished and the tank is
empty,'' Officer Richard Scibilia, a Nassau County police
spokesman, said today. ``People are being allowed to return to
their homes.''
   Rail service was restored by the end of the morning rush. County
Executive Thomas Gulotta said the highway would probably reopen in
the afternoon.
   Tens of thousands of commuters had been forced to use alternate
rail lines or other transportation after the truck carrying 2,500
gallons of propane burst into flames Tuesday morning on Long
Island's Seaford-Oyster Bay Expressway.
   Water had been shot toward the flames from unmanned pumpers for
days. Emergency workers watched the slow burn through binoculars
from a quarter-mile away.
   Firefighters avoided trying to extinguish the blaze until the
gas was spent in order to avoid an explosion.
   Firefighters opened a vent on the tanker Wednesday to increase
the fire's consumption of the propane. Earlier, Fire Chief Raymond
Kuhner said that if the ``accelerated burn'' didn't work, the fire
could go on for eight days.
   At a news conference, Gulotta defended the precautions, saying,
``If this tank had exploded it would have devastated everything
within a 1,000-foot radius.''
   The Long Island Rail Road said 30,000 rail commuters were
directly affected by the closing of several stations. The truck
caught fire about 2,000 feet from the track.
   The closing of the Seaford-Oyster Bay Expressway and the Sunrise
Highway, used by about 70,000 vehicles a day, had forced motorists
to go out of their way to get to and from New York.
   James Pearce, a spokesman for a motorist information service on
Long Island, said trips that usually took 45 minutes were taking 3{
hours. ``I would say the western half of Nassau County is backed up
solidly,'' he said.
   ``This is the worst traffic I've seen here in 22 years on the
job,'' said Freeport Police Officer Roosevelt Hendricks.
   Most of the evacuees stayed with relatives or friends. About 300
stayed at the Seaford Middle School.
   ``I never thought I'd have to be here a second night. I thought
it would be all over with today,'' Judy Crinion said late
Wednesday. ``If there's a house left when we get home, we're going
to be very, very, very happy.''
</TEXT>
