<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Dunaway     05-26 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Dunaway,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Faye Dunaway: Recovering from `Mommie Dearest'</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Faye Dunaway says her performance as an icy,
manipulative Joan Crawford in ``Mommie Dearest'' was too believable
for her own good, but her portrayal of an alcoholic in ``Barfly''
may have helped save her career.
   ``I was too good as Crawford,'' she said in an interview
published in the June 13 issue of US magazine. ``I think that
changed the notion of who I was. ... It created a kind of monstrous
element which I don't think had been part of my life before.''
   In ``Barfly,'' she said, she was able to show the results of
analysis in which she ``learned to relax as a person.''
   ``I'm more accepting of my vulnerability now,'' she said. ``I've
always had enormous insecurity, but I was always frightened of
showing that before, so I sort of hid behind whatever kind of
facade I could.''
   In her newest film, ``Midnight Cruising,'' Ms. Dunaway plays an
ophthalmologist blinded by glaucoma, which required her to learn
what sightlessness is like.
   ``Hearing became very important,'' she said. ``She (her
character) was always seeing with her ears. ... It makes you
realize how lucky you are.''
</TEXT>
