<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade     05-26 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Warning to Japan in Feud Over Beef Import Curbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan must quickly reach agreement on lowering
import barriers to U.S. beef or face retaliatory action, a Montana
senator said Thursday.
   ``Japan has been saying for weeks that they'll come up with an
agreement, but it has not come home with the bacon,'' Sen. Max
Baucus, D-Mont., told a news conference also attended by U.S. Trade
Representative Clayton K. Yeutter.
   Unless Japan moves swiftly to drop barriers to beef imports the
United States is likely to begin steps that could lead to
retaliation, Baucus said.
   An agreement under which the United States accepted Japanese
quotas on its exports of beef expired March 31. Since then, the
countries have been deadlocked on U.S. demands for an end to the
curbs and no increase in tariffs.
   Japan already represents the largest export market for American
beef. In 1986, U.S. beef exporters sold $500 million worth of the
product to the Japanese.
   The Agriculture Department estimates, however, that sales could
be expanded dramatically if Japan would eliminate its quota system
that limits imports of restaurant grade beef, for example, to
58,400 tons. USDA says exports might increase to $2 billion without
the restrictions.
   Yeutter said it was ``just imperative that the government of
Japan and the people of Japan commit themselves to true market
liberalization.'' He said the system of restrictions was ``not
mildly protectionist, it is blatantly protectionist.''
   Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., who like Baucus is a member of the
Senate Finance subcommittee on international trade, reiterated that
the United States was ``not asking for a guaranteed market.''
   ``We've never asked for a guaranteed market,'' Wallop said.
``We're asking for guaranteed access to that market.''
   He emphasized that Japanese beef prices are far above those in
the United States because of the restrictions.
   ``They are cheating their own consumers,'' Wallop said. ``They
are actually stealing from their own consumers.''
   The massive trade bill that Congress recently passed contains a
non-binding provision expressing the sense of the Senate that the
Japanese should drop their barriers to U.S. beef and citrus imports.
</TEXT>
