<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Colombia-Embassy 1stLd-Writethru a0611 05-26 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia-Embassy, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0611,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexican Embassy in Bogota Invaded</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 40 activists wearing black hoods
peacefully took over the Mexican Embassy today and said they were
protesting water and electricity rationing in slum areas of the
capital.
   No weapons were seen among the people who occupied the embassy
in the Colombian capital. There were no known threats to harm
anyone or do any damage.
   The protesters demanded to talk with Attorney General Horacio
Serpa and the managers of Bogota's departments of electric power
and water.
   The Mexican ambassador, Rudolfo Figueroa, was not at the embassy
when the activists rushed into the embassy at 9 a.m., the embassy's
press officer, Constantino Morales, said in a telephone interview
from the embassy with the radio chain Caracol.
   Three embassy officials and an undetermined number of Colombian
employees were in the embassy when the protesters arrived, Morales
said.
   Morales said the three officials were himself, political adviser
Carlos Gonzalez and the consul, Sergio Savedra.
   The protesters had hired a bus, the bus driver, Marcos Conti,
said in an interview with the Bogota radio station RCN.
   As the bus approached the Mexican Embassy, the people on the bus
pulled on black hoods, Conti said. Two Colombian policemen guarding
the embassy, following standing Mexican Embassy instructions about
such takeovers, did not try to use their pistols.
   The intruders said they were members of the April 19 Movement.
   The military wing of the April 19 Movement, known as M-19,
seized the Dominican Republic's embassy and held 16 ambassadors
hostage there for two months in 1980.
   The M-19 also stormed the government's Palace of Justice in
Bogota in 1986. Ninety-five people, including 11 Supreme Court
justices, were killed.
   This is the third time in four years the Mexican Embassy has
been occupied by people with grievances against the government. The
previous occupations, by university students, were peaceful.
   Many of the poorest areas of Bogota, in the south, have had
water and electricity rationed for two months as the capital goes
through its worst drought in 53 years.
   The middle-class and upper-class homes in the northern part of
the capital have not been affected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
