<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Sikhs     05-26 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six More Bodies Recovered From Golden Temple</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Municipal workers recovered six more
decomposed bodies and human bones from the Golden Temple complex
Thursday, and a police officer said as many as 15 more corpses
could be buried around the shrine.
   Two human skeletons, one male and the other female, were
recovered by the workers from the complex on Wednesday.
   In New Delhi, President Ramaswamy Venkataraman promulgated an
ordinance to prevent religious institutions from being used by
radicals and political parties.
   The ordinance bans the use of religious places for campaigns
against the state and calls for five years of hard labor for
violators, government officials said.
   The Golden Temple is the Sikhs' holiest shrine. Militant Sikhs
have been fighting for a separate state in the northern Punjab
region, where they form a majority.
   The workers in Amritsar on Thursday were joined by relatives of
people missing and feared killed by extremists in the temple.
   Amritsar Police Superintendent Baldev Singh said the remains
were ``people tortured and then killed by Sikh terrorists'' and
said a search was under way for more.
   Singh said the bodies recovered Thursday were of two females and
six males.
   ``We are getting lots of human bones and some skulls. It is a
terrible job down here,'' Singh told The Associated Press.
   The workers were seen removing two bagfuls of human bones
recovered from the debris.
   Sikh extremists had turned the Golden Temple into an armed camp.
The radicals were forced out during a police siege of the shrine
earlier this month.
   The siege, from May 9 to 18, resulted in the surrender of more
than 200 extremists and sympathizers. At least 46 people, most of
them Sikh radicals, were killed during the siege. Three other
radicals committed suicide by swallowing cyanide rather than face
arrest.
   There had been frequent reports that people were being detained
and tortured by militants inside the shrine. Several people were
reported missing by families after they went to the temple to pray.
   The Sikh religion was formed about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam. Sikhs, who make up less than 2
percent of India's 800 million population, claim they are
discriminated against by the majority Hindus.
   More than 1,150 people have been killed by Sikh extremists in
Punjab state since the start of the year. In 1987, 1,030 people
were killed.
   Indian security forces raided the Golden Temple in 1984, killing
1,200 people, mostly Sikhs. Prime Minister Indira Gandhi ordered
the raid. Two of Mrs. Gandhi's Sikh guards assassinated her five
months later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
