<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     05-26 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEAVER, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Morrison has some tips for cow chip
tossers: Pick solid chips and watch the wind.
   ``It can be difficult,'' said Morrison, mayor of this Panhandle
town. ``A lot of it depends on the wind. Some are more fragile than
others.''
   Morrison said he doesn't plan to enter the 19th annual Beaver
County Cow Chip Throwing Contest, to be held Saturday.
   ``The year I did it it was windy. One broke up in the air and
the other went about 20 or 30 feet,'' he said. ``When they break
up, they (officials) count the farthest piece. But they usually
don't go too far.''
   About 100 competitors from several states are expected to be on
hand for the men's, women's, children's and VIP divisions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BLACKSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This question could be in the category
with ``Why did the chicken cross the road?'' But here goes.
``What's the best way for fat cats and pets to lose weight?''
   The same as for humans, says a Virginia Tech spealist: diet and
exercise.
   In fact, says Kent C. Roberts, obesity in animals is nearly
always the owner's fault. That's why it's up to the owner to take
the first step _ recognize the problem and don't take drastic
measures.
   The rest you may have heard before.
   ``Starvation, drugs and surgery are not acceptable methods for
treating obesity,'' he said. ``Diet management and appropriate
exercise are the keys to pet weight reduction.''
   Now here's the tough part for both owner and pet.
   ```No treats' is the hard and fast rule for everyone in the
household if a reducing program is to succeed,'' said Roberts in a
recent Virginia Tech Extension bulletin.
</TEXT>
