<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1440EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MinorityFunds     05-26 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minority Funds,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fired University Official Indicted, Believed To Have Fled Country</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former University of Minnesota official
indicted in the disappearance of some $186,000 is believed to have
fled the country, authorities say.
   County Attorney Tom Johnson announced Wednesday that a grand
jury had returned indictments against Luther Darville, who was
fired last month by the university's Office of Minority and Special
Student Affairs.
   Johnson said authorities believe he is in the Bahamas.
   ``We will immediately begin pursuing a federal warrant for
unlawful flight,'' Johnson said. ``He is from the Bahamas, he has
family there.''
   If Darville is found in the Bahamas, extradition could be a
lengthy process, Johnson said.
   Darville was fired after a university audit showed $186,000
missing from the Office of Minority and Special Student Affairs
since 1983. Darville told auditors he had given money to 17
minority students, including nine football players.
   Evidence shows Darville used some of the money himself, Johnson
said. He said he didn't know how much of the money was spent on
athletes or other students.
   One former student athlete, Valdez Earl Baylor, told the Star
Tribune that Darville gave him about $5,000 in cash over a six-year
period. He said the money was handed to him in envelopes.
   Baylor, 24, who played football for the university from 1982 to
1985, said he received money on ``several occasions'' and used it
to fly home to Harrisburg, Pa., to pay rent and to buy food.
   Asked if he thought the arrangement might be illegal, Baylor
said: ``At that time, it didn't even matter to me ... as long as it
was understood that I didn't have to pay any of the money back.
   ``If they keep pursuing it, there's going to be a lot more
information about the athletic department,'' Baylor went on. ``Some
of the fellows might be willing to speak out later on, if they get
angry, and tell the real story. It stems deeper than Darville
giving out money.''
   He declined to elaborate.
   The National Collegiate Athletic Association rules prohibit
``the award of financial aid to a student-athlete that exceeds
commonly accepted educational expenses (i.e., tuition and fees,
room and board, and required course-related books), other than
legitimate loans, based upon a regular repayment schedule,
available to all students and administered on the same basis for
all students.''
   James Lawton, Darville's attorney, has said Darville broke no
laws and said he had never denied that Darville had assisted
athletes.
   University attorney Bill Donohue said the school was uncertain
whether NCAA rules had been violated. Donohue said the county
attorney had requested that the university hold off investigating
possible violations.
   NCAA officials said they had no comment on the case. The
school's athletic director, Paul Giel, also had no comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
