<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1444EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ForeignAid     05-26 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foreign Aid,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Other Countries See US Bases As Liability, Congress Told</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Appealing for an increase in foreign aid,
Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead told senators Thursday
that other countries increasingly see U.S. military bases as a
liability rather than an asset.
   ``This is a disturbing situation,'' he said.
   Whitehead mentioned Greece, Portugal, Turkey and the
Philippines, in all of which the United States is negotiating on
the future of its bases.
   The House on Wednesday approved a bill to provide $14.3 billion
in aid for the fiscal year beginning Sept. 30. The final amount
will depend on agreement between the House and Senate.
   The administration is asking for a 3.7 percent increase in
military aid, with all equipment being transferred for the first
time as grants rather than loans.
   ``Loans only add to our allies' burden of debt, which may not be
repaid anyway,'' Whitehead said.
   He was testifying before the foreign operations subcommittee of
the Senate Appropriations Committee.
   Whitehead said an overall aid increase of 2 percent over this
year's level is needed to restore funds for key programs in
Portugal, South America, the Caribbean and Africa which either got
no money this year or were drastically cut.
   ``We cannot expect others to be dependable friends if we cannot
be one ourselves,'' he said.
   Edward J. Derwinski, undersecretary of state for security
assistance, said there is no debate about the need of the
Philippines for aid.
   ``As a newly restored democracy, an ally, and a country facing a
dangerous communist insurgency, the Philippines is looking for
significantly higher assistance levels from the United States, its
principal security partner,'' he said.
   Lt. Gen. Charles W. Brown, in charge of foreign aid at the
Pentagon, called the request of $110 million for the Philippines a
reasonable amount, saying that it was $15 million less than
Congress earmarked for this year.
   ``In addition, the amount of assistance that the Philippine
armed forces can optimally absorb this year is limited,'' he said.
   ``The Philippines requires a great deal of assistance to resolve
its security problems, but it should be applied in the context of
an efficient and reliable long-term program.''
   Whitehead questioned whether $45 million asked for Afghanistan
will be enough as five million Afghan refugees in Pakistan and Iran
seek to return to their homes following the withdrawal of Soviet
troops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
