<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-SAfrica     05-26 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-SAfrica,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Apartheid Opponents Meet With Black Guerrillas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black South African guerrilla
leaders and white opponents of apartheid sharply disagreed Thursday
over the use of violence to attain their common goal, but they
pledged to hold further talks.
   Four representatives of the African National Congress met in
Frankfurt with eight members of South Africa's National Democratic
Movement.
   The meeting occurred the same day as two bomb blasts in Pretoria.
   Four people were injured in the blasts, which South Africa's
justice minister blamed on the ANC. The ANC is the largest
guerrilla group fighting South Africa's white-led government.
   Wynand Malan, a member of South Africa's Parliament and the
leader of the National Democratic Movement delegation, was asked if
the two sides had discussed violence carried out by the guerrillas
to promote their goals.
   ``We voiced not only our position, but our difference to that
strategy,'' Malan told reporters after the meeting.
   ``We also got an explanation from them again as to the origin of
the armed struggle. We can understand from their perspective
exactly what they are saying, but from our position we are still
fundamentally in disagreement to it,'' Malan said.
   The guerrilla group, based in Lusaka, Zambia, wages a bombing
and sabotage campaign in its bid to oust South Africa's government.
   By law and custom, South African apartheid establishes a
racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no
vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy
and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
   In a joint statement after Thursday's meeting, the two groups
said: ``Common ground was found in relation to the kind of South
Africa we would like to see. However, there were important
differences with respect to some aspects of the strategy through
which this could be achieved.''
   Also attending the press conference was Thabo Mbeki, spokesman
for the guerrilla group in West Germany.
   He defended use of force by the group, which was outlawed by
South Africa in 1960.
   ``That left us no choice but to take up arms. If those
conditions were to change, then of course the issue of whether to
continue or not continue the armed struggle would be
reconsidered,'' Mbeki said.
   Malan earlier defended the decision to meet the four executive
committee members of the guerrilla organization. ``This is a normal
further discussion with the ANC, seeking a common ground and
strategies out of the impasse,'' in South Africa, he told The
Associated Press at an interview in a Frankfurt hotel.
   ``It's the National Democratic Movement's policy to meet with
all political groupings,'' said Malan.
   He said the goal of the meeting was to seek ``common ground''
with the black resistance movement.
   Malan said West Germany was chosen as the meeting site because
``it was the quickest access to a mutually convenient venue.''
   The two sides at the Frankfurt meeting agreed to hold more
talks, though no date was given.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
