<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Stallone 1stLd-Writethru a0688 05-26 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Stallone, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0688,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sly: I've Got Women Problems</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf, `Let's say ...,' to CORRECT spelling from
Birgitte to Brigitte. For release at 6 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As ``Rambo'' and ``Rocky,'' defeats are few and
far between for Sylvester Stallone. But the twice-divorced actor
says he's not always a winner in his real-life experiences with
women.
   ``Let's say I've developed suspicion to an art form,'' said
Stallone in the June 13 issue of US magazine, discussing his split
with actress Brigitte Nielsen.
   ``You develop a sense of, like, protective paranoia,'' explained
Stallone, who also offered some advice on spotting women bent on
breaking a man.
   ``Evil rises to the top eventually, like cream,'' Stallone said.
``You really got to look deeply into their eyes. You can see if
there's gentleness or there is barracuda living behind that
retina.''
   Stallone's problems with women aren't limited to his love life _
the muscular actor says he also has trouble with his mother, who
frequently offers her opinions on his life.
   ``I love her dearly, but she's her own woman,'' said Stallone.
``I say, `Why don't you please try this word, no comment, just this
one time. You'll feel good, really.' But that'll never happen.''
</TEXT>
