<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CankerAward     05-26 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canker Award,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State to Pay Nursery Owner $2.6 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nursery owner has been awarded $2.6
million for 510,000 citrus trees the state destroyed in 1985 in a
program to control what was thought to be an incurable,
fast-spreading citrus canker.
   A judge and six-member jury decided Wednesday the state
Department of Agriculture had to pay Richard O. Polk for burning
his stock as part of a statewide program that destroyed millions of
trees.
   Polk had asked for $3 milllion in his suit.
   In a precedent-setting case in January, Circuit Judge Tim
Strickland ruled the agriculture department unnecessarily destroyed
Polk's stock after scientists testified that canker had been
misdiagnosed and there was never a real threat to the industry.
   ``It's a relief,'' said Polk. ``That's all an American citizen
can ask for is a fair day in court.''
   Attorney J. Davis Connor, co-counsel for Polk, said he hoped the
case might influence the state to settle other cases he plans to
file for affected nursery owners.
   The state, however, said it would appeal the award. It's also
appealing a $1.9 million award earlier this year to two Hardee
County nursery owners.
</TEXT>
