<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     05-26 0833</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0865</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Elizabeth Taylor, former World
Bank President Robert S. McNamara and the Chinese Archaeological
Service have been honored by the Onassis Foundation with prizes
totaling $300,000.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou presented the awards at a ceremony
Thursday. The prizes are given annually in memory of the late
shipowner Aristotle Onassis and his son Alexander, who was killed
in a 1973 plane crash.
   Miss Taylor shared the $100,000 Aristotle Man and Society Prize
with French physician Daniel Defert for their campaigns against
acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Defert was not present.
   ``I'm accepting on behalf of the loved ones who have suffered
not only the empty pain of losing someone dear but also the
humiliation of the abhorrent stigma of AIDS,'' Miss Taylor said.
   Miss Taylor, chairman of the American Foundation for AIDS, was
accompanied by Christopher Forbes, son of publisher Malcolm Forbes.
   McNamara, a former U.S. defense secretary, received the $100,000
Athinai Man and Mankind prize for his work in developing Third
World economies while heading the World Bank from 1968 to 1981.
   Chinese Deputy Culture Minister Wang Jifu accepted the $100,000
Olympia Man and his Environment prize on behalf of China's Bureau
of Museums and Archaeological Data. The award honored the
excavation of a 7,000-strong army of lifesize terracotta warriors
in the tomb of the Emperor Qin Shi Huangdi as a ``contribution to
East-West understanding.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MERRIMACK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of soul singer James Brown says
she had nothing to do with causing a hotel-room fire that was the
basis of three charges against her.
   Adrienne Brown, 38, of Aiken, S.C., pleaded innocent Wednesday
in Merrimack District Court to possession of the drug PCP. The
charge is a misdemeanor punishable by a $1,000 fine and a year in
jail.
   She also was charged with arson and criminal mischief following
the May 10 fire in Bedford. She and her husband were in New
Hampshire for a concert.
   Under New Hampshire court procedures, defendants do not enter
pleas to felonies in district court.
   Mrs. Brown said she wasn't in the room when the fire began. She
was charged with possession of PCP based on lab tests on the
contents of a plastic container confiscated at the time of the fire.
   Bedford police Sgt. Roger Grenier said the criminal mischief
charge is a felony based on the amount of damage alleged, $1,500.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SECAUCUS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative talk-show host Morton Downey
Jr. says he objects to homosexuality, but will care for his
AIDS-stricken younger brother because ``he's my family.''
   Downey's 52-year-old brother, Tony, was a surprise guest on
Downey's recently taped program on acquired immune deficiency
syndrome, said Cynthia Harrison, a spokeswoman for WWOR-TV, where
the show originates.
   Downey, 55, said his younger brother, who was diagnosed nine
months ago as having AIDS, would move to New Jersey from California
to stay with him and his family.
   ``He's my family and I'm going to take care of him,'' said
Downey, known for his anti-gay tirades on his soon-to-be nationally
syndicated program. ``I still object to what I call perverted love,
but nonetheless, he's my brother.''
   The program also deals with the high cost of AIDS drugs such as
AZT. Tony Downey pays $1,200 a week for the medication, said Ms.
Harrison.
   ``He (Tony) had told me a long time ago that if the time came
when there was no reversal, he would like to come on my show and
talk about his lifestyle to help people,'' Downey said. ``I had to
give him his moment.'' The show will be broadcast June 15 on WWOR.
   ``The Morton Downey Jr. Show'' will begin national syndication
Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian David Brenner is being sued by
two law firms involved in a 1986 suit he lost over custody of his
son.
   The Stamford firm of Silver, Golub and Sandak is seeking $65,310
for representing Brenner from April 1986 to November 1986,
according to papers filed in U.S. District Court in New Haven.
   And Epstein and Fogarty, the Stamford firm that successfully
represented the mother, is trying to enforce collection of the
$40,000 award that it was given for its work, attorney Robert
Epstein said Thursday.
   The woman won custody of the boy and child support in Stamford
Superior Court. Records of the case were sealed at Brenner's
request.
   James R. Greenfield, Brenner's new lawyer, declined comment on
the lawsuits.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HENDERSONVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Johnny Cash's plans for
a residential and commercial development in this Nashville suburb
hit a snag when the Board of Mayor and Aldermen denied his rezoning
request.
   The board refused Wednesday night to approve the rezoning, which
was opposed by residents of the community where Cash and his wife,
June Carter, live.
   Cash had hoped to build 219 single-family homes, a shopping
center and an office building on a 95-acres he owns. Residents
mainly opposed the commercial development that would have taken up
17 acres.
