<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CorporateProfits     05-26 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Corporate Profits,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corporate Profits Up Marginally in First Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporations' after-tax profits edged up 0.5
percent in the first three months of the year, a much smaller
increase than in the last quarter of 1987, the government said
Thursday.
   The Commerce Department said after-tax profits rose to an annual
rate of $146.4 billion, following a gain of 2.6 percent in the
previous quarter.
   Manufacturing profits were up in the first quarter, with the
chemical industry enjoying the largest increases. Profits in the
transportation and utilities industries were down, while those in
financial industries showed a tiny gain.
   Analysts said the slowdown in profits showed that companies were
beginning to see some pressures from rising wages and higher costs
for component parts, especially if those parts are imported.
   Bruce Steinberg, senior economist with Merrill Lynch in New
York, said that faced with rising demand, companies are likely to
begin boosting their prices in order to regain lost profit margins.
   ``Because of the squeeze on profits, there will be an incentive
on firms to raise their prices,'' he said, and these increases will
add to growing inflationary pressures.
   Among the details in the profits report:
   _Before-tax profits fell 1.8 percent in the first quarter, to an
annual level of $280.6 billion, after rising 0.2 percent in the
fourth quarter.
   _Corporate profits, after adjusting for depreciation and
inventories, fell 1 percent to $309.9 billion, the second
consecutive quarterly decline.
   _Corporate cash flows, a measurement intended to show the funds
corporations have for investment, rose 1.2 percent to an annual
rate of $381 billion after a 0.5 percent rise in the fourth quarter.
   _Dividend payments to stockholders rose 2.1 percent in the first
quarter to an annual rate of $99.3 billion following a 2.2 percent
rise in the fourth quarter.
</TEXT>
