<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Netherlands-Carlucci     05-26 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Netherlands-Carlucci,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci To Visit Netherlands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci
will make a pre-summit stopover here for talks with Dutch cabinet
officials, a U.S. Embassy spokesman said Thursday.
   Carlucci, who was attending a NATO defense ministers meeting in
Brussels, Belgium, on Thursday, was expected to arrive Friday,
according to spokesman Leonardo Williams. Carlucci is scheduled to
fly to Moscow on Sunday, the first day of the summit between
President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Williams said that talks ``on questions of mutual concern'' had
been planned for Friday between Carlucci and Dutch Premier Ruud
Lubbers, Foreign Minister Hans van den Broek and Defense Minister
Willem van Eekelen.
   On Thursday, Reagan was in Helsinki preparing for his fourth
meeting with Gorbachev.
   Williams refused to provide any details on Carlucci's visit.
   Spokesmen for the Dutch officials he is to meet said they were
surprised at the visit.
   ``We have no firm idea as to what he'll be precisely doing
here,'' a Dutch defense ministry spokesman said. ``We've just heard
of it (the visit).'' He delined to be identified by name in line
with Dutch government practice.
   Currently, there are few defense-related frictions between
Washington and the Netherlands.
   Relations between the two allies came under stress in the first
half of the decade, when successive Dutch governments waffled over
the controversial issue of deployment of 48 nuclear-tipped cruise
missiles on its soil.
   The issue was resolved 2{ years ago when Lubbers' government
decided in favor of deployment by late 1988, a decision made
obsolete by last December's superpower pact to eliminate
medium-range missiles from Europe.
