<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1516EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CatholicEducation Bjt   05-26 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Catholic Education, Bjt,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Educators Look Beyond Parochial Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Religious education will mean more than
having a parochial school building in the parish, as Catholic
educators are charting a future that emphasizes adult education and
teaching children outside the traditional setting.
   Faced with continued enrollment declines, educators moved toward
a broader definition of Roman Catholic education during a weeklong
symposium on their future course.
   The concerns of those working with adults and with Catholic
children attending public schools dominated discussions, while
little talk was devoted to stopping the enrollment erosion at
parochial schools.
   The 300 participants in the Catholic Education Futures Project
left unfinished the work of writing a ``vision statement.'' But
they developed a list of priorities.
   Sister Suzanne Hall, an organizer, said the list reflected a
strong belief that Catholic education must embrace ``radical
aspects of the gospel, including education for peace and justice,
respect for all cultures'' and elimination of racism and sexism.
   Twenty-two organizations sent representatives to the symposium
at the University of Dayton, organized by the U.S. Catholic
Conference and the National Catholic Educational Association.
   Roman Catholic dioceses have lost 3 million students and 4,200
schools since 1965. Last year, 110 more schools closed their doors,
and enrollment fell by 103,000 to 2.6 million in the 8,992
remaining schools.
   In the United States, the Roman Catholic Church has more than 48
million members, making it the largest single body of Christians in
the nation.
   By the new, broader definition, ``Catholic education is not
getting smaller, it's getting larger,'' said the Rev. Thomas
Gallagher, secretary of education for the U.S. Catholic Conference.
``We're not going out of business.''
   Sister Georgette Zalewska, director of adult and religious
education for the Brooklyn, N.Y., diocese, said the church needs to
move beyond ``that school mentality'' and find new ways to educate
senior citizens, adolescents and adults.
   But Sister Patricia Bauch, an education professor at the
Catholic University of America who has studied largely black
parochial schools in inner cities, said the conference ignored the
needs of parents and other Catholic school ``consumers.''
   ``The church has come to see it is very expensive to operate
schools and therefore is looking for other ways to educate
people,'' Bauch said.
   Historically, the public school child who attended weekly
religion classes ``was considered a second-class citizen,'' said
Bishop James Malone of Youngstown.
   But archdioceses around the country are hiring paid, full-time
directors of religious education, like Janet Kayser, a laywoman who
runs the programs for St. Thomas Parish in Crystal Lake, Ill.
   ``When the topic of Catholic education comes up, there's too
much emphasis in thinking it means only schools,'' said Kayser, who
has 650 students in her programs.
   The Rev. Thomas Lynch, pastor of St. James Church in Bridgeport,
Conn., said he is trying to rename the parish school the St. James
Center for Religious Formation to stress prayer classes, scripture
study and other educational activities. But he said his
parishioners ``get nervous'' about such a change.
   Catholic schools must emphasize the teaching of faith ``just as
much as geography, math or anything else,'' said Lynch. He said he
sees no reason to operate a parochial school that ``smells like and
looks like the public school except for maybe a course in religion
and an amorphous Catholic environment.''
   Bishop Francis Schulte of West Virginia, who heads the bishops'
committee on education, said, ``There's no adequate substitute for
the full-curriculum Catholic school.'' But he acknowledged that
``very substantial areas'' exist where Catholic parents simply
don't have a parochial school available.
   Parochial schools flourished in big cities with immigrants from
Catholic lands like Ireland, Italy and Poland.
   ``In early times we saw ourselves in kind of a fortress
mentality to the white Protestant culture that was here,'' said
Brother Raymond Fitz, president of the University of Dayton.
   When Catholics became more affluent and moved to the suburbs,
churches followed, but schools did not.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
