<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     05-26 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Wants Drug-Destroying Force, Contracts-Drug Programs Link</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush proposed on
Thursday that companies lacking ``drug-free programs'' be denied
government contracts. He also called for creation of an
international strike force to find and destroy drug crops.
   A Bush spokesman said the first proposal might include some form
of mandatory drug testing.
   Bush, in what aides described as a major anti-drug initiative,
said, ``I will make adoption of drug-free programs a condition of
obtaining federal contracts and I will ask the states to do the
same.''
   Bush outlined his drug plan, an expansion of previous anti-drug
proposals, at a Chamber of Commerce breakfast in nearby Secaucus,
then underscored his proposals with a visit to a drug
rehabilitation center here, where he talked with patients who had
been drug addicts.
   Later, he was flying to his vacation retreat in Kennebunkport,
Maine, where he will spend a week on strategy and meetings with
Republican leaders and advisers.
   On the drug issue, Bush said that an international strike force,
possibly under the auspices of the United Nations, could ``wipe out
crops wherever they are grown and take out drug labs wherever they
exist.'' U.S. involement would be coordinated by a military officer
reporting to Bush's vice president.
   ``Our military forces have already made a substantial
contribution to our interdiction effort and today they're being
called upon to do more. Their primary target should be the
production of drugs abroad,'' he said.
   Bush also reiterated an earlier call for a Western Hemisphere
drug summit and said he would put his vice president in charge of
anti-drug efforts.
   On another topic, Bush also renewed his call for a federal
special prosecutor to investigate the finances of Democratic House
Speaker Jim Wright.
   Speaking to an Italian-American group at lunch, Bush said, ``We
hear a lot of flak from the Democrats on current ethical problems
in the administration,'' an apparent reference to the legal
investigation of Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   ``I wonder if Mike Dukakis and Jesse Jackson will join me in
calling for the House of Representatives to appoint a special
prosecutor to look into its own troubles, starting with the
speaker,'' he said.
   The private lobbying group Common Cause had earlier called for
an investigation, and Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., filed a formal
complaint about Wright with the House ethics committee Thursday.
   Gingrich's complaint, accompanied by a supporting letter signed
by 71 House Republicans, asked for an investigation in four areas,
including published reports that Wright received unusually high
book royalities from a printing company that did business with his
campaign committee.
   In Newark, Bush also told the Italian-American audience that,
while Dukakis should be proud of his Greek-American ancestry,
``he's not going to be the champion of ethnic America. I'm going to
be the champion of ethnic America.''
   Bush's comments on private companies and drugs marked the first
time he had sought to tie the war against drugs to government
contracts.
   His chief of staff, Craig Fuller, told reporters that the thrust
of the proposal was ``the vice president's notion that employers
should do everything possible to get drugs out of the workplace.''
   ``We didn't come today to write the regulations,'' Fuller said.
However, he said it was ``conceivable that testing of some kind
could be part of it.''
   Fuller said that the vice president saw ``a lot of merit to
random drug testing'' for government contractors. Bush has already
proposed mandatory testing for airline pilots, prison guards and
others who hold safety-related jobs.
   On still another subject, Fuller denied that the decision of
Peter Teeley to step down as Bush's campaign communications
director reflected dissension.
   Campaign aides said on Wednesday that Teeley, a longtime adviser
to Bush, would be reassigned to work on political issues. No reason
was given for the change.
   Teeley has been known to be at odds recently with Fuller.
However, Fuller said, ``I don't think there was a rift. There
wasn't a resignation.''
</TEXT>
