<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hamadi-Trial     05-26 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi-Trial,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Hostages, Relatives Said to Join in Hamadi Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court official said Thursday
that six Americans who were aboard a TWA jet commandeered in 1985
and relatives of a U.S. Navy diver killed in the ordeal will help
prosecute one of the suspected hijackers.
   Mohammed Ali Hamadi goes on trial July 5 in a specially-built,
$7.5 million courtroom on charges of air piracy and murder in the
hijacking. The Americans' legal intervention allows their attorneys
to ask questions during court sessions.
   During a tour to show reporters the courtroom inside Frankfurt's
Preungesheim prison, court spokesman Falk Thomas said eight
Americans _including six people who were on the hijacked jetliner _
had formally intervened in the prosecution.
   ``Six are former hostages. The other two are relatives of
Stethem, I believe the parents,'' Thomas told reporters. He
declined to provide the names.
   Navy diver Robert Stethem was shot to death during the
hijacking. His parents, who live in Waldorf, Md., could not be
immediately reached for comment.
   The practice of legal intervention, common in the German system,
is sometimes called acting as a ``private prosecutor.'' It is
designed to ensure that victims' interests are properly represented
in criminal trials.
   It also gives the intervenors the right of appeal to a higher
court.
   They are not required to be present in the courtroom. However,
Thomas indicated that at least some of the Americans would be here.
   During to tour, the court spokesman said, ``Some of those people
who are coming as witnesses or intervenors in the prosecution could
feel threatened, and we don't want that to happen.''
   Four armed men hijacked the plane on June 14, 1985, on a flight
from Athens to Rome, and forced it to land in Beirut. Thirty-nine
Americans were held captive for 17 days.
   U.S. government officials have indicted Hamadi, but West Germany
refused to extradite him.
   Hamadi is in a Frankfurt prison awaiting trial.
   Thomas, the Frankfurt judge acting as spokesman for the Hamadi
trial, said that the construction costs of the courtroom came to
$7.5 million.
   Seats for 100 journalists and 80 members of the public are
separated from the judges, witnesses and defendant by huge plates
of bulletproof glass. The spectators will listen through a
loudspeaker system.
   Thomas said the trial will start July 5 with reading of the
indictment and a chance for Hamadi to make a statement.
   A juvenile court then will decide whether Hamadi was under 21
years old when the hijacking preparations started. If it rules he
was 21 or younger, then Hamadi would be subject to a maximum of 15
years in prison.
   If the court tries him as an adult, Hamadi could receive life in
prison.
   Hamadi has told West German authorities he was born on June 13,
1964, but he later said he was younger.
   West German and U.S. officials believe he is 23 years old.
   Hamadi's 29-year-old brother, Abbas Ali Hamadi, was sentenced by
a Duesseldorf court to 13 years in prison for kidnapping two West
Germans in Beirut in a failed attempt to gain freedom for his
younger brother.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1845EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Refuseniks     05-26 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Refuseniks,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Unusually Tolerant At Pre-Summit Jewish Demonstration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities allowed an unusually large
demonstration Thursday by Soviet Jews who have been denied
permission to emigrate and who urged President Reagan and Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev to take up their cause at the
superpower summit.
   Despite the tolerance of the protest, a Leningrad refusenik, the
term for Jews refused permission to leave the country, said the KGB
secret police has warned him against accepting an invitation to
meet Reagan on Monday.
   Reagan plans to meet Monday afternoon at Spaso House, the U.S.
ambassador's residence, with the activists and refuseniks to
underscore his concern for human rights problems. The Soviet
government has not objected to the meeting.
   On Thursday, Soviet officials holding a news conference on the
summit said who the president meets with is his business.
   ``The U.S. president, who will be our guest in Moscow, is
certainly free to decide who of Soviet citizens he finds
interesting and useful to meet with outside the framework of the
official events,'' said Deputy Foreign Minister Vladimir F.
Petrovsky said.
   But, he added, ``This American move is hardly aimed at improving
mutual understanding between the U.S.A. and U.S.S.R.''
   Dozens of uniformed and plainclothes policemen shouted at the
demonstrators to disperse and ripped down some of the protester's
posters during the 1{-hour protest within sight of the Kremlin,
where Reagan and Gorbachev will meet starting Sunday.
   But unlike past protests, the officers did not arrest or detain
any of the demonstrators, gathered outside the Lenin Library as
Western journalists watched.
   One uniformed militiaman, asked why the demonstrators were not
hauled away, responded in one word: ``Perestroika.'' That is
Gorbachev's policy of restructuring Soviet society, including some
greater tolerance of dissent and somewhat freer emigration.
   ``A World Without Missiles or Refuseniks,'' proclaimed one large
banner, made of wallpaper. ``We Welcome the Summit,'' read another
poster, which plainclothes KGB officers ripped from the hands of
30-year-old Marina Durnovo.
   Roald ``Alec'' Zelichonok, who has been refused permission to
emigrate for more than 10 years, said he received a letter and
telephone call Tuesday from the U.S. Embassy inviting him to take
part in Monday's meeting with Reagan. Shortly after the embassy
phone call, he said, a KGB officer telephoned.
   ``This officer called and said in light of security measures
around Moscow, my departure for Moscow will not be permitted,''
Zelichonok said by telephone from his Leningrad home.
   Zelichonok, 51, said the officer warned him that if he traveled
to Moscow, ``administrative measures'' carrying possible penalties
of detention, house arrest or up to 15 days in jail would be taken
against him. He said he thought the warning may have been prompted
by his plan to present Reagan a book he and another refusenik wrote
about 18 would-be emigres who died awaiting permission to leave the
country.
   Zelichonok said he intends to attend the meeting with his wife
despite the warning.
   Soviet authorities have cleared the capital of ``undesirables''
during previous international events, such as the 1980 Summer
Olympics.
   The demonstrators said they want human rights to figure
prominently in the Reagan-Gorbachev meetings.
   ``We very much hope that the summit brings success in the area
of freedom of emigration,'' said Ms. Durnovo. ``America is our
hope, our support, the only country the opposes our country.''
   Asked why she wanted to leave the Soviet Union and settle in the
United States, Ms. Durnovo replied: ``It's impossible to live in
this country. I won't be alive by the time there are results of
perestroika,'' said Ms. Durnovo, a 30-year-old Moscow Jew who
applied to emigrate about six months ago. She said she had not been
denied permission to leave yet, but that ``there's never a
guarantee.''
   Many of the protesters were from Leningrad, although
demonstrators said about 15 of them who tried to travel to Moscow
were taken off a train bound for the capital by KGB officers. Other
protesters came from the Ukraine, Lithuania and Moldavia.
   The U.S.-based National Conference on Soviet Jewry reported last
week that 1,086 Jews were allowed to leave the Soviet Union in
April, the highest monthly total in nearly seven years.
   The figure has been rising for about a year, but it falls far
short of the 1979 levels, when the monthly average was about 4,000
departures.
</TEXT>
