<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0694,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Instructors Safely Eject From Navy Jet That Crashed in Woods</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with safe return of instructors.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GROVE HILL, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two flight instructors successfully
ejected from a TA4J Skyhawk Navy training jet that crashed and
burned Thursday in a forest, authorities said.
   The officers were picked up by a search helicopter and returned
safely to base, said Lt. j.g. Mary Chamberlin, spokeswoman for the
Meridian Naval Air Station in Mississippi.
   They were identified as Marine Capt. Thomas Henry Renken and
Navy Lt. j.g. Timothy John Roorda, who was being examined for a
possible broken leg.
   Chamberlin said the jet, based at Meridian, Miss., was on a
routine training mission and crashed 11:45 a.m. in the Scotch
Wildlife Management area in southwest Alabama, 13 miles west of
Grove Hill.
   The crash sparked a wildfire near Alabama Highway 154 that was
fought by state forestry fire crews.
   There were no other injuries.
