<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Wright-Ethics     05-26 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright-Ethics,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethics Committee Gets Formal Complaint To Investigate Wright</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservative Georgia congressman, supported
by 71 House Republican colleagues, asked the House ethics committee
Thursday to investigate allegations that Speaker Jim Wright has
violated House ethics rules.
   The request from Rep. Newt Gingrich, a leader of the Republican
right in the House, came one week after a similar call from the
government watchdog group Common Cause for an ethics committee
investigation of Wright.
   Under House rules, Gingrich's complaint will require the panel,
formally known as the Committee on Standards of Official Conduct,
to vote on whether to investigate Wright, D-Texas. The committee is
made up of six Democrats and six Republicans.
   Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif., chairman of the committee, declined
comment on Gingrich's complaint, but Wright told reporters he hoped
the committee will resolve the issue quickly.
   ``I feel certain I have not violated House rules,'' Wright said.
``I most certainly have never intended to do so.''
   As for Gingrich, who has been calling publicly for such an
investigation since December, Wright said, ``My views toward him
are similar to those of a fire hydrant toward dogs.''
   Gingrich's complaint asked the ethics committee to investigate
published allegations about Wright in four areas, two of which
involved his book, ``Reflections of a Public Man.''
   The complaint cited reports that Wright received unusually high
royalties of 55 percent on the book, which was published by a
printing company that received nearly $300,000 worth of business
from Wright's campaign committee in 1985-86.
   The complaint asked the committee to determine if the royalty
arrangement violated House rules and if Wright's relationship with
the company was used by the speaker as a way to convert campaign
funds to personal use.
   The complaint also asked for an investigation into published
reports of Wright's 1979 intervention with Egyptian President Anwar
Sadat in behalf of a businessman who earlier had allowed Wright to
invest in a proven oil well, and his 1979 intervention with the
Department of Interior to influence a gas lease decision involving
a company in which Wright owned $15,000 worth of stock.
   He said the incidents provide ``direct examples of the use of
public office for personal enrichment.''
   Common Cause cited Wright's book and his financial dealings with
its publisher in its call for an investigation last week, but not
the two 1979 incidents.
   The self-styled citizens lobby also asked for an investigation
into allegations that Wright violated federal ethics rules while
seeking special treatment from the federal Home Loan Bank Board for
Texas constituents and Democratic contributors.
   The 71 House Republicans who signed a letter to the ethics
committee supporting Gingrich's complaint included the entire House
GOP leadership except Rep. Robert H. Michel of Illinos.
   As Gingrich was announcing his complaint against Wright, the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee issued a statement
charging that Gingrich received $13,000 from wealthy friends in
1977 to write a novel he never produced.
   Rep. Beryl Anthony Jr., D-Ark., chairman of the DCCC, said the
objective of the partnership arrangment that provided the $13,000
to Gingrich apparently was ``to allow Gingrich a means for
financial gain not available to the average American.''
   Gingrich said in response that he was paid the $13,000 for a
summer's work researching the novel, but an agent who reviewed the
initial chapters told him he was ``far better at shaking hands than
writing fiction.''
   Gingrich noted he was not a member of Congress in 1977, and
said, ``No one was trying to gain influence over an assistant
college professor.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
