<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TruckFire     05-26 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Truck Fire,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Propane Fire Runs Out of Gas; Neighborhood Out of Danger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEAFORD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An intense propane fire ran out of gas
Thursday, ending a two-day ordeal that forced 500 families from
their homes and shut down a commuter railroad line to New York City.
   The fire in a 2,500-gallon tanker, overturned on the
Seaford-Oyster Bay Expressway, burned itself out at 6:30 a.m.
   ``The tank was empty,'' Inspector Nelson Finkelman of the county
fire marshal's office. ``It literally ran out of gas.''
   ``It was the equivalent of a small bomb,'' Nassau County
Executive Thomas Gulotta said. ``If this tank had exploded it would
have devastated everything within a 1,000-foot radius.''
   Finkelman said the fire burned out sooner than expected,
probably because the tanker was not full when it overturned
Tuesday. It also burned faster after firefighters opened a vent on
the tanker Wednesday to increase consumption of the liquid.
   Within three hours after the fire was out, Long Island Rail Road
began operating trains again on the Babylon line. The truck
overturned just 2,000 feet south of the LIRR track. The Sunrise
Highway and the Seaford-Oyster Bay Expressway also were reopened.
   LIRR said 30,000 rail commuters were affected. And 70,000
motorists were forced to find alternate routes. About 500 families
were urged to evacuate, and many slept in cots in school gymnasiums.
   The accident occurred when defective springs in the truck broke,
shifting the truck's weight, which in turn caused the drive shaft
to separate and the rear portion to dig into the ground.
   The broken shaft acted as a catapult, overturning the truck,
said Ken Cynar, a spokesman for Gulotta.
   The driver and a passenger escaped with minor cuts and bruises.
The driver was charged with driving with a suspended license.
   Gulotta said the county may sue Conservative Gas of Wyandanch,
which owned the tanker and serves 40,000 residential and commercial
customers.
   Nassau County Comptroller Peter King said the emergency cost the
county more than $300,000 in overtime, salaries and equipment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
