<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1843EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC--DioxinStudy     05-26 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC--Dioxin Study,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Blood Tests On `Ranch Hand' Sprayers Shows High Dioxin
Levels</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EDT _ time set by source</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blood tests on Air Force veterans who were
assigned to spray defoliants like Agent Orange in Vietnam show
``unusually heavy'' levels of exposure to dioxin, the U.S. Centers
for Disease Control said Thurdsay.
   The CDC reported results of blood testing among 147 Air Force
men who served in the ``Operation Ranch Hand'' defoliation
activities. But the report drew no conclusion about how _ if at all
_ the men's dioxin exposure might affect their health.
   At least 1,200 men participated in ``Operation Ranch Hand,'' the
code name for the continuing aerial spraying conducted by the Air
Force during the Vietnam War.
   The high levels exposure to the toxic chemical among the Ranch
Hand personnel didn't necessarily come as a surprise, said Dr.
Larry L. Needham, a CDC researcher.
   Sixty-two percent, or 91, of the 147 Ranch Hand veterans who
were tested showed blood-dioxin levels of more than 20 parts per
trillion, commonly regarded as the upper threshold for dioxin
exposure in the general population, CDC researchers said.
   The average blood-dioxin level among the men was 49 parts per
trillion; three Ranch Hand airmen had exposure levels over 200
parts per trillion and two had levels over 300 parts per trillion,
the CDC said.
   In a ``control'' group of 49 veterans, tested for comparison
purposes, only one man had a blood-dioxin level over 20 parts per
trillion _ and he had been exposed to industrial chemicals since
1980 at an Indiana steel foundry, the CDC said.
   The blood tests indicate ``that some Ranch Hand personnel had
unusually heavy TCDD (dioxin) exposure,'' the Atlanta-based agency
said. However, the agency noted, ``no threshold level has been
determined as yet for the health effects of TCDD in humans.''
   Earlier, the CDC reported on blood-dioxin levels among Army
ground troops potentially exposed to Agent Orange, Needham noted.
   ``The one big difference we are seeing,'' he said, ``is the ...
Army ground troops ... did not seem to have elevated exposures.''
   Only two out of 646 such soldiers had blood-dioxin levels over
20 parts per trillion, Needham said.
   Dioxin is a toxic chemical to which virtually all people have
been exposed somewhat, through the environment. However, dioxin
contamination of Agent Orange and other herbicides used to clear
the jungles in Vietnam war operations has prompted concern about
the health of military personnel exposed to such agents.
   A study released in March showed no unusual health problems to
date among more than 1,000 Vietnam veterans who were involved in
the spraying of Agent Orange.
   That study drew criticism because it used estimated exposure
levels.
   New techniques make it possible for scientists to detect dioxin
levels in human blood even years after exposure. The test results
announced Thursday, part of a 1987-88 Air Force investigation, are
from the first ``appreciable'' number of those tests performed on
Ranch Hand personnel, Needham said.
   A report on the 1987-88 Air Force Health Study will be published
after blood-dioxin tests have been completed on all participants
and the report passes executive branch review, the CDC said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0181 </DOCNO>
