<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1904EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DWITeacher     05-26 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DWI Teacher,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher To Spend Summer, Then Weekends in Jail for 8 DWIs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school teacher who pleaded guilty
to eight drunken driving charges will spend the summer and 37
weekends in jail and pay a $5,000 fine.
   Curtis Burton, 41, said at Wednesday's sentencing that he has
told his English students at Bel Air High School about his drinking
problem.
   ``I would like to say I'm remorseful,'' he told Judge D. Clark
Hughes and the crowded courtroom. ``I'm sorry. I can't apologize
for my disease because alcoholism is a disease.''
   Burton was arrested on drunken driving charges in October 1984,
three times in 1985, once in 1986 and twice in 1987. His last
arrest was in January.
   He was not tried until Wednesday because of a backlogged docket,
scattered records and court delays requested by defense attorneys,
prosecutors said.
   After serving a jail sentence from July 4 to Aug. 31, Burton
will go to jail on 37 consecutive weekends. Then he will be on
probation for eight years. His driver's license was revoked
Wednesday.
   Burton's principal and some teachers presented the judge with
character references. Burton told Hughes he has been attending
Alcoholics Anonymous meetings and is receiving counseling.
   ``I'm grateful that nothing tragic has happened,'' Burton said.
``I'm trying hard to overcome this disease and will be doing my
best to see that this never, ever happens again.''
</TEXT>
