<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DiGilio     05-26 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DiGilio,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body Found Believed To Belong To Missing Reputed Mobster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decomposed body found Thursday in a
mortician's bag may be that of reputed mobster John DiGilio, who
disappeared three weeks ago, state and federal officials said.
   ``There's every reason to believe it is John DiGilio,'' said
Col. Clinton L. Pagano, superintendent of state police.
   U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. said credit cards with
DiGilio's name on them were found on the body. If the body is not
too decomposed, fingerprints could be taken for identification, he
said.
   ``We want to get the dental records,'' said Bayonne police Capt.
Tom Lavin. ``That's how badly decomposed it was.''
   Authorities identify DiGilio, a 55-year-old former boxer, as a
soldier in the Genovese organized crime family. After his
disappearance was reported May 7, law enforcement officials
speculated he was killed in an organized crime dispute.
   DiGilio was a colorful figure, acting as his own attorney in a
federal waterfront racketeering trial that ended with his acquittal
last month, often inviting boxing celebrities to court and filing a
harassment suit against federal officials.
   That flamboyance, authorities say, may have led to his death.
   Intelligence indicated that other Genovese family members were
dissatisfied with DiGilio's high profile, and that reputed family
boss Vincent ``Chin'' Gigante sanctioned the hit, officials said.
   DiGilio was to be sentenced on a state loansharking charge May
19, and authorities had also speculated his disappearance was a
ploy connected with sentencing. He has won frequent delays in
trials through claims of mental problems.
   But at the sentencing hearing, DiGilio's lawyer said the only
likely reason for his client's absence was foul play. At the court
proceeding, the judge issued a warrant for DiGilio's arrest.
</TEXT>
