<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BirthControlSentence     05-26 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Birth Control Sentence,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says Sentence Should be Appealed; Woman Ordered to Use
Birth Control</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Constitutional grounds probably exist to
appeal the sentence of an 18-year-old woman convicted of child
abuse and ordered to practice birth control for the remainder of
her child-bearing years, her defense attorney said Thursday.
   Also Thursday, Debra Ann Forster's mother said she understood
the judge's decision ``to an extent'' but hoped the birth-control
requirement could be dropped eventually.
   Robert Billar, a Maricopa County deputy public defender, said he
will recommend that his office appeal the Ms. Forster's sentence,
including ``obviously the provisions for mandatory birth control.''
   Possible grounds include ``constitutional rights to privacy,
religion and so forth,'' he said. Ms. Forster is Roman Catholic;
the church opposes artificial birth control.
   On Tuesday, a Maricopa County Superior Court judge sentenced Ms.
Forster to lifetime probation, with the provisions that she remain
on birth control during her child-bearing years and not see any of
her three children, one of whom was born in jail.
   She had pleaded guilty in April to two counts of felony child
abuse for leaving her two young sons alone in an apartment during a
hot-weather spell, without food or water, for three days last May.
She could have received 30 years in prison.
   Ms. Forster's two boys, 18-month-old William and 6-month-old
Scott, were hospitalized eight days for malnutrition, lesions
caused by a rash and dehydration. Scott was close to death from
dehydration when he was found by Ms. Forster's estranged husband,
police said.
   Ms. Forster told Judge Lindsay Ellis Budzyn she left the
children because she could not cope with the pressures of taking
care of them alone.
   Budzyn said Wednesday the birth-control requirement was the only
way she could make sure the woman would not abuse other children.
   Society offers little or no support to help those who are under
stress so that they do not abuse their children, the judge said.
``We don't have a lot of help out there for people,'' she said.
   Budzyn indicated that Ms. Forster's probation terms, like those
of all cases, could be modified in the future if requested by Ms.
Forster or her probation officer.
   Mary Jane Golotte, Ms. Forster's mother, said Thursday from
Amelia, La., she understood the sentence ``to an extent'' and that
the birth-control requirement is reasonable for the next several
years while the daughter gets life ``back together.''
   However, Ms. Golotte also said she hoped the requirement could
be dropped eventually.
   ``Later, down the road, people do change, and what if she
decides to get married and start her life all over again? What is
there for her to look forward to?''' the mother asked.
   Ms. Golotte also said she disagreed with Budzyn's statement that
Ms. Forster's case was an example of children having children.
   ``I think a lot of it has to do with drugs,'' she said. ``I
don't think it was because Debra Ann was not mature enough to have
children.''
   Ms. Golotte, 33, said that she was 15 when her daughter was born
and that her own mother gave birth to her also at age 15.
   A Catholic church official joined civil liberties advocates in
criticizing the sentence.
   The Rev. Timothy Davern, Phoenix Diocese vice chancellor, said
that he objected to the sentence on the grounds of religious
liberty and what he called its contradictory message.
   Ms. Forster has been sentenced to a lifetime of probation
counseling, he said, but ``the judge seems to be saying that no
amount of counseling could help this person grow to be a whole
person.''
   ``I'm not trying to minimize what she did, but how much does the
average person change between the ages of 20 and 30?,'' Davern said.
   Ms. Forster gave birth to a daughter while in jail awaiting
trial on the child abuse charges. According to court records, a
family friend adopted the daughter, and the sons were being placed
through an adoption agency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
