<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Cooperatives     05-26 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Cooperatives,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Legislature Unshackles Private Cooperatives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet parliament approved legislation
Thursday making it easier for private cooperatives to compete with
state-run businesses and giving local authorities power to promote
certain goods and services with tax breaks.
   The Supreme Soviet, the country's nominal parliament, made some
rare amendments to the law and held back the tax structure for
further changes. The moves came in a three-day session that ended
Thursday after much debate.
   The Supreme Soviet normally only approves laws put forward by
the ruling Communist Party. Debate over the cooperative law, which
delayed the vote for a day, underscored a greater willingness and
ability to speak out under Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
policy of greater openness.
   Officials said that in three months of public debate about the
law before it reached the Supreme Soviet, 42 of its 50 articles had
been amended.
   The amended law, which passed unanimously Thursday as is
traditional, goes into effect July 1.
   ``Local Soviets (governing councils) and other state bodies can
set a preferential tax system on cooperatives and ... members,''
said Alexei Ponomarev, the head of a Supreme Soviet commission that
reported on the cooperative law to the parliament Thursday.
   The law, as initially presented, had given only national
officials the right to give tax breaks.
   The adopted law also guarantees that cooperatives cannot be run
out of business by state-run enterprises. It allows them to conduct
business with foreign companies and receive hard currency as
payment; to own buildings and other property; and to appeal
decisions by authorities not to license a cooperative.
   Cooperatives are owned by the people who work in them and
represent a small sector of the Soviet economy, which is dominated
by state-run ventures.
   The arrangement is permissible under Marxist theory, which
teaches that workers are exploited if they work for anyone other
than the state or themselves.
   A law permitting formation of cooperatives has been adopted
under Gorbachev. Soviet Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov said Tuesday
that 14,000 cooperatives were formed in the first 18 months of the
law and another 6,000 in the past three months.
   Gorbachev has said he is depending on their development to
provide consumer goods and services that the inefficient state-run
economy cannot provide.
   Restaurants are one of the most popular forms of cooperatives
that have opened. Others have formed to make clothing, pump gas,
make home repairs and provide other services.
   In debate Wednesday in the Soviet of Nationalities, one of the
two chambers of parliament, deputy Georgy Tarazevich of Minsk,
Byelorussia, said local authorities should be given the right to
give tax breaks to encourage production of goods and services they
think are necessary.
   ``In my view, it's necessary to transfer to local Soviets the
tax policy regarding cooperatives,'' he said in remarks reprinted
by the government newspaper Izvestia.
   Ponomarev said the overall tax structure also would be reworked,
allowing flexibility depending on ``market conditions as well as
the activity of cooperatives.''
   But he did not say whether the specific tax rates in the law
would be reconsidered.
   Under the law as presented on Tuesday, personal income taxes
would be 27 percent on a monthly income of $1,600 and 53.5 percent
on an income of $3,200. The tax rate eventually reaches 90 percent.
   The average industrial worker in the Soviet Union makes about
$320 a month.
   Officials have said the aim of the progressive tax system is to
encourage the cooperatives to invest in expanding business rather
than paying high salaries to workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0188 </DOCNO>
