<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MilitaryWeapons     05-26 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Weapons,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woodbury Firm, Former Executive Plead Guilty To Illegal Arms Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY HELEN GILLESPIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company with ties to the Iran-Contra
scandal and one of its former executives pleaded guilty Thursday to
charges of selling military equipment abroad without U.S.
permission.
   Fourway Industries Inc. of Woodbury, which manufactures military
parts, pleaded guilty to two counts of a 27-count information
before U.S. District Judge Anne Thompson in Trenton.
   Jacobo Farber, who sold his majority interest in the firm in
October 1986, pleaded guilty to five counts of the information.
   In addition, U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito said the company and
three employees were indicted in San Diego in an alleged conspiracy
to divert weapons parts to Iran.
   By pleading guilty to the New Jersey charges, Forway and Farber
said that from May 1983 to April 1985, the corporation manufactured
and exported military equipment without registering as an exporter
with the State Department, Alito said.
   Both also admitted violating federal law requiring people
exporting military parts on a special U.S. Munitions List to obtain
licenses for each shipment of military parts, Alito said.
   Forway Industries made headlines in March when it was learned
that retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord and his business
partner, Albert Hakim, tried to buy one-third interest in the
company in 1986 with funds allegedly skimmed from the sale of
American weapons to Iran.
   Secord and Hakim face federal charges they conspired to divert
Iranian arms sales profits to the Nicaraguan Contras. They were
indicted in March along with former national security adviser John
M. Poindexter and former White House aide Lt. Col. Oliver North.
   The bid fell through in November 1986 just as news of the
Iranian arms sale broke.
   Forway Industries, which employees 80 people in two red brick
buildings near downtown Woodbury, manufactures and distributes
military spare parts.
</TEXT>
