<HEAD>Dutch Crown Prince Fined In Road Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crown Prince Willem Alexander was
fined $158 for reckless driving after a weekend road accident that
wrecked his car, a spokesman for the royal family said Thursday.
   The 21-year-old heir to the Dutch throne escaped injury in the
Saturday accident in Leiden, where he is studying history at the
university. The prince, who was driving 39 mph in a 30 mph zone,
drove his car into a ditch.
   Leiden is 10 miles north of The Hague.
   The chief prosecutor at the Hague district court imposed the
fine Thursday, the spokesman said. He declined to be identified in
line with Dutch government practice.
   The spokesman said that although the prosecutor's ruling is open
to appeal, Willem Alexander, the eldest son of Dutch Queen Beatrix,
is planning to pay the fine ``without delay.''
   Willem Alexander was passing another car when the road suddenly
narrowed, and he was forced to squeeze into the right lane, police
said.
   The car then swerved into a roadside ditch. The car was declared
a total loss, according to police.
