<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Mayors-Drugs     05-26 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mayors-Drugs,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayors Say Anti-Drug Monies Flowing Too Slowly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's mayors complained to a House
panel on Thursday that local governments face continued delays in
receiving federal monies for anti-drug programs.
   Kansas City, Mo., Mayor Richard Berkley, speaking on behalf of
the U.S. Conference of Mayors, blamed the delays on administrative
problems of state governments as well as the federal government.
   ``Frankly we are frustrated with the bureaucracy and we are
disheartened by the lack of support from the federal government,''
Berkley said in prepared testimony. ``The drug problem is in the
streets, the schools, the playgrounds of our cities. The
hand-to-hand combat is in the cities.''
   Berkley, president of the mayors group, asked the House Select
Committee on Narcotics Abuse to change the law so federal aid could
be sent directly to cities. State agencies now distribute most of
the money after receiving it from the federal government.
   State and local governments are to receive about $456 million
for drug programs in the current budget year, of which $70 million
is for enforcement, $230 million for education and $156 million for
treatment, according to the mayors.
   A Justice Department official acknowledged to the committee that
there had been ``some delay'' by states in preparing and submitting
applications for anti-drug monies in 1987, but he maintained ``all
of those are understandable'' because of the time required to
collect needed data and prepare spending plans.
   ``There is no delay on the part of the federal government,''
said Richard Abell, assistant attorney general in the dpartment's
office of justice programs.
   He said the Justice Department took an average of 37 days to
release monies to a state after it submitted its drug program plan.
   Berkley's remarks reiterated criticisms made last year by the
mayors that federal and state government were not quickly
distributing monies to cities for programs established after a
highly publicized 1986 anti-drug crusade by Congress and the Reagan
administration.
   Berkley also objected to the administration's proposed
elimination of federal aid for drug law enforcement in fiscal year
1989, which starts Oct. 1.
   ``This is not the way to wage a war on anything,'' Berkley said.
   Berkley welcomed Reagan's proposed 1989 increases of $10 million
for treatment and $20 million for drug education.
</TEXT>
