<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MercyKilling     05-26 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mercy Killing,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retired Farmer Will Serve At Least 28 Months For Wife's Mercy
Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 78-year-old retired farmer will serve
at least 28 months in prison for the shooting death of his wife,
who suffered from Alzheimer's disease, a judge ruled Thursday.
   Oscar Carlson, who has said he shot his 71-year-old wife, Agnes,
in February to end her suffering from the disease, will begin
serving his time at the Stillwater state prison immediately.
   Douglas County District Court Judge Paul Ballard gave Carlson a
43-month sentence. With good behavior, Carlson would be eligible
for parole in 28 months.
   Ballard recommended that Carlson later be placed in one of the
state's least restrictive facilities. That decision would be made
by the state commissioner of corrections.
   With good behavior, Carlson would be eligible for parole in 28
months.
   Before the sentencing, Carlson told Ballard that he was ``so
sorry'' for what happened to his wife of 45 years.
   Speaking in a faltering voice and sometimes breaking into tears,
Carlson asked Ballard to place him in a nursing home instead of
sending him to prison.
   ``I hope you will put me in a home, someplace where I can be of
some good to somebody,'' Carlson said.
   Carlson's attorneys had hoped that Carlson, who they said had
never even received a traffic ticket, would not have to serve time
in prison.
   Carlson pleaded guilty several weeks ago to second-degree murder
after Ballard said he would consider a maximum 43-month sentence.
That agreement departs from state sentencing guidelines, which call
for an 18-year sentence for second-degree murder.
   Carlson said in court Thursday during a pre-sentence hearing
that he snapped when he received the news Feb. 28 that his wife had
broken her hip and would have to be hospitalized. The next day, he
took an old pistol to the Crestview Manor Nursing Home in
Evansville where she lived and shot her four times.
   ``I just cracked up. I just couldn't take no more,'' Carlson
said.
   Douglas County Attorney Ann Carrott had opposed the 43-month
sentence. She said that she feels compassion toward Carlson, but
believes sentencing guidelines should be followed.
   She also presented a witness Wednesday who suggested that
Carlson had abused his wife and another who said he had complained
about the high cost of his wife's care prior to her death. However,
the nursing director of the home testified under cross-examination
that an investigation had shown no abuse of Mrs. Carlson.
   Carlson testified last month that his wife asked to be shot.
Carlson said he shot her four times with a .22-caliber pistol and
then sat down to pray and watch her die.
   All three of Carlson's daughters testified last month that they
hoped their father would be shown leniency because of the strain he
was under and his age.
</TEXT>
