<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Orlando     05-26 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Orlando,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Publicist, Master Of Deception Dead At 80</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guido Orlando, a publicist who concocted
stunts involving Pope Pius XII to boost hat sales in 1958 and King
Farouk to get a young starlet a movie contract in 1950, has died.
He was 80.
   Orlando died Sunday in a Hollywood hospital following a heart
attack.
   In 1958 he was hired by the Millinery Institute of America to
boost sales. He invented the ``Religious Institute of Research,''
which released a fictional survey that purported to show that 22
million Roman Catholic women throughout the United States went to
church bare-headed every Sunday.
   Through a friend in the Vatican, Orlando managed to obtain a
statement from the pope pointing to the dignity and decorum of hats
in church.
   Sales soared.
   Eight years earlier, Orlando planted stories that the Egyptian
king, known for his lavish lifestyle and romantic inclinations, was
chasing a 16-year-old American girl around Europe.
   Orlando had access to the king's travel schedule so arranged to
have the girl photographed at every city Farouk visited. By the
time the three-continent tour was over, the girl had gotten what
her parents hired Orlando for _ a movie contract.
   A native of Italy, Orlando staged his first hoax in 1925 when he
sent himself a phony telegram offering himself a part in a fake
play so his father would let him leave Wheeling, W.Va., for New
York.
   He met silent screen star Rudolph Valentino at a party and
became his friend, man-in-waiting and eventually his press agent.
   Orlando retired in the early 1970s, turning to work on an
autobiography, said longtime friend and retired journalist Pat
Anderson.
   In a 1972 interview, Orlando said he was not ``really such a bad
guy. I never hurt no one. ... I'm just a dream merchant. I make
people's impossible dreams _ fame, money, the movies _ come true.''
   There were no survivors. Services will be private.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
