<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     05-26 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranians Attack Tanker; Iraq Claims Iranian Jet Shot Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian gunboats attacked and set ablaze
a fully-laden Norwegian-operated tanker Thursday as it was sailing
out of the Persian Gulf, shipping executives said. No casualties
were reported.
   Iraq said its anti-aircraft gunners shot down an Iranian F-5
fighter over the battlefield in the Salamcheh sector near Iraq's
southern port of Basra.
   Iran said it sent thousands of volunteers Thursday to the
battlefront after their positions east of Basra fell in a lightning
assault Wednesday.
   Iranians hit the 15,530-ton liquefied petroleum gas carrier
Mundogas Rio at 7:45 p.m. as it sailed out of the Strait of Hormuz
and tried to jam its radio communications, said the shipping
executives, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   But the signal for help by the Liberian-flagged tanker, which
carried a shipment of Saudi Arabian oil products, was picked up by
another unidentified commercial ship in the vicinity, the
executives said.
   It was the third attack by the Iranians on neutral shipping
since Washington broadened the duties of the U.S. Navy in the gulf,
allowing warships to interevene in attacks on commercial vessels,
even if they are not sailing under the Stars and Stripes.
   The executives said they were not aware of any U.S. Navy
warships in the area at the time of the attack.
   They said the captain of the stricken vessel reported a small
fire aboard the ship but no casualties among the crew.
   The fire was quickly extinguished and the vessel sailed at full
speed toward the Omani port of Fujairah, outside the Strait of
Hormuz, said the sources.
   Elsewhere, a Baghdad communique said Iraqi warplanes ``scored
effective and accurate hits'' in a raid on the Imam Hassan oilfield
in southwestern Khuzestan province in Iraq's bombing campaign
against Iranian oil lines.
   Iran reported heavy artillery and mortar battles in the
Salamcheh sector, recaptured Wednesday by an estimated 35,000 Iraqi
troops.
   Wednesday's 10-hour battle, Tehran's third major military defeat
in five weeks, underlined a dramatic turnaround in the 7{-year-old
war.
   The Iraqis recaptured the Faw peninsula south of Basra, ending
two years of Iranian occupation, in a two-day April offensive. On
April 18, the U.S. Navy sank an Iranian frigate and several other
craft and disabled a second frigate.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia,
acknowledged that Iranian forces ``had to retreat from parts of the
area they had captured earlier.''
   It said the Iranians were now in ``new positions'' but gave no
details in one of Tehran's rare declarations of a military setback.
   Tehran Radio, also monitored in Nicosia, said ``large numbers''
of volunteers have been dispatched to the battlefront from 19
cities across Iran by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's government.
   The radio did not specify where the volunteers were headed.
   In Qatar, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, Vernon
Walters, said Thursday that Washington and Moscow wanted an
Iran-Iraq cease-fire soon, the Qatar News Agency reported.
   The agency quoted Walters as saying the United States was
seeking a new U.N. resolution to enforce the Security Council's
Resolution 598 passed July 20, which called for a cease-fire.
   Walters was in Qatar as part of a Middle Eastern tour.
</TEXT>
