<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Anglers'Strike     05-26 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anglers' Strike,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boatmen, Fishermen Threaten to Resume Fishing Boycott</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fishers threatened Thursday to end a
weeklong truce in the Great Anglers' Strike after they spotted
government inspectors checking for fishing licenses.
   Fishers and boatmen said they would renew a boycott of Irish
lakes and rivers Friday to protest the new law requiring anglers to
buy licenses for the first time.
   After the law was announced in April, angling clubs declared
their waters off-limits to fishing. Hotels told guests to stay
away, and fishing stores refused to sell licenses.
   The Roman Catholic archbishop of Tuam, Joseph Cassidy, announced
he had negotiated a deal with the government that prevented the law
from being implemented until further talks.
   Fishers said the appearance of the two inspectors in western
Ireland betrayed the terms of the deal.
   Michael Ryan, secretary of the Federation of Boatmen, which
represents lake fishing boats, said the boycott would resume Friday.
   ``The only talking we will do is through Archbishop Cassidy
directly to the government,'' Ryan said.
   The licenses cost from $15.60 to $26.50, depending on the type
of fish sought.
   Charles Sinnott, chairman of Ireland's Western Regional Tourism
Organization, said more protests could harm western Ireland's $60
million dollar tourism industry.
</TEXT>
