<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryStrength     05-26 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Strength,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armed Forces Continue to Cut Manpower Levels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The armed forces continued to slash their
active-duty strength in April to accomodate budget cuts, paring
more than 28,500 positions from the ranks in one month, the
Pentagon reported Thursday.
   As of April 30, the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps had
2,113,202 men and women on active duty, down 28,555 from the
2,141,757 on March 31 and 44,960 below the April 30, 1987, total.
   The Air Force had 581,861 people on active duty at the end of
April, down 12,799 compared with March 31. The Army listed 759,679
personnel on April 30, down 8,532 over the month.
   The Navy reported a decline of 4,065 men and women in April,
with 577,694 on its roster at the end of the month. And the Marine
Corps reported 193,968 on active duty, down 3,159 from March.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci has ordered a cut of almost
36,000 positions from the active-strength totals reported at the
end of fiscal 1987 last Sept. 30. The cuts are to be completed and
the services stabilized at the new levels by the start of fiscal
1989 on Oct. 1.
   Carlucci has told Congress he would rather maintain a smaller
force that is properly equipped and ready to fight than a larger,
but ``hollow,'' force.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
