<DOCNO> AP880526-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Panama-GuardTrip     05-26 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Guard Trip,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guard Training Trip Canceled Amid Panamanian Political Unrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iowa National Guard medical unit's
training trip to Panama has been canceled, but an officer denied
political developments there were the reason.
   ``From what I can tell, the mission just wasn't there,'' said
Lt. Col. Tim Brown. ``There has to be things for the soldiers to do
when they arrive, medical support missions, those kinds of things.
There just wasn't a mission that had enough things for them to do,
I guess.''
   The training exercise was scrapped after a Guard team had looked
at the area, he said. Though Guard officials were monitoring the
Panamanian situation, Brown said he doubted it was a factor.
   He said the decision against the trip was made earlier this
month before the United States broke off negotiations with
Panamanian military leader Manuel Antonio Noriega for him to step
down.
   The Iowa City unit's physicians, nurses, pharmacists and other
medical personnel had been scheduled to work Aug. 4-18 in support
of the staff at the Gorgas Army Hospital, an American military
facility in Panama.
   Because of the change in plans, most of the unit's 156 members
will spend that period at Fort McCoy, Wis., said Maj. Paul Schmid,
executive officer of the 109th Medical Battalion. Another 34 will
be assigned to duties in Guatemala.
   In Guatemala, the Iowa physicians, dentists, paramedics, dental
technicians and other health personnel will work with medical
forces from that country.
   Brown said the assistance had been requested by the Guatemalan
government. The Iowa National Guard will be the first unit to train
in Guatemala, he said.
</TEXT>
