<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WheatGrowers     05-26 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wheat Growers,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheat Farmer Says U.S. A Grain Seller, Not Grain Storer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision by the Agriculture Department to
loosen up acreage controls on 1989 wheat production ``indicates the
United States intends to be a grain seller, not a grain storer,''
the head of the National Association of Wheat Growers said Thursday.
   Frank Johannsen, a wheat farmer from Bayard, Neb., referred to a
USDA announcement on Wednesday that producers would be required to
idle no more than 10 percent of their wheat base acreage to qualify
for 1989 program benefits. The acreage set-aside was 27.5 percent
for 1988.
   Johannsen said the smaller land-idling requirement ``requires a
continuing federal commitment'' to operate the Export Enchancement
Program, or EEP, which has helped reduce surplus U.S. wheat
stockpiles.
   Under EEP, selected foreign countries _ including the Soviet
Union and China _ have been able to buy huge quantities of wheat at
subsidized prices.
   ``We intend to work closely with USDA and the Congress to see
that existing export assistance programs are used effectively and
that the past over-supply of wheat not be allowed to reoccur,'' he
said in statement released by the association's Washington office.
   ``For 50 years _ and often to its detriment _ the United States
has held virtually all the world's surplus grain,'' Johannsen
added. ``With the 1989 wheat program, we shift that burden to our
competitors.''
</TEXT>
