<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--SunflowerseedOil     05-26 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Sunflowerseed Oil,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Subsidy Plans for Oil Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunflowerseed oil exports would be subsidized
under proposed procedures to carry out a new program ordered by
Congress, the Agriculture Department announced Thursday.
   The plan would provide bonuses, or subsidies, to U.S. exporters
so they can charge less to foreign customers, thereby boosting
sunflowerseed oil exports.
   Under the proposal for the Sunflowerseed Oil Assistance Program,
or SOAP, exporters could collect subsidies in the form of surplus
sunflowerseed oil, said Acting Undersecretary Richard W. Goldberg.
   The program was authorized in a 1988 appropriations act, which
directed USDA to buy $10 million worth of sunflowerseed oil ``to
facilitate additional export sales of sunflowerseed oil,''
Goldberg's announcement said.
   Public comments on the SOAP plan can be sent to: General Sales
Manager, Foreign Agricultural Service, USDA, Washington, D.C.
20250-1000.
</TEXT>
