<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Taxes 1stLd-Writethru a0731 05-26 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Taxes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Stage Lockout As Senate Approves Tax Increases</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT new 8th graf with Dukakis reax bgng ``Asked about...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $110 million tax increase is on its way to
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis' desk, a package that state
Republicans hope will embarrass Dukakis as he campaigns for
president on a reputation as a tax-cutter.
   ``He's projecting himself as a tough law-and-order governor, as
a hands-on manager and as a budget-balancer. He's none of those,''
Sen. David Locke, a state co-chairman for Republican George Bush,
said Thursday.
   The tax package includes $70 million to couple the state income
tax with the federal code and $40 million from a tobacco sales tax.
Dukakis approves the former but has sent mixed signals on the
latter.
   The cigarette tax passed the state Senate on Wednesday following
a bizarre lock-out protest by Republican legislators. It is
expected to land on Dukakis' desk after a rubber-stamp final vote
by both houses.
   The governor's administration and finance secretary, Frank
Keefe, supports the measure but Dukakis aides hastily said that
Keefe was speaking for himself.
   Dukakis, before leaving to campaign in California, insisted that
the state can balance its books without the tax proposal.
   ``The governor's position has been, `I'll take a look at it, I'm
not supporting it,''' Dukakis' chief secretary, Hale Champion, said
Thursday.
   Asked about the cigarette tax, Dukakis told reporters Thursday,
``They'll be working this out, and when the budget gets to
conference we'll sit down and decide if we need additional
revenue.''
   In an unusual legislative tactic, six Senate Republicans failed
to return to the Senate chamber Wednesday evening. They locked
themselves in a Senate office and either took the phones off the
hook or ignored calls from Senate leaders.
   Meanwhile, Senate Democrats, in a voice vote, quickly passed the
cigarette tax as well as the $70 million income tax coupling bill.
   The Republicans said they were hoping to delay action on the tax
increase proposals while at the same time trying _ and succeeding _
to draw media attention to the tax bills.
   ``I would not be surprised if it were almost a Machiavellian
plot (by Democrats) to put tax bills on his desk and have him veto
them,'' Locke said. ``He is desperately trying to assume the mantle
of a tax-cutter.''
   Fellow GOP Sen. Paul Cellucci sees the cigarette tax as a
relatively minor issue compared to the state's budget woes.
Lower-than-expected state revenues have forced several downward
revisions in the $12 billion budget plan Dukakis filed in January.
   ``Why is the budget he filed at least half a billion dollars out
of balance, if not more?'' Cellucci said. ``The answer is a simple
one: there's been no discipline in spending.''
   During floor debate, Locke called the proposal ``a premonition
of what lies ahead for America.''
   ``When they elect the Duke, this is exactly what you are going
to get _ when they run out of dough, they raise taxes,'' he said.
   Senate President William Bulger, a Boston Democrat who supports
Dukakis, derided the Republican lock-out as a publicity stunt.
   ``The minority party was well aware of what's been going on,''
Bulger said. ``I'm not sure what constitutes childish behavior on
the part of Republicans. There's no reason for them to have been
gone for so long. ... Republicans know they're not smart. What they
do is look for attention.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
