<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TunaMerger     05-26 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tuna Merger,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Seeks to Block Heinz-Bumble Bee Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department told the H. J. Heinz
Co. of Pittsburgh and Bumble Bee Seafoods, Inc. of San Diego that
it would file suit to block Heinz's attempt to merge the marketers
of two of the country's three leading brands of canned tuna.
   ``The proposed acquistion poses a significant threat to
competition and to the American consumer,'' said Charles F. Rule,
head of the Antitrust Division. ``Canned tuna is one of the most
popular staple foods on the grocery shelf. This merger could result
in major increases in the prices consumers must pay for one of
their favorite foods.''
   Heinz's subsidiary, Star-Kist Foods, Inc., markets several
brands, including Star-Kist, the leading seller. Bumble Bee markets
two, including Bumble Bee, the No. 3 seller. The No. 2 seller is
Chicken of the Sea, a product of Ralston Purina.
   Star-Kist and Bumble Bee account for about 50 percent of the $1
billion tuna market.
   Heinz announced on Feb. 3 that it planned to acquire Bumble Bee
Seafoods, which also produces, distributes and markets salmon,
oysters and Figaro brand cat foods.
</TEXT>
