<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Reagan-Gorbachez Summit Is `Right Thing to Do'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Jesse
Jackson said Thursday that the upcoming superpower summit is a step
in the right direction, but that other nations should be included
in future meetings.
   ``When Reagan and Gorbachev meet in the Soviet Union, they
represent 500 million people, one-eighth of the human race.
Seven-eighths will be locked out of the meeting ... that has to
change,'' Jackson said.
   Still, he said, holding the summit ``is the right thing to do _
to talk it out and not shoot it out. ...our future is to choose
negotiation over confrontation, the human race over the arms race.''
   Jackson made his remarks at a rally with about 1,000 students at
racially mixed Independence High School in San Jose, 50 miles south
of San Francisco.
   He was concluding a 10-day campaign tour of California, where
polls suggest he is running far behind Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis for the June 7 primary.
   In his campus rally, Jackson said he believed he was having an
impact on Dukakis' views on South Africa. Jackson has been urging
that South Africa be designated a terrorist state, and has been
trying to bring Dukakis around to that view.
   Dukakis says he wouldn't rule it out, but also says he believes
economic sanctions would be a more effective first step.
   ``He is adjusting to a new agenda,'' Jackson said. He said
Dukakis is following his lead on the matter, as well as on drug
issues.
   Jackson again criticized the Reagan administration for ``the
disgraceful practice of negotiating with drug dealers, which
discredits our government and is beneath our dignity.'' He repeated
his familiar anti-drug message to the students.
   ``I challenge you today. Let's stop drugs, crack, heroin,
cocaine, PCP. Drugs are dream-busters. Drugs destroy your mind,
your body, your character, your good judgment... As president, I
can stop the supply of drugs. You must stop the demand for drugs,''
Jackson said.
</TEXT>
