<HEAD>Dukakis Campaign Names National Press Secretary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dayton Duncan, a former deputy press secretary to
1984 Democratic presidential nominee Walter Mondale, was named
Thursday as national press secretary for Democratic front-runner
Michael Dukakis.
   Duncan, 38, of Roxbury, N.H., will join the Dukakis campaign in
mid-June, according to a campaign statement. The appointment had
been rumored for several weeks and Duncan traveled with the
Massachusetts governor last week in what campaign aides said was a
trial run.
   Mark Gearan, the current national press secretary, will become
chief press secretary at the campaign's Boston headquarters,
overseeing the expansion of the press staff for the expected fall
campaign against Vice President George Bush.
   Both Gearan and Duncan will report to campaign communications
director Leslie Dach. Duncan will do the bulk of the traveling with
Dukakis in the fall campaign, campaign aides said.
