<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1910EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan     05-26 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Says Soviets Had 100,300 Soldiers In Afghanistan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0797 to fix coding.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union said Thursday it had 100,300
soldiers in Afghanistan when the withdrawal began May 15. It was
the first count the Kremlin had given in the eight years since it
joined the Afghan civil war.
   The number provided by Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev, chief of
the general staff and a first deputy defense minister, was nearly
15,000 below Western intelligence estimates.
   Soviet military forces entered Afghanistan in December 1979,
replaced one Communist government with another and stayed to fight
Moslem guerrillas.
   Akhromeyev gave the figure at a news conference the day after
Gen. Alexei D. Lizichev, another ranking Defense Ministry official,
provided the first Soviet casualty count: 13,310 soldiers killed,
35,478 wounded and 311 missing. Lizichev had refused to reveal the
size of the Soviet force.
   Western diplomats in Islamabad, Pakistan, said Thursday large
Soviet convoys were moving at night in northern Afghanistan in an
effort to speed the withdrawal.
   They said a major movement from Kabul north through the Salang
pass began early Wednesday and continued Thursday, but they did not
have the number of soldiers involved.
   Night travel is unusual and risky, particularly in the Shomali
area just north of Kabul, where reports indicated heavy fighting
recently, the diplomats said. The reports said guerrillas had taken
Qarabagh and Bagram, towns about 30 miles north of the capital.
   The diplomats in Islamabad, all of whom spoke on condition of
anonymity, said they had no indications from Kabul that rebel
pressure had impeded Soviet withdrawal.
   When journalists at the news conference asked Gen. Akhromeyev
for the number of soldiers, he replied: ``The contingent in
Afghanistan as of May 15 numbered 100,300.'' He said 9,500 soldiers
had left since the withdrawal began.
   Reports have said about 20,000 would be out by Sunday, when the
U.S.-Soviet summit begins in Moscow. Under the agreement signed
April 14 in Geneva, half the force is to be withdrawn by Aug. 15
and all Soviet soldiers must be gone within nine months.
   Earlier this week, reports from Islamabad quoted diplomats as
saying only two Soviet units totaling about 3,000 soldiers had left
since May 15.
   Diego Cordovez, the U.N. mediator who arranged the accord, said
Thursday in Geneva the agreement is ``slowly falling into place''
and ``we have a feeling that the implementation has started on the
whole in an effective manner.''
</TEXT>
