<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ForeignNurses     05-26 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foreign Nurses,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Nurses Get One-Year Visa Extension</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a stopgap measure to deal with a domestic
nursing shortage, the federal government on Thursday granted a
blanket one-year visa extension for thousands of foreign nurses
working in the United States.
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service acted following an
appeal last Friday by 42 members of Congress that it grant an
extension.
   In addition to granting a blanket extension _ coverting
five-year visas to six-year visas for foreign nurses _ INS
Commissioner Alan C. Nelson said agency district director ``will
have discretionary authority to grant additional time on a
case-by-case basis.''
   Guidelines for exercising the discretionary authority are being
developed, Nelson said in a statement.
   Meanwhile, he urged hospitals to redouble their efforts to
recruit and retain U.S. nurses and Congress to seek a long-term
solution to a domestic nursing shortage that administrators say
makes it essential for them to employ foreign-born nurses.
   Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., one of the lawmakers who urged
the extension, called the INS response ``an act of compassion.''
   ``There is a desperate shortage of nurses in many parts of the
country,'' Schumer said. ``Even though we all agree that additional
steps must be taken to expand training programs for more American
nurses and improve their pay, we cannot afford to wait at this
point.''
   Schumer pledged to work for legislation to attack the problem.
``The extension doesn't solve the nation's nursing shortage, but it
does buy time,'' he said.
   About 2,000 foreign nurses, 18 percent of the total recruited by
American hospitals, would have been sent home this year had the INS
not extended their visas. Most work in New York or California.
   An estimated 300,000 nursing jobs are unfilled nationwide _ a
vacancy rate that ranges from 10 percent to 20 percent in various
cities.
   The call for visa extensions was backed by nurses unions as a
temporary measure while more American nurses can be recruited and
trained. Union leaders say the profession demands more status and
higher pay _ especially for nurses with long-term experience, who
tend to quit because of burnout and lack of incentives.
   But they say it will take time to accomplish those changes and
that foreign nurses are needed in the meantime.
   Kenneth Raske, head of the Greater New York Hospital
Association, said the visa extension ``averted a potential public
health crisis in New York City'' were an estimated 4,000 foreign
nurses work and about one-fifth faced deportation this year.
   Officials in New Jersey estimated about 200 of the 918 foreign
nurses working there would have been subject to deportation this
year without the extension.
</TEXT>
