<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VigilanteNeighbors 1stLd-Writethru a0642i 05-26 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vigilante Neighbors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0642,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Attacked By Angry Neighbors Torched</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with fire, quotes from neighbors,
background; no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neighbors fed up with drug users and prostitutes
using a nearby house followed up trashing the place by torching it,
police said.
   About 25 residents on the city's southwest side stormed the
house Tuesday night and routed the occupants with baseball bats and
pipes, engaging some occupants in fist fights. Thursday morning,
the house was set on fire, and authorities suspect the people
simply finished the job they started.
   ``Get Out Now,'' and ``Move'' were spray painted on the front
door when the house was ransacked.
   ``Sure it was a lynch mob,'' one resident said. ``But what are
you going to do? We have to be vigilantes.''
   Police, who learned of the row only after it ended, said no
arrests were made. The fire, in which no one was hurt, likely will
go unprosecuted too, police said.
   Some neighbors said the incidents resulted from years of
frustration that had built up in the once tidy, ethnic neighborhood
of mostly Polish, Lithuanian and Ukrainian families.
   ``The neighborhood has changed gradually over the past 20 years,
but in the last five years it has accelerated,'' said Jack
Vassallo, a senior social planner and developer for the Detroit
Employment and Training Department who has lived in the
neighborhood 55 years. ``There are dope houses, car thefts,
prostitutes, you name it. I really hate to see the neighborhood go
down like this.''
   Neighborhood residents said they had asked for police help
numerous times, but authorities said they had no record of
requests, except for a narcotics complaint late last year.
   ``You can't take the law into your own hands,'' 4th Precinct
Cmdr. Daniel McKane said. ``I don't care how frustrating your
problem is.''
</TEXT>
