<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Metzenbaum-Reynolds     05-26 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Metzenbaum-Reynolds,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Accuses Justice Official of Lying to Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senator Thursday accused the Justice
Department's civil rights chief, William Bradford Reynolds, of
lying to Congress and of rejecting the advice of subordinates who
called for an FBI probe of a Republican Party voter registration
challenge in Louisiana.
   At a Senate Judiciary Committee hearing, Sen. Howard Metzenbaum,
D-Ohio, disclosed memos by civil rights division subordinates
urging that the FBI investigate possible criminal violations of the
Voting Rights Act in connection with a GOP voter registration
challenge aimed at predominantly black precincts in Louisiana in
1986.
   In March 1987, Reynolds told the committee that it was the
conclusion of ``everybody who looked at the matter'' from the
division's voting section that ``there was no ... violation of the
Voting Rights Act that would allow us to go in and prosecute.''
   ``You misstated the facts; you lied to the committee,''
Metzenbaum told Reynolds at a Judiciary Committee hearing Thursday.
   ``You state things in half-truths,'' responded Reynolds.
   ``What kind of half-truths, what kind of half-truths?'' yelled
Metzenbaum.
   Reynolds said that another part of the Justice Department, the
criminal division, was consulted on the matter and concluded that
no criminal investigation was warranted.
   Reynolds and a deputy, Jim Turner, insisted that subordinates in
the civil rights division ended up agreeing that no FBI probe was
warranted.
   Since the case involved the Republican Party, ``I wanted to be
darn sure I wasn't going to do something they would question us
about later,'' said Reynolds.
   Metzenbaum released an Oct. 7, 1986, memo by Rebecca Wertz, an
attorney in the voting section, urging the FBI's entry into the
matter. The senator also released another Oct. 7 memo _ this one to
Reynolds from Gerald Jones, chief of the voting section _ which
called for discussions on the appropriateness of having the
criminal section coordinate the investigation.
   In addition, civil rights division investigators wrote a
three-page document that would have been sent by Reynolds to the
FBI director detailing the proposed scope of a criminal probe.
Attached to the three-page document was a note from Jones to Turner
saying, ``As indicated in the earlier briefing papers we sent to
Brad re the Louisiana voter challenge matter, here is the FBI
request we propose to send out.''
   But at the bottom of Wertz' memo, Reynolds said in a handwritten
note:
   ``There is under the circumstances no legitimate reason to
initiate an FBI investigation of the La. activities.'' The note
said that a state court injunction had brought the voter challenge
activity to a halt, that no voters were denied registration rights
and that there was ``no real prospect'' they would be.
   ``On the other hand, there appears to be a concern of possible
harassment, fraud and intimidation of blacks in the upcoming
election,'' said Reynolds' note. ``To the extent such behavior is
found we may well want to initiate an FBI investigation after the
Nov. 4 elections.'' No such probe was ever launched.
   After the hearing, Reynolds' aides said they had provided
Metzenbaum with additional documents on the proposed FBI probe.
None of the additional documents, however, touched on any
involvement by the criminal division in recommending against a
probe, said aides to Metzenbaum.
   Reynolds is counselor to Attorney General Edwin Meese III as
well as assistant attorney general in charge of the Justice
Department's civil rights division.
</TEXT>
