<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon 3rdLd-Writethru a0821 05-26 0834</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0821,0859</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syria Announces Truce, Will Send in Troops; Generals' Car Ambushed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-5 RECAST to include assassination attempt in
lead. Picks up 6th graf pvs, A Syrian ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria said it will send in soldiers
Friday to end a 3-week-old bloodbath between rival Shiite Moslem
armies in the slums of south Beirut. Hours later, assassins tried
to kill Syria's four top generals here.
   The ambush failed, the Syrians reported, and the generals
escaped harm.
   Among the targets was Brig. Gen. Ghazi Kenaan, the officer who
earlier Thursday announced a truce in the south Beirut fighting and
disclosed Syrian plans to deploy its soldiers there.
   The generals' car was riddled with dozens of machine-gun bullets
Thursday night, but none of the officers or bodyguards was hit,
said Maj. Gen. Saeed Bairakdar, commander of Syria's forces in
Lebanon and a survivor of the ambush.
   Kenaan, Syria's military intelligence chief in Lebanon, told
reporters in the Lebanese capital upon his return from Damascus,
``Rest assured the slums war is over.''
   A Syrian official told The Associated Press ending the slaughter
will mean new hope for 18 foreign hostages, most of whom are
believed held in the embattled enclave. He pledged that Syria will
do its utmost to gain freedom for the captives, including nine
Americans.
   Fighting in south Beirut dwindled to sporadic sniper fire
exchanges Thursday after the cease-fire was announced. No
casualties were reported.
   But at 9:10 p.m. (3:10 p.m. EDT) gunmen opened up on the
generals' five-car convoy as it drove through Ghobeiry, one of the
embattled districts of south Beirut, Bairakdar told reporters after
arriving in west Beirut.
   He said the four officers were in Kenaan's bullet-proof Mercedes
500 when it was hit with dozens of bullets ``and the gas tank was
holed,'' forcing the generals to abandon the car and drive away in
one of the others in the convoy.
   The other officers were Brig. Gens. Ali Hammoud, intelligence
chief for the Beirut area, and Zuheir Musattati, a deputy to
Bairakdar.
   They were driving back from a meeting with Sheik Mohammed
Hussein Fadlallah, the spiritual guide of the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God, when attacked, he said.
   It was not clear who the assailants were. Hezbollah controls
most of the territory there.
   In south Lebanon, Israeli warplanes and helicopter gunships
blasted Palestinian guerrilla bases and positions of Hezbollah in
two separate raids.
   Twelve combatants were reported killed and four wounded in the
assaults, the first of which took place during the night and the
second at 8 a.m. (2 a.m. EDT) Thursday.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, is a group of Shiite fundamentalists
believed to be an umbrella for smaller organizations holding the
foreign hostages. It is Iran's main proxy force in Lebanon.
   Hezbollah and the Syrian-backed Amal militia have been locked in
a bloody fight for control of the 16-square-mile south Beirut
enclave since May 6.
   Police said the fighting killed 296 people and wounded 1,000.
Hezbollah gained control of more than 90 percent of the slums
during the struggle.
   On Thursday, Kenaan announced, ``Zero hour has been set. The
Syrian deployment will begin tomorrow (Friday).''
   He refused to disclose the exact time of the deployment, but
said Syrian forces will set up buffer zones to disengage the
combatants and patrol the suburbs to ``establish security.''
   Kenaan said the warring factions will be allowed to operate
``only political and information offices,'' indicating that the
militiamen will have to lay down arms.
   As he spoke, Kenaan was flanked by Bairakdar and Hammoud.
   Syria is the main power broker in neighboring Lebanon, which has
been wracked by civil war for 13 years.
   The three generals conferred with Shiite religious leaders and
politicians before Kenaan's declaration.
   In Damascus, a Syrian government official said a cease-fire
accord was worked out late Wednesday in a meeting between Syrian
President Hafez Assad and a Hezbollah delegation in Latakia,
northern Syria.
   ``Ending the fighting will create new hope for the hostages and
Syria will spare no effort to secure their release, regardless of
their nationality,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   He told AP correspondent Nick Ludington that the accord has been
approved by all parties concerned, including Iran.
   It was not clear if the hostages were part of the deal. But
Iran's acting foreign minister, Ali Mohammed Besharati, predicted
last week that the hostage problem would be solved after peace was
restored in south Beirut.
   Syria has had thousands of troops ringing the slums for days,
but a Syrian source in Damascus said Syria never believed it was
possible to obtain release of the hostages by force. The source,
who also spoke on condition of anonymity, said the first priority
was to preserve the hostages' lives _ ``then there can be hope for
their release through negotiations.''
   Terry Anderson, chief Mideast correspondent for the AP, is the
longest held hostage. He was captured on March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
