<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-HumanRights     05-26 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Human Rights,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama, Cuba Gain U.N. Human Rights Berths; Slap at Washington
Seen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama and Cuba, both targets of U.S.
economic sanctions, were elected to the U.N. Human Rights
Commission on Thursday in what was seen as a slap at U.S. policies
in Latin America.
   Colombia also was elected.
   Western diplomats said the election of Cuba, which has been
accused by the United States of widespread human rights violations,
had been expected because of its strong standing in the non-aligned
movement.
   Cuba replaces Nicaragua and is expected to vote in generally the
same way.
   The secret-ballot vote for Panama, however, appeared to be a
strong sympathy vote for that government and a show of anger over
U.S. sanctions and failed efforts to oust its de facto leader, Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Noriega is under indictment in the United States on drug
trafficking charges.
   The losers were Costa Rica, whose president, Oscar Arias, won
the Nobel Peace Prize last year for his Central American peace
plan, and Guatemala. Panama defeated Costa Rica in a runoff ballot.
   Ethiopia was elected unopposed as one of the African
representatives in another regional vote. Ethiopian authorities
have blocked food relief for famine-stricken regions in an effort
to prevent it from reaching rebels.
   The three Latin American nations were seated for three-year
terms on the major U.N. human rights organization. They were
elected by the 54-member Economic and Social Council, the parent
body.
   Panama's ambassador, Leonardo A. Kamm, said the vote was a
victorious ``message from the people of Panama to those conspiring
to isolate our nation diplomatically. The votes cast for us
demonstrate the political role my country continues to play in the
international arena.''
   Cuban Ambassador Oscar Oramas Oliva said the vote showed that
his country had international support despite efforts by U.S.
officials ``dedicated to a campaign of provocation and lies'' who
sought to condemn Cuba for purported human rights abuses.
   ``This is a victory for truth, reason and the people,'' he said,
adding that Cuba was committed to preserving human rights.
   Cuba was elected on the first ballot, winning 38 votes _ 10 more
than the required 28. Colombia received 46 votes and Panama 31.
   The election was to fill three Latin American seats on the
43-member commission, which represents regional groups.
   The Commission on Human Rights is the major U.N. organization
working to promote and protect human rights. It meets for six weeks
each year in Geneva.
   It makes recommendations to the General Assembly and considers
ways to combat racial discrimination, apartheid and discrimination
against women, children and the disabled.
   Others elected to the commission were Morocco, Swaziland, the
Ukrainian Republic, the Soviet Union, Canada, Sweden, India, Cyprus
and Bangladesh.
   Other elections will be held next year.
</TEXT>
