<HEAD>Palestinians Say Missing Belgian Doctor Was Kidnapped</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Thursday they had no
information about a Belgian physician missing since the weekend,
but Palestinian sources said Dr. Jan Cools was kidnapped in south
Lebanon.
   The Popular Committee, which runs daily affairs at Rashidiyeh, a
Palestinian refugee camp, said in a statement that Cools was
abducted near the ancient port of Tyre by gunmen.
   It said Cools, 32, left his base at the Rashidiyeh camp Saturday
in a taxi headed for Tyre, two miles to the north, and was
``abducted at a road junction leading to Qana,'' about midway. It
gave no further details.
   His Norwegian employers, a relief group called Norwac, said the
Cools left Rashidiyeh at 2 p.m. Saturday.
   Amal, the mainstream Shiite Moslem militia, seized control of
Tyre and other sectors of south Lebanon in April after crushing the
pro-Iranian Hezbollah in the area.
   A statement from Amal said it was ``investigating the Belgian
doctor's case'' and ``parties carrying out their own plots in south
Lebanon'' may have kidnapped him. It did not elaborate.
   Eighteen foreigners are missing, and most are believed to be
captives of Shiite extremists linked to Hezbollah. Held the longest
is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press, who was seized March 16, 1985.
