<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2135EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MilitaryLove     05-26 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Love,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marines Drop Charges Against Navy Officer Who Married Enlisted Man</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy officer who defeated fraternization
charges brought against her because of her relationship with a
Marine enlisted man said Thursday she loves the service and hopes
her case will change military policy.
   ``I love my husband. I love the Navy, and I don't see why the
two are not compatible,'' Lt. Kathleen A. Mazure, 29, told
reporters at a news conference a day after a Marine Corps general
dropped the charges.
   Ms. Mazure, a dentist assigned to the Marine Corps Air Ground
Combat Center at Twentynine Palms, Calif., was accompanied by her
husband, former Lance Cpl. Scott Price, and her parents, Jim and
Pat Mazure.
   ``I hope that from out of this the fraternization policy will
become more defined, so that people won't have to go through what I
had to, because it is very ill-defined,'' she said.
   Ms. Mazure, formerly of Mercer Island, Wash., was cleared of all
charges after Tuesday's 4{-hour hearing before Maj. Gen. Gene
Deegan, said Mark Rosenbaum, an American Civil Liberties Union
lawyer.
   ``I'm very proud of my wife for holding up so well,'' said
Price, 24, of Eden, Texas, who married her Nov. 28 and left the
Marines after the charges were brought.
   The charges brought Nov. 25 marked ``the first time in the
history of the United States ... that charges of fraternization
have been brought against an officer for conduct with a member of
another branch of the service,'' Rosenbaum said.
   He emphasized that Ms. Mazure and her husband were not in the
same chain of command.
   On Jan. 11, a hearing was held to determine whether she should
be court-martialed and on Jan. 19 the hearing officer recommended
there should be no court-martial, Rosenbaum said.
   Deegan overruled the recommendation and on Feb. 16 the case was
referred to a court-martial. On Monday the court-martial charges
were dropped and on Tuesday Deegan held a non-judicial hearing that
resulted in final dismissal of the allegation, the attorney said.
   A base spokesman, Chief Warrant Officer Doug Hauth, said Deegan
``was of the opinion that because of her background and training
and short time assigned to this Marine Corps command, that
fundamental fairness required that she not be held criminally
accountable for her relationship.''
   Ms. Mazure said she does not believe the incident will affect
her career. ``I feel that the work I do and the way I am should be
able to show for itself what kind of person I am, that I do intend
to make the Navy my career,'' she said.
   Ms. Mazure said she was stationed in Jacksonville, Fla., when
she met Price during an evening of dancing in July 1986, and that
neither knew the other was in the service until after several dates.
   They kept in touch through letters when Price was transferred to
the California desert base. She said she was offered a post at
Twentynine Palms and was transferred there on Sept. 27, 1987.
   Rosenbaum said items presented at Tuesday's hearing included a
document from the office of the chief of naval operations ``that
states that there is no formal policy regarding fraternization.''
   Also presented was a 1985 study by the Department of Navy
``which found that fraternization ... within one's own chain of
command ... was absolutely rampant and that the majority of
individuals in the Navy simply had no idea as to what constitutes
wrongful fraternization,'' he said.
</TEXT>
