<1ST_LINE>u w AM-S&LInsuranceFund     05-26 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&L Insurance Fund,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Would Prevent Healthy S&Ls from Fleeing FSLIC</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: St Germain, no period, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee's chairman
introduced legislation Thursday that would prevent healthy savings
institutions from fleeing the ailing federal fund that insures
their deposits.
   Sixteen Democrats and seven Republicans are backing a bill
introduced by Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I. It would bar S&Ls
from leaving the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp. until
Aug. 10, 1989 _ one year longer than a ban currently in effect.
   Congress last summer included the initial moratorium in
legislation providing for a $10.8 billion industry-financed
infusion into FSLIC, which insures S&L deposits up to $100,000.
   Because the insurance premium charged by FSLIC is roughly 2{
times greater than the premium charged the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp., legislators fear that thrifts eligible for
admission to the FDIC will leave FSLIC and become banks.
   The General Accounting Office, the auditing arm of Congress,
warned last week that the S&L fund may not have enough money coming
in to take care of the roughly 500 S&Ls listed as insolvent.
   ``Any flight of (healthy) institutions whose insurance premiums
help pay the bills would be a further blow to an already weakened
fund,'' St Germain said in a statement.
   St Germain introduced the legislation after receiving a letter
Wednesday from the top federal regulator of savings institutions,
Federal Home Loan Bank Board Chairman M. Danny Wall, who supports
extending the moratorium.
   Wall said the bank board did not know how many S&Ls would leave
the fund if they could, but, he said, ``The most important value in
this equation at the moment is perception _ the perception that
without the moratorium there may be a major exodus from FSLIC.''
   Mark Clark, senior vice president of the U.S. League of Savings
Institutions, the largest trade group in the industry, said
extending the moratorium is unfair to savings institutions and
breaks the agreement Congress made with the industry last year.
   ``We don't advocate mass exodus. All we're saying is there ought
to be free choice,'' Clark said.
</TEXT>
