<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Orol     05-26 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Orol,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexican Filmmaker Dies at Age 90</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Juan Orol, a leading director during the
``golden age'' of Mexican cinema, died Thursday of complications
from diabetes, his family said. He was 90.
   Among his best known movies were ``Mother Dearest,'' his first,
in 1935; ``The Right and the Duty'' in 1937; and ``The Reign of the
Gangsters'' and ``Tania, the Beautiful Savage,'' both in 1947.
   Orol was born in Spain and emigrated to Mexico in 1917.
   He was a founding member of the Association of Movie Producers.
He served as producer, director, screenwriter and editor on almost
all his movies.
   Many of his films featured music, especially with tropical
rhythms, and gangsters, cabarets or wrestling.
   Orol dressed in classic gangster style at a tribute to him in
April, wearing an elegant black suit with white stripes, a white
shirt with black stripes, a black satin tie and black shoes and
socks.
