<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cuba-Bombing 1stLd-Writethru a0705 05-26 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-Bombing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Castro Bombing Hits Home of U.S.-Cuba Forum Sponsor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th graf, `The Sheraton-Brickell ..., to
UPDATE with event taking place without incident; INSERTS 1 graf
after 14th graf, `He is ..., to UPDATE with Sanchez admitted to
forum as observer.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second anti-Castro terrorist bombing here this
month forced a forum on U.S.-Cuba relations out of a downtown hotel
Thursday, and some Cuban exile leaders say such incidents must end.
   The 3 a.m. blast Thursday injured no one, but demolished a
garage door, tore away part of a concrete wall and blew out the
windows of a car at the home of Maria Christina Herrera in Coral
Gables.
   Ms. Herrera, a Miami-Dade Community College professor who heads
a group advocating more dialogue with Castro's Cuba, sponsored a
forum on the future of U.S.-Cuba relations on Thursday afternoon.
The site of the forum was hastily moved after the bombing.
   ``This is a cowardly attack,'' she said in her damaged home.
``This is an attack on freedom, democracy and freedom of expression
_ the right to do whatever you want in a civilized way.''
   The Sheraton-Brickell Point Hotel, where the forum was to take
place, pulled out after the bombing. But University of Miami
President Edward T. Foote agreed to let the university serve as
host for the event instead, ``in the interests of academic
freedom,'' said a school spokeswoman, Conchita Ruiz-Topinka.
   The event went off without incident at the university's faculty
club, where security guards screened everyone who attended.
   The FBI and Coral Gables police were investigating the case. No
one claimed responsibility for the attack, but authorities had few
doubts about its motivation.
   ``She feels that a new approach should be used toward Cuba,''
said FBI Special Agent George Kiscynski. ``She has probably made
some enemies in the community, and has become the victim of a
terrorist attack.''
   The bombing was the second this month apparently aimed at
protesting closer relations with Cuba. On May 3, a pipe bomb blew
in the door of the Cuban Museum of Arts and Culture after a show
featuring some painters still in Cuba who critics said were too
close to Cuban leader Fidel Castro.
   Some of the same Cuban radio talks shows and news programs that
had called for opposition to the art show also bitterly attacked
the forum sponsored by Ms. Herrera's group, the Institute of Cuban
Studies, and she blamed them for inflaming the situation.
   ``All of these people in the community that are haranguing
people on the radio against our debate today are somewhat
responsible for this action, morally at least,'' she said.
   Xavier Bray, founder of the Spanish American League Against
Discrimination, said the attacks undermine the freedoms Cubans came
to the United States to enjoy.
   ``This isn't a question to be settled only by the force of arms,
but by the force of reason, by being able to exchange ideas,'' he
said Thursday.
   The bombing came 2{ hours after a meeting at Ms. Herrera's
house, at which conference organizers decided not to include a
visiting representative of the unofficial Cuban human rights
commission, Elizardo Sanchez Santacruz.
   He is a former political prisoner given permission by the Castro
government to set up his organization. His trip to the United
States and request to be included in the forum made anticommunists
here suspicious, and the organizers decided his participation would
only further anger anti-Castro militants.
   Sanchez was allowed into the meeting at the university as an
observer, not a participant in the forum.
   Bill Ripple, general manager of the Sheraton-Brickell Point
Hotel, said the hotel canceled the conference ``based on the best
interests of our employees and guests because of the recent
incidents, including the bombing.''
</TEXT>
