<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ChemicalWarfare     05-26 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Warfare,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Tour British Facility, Debate Weapons Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Soviet experts to visit a
chemical weapons facility in Western Europe accused the United
States Thursday of blocking progress on a global treaty banning the
weapons.
   At a news conference, the Soviet and British envoys to the
40-nation treaty negotiations disagreed about the consequences of
America's resumption of the production of binary chemical weapons
last December.
   Yuri Nazarkin, chief Soviet envoy to the talks in Geneva, said
the U.S. plans ``undoubtedly run counter to the aim of a chemical
weapons convention and they undermine the confidence-building
process.''
   But Nazarkin said the three-day visit to Britain's Chemical
Warfare Defense Center by a 13-member group of Soviet technical and
military experts helped pave the way for a chemical weapons ban.
   ``We firmly believe that this convention will be achievable
soon,'' he said.
   He said British officials were forthcoming in talks and helpful
in showing the Soviets around the sprawling 7,000-acre facility at
Porton Down, where the Soviets watched soldiers in gas masks react
to a simulated nerve gas attack.
   Tessa Solesby, the British negotiator at the Geneva talks, said
Washington resumed making chemical weapons to counter the Soviets'
production and to replace aging stockpiles.
   Miss Solesby also rejected arguments by Nazarkin that the Geneva
talks needed a push from the American, Soviet and British leaders,
and said the main problem was the difficulty of verifying any
agreement.
   ``It is not a matter of lack of political will. ... it's the
technical difficulties that remain,'' she said.
   Dr. Graham Pearson, director of the Porton Down center, said the
Soviet visit was a ``significant first step toward building
confidence between the Soviet Union and the United Kingdom.''
   Britain ceased making chemical weapons and destroyed its
stockpile in the 1950s and says Porton Down is only for defensive
measures, such as the production of gas masks and monitoring
equipment.
   In July, a British team will visit the chemical warfare facility
at Shikhany in eastern Russia.
   Western experts visited Shikhany briefly last year and Soviet
inspectors went to a U.S. Army chemical weapons disposal plant in
Toole, Utah.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev acknowledged last year for
the first time that the Soviet Union has a chemical weapon
stockpile, which he put at 50,000 tons, but said production of more
weapons had stopped.
   Western governments say the Soviet stockpile totals 300,000
tons, which would make it the largest in the world.
   The Soviets say the United States has a 50,000-ton stockpile _
20,000 tons higher than Western estimates.
   The United States' renewed production of binary weapons _
separate agents that are lethal only when combined _ ended an
18-year moratorium on making the arms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
