<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NATO 2ndLd-Writethru a0664 05-26 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0664,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allies Asks Italy To Take U.S. Jet Fighters</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New grafs 1-10 UPDATING with formal request, comment by
Carrington, Italy agreed in principle. Picks up 5th graf pvs, ``All
agreed ... DELETING final 6 grafs to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO formally asked Italy Thursday to
be the host country for a U.S. jet fighter wing that Spain is
expelling from its territory.
   But the allies quarreled over how to pay for the move, officials
said.
   Italy was expected to accept the 72 nuclear-capable F-16 jets if
the allies paid to expand Gioia del Colle, a small air base in
southeastern Italy that could be the planes' new home.
   A U.S. official in Brussels said a final decision on the Italian
site would be made later. He also said details on financing the
move would be put off.
   In Rome, a senior Italian official said Italy agreed in
principle to accept the F-16s, but the government and Parliament
must still examine the proposal.
   The issue dominated the opening session of a two-day meeting of
defense ministers from all North Atlantic Treaty Organization
members except France, which is not part of NATO's joint military
structure.
   The defense chiefs also planned to issue on Friday a joint
statement of support for President Reagan prior to his meetings
next week in Moscow with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, said
the officials.
   All the officials spoke on condition they not be identified.
   Alliance officials portrayed the decision to ask Italy to accept
the jets as an important display of Europe's resolve to bear its
share of the NATO defense burden.
   ``This is an important step toward preserving NATO's common
defense and to sharing the burdens of doing so equitably among the
alliance as a whole,'' said Lord Carrington, the NATO
secretary-general.
   ``All agreed that this is an alliance matter and that the
alliance should help finance it,'' said Gen. Wolfgang Altenburg of
West Germany, the alliance's chief military adviser.
   Spain declared in January that the F-16s would have to leave
Spanish territory within three years as part of a domestically
popular drive to lessen the U.S. military presence in Spain.
   The planes play an important role in NATO's strategy for
carrying out a nuclear response to a possible attack by the
Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
   Altenburg told reporters that NATO's Military Committee, the
alliance's highest military authority, advised the defense
ministers meeting that Italy was ``the only suitable country'' to
take the aircraft, which are dedicated to the defense of southern
Europe.
   Italy has indicated it would be willing to have the F-16s based
on its soil, as long as a formal NATO request was made and the
alliance paid for moving the planes and the 4,000 U.S. personnel
and their dependents.
   The NATO defense ministers agreed in principle that the cost of
relocating the U.S. jet fighters should be met by NATO's
infrastructure budget, which is a common pool of money used to
build military facilities.
   There was disagreement, however, over whether the amount needed
for the move _ estimated by U.S. officials at roughly $500 million
_ should be added to the infrastructure budget. The American view
was that 100 percent of the cost should be added to the budget.
Others said no additional money should be made available, according
to several officials.
   It appeared that the financing details would be left unresolved
for the time being. The planes aren't scheduled to be moved until
1991.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci told his NATO colleagues
that a decision to keep the F-16s in Europe would help blunt U.S.
congressional complaints that the European allies are not pulling
their weight in the alliance, said an official who was present at
the ministers' meeting.
   The ministers were expected on Friday to publicly call for an
alliance study of how common defense costs and responsibilities are
shared.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
