<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0746 05-26 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0746,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas and Contra Rebels Begin New Round of Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with quotes,
details following meeting. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan rebels on Thursday offered
a plan to lay down their arms, but set conditions the government
termed ``provoking, preposterous'' and contrary to earlier accords.
   The U.S.-supported rebels, known as Contras, tied their proposal
to stop pursuing the 6{-year-old war to measures aimed at what they
called ``democratization of Nicaragua.''
   The rebels, speaking at the opening of a new round of peace
talks, demanded within five days freedom of the press and broadcast
media, an end to the military draft, and freedom to supply their
forces in the field.
   Manuel Espinoza, the presidential spokesman, quickly described
the plan as preposterous and said, ``The Contra proposal is
unrealistic and casts aside all that has been done and agreed upon
until now and makes new proposals.''
   Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco said, ``With this
proposal, they're acting as if they had won the war and the
Sandinistas had surrendered.''
   Alfredo Cesar, chief of the rebel delegation, said Thursday the
offer contains ``democratic changes the country should make at the
end of the war.''
   Tinoco said the leftist Sandinista government was proposing
discussion of ``guarantees in the electoral process, dates for
municipal elections, reforms in the electoral law, pluralistic
representation in the electoral council and guarantees and norms
for the functioning of a mixed economy.''
   Rebel leaders said their plan deals with both military and
political issues.
   At the center of the Contra proposal was a demand that the
Sandinistas ease their control over the army and government. They
also seek constitutional reforms and freedom of expression.
   Under what the rebels call a ``flexible'' timetable, they would
lay down their arms sometime before Christmas.
   ``We have come here to present a comprehensive proposal to the
government for a global solution to the war,'' Cesar said late
Wednesday.
   He leads delegates of the Nicaraguan Resistance, umbrella
organization for the rebels.
   Cesar said the rebels were prepared to make a ``special effort
to achieve a definitive cease-fire.''
   The delegations met under tight security at the Camino Real
Hotel. Gen. Humberto Ortega, the defense minister and the brother
of President Daniel Ortega, heads the government delegation.
   Rebel representatives include their military leader, Col.
Enrique Bermudez, who was making his first trip to Managua since
the war started in late 1981.
   Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo and Joao Baena
Soares, secretary-general of the Organization of American States,
were witnesses.
   Cesar said rebels ``are not optimistic'' about the outcome of
the meeting because they said the government has not complied with
a preliminary peace plan agreed upon March 23 in Sapoa, a southern
border town.
   At Sapoa, the two sides agreed to a 60-day cease-fire and on the
basis for further talks to arrange a permanent truce.
   The cease-fire expires May 30, but President Ortega said he
would extend it for an additional 30 days.
   Rebel leaders have said they want a permanent truce but will not
break Ortega's unilateral extension of the peace.
   The meeting was the third between rebel and government
representatives in Managua since the Sapoa accord.
   Ortega says the war has killed 26,500 people and caused $3
billion in damage to the economy.
</TEXT>
