<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-26 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Few Blustery Storms Rumble Across The North Central Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Isolated showers and thunderstorms rumbled across the north
central region Thursday, with rain, hail and gusty winds in parts
of North Dakota as a cold front moved slowly across the region, but
much of the nation was dry.
   In western North Dakota, Watford City reported winds gusting to
60 mph, and Roseglen reported 56-mph gusts. Other showers and
thunderstorms were reported on the Minnesota-Iowa line and in
northern Lower Michigan.
   Central Florida also had showers and thunderstorms, and showers
were scattered across much of New England. Other showers and
thunderstorms were developing over the Colorado Rockies into north
central New Mexico.
   Skies were mostly sunny Thursday afternoon from the Ohio Valley
and middle Atlantic states into the Southeast, with readings in the
60s and 70s.
   Temperatures across the central and southern Plains into Texas
were in the 70s and 80s, with skies partly cloudy.
   Skies were partly cloudy in the central Pacific Coast, and sunny
skies prevailed from the valleys of California across the desert
Southwest.
   The low for the nation Thursday was 28 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT cdt ranged from
45 degrees at Caribou, Maine, to 103 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
   The national weather forecast for Friday called for numerous
showers and thunderstorms across the southern tip of Florida,
scattered showers across the Northern Pacific and the northern
Rockies. Scattered showers and thunderstorms will develop late in
the afternoon across western parts of South Dakota. Otherwise, most
of the nation will have mostly sunny skies.
   High temperatures will be in the 70s or 80s over much of the
nation; in the 60s along the central and northern Pacific Coast
into northern Washington state; into the 90s across inland southern
Texas; and, from the mid 90s to 105 degrees across the desert
Southwest.
</TEXT>
