<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reed-Extortion 1stLdWritethru a0653 05-26 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reed-Extortion, 1st Ld Writethru, a0653,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Montgomery Grand Jury Hearing Allegations Against Reed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES with comments from Montgomery D.A. Jimmy Evans,
changes byline; edits thruout; no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER VILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Alabama NAACP, accused
of taking $10,000 to use his influence as a lawmaker to help a
murderer get early parole, appeared before a county grand jury
Thursday, one day after he was indicted on federal extortion
charges.
   A federal grand jury is scheduled June 14 to hear the bribery
charges against Thomas Reed, the longtime state president of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   Federal investigators said their investigation is aimed solely
at Reed, who's also a state representative. Montgomery County
District Attorney Jimmy Evans said the county grand jury is looking
into the problem of preferential treatment of prisoners by state
parole officials.
   Several officials of the State Board of Pardons and Paroles also
appeared before the grand jury Thursday.
   ``I'd say for the last four or five years we've had a nagging
question in this state: Can you buy early release or early
parole?'' Evans said. ``We're interested in knowing how widespread
the practice is.''
   Evans said the grand jury would probably return Friday for a
short session. He did not say when he expected the investigation to
finish.
   Reed, co-chairman of the Legislature's Joint Prison Committee,
is accused of taking $10,000 from the uncle of Anthony Chesser and
agreeing to use his influence as a legislator to try to get
Chesser's early release from prison.
   The FBI's investigation surfaced last week, with Reed
complaining it was in retaliation for his efforts to remove the
Confederate battle flag from the Alabama Capitol dome. Reed, a
businessman, in 1970 became one of the first two blacks elected to
the Alabama Legislature this century.
   The FBI said Reed got the state parole board to move up
Chesser's parole consideration date from 1994 to 1989. Chesser,
convicted of murdering his wife, began serving a 40-year sentence
in August 1984. But then Reed's efforts were reversed, and the
uncle demanded a refund.
   Reed repaid $8,000 and promised to refund the rest, the FBI said.
   The meeting between the uncle and Reed was taped, with the
uncle's cooperation, the FBI said. ``You could hear the money being
counted,'' said U.S. Attorney Jim Wilson.
   Reed's central Alabama district does not include Anthony
Chesser's hometown of Phenix City, and his uncle, Bobby Gene
Chesser, is from Columbus, Ga. The two legislators who represent
Phenix City, Rep. Charles Adams and Sen. Danny Corbett, said
neither Reed nor Bobby Gene Chesser contacted them about getting an
early parole for the convicted murderer.
   The FBI's investigation of Reed, 60, surfaced last week, with
Reed complaining the probe was in retaliation for his efforts to
remove the Confederate flag from the Alabama Capitol dome.
   Reed drew widespread attention Feb. 2 when he made a symbolic
bid to remove the flag from the Capitol. Reed and 13 other black
legislators were arrested and charged with misdemeanor trespassing
in a case that is pending.
   The FBI has denied any connection between the flag controversy
and the case against Reed.
</TEXT>
