<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0831,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Talks Tough on Drugs; Dukakis Faces Tax-Hike Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to fix day; INSERTS 1 graf after 9th graf pvs,
bgng: ``You'd rather... with ABC-Post poll showing Dukakis ahead</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush on Thursday proposed an international
strike force to hit ``quick and hard and often'' at foreign drug
operations. Democrat Michael Dukakis campaigned in California while
more than $100 million state tax increases neared his governor's
desk back in Massachusetts.
   Bush, the all-but-sure Republican presidential nominee, also
called for denying federal contracts to U.S. companies lacking
``drug-free programs,'' a proposal an aide said could involve
mandatory drug testing.
   Dukakis, however, made fun of Bush's recent drug proposals:
``The question is, `Why haven't these been done the past seven
years? Isn't the vice president in charge of this (anti-drug)
effort?''
   Democrats Dukakis and Jesse Jackson were concentrating on
California, the biggest delegate prize in the June 7 presidential
primary finale, while Bush campaigned in New Jersey on the way to
his Maine seacoast retreat.
   For Dukakis, who has campaigned as a tax-cutting governor, the
prospect of being saddled with an election-year tax increase loomed
as he sought votes 3,000 miles away.
   His state legislature gave approval to increases in cigarette
and other taxes totaling more than $100 million as a remedy for
newly found budget deficits. A final vote was needed, but the
legislation cleared its major hurdle over Republican objections.
   Dukakis declined to say whether he would sign the cigarette tax
increase.
   With Dukakis leading Bush in recent polls, the vice president's
pollster Robert Teeter said the Bush campaign is concerned but not
panic-stricken.
   ``You'd rather be ahead. But surely there is no feeling of
crisis or panic,'' Teeter said. ``We're a long way ahead of the
election. A lot of decision-making is yet to come.''
   An ABC-Washington Post poll gave Dukakis a 53 percent to 40
percent lead over Bush, ABC reported Thursday night. The survey,
based on telephone interviews with 1,508 people between May 19 and
Monday, had a margin of error of 3 percentage points.
   Bush plans to take a week off for meetings with party leaders
and advisers in Kennebunkport, Maine.
   He launched a new anti-drug initiative on Thursday, including
the call for a drug strike force, possibly under the auspices of
the United Nations, to be created ``to hit back, quick and hard and
often, at foreign drug operations.'' U.S. involvement would be
coordinated by a military officer reporting to Bush's vice
president.
   Bush spoke in Secaucus, N.J., then visited a drug rehabilitation
center in nearby Newark, where he talked with patients.
   He said he opposed relaxing the Justice Department's ``zero
tolerance'' policy for seizing yachts and other vehicles in which
drugs are found. ``I think it makes great sense,'' he said.
   With his own aides acknowledging the vice president has been
hurt by the controversy over Attorney General Edwin Meese III, Bush
sought to turn the attention to the Democrats by renewing his call
for a federal special prosecutor to investigate House Speaker Jim
Wright's finances.
   ``I wonder if Mike Dukakis and Jesse Jackson will join me in
calling for the House of Representatives to appoint a special
prosecutor to look into its own troubles, starting with the
speaker,'' Bush said.
   Dukakis visited a company-sponsored day care center in Palo
Alto, Calif., where he called for more investment in schools and
``clear guidelines'' to limit corporate mergers.
   ``Today as in 1960 we're fighting for the economic future of
America,'' Dukakis said. ``And now, as then, old ways simply will
not do.''
   Dukakis offered no defense of Wright, except to say it was
``proper and appropriate'' that the speaker had pledged cooperation
with any ethics committee probe into his activities. Dukakis said
Bush should not try to exploit the Wright issue, and referred again
to administration dealings with Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega.
   ``I'm going to continue to insist on a full explanation from the
administration about what's going on'' with Noriega, he said.
   Jackson also made California campaign appearances, a day after
he and Dukakis debated in San Francisco. He said Dukakis has
followed his lead on South Africa and in making drugs an issue.
   ``He is adjusting to a new agenda,'' Jackson said in San Jose.
   The two men met privately after the debate, an hour-long session
in which they aimed their strongest words at the Reagan
administration for dealings with Noriega.
   Jackson, who released a five-year budget blueprint this week,
did urge Dukakis to spell out his spending plans.
   ``The governor is laying out a budget of promises but not a
budget of numbers,'' Jackson said.
   Dukakis replied that his experience as governor taught him it
was a ``serious mistake'' to lay out a detailed budget plan so far
in advance, because the revenue picture can change drastically.
   The Dukakis campaign, meanwhile, announced the appointment of
Dayton Duncan as national press secretary. He was deputy national
press secretary in Walter Mondale's 1984 campaign.
</TEXT>
