<HEAD>Suspicious Device Found Near Sen. Kennedy's Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspicious device was removed from an office
down the hall from Sen. Edmward M. Kennedy's office in a downtown
Boston federal building Thursday, but authorities later found it
was not a bomb, an FBI spokesman said.
   ``It has no explosive capability. It has no incendiary
capability,'' said FBI spokesman Jack Cloherty. The parcel
contained some inactive electronic components, he said.
   Cloherty said agents were trying to determine if the parcel was
planted in the Department of Health and Human Services office as a
ruse or simply left behind. No calls claiming responsibility for
the device were received, he said.
   Bomb squad officers took the device to an island in Boston
Harbor and determined that it was not explosive, said police
spokesman John Eisenthal. It was destroyed with a high-pressure
water cannon.
   The device was found in a paper bag in the office on the 24th
floor of the John F. Kennedy federal building, about 15 yards from
a district office of Sen. Kennedy, who was in Washington, said a
spokesman in his Boston office.
   Workers were allowed back onto the floor after the device was
removed, police and the FBI said.
