<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Congress     05-26 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Congress,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislature Inaugurated Weeks Late</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators set aside a
drawn-out dispute over election results on Thursday, allowing the
National Assembly to convene formally nearly one month late.
   Lawmakers from the Republican Nationalist Alliance and the
governing Christian Democrats reached accord to open the
legislature after three hours of negotiations at the National
Assembly, El Salvador's single-chamber congress.
   The rightist Alliance, known by its Spanish acronym Arena, won
at least 30 seats in March 20 elections for the 60-seat Assembly.
   Arena contends it won 31 seats and that the Christian Democrats
stole one through fraud. Arena's claim to the seat is pending
before the Supreme Court.
   The Central Elections Council gave the Christian Democrats 23
seats and the small National Conciliation Party seven seats.
   The National Assembly was to have been installed May 1.
   By Thursday night, only one legislator of the National
Conciliation Party backed the Arena-Christian Democrat agreement.
He indicated he would vote with Arena on most bills, in effect
giving the rightists a majority.
   Ricardo Alvarenga Valdivieso, president of the legislature,
announced the agreement at an impromptu news conference in the
Assembly.
   ``We have had differing positions and juridical arguments, but
when the will exists anything is possible in order to respond to
the clamor of a people that wants to see the Assembly working,''
said Julio Rey Prendes, the Christian Democratic Party leader and a
legislator.
   Alfredo Cristiani, president of Arena and one of its lawmakers,
said: ``We're pleased this problem has been resolved. Here there
are no winners and no losers. From now on, the winner is the
Salvadoran people, who will benefit by the normalization of the
Assembly.''
   Arena tried to unilaterally install the legislature on May 1
with its 30 lawmakers. According to law a majority of lawmakers
must be on hand to inaugurate an assembly session, and the other
parties refused to recognize the body's validity.
</TEXT>
