<HEAD>Ammunition Dump Explodes, Killing One and Wounding 48</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Explosions at a military arms dump in
central Zambia killed one person and wounded 48, most of them
seriously, the government said Thursday.
   The explosions at the Kohima army barracks at Kabwe, 75 miles
north of Lusaka, went on for six hours Wednesday night, said Grey
Zulu of President Kenneth Kaunda's governing party. Officials did
not say if sabotage was suspected.
   Zulu said the government ordered an investigation.
   Buildings and factories near the barracks were set ablaze.
Shrapnel, debris and the remnants of armor-piercing missiles were
found up to 10 miles from the munitions dump.
   Doctors at Kabwe hospital said the wounded included women and
children living in houses near the barracks. They said emergency
services were disrupted because explosions cut power lines to the
hospital and its standby generator had been stolen.
   Home Minister Paul Maluktila and the military and civil defense
chiefs visited Kabwe on Thursday, officials said.
