<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-JapanDefense     05-26 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan Defense,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Upholds Japanese Role as Non-Military Superpower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials on Thursday strongly defended
restrictions against Japan becoming a global military power as
trade and foreign aid spending transform it into a political and
economic superpower.
   Foreign aid is a natural area for Japan to contribute to global
stability ``given Japan's policy, which we fully support ... not to
play a global military role,'' said Deputy Defense Secretary
William Howard Taft IV.
   Japan will surpass the United States as the world's leading aid
donor this year and it can still afford a further ``dramatic
increase'' in aid, Taft added.
   Taft's statement was distributed to the Senate defense
appropriations subcommittee. His position was echoed in testimony
by other Pentagon officials and the State Department at a hearing
on the defense burden shared by the United States and its Northeast
Asian allies, Japan and South Korea.
   Assistant Defense Secretary Richard L. Armitage reminded
senators that after the defeat of Japan in World War II, ``the
United States played a major and direct role'' in framing the
constitution that continues to bar Japan from maintaining offensive
military force.
   Asian neighbors occupied by Japan during the war and the
Japanese people themselves ``don't want to see Rising Sun flags on
strategic bombers, carrier battle groups or other power projection
systems _ nor do we,'' Armitage added.
   He said Japan obviously could afford to spend more on
self-defense and will do so, but ``in terms of military roles and
missions, Japan is correctly oriented already.''
   Meanwhile, Japan should substantially increase unrestricted aid
grants to poorer countries in addition to boosting existing support
for the upkeep of 55,000 American military personnel in Japan, he
said.
   Other countries in the region accept a defense-oriented military
buildup by Japan but ``they remain sensitive about any indication
that Japan might develop offensive capabilities or seek a regional
security role,'' said Gaston Sigur, assistant secretary of state
for East Asian and Pacific affairs.
   Japan has doubled its foreign aid several times since 1980 and
in the coming year will pass the United States as the world's
leading aid donor, Taft said.
</TEXT>
