<DOCNO> AP880526-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NBCSuit     05-26 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NBC Suit,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Asks Injunction Against Montana Polling Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE O'CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state law that bans exit polling within
200 feet of the voting place is an unconstitutional infringement on
the right to free speech, a lawyer for the NBC television network
argued Thursday.
   Floyd Abrams, a New York City attorney specializing in
media-related cases, cited a 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
decision striking down a similar law in Washington state earlier
this year.
   NBC, in arguments before U.S. District Judge Charles Lovell, is
trying to have the 1985 law lifted for the state's June 7 primary
election. Lovell took the arguments under advisement. No decision
is expected until next week.
   Exit polls ask people after they've cast their ballots for whom
they voted and are used by news organizations to project the
winners of elections. The state contends its ban protects voters'
privacy and voting decorum.
   Patricia Schaeffer, an assistant attorney general representing
Montana, said the law was designed to balance the interests of the
media in reporting on elections and the right of voters to ``order
and dignity'' at the polls.
   Some legislators felt voters and been harassed and intimidated
by people conducting exit polls in the past, she said.
   Abrams contended that the law was enacted out of frustration
over election night projections that declare winners before voting
ends and maintains the statute denies the network its First
Amendment rights.
   He said other state laws already protect the decorum of the
voting place and can be used if troubles arise with pollsters, he
said.
   Asking people how they voted after they cast their ballots
``cannot be said to be an intrusion upon privacy,'' Abrams said.
``A voter has the right to say `I don't want to talk to you','' he
said.
   The 9th Circuit ruled that exit polling is a form of speech
protected by the First Amendment. It said the Washington law, which
prohibited exit polling within 300 feet of a voting place, violated
the Constitution and was not the least restrictive means of
guaranteeing decorum at the polls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PhonyGold     05-26 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phony Gold,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Convicts Three Americans in Absentia for Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Americans who court
officials said used names of U.S. officials to sell phony gold
certificates were convicted of fraud Thursday in their absence and
given prison terms of five to 12 years.
   Court officials said the men used names including that of
Secretary of State George Shultz to operate a company with a
claimed worth of up to $270 million and which sold investment
certificates for gold that did not exist.
   The trial was held at the court of Ras al-Khaimah, one of the
seven emirates that make up the United Arab Emirates.
   The court identified the men as Fredrick Gonzalez and Donald
Edward, sentenced to 12 years imprisonment each, and Larry Gazier,
who received a five-year prison term. The whereabouts of the
fugitives were not known and their hometowns not released.
   Officials said the other two members of the ring were Konisa
Maskerensi, an Indian, and Ahmed Zoghbur, an Arab, who were each
sentenced to a year in jail. The two are under arrest.
   The ring claimed to own the gold in Switzerland and United
States and sold the certificates in Western Europe. The fraud was
uncovered when they tried to sell more in the Emirates, court
officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
