<DOCNO> AP880526-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Accutane     05-26 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Accutane,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA Wants Company To Depict Deformed Infant On Drug Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA DOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators want a photograph of a
deformed infant on the warning label of Accutane, a powerful
anti-acne medicine that can damage the fetuses of pregnant women, a
pharmaceutical company said Thursday.
   That and other U.S. Food and Drug Administration requirements,
which are ``not written in concrete,'' an FDA spokesman said,
follow an FDA panel's recommendation last month that the drug
remain on the market.
   Hoffman-La Roche Inc. spokeswoman Carolyn R. Glynn said the
company is ``in agreement with'' the FDA's order, which does not
stray much from the advisory panel's recommendations on the
prescription drug, which was introduced in 1982.
   The company agrees that female patients should be shown the
infant deformities Accutane can cause, but the photo ``may be more
appropriate ... to use on the patient consent materials'' signed in
the doctor's office, she said.
   Those materials, planned for issue early this summer, would
include a form to be signed by female patients stating they
understand the risks associated with the drug, she said.
   Ms. Glynn said company officials previously discussed using such
a photograph, but not with the FDA or the advisory panel. ``It's
not an issue of using the picture, it's where you use the
picture,'' she said.
   The spokeswoman for the Nutley-based company said
Hoffman-LaRoche received the FDA's requirements in a letter dated
May 19, on Wednesday. She released the order Thursday afternoon.
   The FDA left it to Hoffman-La Roche to release the order or keep
it confidential, she said.
   ``But until we have the opportunity to review the letter we're
not in a position to say `Well, yes we agree with this' or `No, we
don't agree with that,''' she said.
   FDA spokesman William Grigg said that ``there's still some
negotiating room'' if the company wants to alter some of the
requirements from the FDA.
   ``The agency and the company are trying to emphasize that these
are not just minor birth defects that occur rarely, but that if a
woman does become pregnant ... the chances are very very high that
she will have a very grossly debilitated infant that probably can't
take care of itself as it grows up,'' Grigg said.
   The advisory panel and the FDA embraced a proposal by Roche to
sell Accutane only in a so-called blister package in which explicit
patient warnings _ including a sketch of a pregnant woman with a
red X drawn through it _ would be sealed in at the factory to make
sure the patient would see them.
   ``Everybody agrees that we have to minimize birth defects if the
drug is going to remain on the market,'' Grigg said.
   Ms. Glynn said the company, which must respond to the FDA's
letter within 15 days, hopes to have the patient consent kit on the
market by late June, and have the new blister packaging in drug
stores no later than September.
   Since its introduction in 1982, Accutane has carried specific
and explicit warnings that there is a high risk it will cause birth
defects if taken during pregnancy.
   Those warnings have been strengthened in recent years, but the
FDA grew concerned that too many women, and perhaps doctors, were
ignoring them.
   The advisory panel that convened in April concluded the benefits
of the drug _ the only one on the market that can cure the severe
scarring type of acne it is intended to treat _ outweighed the risk
of misuse.
   The FDA has received reports of 66 birth defects associated with
the drug since 1982. Forty-five of the defects were in the first
two years of the drug's use when warnings were less severe. There
have been 21 reports since 1985, when labelling cautions were
strengthened.
</TEXT>
