<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mozambique     05-26 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mozambique,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa, Mozambique Agree on Security Meetings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa and Mozambique agreed
Wednesday to resume security meetings that lapsed three years ago
when relations between the two countries deteriorated.
   A meeting between the two countries on Wednesday included
ranking diplomats and military officials and was the latest
indication that hostilities were easing.
   The two sides said in a statement that they would resume
meetings of a joint security commission ``at the earliest possible
date.'' The commission was set up in line with the 1984 Nkomati
Accord, a mutual non-aggression treaty in which each country
pledged to halt support for guerrillas fighting against the other
government.
   The commission has been defunct since 1985, when Mozambique
found documents indicating that South Africa was still aiding
Mozambican rebels despite the treaty.
   Since then, Mozambique has persistently accused South Africa of
continued covert aid to the Mozambique National Resistance rebel
movement. South Africa denies it.
   The war has devastated Mozambique's economy and is the main
cause of a famine that has left almost 6 million of the country's
14.5 million people in need of food aid.
   ``The two delegations affirmed the commitments of their
respective governments not to support the commission of violence
against the peoples of their respective countries,'' the statement
said.
   The army commander, Lt. Gen. Tobais Dai, led Mozambique's
delegation at Wednesday's talks. South Africa's delegation was
headed by the director-general of the Foreign Affairs Department,
Niel Van Heerden, and included the army chief, Lt. Gen. A.J.
Liebenberg.
</TEXT>
