<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Britain,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Minister Says U.N. Gulf Force Unlikely</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British minister on Wednesday said it
was unlikely that a multinational U.N. force would be created to
escort commercial vessels through the Persian Gulf.
   At a news conference, Ian Stewart, minister of state for the
armed forces, praised cooperation among Western naval task forces
in the waterway, where Iran and Iraq are at war.
   But, when asked about the chances of implementing a Soviet
proposal for the creation of a U.N.-sponsored force to replace the
individual contingents in the gulf, he said: ``We don't see it as
an immediate possibility at all.''
   The United States, the Soviet Union, Britain, France, Italy,
Belgium and the Netherlands have forces in the gulf to protect
ships bearing their national flags and to destroy mines.
   ``It sounds attractive in theory but it would be very difficult
to put ... together in practical terms,'' Stewart said. ``There has
never been a U.N. naval task force of that kind and certainly not
when two parties are still actively at war.''
   Stewart met earlier Wednesday with Crown Prince Sheik Hamad bin
Isa Al-Khalifa, commander of the Bahrain Defense Force.
   The British minister said countries in the region have been
``very helpful'' in efforts to limit the effects of the 7{-year-old
war on shipping lanes of the oil-rich region.
   Stewart said there have been ``less hostilities and less
activities at sea than would probably have been the case before''
the foreign navies sent forces to the gulf.
   Iran attacks neutral vessels in retaliation for Iraqi raids on
its shipping lanes. Iran also has been blamed for sowing mines in
the waterway.
   Earlier this month, Washington expanded the duties of its naval
task force, allowing the warships to intervene in attacks on
neutral vessels even if they were not flying American flags.
   Steward welcomed the U.S. decision, but would not say if Britain
will follow suit.
   So far, Iran has not attacked vessels under any military escort.
   One of the British warships, the frigate HMS Beaver, is on a
port call in Bahrain. Stewart was scheduled to inspect it and to
visit other gulf countries.
</TEXT>
