<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Minnelli Adv27   05-26 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Minnelli, Adv 27,0809</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, May 27, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Liza Minnelli in Unusual Variety Special on ABC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been 16 years since Liza Minnelli's had a
special on network television, and it took an unusual idea to get
her onto the small screen for ``Liza Minnelli: Triple Play'' on ABC
next Tuesday.
   ``They (ABC) ask me every year. This year I think we shocked
them because we said `yes.' It took me since 1972 to think of
something different,'' Minnelli said recently on a shooting break.
   ``The last special that was my own was in 1972. I was in
`Baryshnikov on Broadway' and `Goldie and Liza Together,' not my
own.
   ``I got tired of `in concert.' `Liza with a Z' was the first
in-concert special. Then everybody else did them.''
   The one-hour special will air next Tuesday. Minnelli's co-stars
are John Rubinstein, Louis Gossett Jr. and Ryan O'Neal.
   ``The best thing about it is not having to perform alone,''
Minnelli said, ``not going out there, singing your songs and going
home. You get to the point where the joy is working with other
people. That's where the real kick is and the challenge, too. I'm
working with people I admire and hadn't had a chance to work with
before.''
   Songwriter Fred Ebb had the idea that made Minnelli say ``yes''
this time. The same four-line dialogue to begin a short play was
given to three sets of writers _ Lanford Wilson, Terrence McNally
with Wendy Wasserstein, and Ebb and his partner John Kander.
   Wilson wrote a drama, McNally and Wasserstein a romantic fantasy
and Kander and Ebb a musical.
   Minnelli has worked with Kander and Ebb a lot and was in the
1984 Broadway musical ``The Rink,'' with book by McNally.
   ``We got the writers we wanted, first crack out of the box,''
she said. ``We were really thrilled.
   ``We didn't know what they were writing. We hired the best and
trusted them.''
   Minnelli got British director Piers Haggard whom she hadn't
worked with before but admired. ``Martin Scorsese one day showed me
two episodes of the original British TV version of `Pennies from
Heaven' that Piers directed. It was brilliant,'' she said. ``When I
went to London in 1983 I looked him up. Calling strangers is
something I'm not wont to do, but I was in such admiration of this
man.
   ``I've kept looking for things to do with him. This is just
perfect. He has understood the different styles and made this work,
within our budget.''
   The scenes shot the day of the interview take place in a parlor
complete with Tiffany lamps. Stand-ins walked through, while
minions with tape measures and light meters announced measurements
to adjusters of light reflectors.
   Then Minnelli and Rubinstein rehearsed moving from chair to
settee. Haggard had them repeat it slower. Minnelli asked that her
chair cushion be higher and two blankets were folded under it. She
thanked the woman who handed her the high-heeled shoes that she
donned for the scene's three takes.
   Minnelli won't be watching her ``Triple Play.'' As soon as
shooting ended, she and her husband, Mark Gero, left for a European
vacation. She has accepted an invitation from Frank Sinatra and
Sammy Davis to replace Dean Martin in six weeks of concerts next
fall.
   Meanwhile, she said, she needed the vacation because of the
grueling schedule of the TV special.
   ``We work from 6 in the morning to 8 at night, then go home and
faint. But I'm healthy and enjoying it. A lot of it is making sure
when I'm working I get plenty of sleep.
   ``There's a basic tension in the air,'' she said. ``I think the
writers have done some really gutsy stuff that hasn't been seen.
It's not just nice, safe, sitcom stuff. It is about interesting
things. We'll see how it goes over. ``I think we're taking some
chances, some risks. Anytime you try to do that, it's a little
anxious, a little nervous.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   `TODAY' ANCHOR AWAY _ Jim Lehrer of PBS' ``The MacNeil-Lehrer
NewsHour'' will be among the guest hosts filling in for Bryant
Gumbel on the ``Today'' show this summer. Gumbel is busy preparing
to be prime-time anchor of NBC's Summer Olympics coverage this
September. Former NBC newsman Tom Snyder fills in the week of June
6, Lehrer is on the week of June 13 and NBC Sports' Bob Costas, who
is getting his own late-night show later this summer, fills in the
week of June 27. Gumbel is back the week of June 20.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, May 27</NOTE>
