<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   05-26 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0526</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn announced a
$13.64 billion cash offer for Texaco Inc. after the oil company's
management broke off talks with him on the troubled oil giant's
future.
   Such a takeover attempt, revealed Wednesday, would be the
largest ever undertaken.
   Icahn, whose 14.8 percent stake makes him the largest
shareholder in Texaco, had been negotiating with top managers over
how to restructure the company following its emergence from
bankruptcy court reorganization last month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's trade deficit narrowed
dramatically during the first three months of the year as an
all-time high in U.S. export sales offset a relentless climb in
imports, the government said.
   The Commerce Department reported Wednesday that the trade gap
from January through March totaled $35.9 billion, a 12.7 percent
drop from a deficit of $41.2 billion in the fourth quarter of 1987.
   It was the second quarterly improvement in the deficit in the
past two years and represented the biggest decline since the
deficit fell by 18.9 percent in the fourth quarter of 1982.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes rose 4.5 percent in
April, the biggest advance in 17 months, as buyers rushed to close
deals before interest rates went up, a real estate trade group
reported.
   The National Association of Realtors said Wednesday that
existing single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 3.48 million units last month, following increases
of 2.5 percent in both February and March.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's commercial banks appear to be
recovering from their worst year since the Depression despite
mounting bank failures in the Southwest and continuing problems
with loans to Third World countries, federal regulators said.
   ``The banking system as a whole is sound and getting sounder
...,'' Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. Chairman L. William Seidman
told the Senate Banking Committee on Wednesday.
   In particular, the performance of farm banks, the sore spot of
the industry several years ago, is slowly improving as agriculture
recovers from its slump, Seidman said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business failures declined by 10.1 percent in
the first quarter over a year earlier as more farmers and retailers
climbed out of the red, a report said.
   Dun & Bradstreet Corp., a business-information firm, said
Wednesday that 15,211 companies nationwide went under during the
first three months of this year, compared with 16,924 in 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc., newly crowned as the
nation's largest publicly owned textile company, said Chicago
conglomerate Farley Inc. wants to buy as much as 25 percent of its
common stock.
   Pepperell said Wednesday it was notified that Farley filed with
the Federal Trade Commission seeking permission to purchase up to
25 percent of Pepperell's approximately 32 million outstanding
shares.
   Farley includes in its holdings Fruit of the Loom Inc., the
underwear manufacturer. Pepperell recently acquired J.P. Stevens &
Co. in a joint buyout with Odyssey Partners Inc.
</TEXT>
