<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0804EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   05-26 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0459</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>RENTON, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines announced it would buy up
to 100 Boeing 757-200s to replace aging aircraft in its fleet,
giving Boeing Co. its second multibillion-dollar order in as many
weeks.
   American officials said Wednesday they were ordering 50 757s for
delivery between July 1989 and November 1991, with an option to
purchase 50 more. The deal could be worth more than $4 billion to
Boeing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Stores Co. agreed with federal
regulators not to buy any shares of Lucky Stores Inc. until
Saturday.
   A 10-day waiting period following filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission of American Stores' $2.5 billion buyout bid for
Lucky, the country's sixth-largest grocery retailer, expired
Wednesday.
   But the Federal Trade Commission asked American Stores, the
nation's third-largest grocery chain, not to purchase any shares of
Lucky stock until Saturday so regulators could review any possible
antitrust implications of the merger.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court upheld a ruling
temporarily forbidding Hallmark Cards Inc. from making greeting
card designs resembling those of a small competitor, clearing the
way for a full trial of the company's $50 million damage suit
against Hallmark.
   Blue Mountain Arts brought suit against Hallmark about two years
ago, alleging that Hallmark's ``Personal Touch'' line of greeting
cards is deceptively similar to their ``AireBrush Feelings'' and
``WaterColor Feelings'' lines.
   The appeals court ruling came Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenneco Inc., the 10th-largest U.S. oil company,
announced it is getting out of the oil business by selling its oil
and natural gas operations and concentrating on other industrial
and pipeline ventures.
   The Houston-based company, which posted 1987 revenue of $14.8
billion, will use part of the proceeds from the sale to help pay
its hefty $8.5 billion debt, Tenneco spokeswoman Suzanne Thomas
said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first McDonald's to open in a
communist country has run into an unexpected problem: Trained
employees are quitting because they find they have to work like
Westerners and get paid like East Europeans.
   Since the U.S. fast food chain opened its outlet in Belgrade in
March, 40 employees _ about one-third of its workers _ have
voluntarily left their jobs despite a high unemployment rate in
Yugoslavia.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market closed mixed Wednesday in slow trading. The Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials finished at 1,961.37, down 1.16
points.
   Bond prices edged higher.
   The dollar rose against major foreign currencies.
   Precious metals futures prices fell broadly on profit-taking as
fears of inflation eased.
</TEXT>
