<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     05-26 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices rebounded from an early
sell-off to finish little changed in quiet trading.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Wednesday, contracts for
July delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude
oil, settled at $17.37 per 42-gallon barrel, down 3 cents from
Tuesday's close.
   Among refined products for June delivery, wholesale unleaded
gasoline settled at 51.72 cents a gallon, down 0.13 cent, while
wholesale heating oil closed at 47.31 cents a gallon, unchanged
from Tuesday.
   Analysts said July crude broke through the psychologically
important $17.30-per-gallon barrier early in the trading session
following the release of statistics that showed a recent buildup in
U.S. oil inventories.
   ``The market showed a little weakness on the statistics,'' which
also showed an increase in refining runs, said John Hill, vice
president at Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   Traders interpret an increase in refining as a signal that
product inventories might increase in the near future.
   But ``sellers didn't come out in force,'' Hill said, and oil
futures prices were able to regain some ground in quiet trading.
</TEXT>
