<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0225EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Icahn-Profile Bjt   05-26 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Icahn-Profile, Bjt,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For Icahn, The Deal's The Thing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Texaco-Icahn, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carl C. Icahn is a man obsessed with making
deals.
   Before his record-shattering, $13.64 billion offer for Texaco
Inc. on Wednesday, the 52-year-old financier had already tracked,
cornered and _ in some cases _ acquired some of America's most
imposing corporations.
   There was Marshall Field & Co., the retailer. And
Chesebrough-Ponds Inc., the consumer products company. Phillips
Petroleum Co., USX Corp., ACF Industries Inc., Trans World Airlines
_ and on and on.
   His scrapbook of corporate raids reads like a Standard & Poor's
Register of U.S. companies. Indeed, Icahn is so well known in the
takeover business, he says he was considered for _ but turned down
_ a role in the movie ``Wall Street,'' which starred Michael
Douglas as a vicious corporate raider.
   Always his own boss, Icahn is a master strategist who recently
described himself in Fortune magazine as ``obsessive in everything
I do.''
   Often reluctant to speak to the press, he is actually quite
loquacious in person, people who know him say.
   ``I talk to him all the time. I mean, I listen to him all the
time. There's a difference,'' Texaco Inc. President James W.
Kinnear joked recently.
   Icahn's involvement with Texaco has been no laughing matter to
Texaco's managers, however.
   After launching a slate of candidates for the company's board of
directors and negotiating with Texaco over the terms of a
restructuring, Icahn decided Wednesday to take matters into his own
hands and make an offer to acquire the company at $60 a share _ in
cash.
   It would be the largest deal of its kind in American history.
   Holding 14.8 percent of Texaco's stock, Icahn had been
pressuring the oil giant to put itself up for sale since it emerged
from a 13-month reorganization under the supervision of a
bankruptcy court judge.
   ``I've learned one thing: What counts is which way the tide is
going _ on the last day,'' he said recently in describing his
protracted battle with Texaco.
   Whatever happens, it is generally agreed that if anyone could
dislodge the status quo at Texaco, it's Icahn, the man whose very
name can send shivers through boardrooms across the land.
   He has made a reputation by buying up shares in companies with
assets worth more than their stock price, then selling the
companies off later, in whole or in pieces, at a highe price.
   Sometimes companies have agreed to buy the stock back at a
premium to get him to leave them alone, a practice known as
``greenmail.'' Other times, as with Trans World Airlines and ACF
Industries, Icahn has retained a management role, but also has used
the company as a vehicle for more takeover attempts.
   One way or another, Icahn almost always walks away millions of
dollars richer.
   To his critics, Icahn is little more than a pirate in a coat and
tie. But Icahn says the real villains are corporate chieftans who
are wasteful, inefficient and more interested in protecting their
high-salaried jobs than looking out for the interests of their
stockholders.
   That, more than the money _ which he does not need _ is what
keeps him in the takeover game, Icahn recently told The Associated
Press.
   ``I think there's no question there's a competitive force in me.
But it's also a sense of outrage about the way companies are run,''
he said.
   Actually, Icahn's management has been paying off at both TWA,
which he took over in January 1986, and ACF, a conglomerate he
bought in 1984 and stripped down to its core railroad-car business.
   ``The guy is a deal man ... one of the toughest negotiators
you'll ever see,'' said John Pincavage of the investment firm
PaineWebber Inc. ``We ought to use him against the Russians. I
mean, this guy is good.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
