<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TakeoverBids     05-26 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Takeover Bids,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biggest Corporate Takeovers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Texaco-Icahn, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If financier Carl Icahn proceeds with a formal
$13.64 billion bid for Texaco Inc. it would be the largest such
takeover attempt ever.
   Here are the 20 biggest such acquisitions in U.S. history:
   _Gulf by Standard Oil of California (now Chevron), $13.4
billion, 1984.
   _Getty Oil by Texaco, $10.1 billion, 1984.
   _Standard Oil by British Petroleum (which already held a 55
percent stake), $7.9 billion, 1987.
   _Conoco by DuPont, $7.4 billion, 1981.
   _Federated Department Stores by Campeau, $6.6 billion, 1988.
   _Marathon Oil by U.S. Steel (now USX), $6.5 billion, 1982.
   _RCA by General Electric, $6.4 billion, 1986.
   _Superior Oil by Mobil, $5.7 billion, 1984.
   _Shell by Royal Dutch-Shell (which already held 69.5 percent),
$5.7 billion, 1985.
   _General Foods by Philip Morris, $5.6 billion, 1985.
   _Southern Pacific by Santa Fe (now Santa Fe Southern Pacific),
$5.2 billion, 1983.
   _Sterling Drug by Kodak, $5.1 billion, 1988.
   _Hughes Aircraft by General Motors, $5 billion, 1985.
   _Nabisco by R.J. Reynolds (now RJR Nabisco), $4.9 billion, 1985.
   _Signal by Allied (now Allied-Signal, $4.9 billion, 1985.
   _Sperry by Burroughs (now Unisys), $4.8 billion, 1986.
   _Connecticut General by INA (now Cigna), $4.3 billion, 1981.
   _Texasgulf by Elf Aquitaine, $4.2 billion, 1981.
   _Cities Service by Occidental Petroleum, $4 billion, 1982.
   _American Hospital Supply by Baxter-Travenol, $3.8 billion, 1985.
</TEXT>
