<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Icahn-Bids     05-26 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Icahn-Bids,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Icahn Has Bid for Other Giants _ and Sometimes Won</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Texaco-Icahn, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the other companies financier Carl Icahn has
sought, and the results:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1978</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Wins proxy fight for control of Baird & Warner, a real estate
investment trust with assets of about $30 million. Molded it into a
vehicle for later bids.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1979</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Buys 8 percent of Tappan Co. and declares a proxy fight for
control of the company. Within a year, Tappan sells out to Sweden's
AB Electrolux at more than double the price per share Icahn paid
for his stake.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1980</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Acquires about 9 percent of Hammermill Paper Co. and launches a
proxy fight, which he narrowly loses. Makes a profit of $9 million
when Hammermill buys his stake.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1982</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Seeks control of Marshall Field & Co., the retailer. Other
investors join his group. Marshall Field agrees to be acquired by
Batus Inc., the U.S. subsidiary of BAT Industries PLC. Icahn makes
a profit of about $11 million.
   _Turns a profit of $3 million on a $4 million investment in
Anchor Hocking Corp., the glassware maker, which buys back his
stake.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1983</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Makes a profit of $19 million on a three-month investment of
$35 million in Gulf & Western Inc.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1984</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Chesebrough-Ponds Inc. pays Icahn $70 million to buy back 1.8
million shares he holds in the company.
   _Pursues ACF Industries Inc., a railcar-leasing company, turning
down a buyout offer from management and acquiring the company for
$410 million. Later sells off assets for a profit.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1985</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Announces $8.1 billion tender offer for Phillips Petroleum Co.
Phillips announces a recapitalization plan and Icahn withdraws,
taking trading profits of $52.5 million and payment of expenses of
$25 million.
   _Seeks control of TWA Inc. Texas Air Corp. makes a competing
bid, Icahn offers to withdraw if paid $16 million in ``expenses,''
but Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo refuses. TWA backs Icahn's
offer, and he wins control of the company.
   _Bids for Uniroyal Inc., which escapes by being taken private by
Clayton & Dubilier Inc. Icahn accepts a $5.9 million payment in
return for dropping his bid.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1986</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Seeks control of USX Corp., the oil and steel giant, for $8
billion. Withdraws the offer in early 1987 but continues to hold an
11.4 percent stake in the company.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1987</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _TWA, controlled by Icahn, offers $1.65 billion for USAir Group
Inc. but drops out after USAir completes an agreement to buy
Piedmont Aviation Inc. for $1.6 billion.
</TEXT>
