<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pepperell-Farley Bjt   05-26 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pepperell-Farley, Bjt,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farley After Up to 25 Percent Of West Point-Pepperell</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farley Inc., one of the nation's largest
privately owned conglomerates, is going after a major stake in West
Point-Pepperell Inc., a major textile manufacturer which itself
just swallowed a rival company.
   Pepperell announced Wednesday that Farley had filed with the
Federal Trade Commission seeking permission to acquire between 15
percent and 25 percent of the West Point, Ga., company's
approximately 32 million outstanding shares.
   Rumors have been circulating for several weeks that Farley,
whose holdings include Fruit of the Loom Inc., was interested in
buying into Pepperell.
   Pepperell said it did not know how much Farley, owned by William
F. Farley, already owned or what Farley's intent is. However,
Farley has filed no other papers with security agencies, meaning it
has less than a 5 percent stake in the company.
   Pepperell's stock was among the most active in trading Wednesday
on the New York Stock Exchange as 1.2 million shares changed hands,
with the price climbing $4 a share to close at $35.375.
   A spokesman at Farley's Chicago headquarters would say only that
Pepperell ``is a fine company and we think it's a good investment.''
   Farley has $300 million available for acquisitions from a bond
issue earlier this year, the spokesman said, but some analysts
expressed surprise over the move because of the high debt carried
by both Farley and Pepperell.
   Farley has about $1.4 billion in debt, and Pepperell owes about
$1.1 billion after its recent $1.22 billion buyout of rival textile
maker J.P. Stevens & Co.
   ``It didn't seem to make much sense to me when I first heard
talk of him (Farley) buying the entire company,'' said Kay Norwood,
an analyst with Interstate Securities in Charlotte, N.C.
   But she said Pepperell's acquisition of Stevens will ``pay off
in a major way,'' and ``if (Farley) is approaching this from the
standpoint of investing, ... he's a pretty smart fellow.''
   Patricia Ryan, an analyst with Raymond James in St. Petersburg,
Fla., said, ``We had been hearing the rumors that (Farley) was
interested since the beginning of May. I am a little surprised he
is willing to take on that much debt.''
   Farley's filing under the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act gives the FTC
and the U.S. Department of Justice up to 30 days to review the
proposed deal for anti-competitive effects. The agencies can take
no action, seek a negotiated settlement or seek an injunction
blocking the deal. The parties also could voluntarily back out.
   Pepperell recently became the nation's largest publicly owned
textile company through the Stevens acquisition.
   Pepperell joined with its rival suitor for Stevens, New York
investment firm Odyssey Partners, to acquire Stevens in a deal
which left Pepperell with most of Stevens' linen and towel
operations and gave the company about 25 percent of the nation's
home fashion textile market.
   Pepperell sold Stevens' carpet and industrial fabrics division
to Odyssey, and to satisfy antitrust concerns, sold Stevens' sheet
and towel plants to Bibb Manufacturing Co. of Macon, Ga.
   A health-conscious, former door-to-door encyclopedia salesman,
William Farley also controls Acme Boot Co., Anaheim Citrus Products
Co., Doehler-Jarvis and Southern Fastening Systems through Farley
Inc.
   Farley Inc. employs about 25,000 workers.
   Late last year, William Farley toyed with entering the
Democratic presidential derby, but backed out in November, saying
he had waited too long to get in the race.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
