<DOCNO> AP880526-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0412EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MediaGeneral-Sugarman Bjt   05-26 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Media General-Sugarman, Bjt,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugarman Apparently Loses Bid For Media General Board Slate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burt Sugarman says he is not surprised he
may have lost his bid to put three people on the board of Media
General Inc., but that the 10.3 million votes his plan got should
send a message to the company.
   Sugarman, a California-based investor, launched a $1.8 billion
takeover bid for Media General earlier this year.
   ``From the outset of the proxy contest with Media General, we
recognized that it would be an uphill battle,'' Sugarman said
Wednesday after the company announced that preliminary results from
Friday's shareholders' vote show the incumbent management nominees
won re-election.
   The returns show the three incumbents have received more than 56
percent of the vote, compared with 42.6 percent for Sugarman's
proposed slate, Media General President James S. Evans said.
   Evans said Corporation Trust Co., an election inspection
company, told him the incumbents received 13.5 million votes and
Sugarman's ticket of himself, Harold Simmons and David Gotterer got
just under 10.3 million votes.
   Evans said a final report on the vote will come after both sides
get an opportunity to inspect proxies and raise any questions with
Corporation Trust.
   Sugarman said the shareholders who backed his slate ``cast their
proxies in favor of enhancing values for all shareholders _ whether
it be through our $70-per-share cash merger offer or another type
of transaction.
   ``We fully expect that Media General's management and their
board of directors will respect the opinion of this large group of
shareholders and initiate action that will maximize shareholder
value,'' added Sugarman, who in his address to shareholders at
Friday's annual meeting talked about the possibility of splitting
Media General up into two or three smaller companies.
   Evans said Corporation Trust told him that 86 percent of Media
General's total outstanding 28 million Class A shares voted.
   The family of Media General Chairman D. Tennant Bryan owns 71
percent of the company's controlling Class B shares, which control
seven of the 10 board seats.
   Sugarman owns 10 percent of Media General's Class A holdings,
and in February he offered $61.50 a share for Media General, a bid
he later boosted to $70 a share, or about $1.8 billion.
Subsequently, he offered his own slate to challenge the three
Bryan-supported directors seeking re-election to the board's three
Class A seats.
   As the shareholders meeting approached, lawyers for both parties
sought court relief from what they characterized as false and
misleading information the other side was giving shareholders about
the proxy battle. U.S. District Judge Richard L. Williams denied
both parties' motions, saying the proper time to file them would be
after the annual meeting.
   ``Any further challenge by the Sugarman group is likely to come
through the courts, where we have litigation already pending,''
Evans said Wednesday.
   Media General owns several daily newspapers, including the
Richmond Times-Dispatch and The Richmond News Leader, as well as
several weekly papers, television stations and cable operations.
   Sugarman is chairman and chief executive officer of Barris
Industries Inc., a producer of television programs, and Giant Group
Ltd., whose holdings including cement businesses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0422EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Apples-Europe Bjt   05-26 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Apples-Europe, Bjt,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Stops Imports Of U.S. Apples</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reduced demand for apples, coupled with
rising foreign supply, has prompted the European Economic Community
to stop importing the fruit from the United States and some other
countries, according to an EEC spokeswoman.
   The 12-nation European trading bloc imposed import quotas on
apples this year and orth America _ which includes apples from the
United States and Canada _ reached its limit of 17,600 metric tons
in late April, Ella Krucoff said.
   ``The reason (the EEC) thought it was an emergency situation was
that consumption was down and imports were way, way, way up,'' Ms.
Krucoff said in a telephone interview Wednesday from Washington,
D.C.
   The quotas will remain in place until Aug. 31, the end of the
current apple season, she said.
   ``This is a one-time thing,'' Ms. Krucoff said, adding that it
was the first such EEC restriction covering U.S. apples in at least
10 years.
   The EEC quota system has also banned further imports of apples
from Chile, a major supplier at this time of year, Ms. Krucoff
said. That country's limit was more than 142,000 metric tons, she
said.
   Washington state is the largest U.S. apple producer, but
traditionally has not had much success in cracking the European
market.
   However, the nation had been enjoying a record export year to
Europe prior to the imposition of the quotas, said Charles St. John
of the Washington Apple Commission. Exports to Europe had jumped
from 500,000 boxes last year to 2 million boxes prior to the ban,
he said.
   A box normally holds about 42 pounds of apples.
   The ban's impact on total U.S. exports will not be great, St.
John said.
   ``Normally after the first of May exports really start to taper
off because of the Southern Hemisphere crop,'' he said.
   Still, negotiations are underway to allow for additional U.S.
exports to EEC countries, he said.
   The financial impact of the decision on U.S. apple growers is
unclear, because apples destined for EEC countries will now have to
be sold elsewhere, which could depress prices, St. John said.
   He called the EEC quota a ``protectionist activity'' for the
benefit of European growers.
   Washington state produces half the nation's supermarket apples,
with this year's record crop expected to produce about 67 million
boxes.
   The nation has also produced a record fresh market crop of about
130 million boxes this year.
   About 15 percent of the Washington state crop, or 10 million
boxes, remains to be sold before the end of the season in August,
St. John said, adding that most of those apples will go to domestic
markets.
   The majority of Washington state exports traditionally go to
Asian countries, and St. John said it was unclear if the EEC ban
would prompt increased competition with Chile for Asian markets
this year.
   The EEC is made up of France, West Germany, Italy, Luxembourg,
Belgium, the Netherlands, Denmark, Greece, Ireland, Portugal, Spain
and Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
