<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0735EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Budget     05-26 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Could Vote on Fiscal 1989 Budget Today If Compromise Reached</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: May be topped; also ran on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional negotiators have ironed out most
of the details of a $1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 budget, and House
leaders are hoping the rest of the differences can be resolved in
time for a vote today.
   Rep. William H. Gray III, D-Pa., chairman of the House Budget
Committee, said Wednesday there were only about $150 million in
differences remaining and that he anticipated a speedy resolution.
   The House Rules Committee cleared the way for the vote today
with its approval on Wednesday of a resolution allowing immediate
action on the budget compromise. Usually, the resolution has to sit
for three days before a vote. Congress leaves town at the end of
business today for a Memorial Day holiday.
   Both the House and Senate have passed budget resolutions that
follow the outlines of last fall's deficit reduction agreement with
President Reagan. That agreement spelled out spending totals for
military, foreign aid and domestic agency accounts.
   But negotiators have been bogged down for six weeks over
priorities within the domestic budget.
   The budget doesn't require the president's signature. However,
it serves as a guide for Congress in producing its 13 annual
spending bills and any changes in taxes or entitlements that would
require the president's signature.
   The $14 billion in new taxes for fiscal 1989 contained in the
deficit agreement were enacted last December.
   The budget has to comply with the Gramm-Rudman balanced-budget
law, as well as meet the budget agreement with the president. The
Reagan administration already has warned that the spending plans of
the Democratic-controlled Congress might exceed the limits of
Gramm-Rudman.
   If the administration determines that a deficit of more than
$146 billion could be expected in fiscal 1989, automatic spending
cuts would be imposed next fall to bring the budget into line.
   The budget already is six weeks past its statuatory deadline,
and the House has begun approving spending bills without the final
budget outline.
</TEXT>
