<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Obit-Shimkin     05-26 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Obit-Shimkin,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Driving Force Behind Simon & Schuster Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leon Shimkin, who joined Simon &
Schuster as a 17-year-old bookkeeper and eventually bought the
entire publishing company, has died at the age of 81 at New
Rochelle Hospital.
   Shimkin, who lived in Larchmont, was chairman of the board of
Simon & Schuster and one of the founders of Pocket Books, the
company's mass market paperback division.
   He sold Simon & Schuster to Gulf & Western in 1975, but
continued to go to the office he maintained in the Simon & Schuster
building in midtown Manhattan twice a week until he became ill last
winter, according to his son, Michael.
   Shimkin died Wednesday of ``natural causes,'' his son said this
morning.
   In pursuit of his goal to combine ``the creative art of
publishing with the science of commerce,'' Shimkin played a major
role in transforming book publishing from a cottage industry to big
business.
   In his history of paperback publishing, ``Two-Bit Culture,''
Kenneth C. Davis said that many in publishing resented Shimkin's
``dollar-oriented publishing.''
   ``But few people inside publishing begrudged Shimkin his
financial savvy, and it was soon acknowledged that the way of the
shrewd businessman was the track that the publishing business was
heading down.'' Davis wrote.
   Shimkin was born in Brooklyn, the son of Russian immigrants, and
joined the company in 1924 after completing his freshman year at
New York University. Shimkin finished his degree at night and, out
of gratitude, became a major benefactor to the school, which has
named a building on its Washington Square campus after him.
   Although he rarely involved himself in the editorial side of the
business, he was responsible for two books published in the late
1930s that are still among the company's biggest sellers: ``Your
Income Tax'' by J.K. Lasser and ``How to Win Friends and Influence
People'' by Dale Carnegie.
   He is survived by his wife, Rebecca; a daughter, Emily Gindin of
Princeton, N.J; and his son, who lives in New York.
   Funeral services are planned for 10 a.m. Friday at Temple Israel
in New Rochelle. The family has requested donations be made to
charity in lieu of flowers, Michael Shimkin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
