<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Indicator     05-26 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Indicator,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Says Leading Indicator Continued Recovery In March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community's
economic sentiment indicator recovered strongly in March amid
optimism about Europe's economic prospects for the next year, the
EEC Commission said Thursday.
   The indicator was at 103 in March, up 0.3 percentage points from
102.7 in February, and up 0.4 percentage points from 102.6 in
November 1987 when the indicator fell steeply in the aftermath of
the October stock market crash.
   The EEC's economic sentiment indicator is made up of an
industrial, construction and consumer confidence indicator and
share price indices.
   The Commission said in a statement that expectations for the
economy of the 12-nation trade bloc had brightened steadily since
November 1987.
   It said the March indicator confirmed ``no signs of an economic
downturn are discernible at the present time.''
   By comparison, the Commission said the leading U.S. indicator
improved ``appreciably'' in February for the first time since the
stock market crash. Japan's indicator was unchanged in January.
   The Commission said that the improvement in the value of the
dollar since the beginning of 1988 had strengthened export demand
and made assessments by European industry of export orders less
pessimistic.
</TEXT>
