<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0951EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Rowntree     05-26 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Rowntree,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suchard Offers $4.3 Billion For Rowntree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rowntree PLC, the British confectioner that is
trying to keep two Swiss suitors at bay, on Thursday rejected a
2.32 billion pound, or $4.3 billion, offer from chocolate maker
Jacobs Suchard AG.
   Rowntree said the $17.77-a-share cash bid from Suchard, a
Zurich-based candy and coffee group that controls more than 29
percent of Rowntree, did not fully reflect the company's value.
   Investors apparently agree. Rowntree's stock was trading above
$18.50 a share Thursday on the London Stock Exchange.
   The bid was the latest development in the battle _ dubbed in
Britain as the ``candy bar wars'' _ between Suchard and Nestle SA
to gain control of Rowntree.
   Nestle, based in Vevey, Switzerland and holder of a 16-percent
stake in Rowntree, has offered $16.55 a share, or about $3.91
billion for the confectioner. Rowntree repeatedly has rebuffed
Nestle's overtures.
   On Wednesday, the British government cleared the way for
Nestle's bid by deciding not to refer the proposed takeover to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
   The government also approved Suchard's stake in Rowntree in the
same manner but said a full bid by Suchard would need further
clearance.
   Immediately after the approvals were announced, Suchard said it
would seek Rowntree board approval for a possible cash bid or for
other means of joining the two companies' confectionery businesses.
   The Conservative government's clearances sparked a row in
Parliament, where opposition politicians and some Conservatives
attacked what they saw as the government's failure to ensure that
York-based Rowntree remains in British hands.
   Suchard aggressively began building its stake in Rowntree last
month, when it launched a ``dawn raid'' that took its holding to
14.9 percent.
   Nestle, saying Suchard forced its hand, then responded with a
bid for all of Rowntree.
   But this didn't stop Suchard from increasing its stake further
to just under 30 percent, the maximum it could hold under British
takeover regulations without launching a full takeover bid.
</TEXT>
