<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Dumping     05-26 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Dumping,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Imposes Anti-Dumping Duties on Japanese Computer Printers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese exporters of computer printers
to the European Economic Community must pay anti-dumping duties
beginning May 27, the EEC Commission said Thursday.
   The anti-dumping duties followed an investigation that showed 14
Japanese companies were dumping _ selling at unfairly low prices _
in the 12 EEC member states.
   Sales of Japanese computer printers rose from 390,000 units in
1983 to 1.52 million in 1986, accounting for 73 percent of the EEC
market, the commission said in a statement. Sales in 1987 totaled
about $1.3 billion.
   The EEC Commission said Brother Industries Ltd., Seiko Epson
Corp., Citizen Watch Co. Ltd., Fujitsu Ltd., NEC Corp and Seikosha
Co. Ltd. must pay duties of 33.4 percent.
   In addition, the company said, Alps Electrical Co., must pay 7.4
percent; Copal Co. Ltd, 18.6 percent; Japan Business Computer Co.
Ltd., 22.4 percent; Nakajima Ltd., 12.3 percent; Oki Electric
Industry Co. Ltd., 9.2 percent; Shinwa Digital Industry Co. Ltd.,
10.5 percent; Star Micronics Co. Ltd., 13.6 percent and Tokyo
Electric Co. Ltd., 4.8 percent.
</TEXT>
