<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     05-26 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0301</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices held steady today as the market
absorbed the news of stronger economic growth in the first quarter
of the year.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up 2.00 to
1,963.37 in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers slightly outnumbered gainers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 400 up, 413 down and 511
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 52.08 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The Commerce Department said this morning that the gross
national product grew at a 3.9 percent annual rate, after
adjustment for inflation, in the first three months of 1988. That
was up from a previous estimate of 2.3 percent.
   Many analysts had voiced concern earlier in the week that a
stronger figure would reinforce investors' worries about a possible
revival of inflation and upward pressure on interest rates.
   Rates rose in the government securities market following the
news. But brokers said traders evidently concluded that the
revision had already been taken into account in stock prices.
   Tenneco rose \ to 46 on top of a 4]-point gain Wednesday, when
the company said it planned to put its oil and gas properties up
for sale.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .17 to 143.94. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .59 at 291.17.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 1.16 to
1,961.37.
   Gainers outpaced losers by about 7 to 6 on the NYSE, with 784
issues higher, 636 lower and 523 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 138.31 million shares, against 139.93 million in the
