<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Ford-FuelEconomy     05-26 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford-Fuel Economy,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford To Meet Fuel Economy Rules Rather Than Seek Reprieve</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. will meet the 27.5
miles-per-gallon fuel economy standard for its 1989 fleet rather
than seek a reduction in the standard from the federal government,
a Ford executive said.
   Ford will meet the Corporate Average Fuel Economy, or CAFE,
standard drawn up by Congress in 1975 by selling more small cars in
1989, said Philip E. Benton Jr., president of the Ford Automotive
Group.
   CAFE is the average fuel economy rating of the vehicles each
automaker sells in the United States during a model year, which
begins Oct. 1 and ends Sept. 30.
   That means that a company whose large cars sell better than its
small cars could be penalized because its average fuel economy is
too low.
   The U.S. Transportation Department lowered the standard from
27.5 mpg to 26 mpg three years ago at the request of Ford and
General Motors Corp., the nation's two largest automakers.
   Chrysler Corp., the third-largest U.S. automaker, argued against
the change because its fleet met the 27.5 mpg standard.
   Ford and GM had argued that low, stable gasoline prices had
increased demand for larger and luxury cars. The companies
threatened to cut big car production and lay off workers to meet
the standard rather than pay stiff fines for selling the larger
vehicles.
   GM and the Automobile Importers of America, which represents all
Japanese automakers and all but two European makers, have asked
that the 27.5 mpg standard for 1989 be reduced to 26 mpg standard
that was in effect for 1986, 1987 and 1988 models.
   Benton said Ford would break with the other automakers and added
that Ford is continuously reducing the weight of its cars and
engines.
   ``We're effecting change in that way and we also are using heavy
marketing actions. We're selling every small car we possibly can to
bring down the average,'' Benton said Wednesday.
   Ford also will use credits built up in previous years when its
fleet's average fuel economy exceeded the standards, he said.
   Benton was in Monroe to present a quality award to the Monroe
stamping plant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
