<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened slightly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, then turned mixed as some
meteorologists offered drier weather forecasts.
   Analysts attributed the lower opening primarily to
follow-through selling after Wednesday's sharp declines, especially
in the soybean pit.
   Wednesday's losses were sparked by predictions for rain in the
Midwest early next week. But some of today's early forecasts
offered a drier outlook, and bullish traders began buying contracts
on any significant dip in prices, said Walter Spilka, an analyst in
New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Wheat prices also were pressured by the Agriculture Department's
authorization of a program that will allow sharply higher wheat
production next year, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 2\ cents to 6 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.39 a bushel; corn was \ cent to
} cent lower with July at $2.14{ a bushel; oats were \ cent to {
cent lower with July at $1.71{ a bushel; soybeans were 6\ cents
lower to { cent higher with July at $7.58 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .20 cent higher with June at
71.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .28 cent
higher with May at 80.97 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent lower to
.20 cent higher with June at 52.75 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were unchanged to .30 cent higher with July at 53.52 cents
a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures finished lower on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
