<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Japanese     05-26 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Japanese,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honda Says Earnings Rose 63.2 Percent In Latest Fiscal Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honda Motor Co. Ltd. said its profit from
consolidated, worldwide operations rose 63.2 percent in its latest
fiscal quarter as revenue climbed 3.4 percent.
   The automaker said its results were helped by increased car
sales in Japan, cost-cutting efforts, successful currency hedging,
and improved profits from non-consolidated subsidiaries and
affiliates.
   Honda said it made a profit of 33.0 billion yen, or $264
million, in the three months ended March 31, which was a
transitional quarter because the company is changing to a new
fiscal year. The results were compared to the profit of 20.2
billion yen in the quarter ended Feb. 28, 1987.
   Honda's revenue rose to 795 billion yen, or $6.36 billion, in
the quarter ended March 31, from 769 billion yen in the quarter
ended Feb. 28, 1987.
   For the latest six-month period, Honda's profit rose 51.7
percent to 56.7 billion yen, or $453 million, from 37.4 billion yen
in the six months ended Feb. 28, 1987. Revenue rose 11.3 percent to
1,585 billion yen, or $12.7 billion, from 1,424 billion yen a year
earlier.
   Honda is changing to a fiscal year beginning April 1 instead of
March 1. It used an exchange rate of 125 yen to the dollar to
calculate the dollar value of its profits and revenue.
</TEXT>
