<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1400EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Boeing-757 1stLd-Writethru   05-26 0889</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boeing-757, 1st Ld-Writethru,0913</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Boeing Orders May Foretell Sellers' Market, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to update with United order, picks up 10th
graf, ``It can't.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENTON, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thanks in part to the new-found popularity
of its 757 twinjet, Boeing Co. appears headed for its fourth
consecutive year of record commercial jet orders, industry analysts
say.
   The giant aerospace company may be entering a sellers' market
for aircraft, and an order announced Wednesday by American Airlines
for as many as 100 of the 757s may be one of the last at bargain
prices, the analysts believe.
   American said it was ordering 50 757s for delivery between July
1989 and November 1991, with an option to purchase 50 more for
delivery through December 1993. Robert W. Baker, American's vice
president for operations, declined to give exact figures, but said
the deal was on ``very favorable terms for American'' with the firm
order worth slightly more than $2 billion and the second 50 planes
about the same.
   Today, United Airlines announced it was ordering 30 757s, with
options on 30 more. United Chairman Stephen M. Wolf placed the
value of his company's order at more than $2 billion.
   And 10 days ago, International Lease Finance Corp. of Beverly
Hills, Calif., ordered 100 Boeing jetliners and took options for 24
more. The $4.6 billion price  $25 billion in
1988 orders was possible.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes President Dean Thornton on Wednesday
acknowledged that 1988 could see a record, but said he felt
uncomfortable saying Boeing was on a roll.
   ``It can't keep up at this pace,'' he said. ``The past three
years have been successive record years in terms of orders. I don't
think it can continue, but I wouldn't hazard a guess as to when it
will end.''
   Thornton said it's a coincidence that Boeing is receiving large
orders in quick succession. But Demisch and others say now may be
the time to buy.
   ``We're moving toward a sellers' market for airplanes,'' Demisch
said, adding that as orders continue to build, aircraft prices
could rise by 10 percent to 20 percent.
   ``The desire to sort of get in before the gates close and prices
go up is not far from the airlines' mind,'' he said.
   Nisbet said the recent huge orders may ``encourage everyone to
hurry up and get their place in line'' for new aircraft needed in
the 1990s.
   Demisch said ``American got a very good deal'' at a price of
roughly $40 million a plane. Depending on configuration, 757s
normally sell for $41 million to $47 million each.
   American's new jets will primarily replace its aging Boeing 737s
and 727s, Baker said. The 194-passenger 757 jetliner, with a range
of about 3,300 miles, burns 25 percent less fuel than comparable
aircraft and will be powered by two Rolls Royce engines.
   The 50 additional planes, if ordered, would be delivered through
December 1993. In an interview with The Seattle Times last week,
American President and Chairman Robert Crandall said the airline
could order yet another 100 757s by the end of the century.
   Baker said American chose the 757 because of its economy,
quietness, and because crews flying the widebody Boeing 767s in
American's fleet can easily switch to the smaller jet. Also, he
said, more than half the parts in 767s are interchangeable with
those in 757s.
   Boeing launched the 757 in 1978 as a high-technology,
fuel-stingy replacement for its 727 tri-jet, which entered service
in 1964. But a drop in fuel prices stalled sales, with just 239
757s ordered through 1987.
   ``I think most of you know that we've been probably a little
disappointed with the 757 over the years,'' Thornton said.
   That's changed, with 90 of the planes ordered this year.
   Baker said the 757 makes sense with growing passenger demand
coupled with growing airport congestion. He said the ``realization
that those of us who are going to survive deregulation must begin
the process of retiring the first generation of aircraft makes this
airplane really kind of come into its own and be recognized for its
merits.''
   He said American wasn't rushed into the order, but had studied
it for months. ``You're betting your company when you buy a fleet
of 50 or 100 airplanes,'' he said. ``You want to be darn sure
you've looked at everything you can think of.''
   Thornton said Boeing plans to increase 757 production at its
Renton plant from four to five a month sometime next year. However,
he said Boeing doesn't expect to need to hire many new workers.
</TEXT>
