<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1438EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ComputerBookMart     05-26 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer BookMart,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Announces Computerized Book Browsing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Writers will be able to reach their public by
computer in June when a Florida company introduces a way to browse
through books electronically.
   ``We consider this the latest exercise of First Amendment
rights,'' said company president Joe Barcheski.
   The BookMart database will allow authors to reach readers
without going through the grueling process of submitting and
rewriting manuscripts for a publisher's approval.
   The database will also allow publishers to scan new books.
   BookMart is the brainchild of writer Samuel Bleecker, who along
with two partners have formed PubTronix, based in Pompano Beach,
Fla.
   The on-line computer service will provide access to five pages
of text and a book-jacket description of each volume for the price
to the shopper of a telephone call.
   The author or publishing company, however, will have to pay $250
a year for each computer listing.
   After browsing listings by subject, author or title, readers can
order a work by credit card and get it on a floppy disk, or in book
form if it has been published, Barcheski said.
   PubTronix announced BookMart last weekend at the Florida State
Writer's Conference in an effort to attract unpublished writers
seeking a forum outside the publishing world.
   ``In the next few weeks we will also be competing agreements
with several publishers'' for listings, Barcheski said.
   BookMart will go on line sometime in mid-June with about 1,000
titles listed and hopes to expand to as many as 10,000 titles, he
said. The on-line telephone number to RAC Information Systems in
Great Neck, N.Y., will be advertised in computer magazines and on
electonic billboards nationally when the start-up date is set,
Barcheski said.
   In addition to books, Barcheski, Bleecker, and Herb Rubinsky,
president of RAC, plan to use the database to sell rare books, such
as first editions and those carrying an autograph that would be of
interest to a national audience. The men also intend to begin
compiling magazine articles with RAC's staff of 30.
   Eventually, the men want to offer BookMart in kiosk units to
book stores as a way to boost selection without being buried in
inventory, Barcheski said.
   ``With a BookMart listing, a publisher can effectively reach the
home shopper and in the near future, the book store browser for a
very low cost,'' said Bleecker. ``Publishers are, therefore, no
longer required to distribute physical inventory to have a
nationwide audience.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0309 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Boeing-United 3rdLd-Writethru   05-26 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boeing-United, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United Orders 30 757s, Options 30 More</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 17th graf to CORRECT typo in `corporate' and 18th graf
to CORRECT UAL Corp. sted UAL Inc.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines today ordered 30 Boeing 757-200
jetliners and took options for 30 more, giving Boeing Commercial
Airplanes its third multibillion-dollar order for aircraft in two
weeks.
   United's firm order for 30 jets is valued at more than $1.3
billion, Boeing said. Deliveries of the jets are to be over a
three-year period beginning in 1989.
   United has chosen Pratt & Whitney engines to power its new
planes, which will be outfitted to accommodate 192 passengers in
two classes.
   On Wednesday, American Airlines announced it was ordering 50
757s worth more than $2 billion and taking options on an addition
50. On May 16, International Lease Finance Corp. ordered 100 Boeing
planes and took options on 24 more, a deal with a total value of
$4.6 billion, a Boeing record for a single order.
   ``It's been a very pleasant week, hasn't it?'' Boeing spokesman
Jim Boynton said in confirming the order. He repeated Boeing's
earlier statements that the new work would mean no new major hiring
at Boeing's 757 assembly plant in the Seattle suburb of Renton.
   In Chicago, United Chairman Stephen M. Wolf placed the value of
his company's order at more than $2 billion and said United chose
the 757 because of its cost-efficient operation.
   ``Our objective in returning to to our core business of running
an airline is to grow United Airlines and to establish it as this
nation's pre-eminent airline,'' Wolf said in a statement.
   ``The 757 will strenthen our domestic network and with operating
efficiencies that will enable us to compete more efficiently,'' he
said.
   United will take delivery of its first 757 in August 1989, Wolf
said. The delivery schedule for the first 30 airplanes calls for
delivery of six in 1989, 21 in 1990 and three in 1991.
   Delivery of more 757s depends on the airline's ability to
produce a consistent level of earnings, Wolf said.
   The 757 is a twin-engine, short-to-medium range jetliner and is
the most fuel-efficient aircraft Boeing builds. It also is designed
to meet the most stringent noise and operational restrictions at
U.S. airports.
   Boeing has had 356 jets ordered in 1988 with an estimated value
of $14.9 billion. That's just 10 fewer than the 366 Boeing
commercial jets ordered for all of 1987. The value of 1987 jet
orders was $19.9 billion, a company record.
   Industry analysts say Boeing could be headed for its
fourth-straight year of record orders, with some predicting a total
of up to $25 billion.
   Boeing has had 120 firm orders for 757s this year. Until
recently, the plane was a disappointment for Boeing, which only had
239 orders for the twinjet from 1978 through 1987. However,
industry officials say the plane's fuel efficiency, larger size and
availability in the early 1990s have brought it new popularity.
   United said it would finance part of the transaction through the
sale of its McDonnell Douglas DC-8 fleet to GPA Corp., a subsidiary
of GPA Group Ltd, based in Shannon, Ireland. The DC-8s are less
fuel-efficient than the 757s.
   United, which was started by Boeing, Pratt & Whitney and three
other companies in 1929, is Boeing's largest customer. With the new
order, United has purchased 528 jetliners from Boeing, including
all models the company has built.
   United and Boeing severed corporate ties in 1934.
   The announcement came at a meeting at which shareholders
approved a change in the name of United's parent company from
Allegis Corp. to UAL Corp.
   The company, formerly UAL, adopted the name Allegis in February
1987 as part of an ill-fated effort to structure itself as a
travel-and-hotel conglomerate. The ensuing stockholder uproar
forced the resignation of then-Chairman Richard Ferris and led to a
sell-off of all of the company's holdings except United.
   United already has taken delivery of 22 737-300s, part of an
order of 110 from Boeing, and will begin taking delivery of 15
747-400s next year, spokesman Joe Hopkins said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
