<DOCNO> AP880526-0311 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f FirstCarComesOffLine     05-26 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>First Car Comes Off Line</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Toyota produced in Kentucky
rolled off an assembly line Thursday and was greeted by cheers from
the plant's 1,100 employees.
   The white, four-door Camry sedan with a sunroof rolled onto an
80-foot stage to the applause of the employees and Toyota
officials. Its appearance was greeted by flashing lights and the
Toyota theme song.
   The car then went through a quality inspection and Katsuro
Nakamura, general manager of the Toyota plant in Japan, gave an OK
sign.
   ``This car is a symbol of our most important company principle,
teamwork,'' said Kaneyoshi Kusunoki, president of Toyota Motor
Manufacturing, U.S.A., Inc.
   The car rolled out Thursday was a pilot vehicle. Commercial
production is expected to begin in mid-summer.
   Full production will be reached in early 1989 with one shift
turning out 400 cars per day. Another shift will be added next
year, giving the plant an annual quota of 200,000 vehicles annually.
   Ground for the $800 million plant was broken May 5, 1986. A $300
million expansion to add a power train plant, which will produce
engine axles and steering components, was announced Nov. 9, 1987,
bringing the total investment in Kentucky to $1.1 billion.
   The Kentucky plant is Toyota's second in the United States. Its
first is a 50-50 joint venture with General Motors Corp. in
Fremont, Calif., called New United Motors Manufacturing Inc.
   NUMMI uses a GM plant previously shuttered because of
troublesome labor relations.
   Unlike Honda, which began producing cars on its own in the
United States in 1982, Toyota was more cautious and waited to gauge
the success of the NUMMI experiment before making the heavy
investment required to build its own plant.
   The Georgetown plant is considered the largest under one roof in
the United States.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
