<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-WallStreetJobs     05-26 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street Jobs,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forecast: Crash to Cost Wall Street 26,000 Jobs by January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street has lost 8,200 jobs since October's
stock market crash and likely will shed another 18,000 workers by
year's end, an economist said Thursday.
   The report by New York University Professor Matthew P. Drennan
was slightly more optimistic than his forecast late last year that
the securities industry in New York would lose 28,000 jobs by the
end of 1988 because of the crash.
   Drennan revised his prediction to about 26,000 because trading
volume on the New York Stock Exchange held up better than expected
during the first quarter of 1988.
   ``However, that support for employment is now crumbling,'' he
said.
   Market volume last month was 17 percent lower than in April
1987, and so far this month is 12 percent off last May's level,
Drennan, of NYU's Urban Research Center, said in an annual economic
report.
   ``This pattern of greatly reduced volume of stock trading is
expected to continue through the remainder of 1988. Consequently,
securities industry employment in the city is likely to take
another big hit,'' he said.
   Other reports have made similar forecasts. The state
comptroller's office in December predicted the loss of 20,000
securities industry jobs in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
