<DOCNO> AP880526-0315 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1556EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TroubledNukes Bjt   05-26 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Troubled Nukes, Bjt,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shoreham Abandonment May be First of Many Blows to Nuclear
Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tentative decision to close the $5.3
billion Shoreham reactor on Long Island, N.Y., may be only the
first of several severe blows awaiting the nation's troubled
nuclear power industry.
   An agreement reached early Thursday between the Long Island
Lighting Co. and New York state would result in the abandonment of
Shoreham, which, though complete, has never generated commercial
power. It would be the first U.S. nuclear plant to be scuttled
without ever operating.
   A similar fate may await the equally costly Seabrook nuclear
plant in New Hampshire. Like Shoreham, Seabrook has been embroiled
in legal and political problems over the issue of whether residents
and tourists in its much-traveled resort area could be safely
evacuated in the event of a major emergency.
   Adding to Seabrook's woes is the recent declaration of
bankruptcy by the plant's owner, Public Service Co. of New
Hampshire. Gov. John Sununu recently said the bankruptcy filing may
actually be a blessing in disguise, allowing a new financial
package to be put together that could put Seabrook back on track.
   But many financial analysts doubt that, and Democratic
presidential front-runner Michael Dukakis, who if elected would
appoint a new Nuclear Regulatory Commission, is foresworn to close
the reactor.
   In addition to Seabrook, more than a dozen other plants are in
deep trouble. Voters in the Sacramento, Calif., area will decide in
June whether to close the long-plagued Rancho Seco plant owned by
Sacramento Municipal Utility District.
   The Pilgrim plant in Massachusetts, owned by Boston Edison, will
be the subject of a similar referendum in November.
   Rancho Seco and Pilgrim were singled out recently by an
anti-nuclear group, Public Citizen, as the two worst commercial
nuclear plants in the nation. The group, virtually duplicating a
``worst'' list put out a year earlier by the NRC, also named 14
other plants as candidates for permanent shutdown.
   Among them are two Peach Bottom reactors in Pennsylvania, shut
down by the NRC last year after federal investigators found plant
operators sleeping on duty, and several plants belonging to the
Tennessee Valley Authority, whose nuclear program has been
embroiled in a wide variety of management and safety problems.
   All five of TVA's operating reactors were shut down in 1985 for
safety improvements, and only one, Sequoyah Unit 2, was allowed
just recently to restart. Meanwhile, TVA had to cancel plans to
build eight other reactors, and construction, already under way, of
four others was slowed.
   While TVA hopes to restart all the facilities closed in 1985,
the future of those under construction remains dark.
   The industry insists the overall outlook for nuclear power is
good, if not bright. It points to an increase of 10 percent last
year in electrical generation and an improved safety and efficiency
record, in which sudden shudowns dropped to 2.7 per reactor,
compared with 3.9 the previous year and 7.4 in 1980.
   But the fact remains that many reactors are candidates for
closure, and no utility has planned a new nuclear power plant since
the 1970s.
   Among other plants cited by Public Citizen and the NRC as
problem reactors are Fermi No. 2 in Michigan, Oyster Creek in New
Jersey, three Browns Ferry TVA units in Alabama, Davis-Besse in
Ohio, Dresden No. 2 in Illinois, Fort St. Vrain in Colorado and
Byron No. 1 in Illinois.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0316 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2047EDT</FILEID>
