market, totaled 187.85 million shares.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday morning that the gross
national product grew at a 3.9 percent annual rate, after
adjustment for inflation, in the first three months of 1988. That
was up from a previous estimate of 2.3 percent.
   Many analysts had voiced concern earlier in the week that a
stronger figure would reinforce investors' worries about a possible
revival of inflation and upward pressure on interest rates.
   Rates rose in the government securities market following the
news, amid conjecture that the Federal Reserve was tightening
credit a bit further.
   But brokers said traders evidently concluded that the revision
had already been taken into account in stock prices.
   Texaco accounted for most of the Dow Jones industrials' rise,
climbing 3[ to 50. Late Wednesday Carl Icahn, the company's largest
shareholder, proposed to offer $60 a share to take it over.
   USX, another company in which Icahn holds a stake, gained 1 to
30{.
   Tenneco slipped [ to 45| after gained 4] Wednesday, when the
company said it planned to put its oil and gas properties up for
sale.
   Newhall Land & Farming jumped 4] to 44{. Late in the day the
company said it wasn't involved in any talks about being acquired.
   Long Island Lighting rose 1\ to 11]. The utility reached an
agreement with New York state officials to settle a long dispute
involving its Shoreham nuclear power plant, which is to be
dismantled.
   Sears Roebuck led the active list, up \ at 34{ in trading
largely attributed to strategies focused on the company's dividend.
   U.S. Shoe fell ~ to 17|. The company reported lower earnings for
the fiscal quarter that ended April 30.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
