<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SouthKorea 1stLd-Writethru   05-26 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Clash With Police Over U.S. Imports; Students Attack
American Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 2 grafs after 10th, `The attack...' to ADD government
official saying anti-U.S. views not widespread. Picks up 11th pvs,
`Radical students...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students shouting ``Go Home Yankees!''
attacked an American bank with rocks and firebombs Thursday, and
farmers protesting U.S. agricultural imports hurled cow dung at
police during a clash outside the National Assembly.
   Prime Minister Lee Hyun-jai ordered a crackdown on violent
protests and radicals, but the mandate seemed to have little effect
on the wave of anti-American rage.
   About 30 students dashed out of sidestreets and hurled rocks and
firebombs at a branch in southern Seoul of the KorAm Bank, police
said. Police said four people were arrested.
   The bank, a joint venture between the Bank of America and Korean
business groups, was not damaged. It had not yet opened for
business and had shutters over the windows and entrance.
   Riot police fired tear gas in front of the National Assembly
building in Seoul to disperse farmers protesting plans to increase
imports of U.S. agricultural products.
   At least five people were injured.
   About 500 farmers, with two calves at the front, hurled cow dung
and clashed with police after a rally attended by about 1,500
farmers. Police kicked and punched the protesters, who shouted
``Oppose American beef and its pressure to open the Korean market!''
   One calf ran amok through 1,000 riot police surrounding the
assembly compound.
   The United States is pushing South Korea to widen its markets to
American imports. The trade issue has fanned anti-U.S. sentiment.
   The attack on the bank was the first on U.S. business interests
in the wave of violent protests that have been aimed mainly at the
United States.
   A senior government official said Wednesday that the
anti-American sentiment of the radical students is not shared by
most Koreans.
   Hyun Hong-choo, minister of legislation, said: ``We are
confident the majority of the people are happy with our relations
with the United States.'' He was commenting at a lunch with the
press about the recent unrest.
   Radical students blame the United States for the partition of
the Korean peninsula and accuse Washington of supporting military
rule in the South. They demand the withdrawal of the 42,000 U.S.
troops stationed in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   The Korean peninsula was divided by U.S. and Soviet troops that
ended the Japanese occupation in 1945 at the end of World War II.
   Last week, protesters hurling rocks and firebombs attacked U.S.
cultural centers in Seoul and in the southern city of Kwangju and
hurled homemade bombs at the U.S. Embassy in Seoul.
   Dissidents said Thursday they would continue the anti-U.S.
campaign and called a major anti-U.S. rally in Seoul on Friday to
mark the end of the eighth anniversary of a 1980 civil uprising in
Kwangju, where thousands of students and citizens battled police in
daily protests.
   Dissidents contend the United States condoned the South Korean
army's bloody suppression of the nine-day uprising, in which at
least 191 people were killed.
   A 20-year-old student who had called for a full probe of the
Kwangju uprising died in a hospital Thursday after dousing himself
with kerosene and setting himself afire during a campus rally May
18.
   About 400 students shouting anti-U.S. and anti-government
slogans staged a sit-in protest at the hospital in Seoul where Choi
Duk-soo died. Choi was a student at Dankook University.
   In South Korea, suicide is sometimes used as a form of protest.
   In a Cabinet meeting, Lee called for a crackdown against
radicals and tighter security around foreign facilities.
   Lee said the recent protests posed a threat to the people and
``inflicted undesirable influence on the nation's security and
diplomacy before staging the Olympics.''
   The Olympic Games open in Seoul in September.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
