<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Economy 1stLd-Writethru   05-26 0990</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru,1016</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Large Decline in Trade Deficit Fuels Surprising First Quarter
Growth</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 15th graf pvs, bgng: Analysts
predicted, to UPDATE with comment on inflation prospects from Beryl
Sprinkel, investor. Picks up 16th graf pvs, About 80</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy grew at a surprisingly rapid
annual rate of 3.9 percent from January through March, much better
than previously believed, because of the biggest decline in the
trade deficit in eight years, the government reported Thursday.
   The Commerce Department said the gross national product, the
broadest measure of economic health, was propelled during the first
three months of the year by an export surge, a rebound in car sales
and a boom in business capital investment.
   The report represented a sharp upward revision from an initial
estimate made a month ago that the GNP grew at a more modest 2.3
percent rate in the first quarter.
   It provided fresh evidence that the economy has escaped
unscathed from last fall's stock market crash, and it sent
economists scurrying to revise up their growth estimates for the
full year.
   ``You would have to say that not only was the stock market crash
ignored, but the economy thumbed its nose at it,'' said Robert
Dederick, chief economist of Northern Trust Co. of Chicago.
   Allen Sinai, chief economist of the Boston Co., said he had
revised his forecast to show GNP growth of 3.5 percent for all of
1988. That would be the fastest rate of growth since 1984.
   ``The Reagan years are ending with a bang. The first quarter GNP
report shows an economy that is amazingly strong and resilient for
such an aging expansion,'' Sinai said.
   All the good economic news is especially pleasing to Republicans
in an election year when they hope George Bush will win the White
House running on a platform emphasizing the peacetime record of 66
months of expansion since the last recession in 1981-82.
   The economic growth in the first quarter was a far cry from the
recession that some analysts had predicted immediately following
the Oct. 19 collapse in stock prices. However, economists now have
begun to worry that inflationary pressures have begun rising
because the economy is growing so rapidly.
   Those fears are present despite the fact that a GNP price index
which measures a changing marketbasket of goods rose at an annual
rate of just 1.7 percent in the first quarter, the smallest
increase since late 1984.
   Analysts said this performance masked growing price pressures
stemming from tight labor markets and the rising number of
industries that are pushing against capacity constraints.
Unemployment fell to a 14-year low of 5.4 percent in April.
   In a second report Thursday, the government said after-tax
corporate profits rose just 0.5 percent in the first quarter of the
year following a much larger 2.6 percent rise in the fourth quarter.
   Bruce Steinberg, senior economist with Merrill Lynch in New
York, said the weak profit rise in the first quarter would add to
inflation pressures as companies seek to boost revenues by raising
prices in coming months.
   ``The inflation environment is deteriorating. The economy is
growing too rapidly for stable prices,'' Steinberg said.
   Analysts predicted that the Federal Reserve, whose job it is to
worry about inflation, will push interest rates higher to dampen
demand. The central bank already has tightened credit conditions
twice in the past two months.
   Frank Cappiello, a Wall Street investment adviser, said the fast
GNP growth in the first quarter was adding to inflationary
pressures and setting the stage for a recession next year.
   ``What (the GNP increase) reflects is light from a dying star,''
Cappiello said during an appearance in Omaha. ``You're seeing the
best growth in the economy. I think from here on in it will be
dragged down by higher (interest) rates.''
   But Beryl Sprinkel, the president's chief economic adviser,
disputed that contention, saying there was no evidence of either
recession or inflation threats in the GNP figures.
   ``We had an upward revision in real growth, a downward revision
in inflation and greater strength on the exports side,'' Sprinkel
said in an interview. ``These are all objectives of this
administration.''
   The administration's current forecast calls for GNP growth of
2.9 percent this year. With the fast start, the economy could grow
as slowly as 1.9 percent for the rest of the year and still reach
that estimate.
   About 80 percent of the improvement in the GNP report from the
previous estimate came from a bigger shrinkage in the trade deficit
than previously believed. The trade defict declined at an annual
rate of $16.7 billion in the first quarter, the sharpest narrowing
since early 1980, as exports, after adjusting for inflation, rose
20.7 percent while imports were up only 3.4 percent.
   The 3.9 percent overall GNP growth rate followed an even
stronger 4.8 percent rise in the fourth quarter. However, that
increase came almost entirely from a buildup of unsold inventories
which was occurring at the same time that consumer spending was
posting a rare decline.
   Growth in the first quarter was much more balanced, with
consumer spending rising by 4.3 percent, reflecting in large part a
rebound in car sales.
   In addition, business investment for capital equipment shot up a
remarkable 32.8 percent, the biggest rise in more than four years.
Analysts attributed this investment surge to the improving trade
deficit which has sent U.S. companies scurrying to expand
production facilities in order to meet higher export demand.
   Analysts said they were looking for slightly slower growth of
around 3 percent in the current April-June quarter due to an
expected slowdown in growth of export sales, consumer spending and
business investment from the rapid rate of the first quarter.
   The various changes left the GNP rising by $37.2 billion in the
first quarter, an annual level of $3.92 trillion, after adjusting
for the effects of inflation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
