<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1800EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-LILCOChronology     05-26 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LILCO Chronology,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chronology of LILCO History</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also ran on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some key dates in the history of the
Shoreham nuclear power plant:
   April 13, 1966: The Long Island Lighting Co. announces plan to
build a nuclear power plant, costing up to $75 million.
   May 24 1968: LILCO applies for U.S. Atomic Energy Commission
license to construct Shoreham plant.
   April 12, 1973: LILCO receives construction permit.
   Aug. 30, 1978: Emergency plan in case of an accident at Shoreham
approved by Suffolk County Executive John Klein.
   March 28, 1979: Accident at Three Mile Island nuclear plant in
Pennsylvania.
   June 15, 1980: Congress mandates adequate emergency plan before
the Nuclear Regulatory Commission can license a plant.
   March 23, 1982: County Legislature undertakes new emergency
plan, declares no plan will be valid without its approval.
   Feb. 16, 1983: Legislature says no plan could adequately protect
residents from a major accident at Shoreham.
   Jan. 22, 1984: LILCO announces completion of all basic
structures at Shoreham, after 11 years of work.
   March 6, 1984: LILCO says delays in completing Shoreham have
caused a fiscal crisis forcing it to eliminate 1,000 jobs, cut
salaries and halt dividends to save $374 million.
   March 8, 1984: State, county and towns file suit over LILCO's
intention to rely on its own emergency plan.
   Feb. 21, 1985: State court rules that LILCO lacks authority to
carry out its own emergency plan.
   April 17, 1985: Atomic Safety and Licensing Appeals Board, an
arm of the NRC, approves LILCO emergency plan.
   June 26, 1985: State Public Service Commission bars LILCO from
charging customers for $1.35 billion of the cost of building
Shoreham.
   July 3, 1985: NRC licenses Shoreham to operate at up to 5
percent of full power for testing.
   July 7, 1985: Low-power testing begins.
   Feb. 13, 1986: Federal Emergency Management Agency conducts
drill of LILCO emergency plan, over county and state objections.
   April 15, 1986: Regional FEMA director resigns, saying he was
pressured to soften his criticism of LILCO's emergency plan in
report on drill.
   April 26, 1986: Accident at Chernobyl nuclear plant in the
Soviet Union.
   June 11, 1987: NRC denies LILCO's request to operate Shoreham at
up to 25 percent of capacity.
   Oct. 29, 1987: NRC changes its rules to allow for plant
licensing even if local governments refuse to participate in
evacuation planing.
   March 29, 1988: Long Island Power Authority, formed by state
Legislature to explore takeover of LILCO, votes to attempt takeover.
   May 25, 1988: Gov. Mario Cuomo gives LILCO a midnight deadline
to accept a settlement under which it would scrap the $5.3 billion
Shoreham plant but remain investor-owned.
   May 26, 1988: Tentative agreement announced. As part of the
pact, the state would buy Shoreham for $1 and have it
decontaminated and decommissioned at LILCO's expense.
   Should the agreement be approved by various state agencies and
portions of it by the state Legislature, it would mark the first
time a completed nuclear power plant was abandoned before it opened.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
