<HEAD>Gannett To Buy Back Up to 7.5 Million Shares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gannett Co. Inc. said Thursday it plans to buy
back up to 7.5 million shares of the company's 162 million issued
shares of common stock.
   Gannett's board of directors authorized the repurchase on the
open market or in privately negotiated block transactions,
depending on price, availability and other corporate developments,
the company said in a statement.
   The purchases will occur ``from time to time,'' and no maximum
or minimum prices have been set, the company said.
   Allen H. Neuharth, chairman of Gannett, and John J. Curley,
president and chief executive officer of the company, said the
current low trading prices of Gannett's stock make it an
``excellent investment compared to recent media acquisition
prices.''
   Gannett stock closed at $30.75, up $1.12{ in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading Thursday.
   Gannett publishes USA Today, 89 daily newspapers, 35 nondaily
newspapers and USA Weekend, a newspaper magazine. It also operates
10 television stations, 16 radio stations and Gannett News Service
in addition to other news and information systems and facilities.
