<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BilzerianLawsuit     05-26 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bilzerian Lawsuit,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corporate Raider Files Slander Suit Over Remark That He
``Welshed''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Well-known corporate raider Paul A.
Bilzerian, who frequently battles industrial titans, has filed a
slander suit against a Little League officer.
   The suit, filed Wednesday in Pinellas Circuit Court, charges
that Rick Brannelly, first vice president of the Northeast Little
League, made false statements about Bilzerian that appeared in an
article in the St. Petersburg Times on Saturday.
   The dispute revolves around whether the league met its 1987
fund-raising goal or fell short by $52.25 as charged by Bilzerian,
who bought the Singer Co. in February for $1.06 million.
   In spring and summer, Bilzerian has coached a baseball team of
5, 6 and 7-year-olds and his Tampa based firm, Bicoastal Financial
Corp. has sponsored a team.
   In the newspaper article, Brannelly maintained Bilzerian failed
to provide a matching $5,000 donation he promised to the league if
it raised $5,000 on its own.
   Brannelly claimed Bilzerian ``welshed'' on the promise made
before dozens of people, according to the Times.
   Bilzerian's attorney Michael Ingram was quoted in the story
saying the league failed to meet its fund-raising goal and
therefore Bilzerian was under no obligation to make the donation.
   Such statements by Brannelly, the suit alleges, have ``a
tendency to injure Bilzerian in his office, occupation, business or
employment.''
   The suit seeks punitive damages in excess of $5,000, the minimum
amount required to get a civil case into circuit court.
   Bilzerian was out of town and could not be reached for comment
Thursday. Ingram was called but was not available Thursday.
   Singer spokesman Tom Elliott said only ``I think it's all pretty
much in the complaint.''
</TEXT>
