<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 1936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FuelSpill 1stLd-Writethru   05-26 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fuel Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dime-Size Flaw Blamed In Tank Collapse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `A combination...', to CORRECT that official
is head of a team that investigated the accident, sted head of the
institute itself; SUBS 5th graf to delete redundant first reference
to Mesloh.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fuel tank collapse that caused the
contamination of drinking water in three states stemmed from a
dime-size flaw in the tank's nearly 50-year-old steel wall, Ashland
Oil Inc. said Thursday.
   The 4-million-gallon storage tank collapsed Jan. 2 as it was
being filled with 3.8 million gallons of oil, spilling more than
700,000 gallons into the Monongahela River and then the Ohio River.
   A combination of factors aggravated the impact of the flaw and
caused the wall of the tank to split in less than a second, sending
the oil over the dike ``like a skier going off a jump,'' according
to Ray Mesloh, head of a team from an independent research
institute that investigated the accident for Ashland.
   The steel wall of the tank was first assembled in Cleveland in
1940. It was taken apart and reconstructed at the company's
Floreffe Terminal south of Pittsburgh in 1986.
   The original welds and the welds made during the reconstruction
made the steel more brittle, said Mesloh, of the Battelle Memorial
Institute of Columbus, Ohio.
   Other factors in the collapse were the relative weakness of
World War II-era steel, pressure from the 3.8 million gallons of
diesel fuel inside and the cold weather, he said.
   ``If you had a combination of these same events, it could happen
again,'' said John R. Hall, chairman of the Ashland, Ky., firm.
   However, Hall said, ``Once again, and I hope for the last time,
we apologize.''
   The flaw was in the steel before Ashland assembled the tank near
Cleveland. It was caused by a torch, possibly one used to cut the
plate at the mill where it was made, Mesloh said.
   The flaw, a small, rusting cavity about one-eighth inch deep,
was located near a weld about 8 feet from the bottom of the tank's
48-foot-high wall, said Mesloh, displaying the defective steel at a
news conference.
   ``It is likely that flaw would have been found by X-raying,''
Mesloh said.
   Hall also emphasized that similar fuel tanks are in use around
the country and that the Jan. 2 accident could happen elsewhere,
too.
   The American Petroleum Institute said there were about 1,850
major oil terminals in 1987, many with more than one tank, in the
United States. The institute does not track the age of tanks, said
spokeswoman Jane Van Ryan.
   Ashland has concluded that improvements are needed in some of
the 1,000 large tanks it has inspected and has abandoned the
practice of moving old tanks, Hall said.
   The estimated 713,000 gallons of oil that escaped the tank's
protective dike forced communities along the Monongahela and Ohio
rivers in Pennsylvania, Ohio and West Virginia to close their
drinking water intakes. About 23,000 suburban Pittsburgh residents
were without tap water for almost a week.
   The accident spawned a flurry of legislation in Congress,
including a bill that Rep. Doug Walgren, D-Pa., on Thursday said
``would have required Ashland to test the tank before using it.
That is not now required.''
   Walgren's bill would set standards for above-ground tanks with
capacity of morew than 4,200 gallons.
   The U.S. Bureau of Standards, the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency and the Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Resources
are also investigating the Ashland spill.
   Besides failing to obtain all the local permits required for
erecting the tank, Ashland said it failed to fill the tank with
water, a test recommended by the American Petroleum Institute.
   More than 4,000 claims seeking about $18 million in damages have
been filed against Ashland, which says it is fully covered by
insurance. Ashland said it has paid about $7 million, including $6
million in clean-up costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880526-0332 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Budget 1stLd-Writethru f0222 05-26 0876</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0222,0901</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Passes $1.1 Trillion Budget After Negotiators Reach
Agreement</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf to UPDATE with details on vote;
INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf pvs bgng, `Under the,' to UPDATE
with details of final dispute; INSERTS 1 graf after 11th graf pvs
bgng, `Education, health,' to UPDATE with details on new drug
spending; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House passed a $1.1 trillion federal
budget for the 1989 fiscal year Thursday after negotiators from the
House and Senate solved a month-long dispute over domestic spending.
   The measure was approved by a 201-181 vote and sent to the
Senate, where it was expected to be accepted after that chamber
returns from its Memorial Day recess next month.
   Twenty-six Republicans joined 175 Democrats in voting for the
measure, which is moving toward its earliest congressional approval
in years. The legislators, however, already have upheld their
annual tradition of missing the April 15 deadline set in the law
for completing the budget.
   The spending plan would satisfy the limits placed on defense,
domestic and international affairs spending that were set in last
fall's budget summit agreement between President Reagan and
congressional leaders.
   It also would avoid automatic spending cuts under the
Gramm-Rudman balanced budget law later in the year by producing a
deficit just under the law's $146 billion deficit ceiling.
   ``It has been designed bipartisanly, in good faith to avoid''
the automatic cuts, said House Budget Committee Chairman William H.
Gray III, D-Pa.
   However, some lawmakers warned that Gramm-Rudman spending cuts
could still be forced later this year if the economy worsens.
   ``We should be scaling back spending below the summit levels,''
said Rep. Willis D. Gradison Jr., R-Ohio.
   Under the law, the budget's deficit will be recalculated in
August, and a weakening economy usually increases federal spending
and reduces the taxes it collects.
   The last dispute that negotiators from the two chambers resolved
was over new spending in domestic entitlement programs. In such
programs, formulas in the law automatically decide how much money
will be spent.
   The House wanted to increase that spending by $100 million next
year and $1.3 billion over three years, while the Senate sought a
$500 million increase for 1989 and $2 billion more over three years.
   Under the compromise, such spending will grow by $375 million
next year and by $2.2 billion over the three years, with most of it
being used for nutrition programs for the poor.
   The measure contains $299.5 billion in new defense spending,
$18.1 billion for international affairs and $148 billion for
domestic programs for the next fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1.
   The amount for the Pentagon is an $8.1 billion increase over
military spending this year, but below the amount that would have
been needed to keep up with inflation.
   Education, health, social services and job training programs
would all be given enough money to keep up with inflation. And
selected other programs _ including those for AIDS research and
treatment, anti-drug initiatives, space and air traffic control _
would get enough new money to surpass the costs of inflation.
   The election-year measure would allow an additional $1.4 billion
in anti-drug spending to be provided later this year if Congress
and the White House decide that an emergency exists. The extra
money would have to be covered by spending reductions in other
areas or by new revenues.
   In legislation passed in December that enacted the terms of the
budget summit, $14 billion in new taxes for fiscal 1989 already
have been written into law. The budget approved Thursday includes
no other additional revenues.
   The House passed its original version of the budget March 23,
and the Senate completed its work April 14.
   The two chambers had differences _ small ones in budget terms _
over how the domestic spending was to be divided.
   The Senate sought $13.4 billion for space and science programs
and $36.6 billion for education and job programs, while the House
wanted $12.5 billion for science and $37.6 billion for education.
   In their compromise, the lawmakers agreed to $13 billion for
science and $37.2 billion for education.
   They also agreed to a 4 percent pay raise for military personnel
and federal civilian employees to take effect in January. The
Senate had sought a 2 percent increase for civilians and a 4.3
percent raise for the armed services, while the House had sought a
3 percent increase for each category.
   The raise also would apply to members of Congress, who already
earn $89,500 annually. If included in forthcoming appropriations
bills, members of Congress would earn $93,080 a year, a raise of
$3,580.
   The budget does not require the president's signature, and is
used as a guideline by Congress as it passes the 13 appropriations
bills that actually provide money for federal spending. But this
year, its value seems even more questionable than usual.
   While the House-Senate negotiators spent six weeks trying to
iron out their differences, the two chambers' appropriations
committees began work on their spending measures.
   Thus, the House already has passed four of the 13 appropriations
bills, while the Senate appropriations committee has taken the
first steps in writing its spending measures.
</TEXT>
