<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BankBid     05-26 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders Extension Of Bank of NY Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New York Co. said Thursday it agreed to
extend its hostile $1.1 billion bid for Irving Bank Corp. for one
week until next Friday.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said the company made the
extension at the request of the U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
   The court is hearing a suit Irving filed last week against Bank
of New York alleging the unwanted suitor violated federal
securities laws when it amended its takeover bid to seek two-thirds
of Irving's stock rather than all of it.
   Irving claimed the company failed to adequately notify
shareholders of the financial ramincations of the amended offer.
   Irving management is backing a friendly merger with the
state-run Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, Italy's second-largest
bank.
   Bank of New York is offering $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its
stock for each of Irving's outstanding shares.
   The company is proceeding with its tender offer although it
recently lost a crucial proxy battle for control of Irving's board.
As of last Monday, it held about 50 percent of Irving's shares,
including those it owned and those tendered to it.
   Banca Commerciale is offering $80 a share for a 51 percent stake
in Irving, or about $760 million. The bid is part of a complex
restructuring plan that includes sale of Irving assets, several
cost-cutting measures and a special $10 dividend.
</TEXT>
