<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 2210EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ShorehamImpact 2ndLd-Writethru f0269 05-26 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shoreham Impact, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0269,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High-Priced Power Nothing New on Long Island</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `According to ..., with 1 graf to include
residential rate; picks up 6th graf: ``We are ...; Also moved on
general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher electricity prices caused by
scrapping the Shoreham nuclear plant could cramp Long Island
industry, already burdened by high energy costs, economists and
industrialists said Thursday.
   ``No doubt about it, higher rates will hurt growth,'' said
Martin Melkonian, a Hofstra University economics professor. ``But
it won't be the factor that brings Long Island to its knees.''
   Melkonian was a co-author of ``Project 2000,'' a report on the
island's energy needs written for businesses.
   He noted that the Long Island Lighting Co.'s rates have
increased more than 300 percent in the last decade compared with a
national average of 195 percent and are already among the highest
in the nation.
   According to Energy User News, a trade publication, LILCO has
the seventh-highest commercial rates in the nation. For residences,
the cost is 11.7 cents per kilowatt-hour, meaning a household that
uses 600 kilowatt-hours a month would have a monthly bill of
$70.20, LILCO reported.
   ``We are used to the high cost of energy,'' Melkonian said.
``The cost of energy in relation to the total value of the product
output here is relatively small.''
   Under Thursday's agreement to dismantle the never-used, $5.3
billion plant, the estimated $500 million decommissioning cost will
be paid for by ratepayers over 10 years.
   Richard Kessel, a state negotiator on the LILCO deal and Gov.
Mario Cuomo's chief adviser on consumer issues, said the agreement
would increase the average Long Island resident's electric bill by
a little more than $3 per month.
   LILCO would get a guaranteed 5 percent increase in rates each
year for three years, and 5 percent would be the target increase
for each of the following seven years.
   James LaRocca, president of the Long Island Association, an
organization of 2,000 companies, said that would mean a 63 percent
total increase.
   ``This is a very expensive deal which has to be borne entirely
by Long Islanders,'' he said. ``Our rates will be significantly
higher when three other utilities in New York are in the midst of a
multiyear rate freeze.''
   ``We are already seeing the consequences of Long Island's
decreasing ability to compete,'' LaRocca said.
   A direct mail company recently fled Suffolk County for
Pennsylvania and saw its electric bill plummet from $48,000 a month
to $19,000 a month, LaRocca said.
   Grumman Corp. of Bethpage, the Navy's prime contractor and Long
Island's largest employer, expanded its facilities last year but
did it in Houston, citing the high cost of energy and taxes on Long
Island.
   Grumman has 23,500 employes on the island. It pays $30 million a
year for electricity.
   ``People with cheaper power can be more competitive in the
market,'' said Robert Harwood, a Grumman spokesman. ``The cost has
to be passed along to the consumer and in our case that is the
American taxpayer.''
   Harwood found a silver lining, however, to the steady rate hikes
planned: some certainty and stability, with companies able to plan
better.
   ``Our overall problem is that we did not know what was going to
happen with rates,'' said Harwood. ``Now we can plan.''
   Long Island has a thriving economy with one of the lowest
unemployment rates in the country, a highly skilled and educated
work force and one of the largest multinational business
communities in the region.
   ``There will be a substantial impact on rates, particularly with
those in the manufacturing industry,'' said Martin Cantor, Suffolk
County's director of economic development. ``But I think the rates
will be absorbed without too much hardship.''
   Wayne Prospect, deputy supervisor of the Suffolk Legislature,
criticized the proposed settlement as an ``economic bailout for
LILCO.''
   ``The people of Long Island wanted that nuclear power plant
closed,'' he said. ``I guess higher electric rates is the economic
tradeoff.''
</TEXT>
